<h1>Slavery-Charles Mitchell</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
CHARLES MITCHELL<br>
<br>
When James Tilton, Washington's first surveyor-general left the Atlantic for the Pacific, a mulatto boy named Charley, born in slavery, was given him by a relative in Talbot County, Maryland. After living in the Tilton family at Olympia for five or six years, and attaining his growth and almost his majority, Charley was approached by colored men, told of the pleasure of freedom at Victoria, and induced to try to make his escape.<br>
<br>
The colored steward, on the steamer <B>Eliza Anderson</B> stowed him away one September day, just before the boat started from the southern end of her route. About the time the steamer got to Seattle, Charley was found by Captain Fleming. To prevent his escape Captain Fleming had Charley locked in a spare room.<br>
<br>
At Victoria, the colored men were waiting on the wharf, and when they learned from the steward of the situation two of them made affidavit that a "...negro boy, a fugitive slave, who had made frequent attempts to escape and secure his freedom, was on board the steam <B>Eliza Anderson</B>, detained there against his will."<br>
<br>
On the strength of this Henry P.P. Crease, an attorney, made application to  Chief Justice Cameron for a writ of habeas corpus. Captain Fleming resisted the law for a time, but was finally obliged to release Charley from confinement, the boy walking ashore with his new found friends.<br>
<br>
Fleming filed a written protest, and demanded the return of Charley that he might be "...taken back to his master..." describing him as a "negro boy named Charley, the property of James  Tilton, of Olympia, Washington Territory, who ran away from his master, etc.<br>
<br>
Governor McGill, on the boat at the time also protested, alleging that the whole proceeding was illegal and in violation of international law. General Tilton claimed that he did not regard Charley as a slave but as an orphan under his control until of legal age; and further that his services were of no pecuniary value and his escape was a matter of indifference.<br>
<br>
This was the only case of negro slavery, or of anything resembling such slavery in the history of the Territory or State.<br>
<br>
Clarence Bagley, <B>History of King County.</B> Chicago: S.J. Clarke Publishing Company, 1929. p. 356.57.<br>
<br>

- - - - - - - - -<br>
<br>
Quintard Taylor, Jr. <B>A History of Blacks in the Pacific Northwest.</B><B> 1788-1970.</B> A thesis submitted to the faculty of the graduate school of the University of Minnesota, 1977.<br>
<br>
An problem facing the slave holder in the Pacific Northwest was the region's close proximity to foreign possessions such as British Canada or Mexico which before 1848 included present day California and Nevada.<br>
<br>
An incident involving a young slave, Charles Mitchell, illustrates this point. Charles was owned by Major James Tilton, of Olympia, Washington Territory's surveyor general. On September 29, 1860, Mitchell stowed away on the <B>Eliza Anderson, </B> an American steamer bound for Victoria, British Columbia. After the steamer was under way, he was discovered by ship's officers and locked in a cabin to await the ship's return to Olympia.<br>
<br>
<B>The Eliza Anderson</B> docked at Victoria with the fugitive slave still a prisoner, when Black residents of the Canadian city learned of his plight and through the local sheriff secured his release from the vessel.<br>
<br>
When a hearing took place in Victoria to determine Mitchell's status, the chief justice of the British Colony granted the slave freedom on the grounds that a person aboard a foreign vessel in a British port was subject to the laws of Great Britain.<br>
<br>
Tilton protested to the American Secretary of State but no action was taken.<br>
<br>
Quintard Taylor, Jr. <B>A History of Blacks in the Pacific Northwest, 1788-1970.</B> University of Minnesota, 1977.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
Another version of the same story written from a more "legal" point of view was published in the <B>British Columbia Historical Quarterly</B> for October, 1942. Written by Robie L. Reid and entitled "How One Slave Became Free," <B>British Columbia Historical Quarterly</B> VI (October, 1942), p. 251-256.<br>
<br>
Mr. Reid concluded his article by writing:<br>
<br>
"After reading the whole proceedings in the matter one wonders if Captain (John R.) Fleming was really anxious to return Charles to his owner. He was a man of some education and standing, otherwise he would not have occupied the position he did. He was in touch with a lawyer and a good one, George Pearkes, as is shown by his
protest.<br>
<br>
"And yet he thought his case good enough for him to appear on the trial and act as Counsel for himself. It almost seems as if he were more anxious to save his face with his Olympia friends than to carry Charles back to that town in triumph."<br>
<br>
Mr. Reid in writing his article contacted an attorney, Mr. G.L. Murray of Vancouver, who responded by letter, G.L. Murray to R.L. Reid, September 14, 1942.<br>
<br>
"(1) At one place Wheaton's International Law, a recognized American authority suggests that the view that there is any right to liberate a slave from a foreign ship in British waters cannot be supported.<br>
<br>
(2) Yet in certain cases it has been done, although cases cited on this point do not state whether it was by way of Habeas Corpus or otherwise.<br>
<br>
(3) It is submitted that Wheaton's view is wrong because foreign ships in British ports are subject to British law, and hence must be subject to British civil remedies.<br>
<br>
(4) A close reading of the decided cases cited by Wheaton clearly leads to the conclusion that once a ship is subject to British jurisdiction by virtue of its being in a British port, it makes no difference what the legal status of a slave may be by reason of any law or enactment of the home State of the foreign ship."<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
The protest submitted by Captain Fleming of the <B>Eliza Anderson</B> reads in full:<br>
<br>
United States Mail Steamship<br>
<B>Eliza Anderson</B><br>
Victoria, September 26th, 1860.<br>
<br>
Whereas a Negro boy called "Charles" the property of James Tilton, Esq. of Olympia, Washington Territory, did on the 24th inst run away from his master and secrete himself on board this vessel, and upon the fact being made known to the undersigned the said negro was placed in charge of one of the officers of the ship that he might be returned to his master and whereas upon the arrival of the ship at Victoria, a writ of Habeas Corpus was issued by Chief Justice Cameron and placed in the hands of the Sheriff of Victoria who demanded of the undersigned the delivery of the said Negro and upon the refusal of the undersigned to deliver the Negro the said Sheriff threatened to force open the room in which the Negro was confined on board of said vessel,<br>
<br>
Whereupon, the undersigned to prevent the destruction of property
and in all probability much bloodshed opened the door of said room and upon doing so the Sheriff took the Negro from on board said vessel.<br>
<br>
Now, therefore the undersigned protests against the whole proceedings as illegal and a breach of international law, and demands the immediate delivery of the said negro Charles that he may be returned to his master.<br>
<br>
John R. Fleming<br>
Captain, U.S.M. Steamship<br>
<B>Eliza Anderson.</B><br>
<br>
Sworn to and subscribed before me<br>
this 26th day of September, A.D. 1860.<br>
Signed George Pearkes, Notary Public.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
CHARLEY<br>
<br>
Ronald Carey, "How the mail went through...over, around New York to Oregon Territory...via Panama," <B>Sea Chest XI (</B> June, 1978), p. 125-127.<br>
<br>
At Olympia the mail for the lower Sound was placed aboard the steamer <B>Eliza Anderson</B> then operated on the Puget Sound Mail route by Captain John R. Fleming.  Captain Daniel T. Bradford was the other large stockholder in the vessel, and James Scranton had the mail contract.  The new system got under way in November and before mid winter rains came it was a great success....<br>
<br>
Captain Fleming was meticulous in the exchange of newspapers at each port of call and the vessel called at Victoria each week, anyway. Perhaps he would have continued to carry the mail as an accommodation, had it not been for an incident that occurred in Victoria the previous September.<br>
<br>
At that time a large colony of free Negroes resided n Victoria, and on September 25, 1860 the sheriff at Victoria was advised that a fugitive slate was being held captive aboard the <B>Eliza Anderson</B>. Armed with a writ of habeas corpus, the sheriff went aboard the <B>Anderson</B> and found the person he sought, a youth named Charley locked in the lamp room.<br>
<br>
The boarding angered Captain Fleming, who looked upon the invasion of his steamer as an international incident, even thought she was tied to a Victoria wharf at the time.  All he knew of Charley was that he was a minor, and he belonged to the household of James Tilton, the first Surveyor General of
Washington Territory. Charley had stowed away on the <B>Anderson</B> and Captain  Fleming felt it his duty to return the boy to Olympia.<br>
<br>
Actually Charley was the child of a slave girl who had belonged to Tilton's aunt in Maryland.  The boy's father was a white man, an oysterman on Chesapeake Bay. When Charley was only two years old his mother had contracted cholera, and on her death bed, at a time when she was most miserable she had said, "Missie, take care of Charley..."<br>
<br>
This had been done and the care of the boy finally fell to the older daughter of the aunt. Then, in 1853, James Tilton was appointed by the President to survey the new Territory of Washington, so that settlers could locate their claims. This was to be a free state, so Charley was turned over to tilton, with the understanding that he would be brought up in such a way that he could support himself when grown.<br>
<br>
Tilton took the responsibility seriously and was determined that Charley should learn a trade. One trade that  Tilton though particularly desirable was that of steward on a vessel such as the <B>Eliza Anderson.</B> Charley was sent to school at Fort Steilacoom and later at Olympia, but the training was of a vocational nature and Charley did not find much stimulation in the trades. As a result of his trips on the <B>Eliza Anderson</B> he had met the free negroes of Victoria and he finally stowed away on the vessel in order to join them. Before he got to Victoria, however, Captain Fleming discovered him, and locked him in the lamp locker.<br>
<br>
When the boy was taken off the vessel in Victoria, Captain Fleming charged that boarding a United States mail steamer was a violation of international law. At a hearing the next day, before the Chief Justice of Vancouver Island, Captain Fleming appeared for the defense. He said the case would probably be brought before the United States government, so he would make no statement except to enter a protest against the taking of the boy from his custody.  The protest was recorded, but the judge found Captain Fleming in violation of British law, his arrest of Charley illegal.<br>
<br>
When he returned to Olympia, moreover, Captain Fleming was surprised to learn that the Tiltons did not want Charley back. they said that they had been trying to fulfill a responsibility to the boy's mother. Now that he, himself had relieved them of that responsibility, they would like to leave things as they were.<br>
<br>
Chagrined, Captain Fleming remarked to an Olympia reporter that it was one of the rare cases in which kidnapping or stealing was acceptable to both the stealer and the stealee.<br>
<br>
Ronald Carey, "How the mail went through...over, around New York to Oregon Territory...via Panama," <B>Sea Chest.</B> XI (June, 1978) p.
125-27.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
FUGITIVE SLAVE CASE.<br>
<br>
"Fugitive slave case," <B>Pioneer and Democrat.</B> September 28, 1860.<br>
<br>
The people of Victoria, especially the black element and their sympathizers, haive been greatly exhilerated at the escape of a boy from this side, who it appears was by some negroes, who<br>
knew nothing of the facts, a slave  of  Gen.  Tilton,   Surveyor-General of this Territory.<br>
<br>
Not deeming it necessary to go  into a lengthy detail of the causes which led to the escape of the boy Charley, we will endeavor in as brief a manner as possible, to present the circumstances and influences by which the boy was surrounded, and the arguments used to wean his affections from those who have been to him a father and mother rather than master or mistress, as stated in the affidavit of the Victoria blacks, at whose instance the warrant <B>to search the Anderson</B> wao issued by Chief Justice Cammon.<br>
<br>
For the last two or three years a number of black ingrates about here, who have lost not only that respect of our citizens which was due to them as <B>niggers</B>, but were the despised of people of their own color, have been assidious in their attentions to Charley, and constant in their endeavors to bring about a rapture between the boy and his benefactors, by holding out enticements to him of so flattering a nature as might well be supposed could not be resisted by a boy of his age.<br>
<br>
The delightful prospect held out to his of profitable employment, when once he should become his own master; the feasibility of becoming a "free boy, by running away frcm his master and making his escape to Victoria, and his degendered condition while a "slave," all tended to inflame his mind, but, until the arrival of a fleshy looking darky here week before last from Victoria, were insufficient to alienate his affections from his former benefactor and dashing appearance of this decided Charley, and on Monday morning last he concluded to rush to freedom.<br>
<br>
For this purpose he was taken away by the aforesaid darky.......being temporarily employed as a worker on the Anderson, and <B>his</B> presence....... was not discovered until the steamer arrived at Steilacoom or Seattle.<br>
<br>
While the vessel as undergoing a search for a Being questioned by Capt.  Fleming as to where and how he came to be there Charley revealed all, and was set to work to pay his passage, as well as
to learn him a lesson in smuggling himself on a vessel without the knowledge or command of the officers.<br>
<br>
Nothing more was thought of him until the Captain's attention was directed to the boys possible intention if meating his escape by the Excellency Gov.  McGill, who happened to be on board with his family, which latter gentleman had received an intnuation of Charley's purpose through his little son, and it was then, and when within four miles of Victoria that he was placed in close confinement by the officers the boat, with a view of returning him to his owner.<br>
<br>
Within half an hour after arriving at this port of universal equality, a rabble of "Philantropic free blacks" and "English humanitarians" had assembled to set a head boy frre. Great was the rejoicing but short was the triumph.  Capt.  Flemming who had anticipated nothing of this sort of rescue, happening to be absent, the Anderson was in charge of her first sailer, a gentleman in no way well-disposed to the free-blacks of Victoria.<br>
<br>
With a few .... ... and many maledictions upon their heads, "philantropists and humanitarians" were sent scampering up the wharf.  The promise to "break open their heads if the attempt was made to break open the vessel's state rooms," which had been threatened by some of the mob, appeared to have some effect upon the arder of the crowd, and the "breaking doors" was not attempted.<br>
<br>
By, this time the Captain had returned. Prior, however, in his arrival aboard, a negro employed aboard as cook, the dandy negro steward of whom we have before made mention, and a Victoria negro named Jerome, (if we are not mistaken in the name,) had joined in an affidavit wherein the swore "that a negro boy, a fugitive slave who had made frequent attempts to escape and secure his freedom was then on board the Anderson, detained there against his will."<br>
<br>
Upon this: H.P. P. Crease Esq. says the Colonist, "immediately waited upon Chief Justic Cameron and applied for a writ of habeus corpus, which his lordship granted, and made returnable at 10 o'clock this morning.  The writ was handed to sheriff Naylor, and that officer, accompanied by Sert.  Carey, of the police force, went on board the Anderson, and demanded the alleged fugitive.<br>
<br>
The officers in charge of the boat stated that Capt Fleming being on shore, they did not feel justified in taking any steps in the matter.  Captain  Flemming soon made his appearance,, however, and declined delivering the fugitive-up until he had consulted an Acting Governor McGill, of Washington Territory, who is in town.<br>
<br>
The sheriff then requested that the room in which the slave was confined might be pointed out, which was done, and Sergeant Carey
left to guard the door."<br>
<br>
Thus far the Colonist is correct; but it is decidedly in error in saying that "Capt.  Flemming and Gov.  McGill subsequently consulted authorities, and arriving at the conclusion that the slave could not be held, consented to deliver him up; and at 4 o'clock, Sheriff Naylor again visited the steamer, and securing the prisoner, took him to jail."<br>
<br>
On the contrary, not only Capt.  Fleming but Gov.  McGill protested from first to last against the legality of the proceedings or the detention of the boy, but denounced the whole affair, from begiming to end, as a violation of international law, and as an insult to the flag which should have secured respect not only for the vessel, but for the property and passengers on board.<br>
<br>
He denies the right of a British court of justice annuling any engagement which is legal by our laws.  He denies its right of annuling the relationship existing beyween guardian and ward, such as existed between General Tilton and the negro boy Charley who is a minor; and he very much question the propriety of issuing a writ of habes corpus upon so frivolous testimony as was produced before Justice Cameron.<br>
<br>
The witnesses before him testify that "the boy is a slave of Gen.  Tilton." The truth is, he is not and never was.  The witnesses swear "Charley was made frequent attempts to escape." The facts are, he is welcome to any additional liberty he may be supposed to be at present invested with, and it is hoped he will stay away.<br>
<br>
But it is not true that he has never before made such attempt.  It is his first, though his opportunities for effecting his escape have been innumerable.  And, lastly, the Governor protests against search being instituted upon American vessels engaged in the merchant serrices between here and Victoria, under the pretence of asserting whether they are engaged in the slave trade, <B>under</B> <B>any circumstances</B>.<br>
<br>
It is only owing to the absence of a proper naval force that his conduct on that occassion as warranted the British journals in <B>proclaiming</B> our Governor's assent the recent outrage.  Had there been a United States vessel of war there the time, the affair would not have so terminated.  But, under the circumstances, we had to succumb to superior force.<br>
<br>
Before leaving Victoria Capt.  Fleming filed the following protest against the action of Chief Justice Cameron which he requested be filed with the proceedings in the case.  As the wlole affair will be submitted at once for the consideration of our goverrment, we defer further comment, only wondering what the next act of British aggression may be to which our citizens must
quietly submit, and what the next insult our government will be submissively pocket.<br>
<br>
U.S.M.S.S. ELIZA ANDERSON<br>
<br>
Victoria, Sepi. 26th, 1860<br>
<br>
Whereas,, a negro boy called Charles, the property of James Tilton, Esq., of Olympia, Washington Territory, did on the 24th inst., run away from his master, and secrete himself on board this vessel, and upon the fact being known to the undersigned, the said negro was placed in charge of one of the officers of the ship, that he might be returned to his master; and<br>
<br>
Whereas, upon the arrival of ship at Victoria,, a writ of habeas corpus was issued by Chief Justice Cameron and placed in the hands of the sheriff of Victoria, who demanded of the undersigned the delivery of the said negro, and upon the refusal of the undersigned to deliver the said negro the said sheriff threatened to force open the room which the negro was confined on board of said vessel, whereupon the undersigned, to prevent destruction of property, and in all probability much bloodshed opened the door of said room,, and upon doing so, the sheriff took the negro from on board said vessel.<br>
<br>
Now therefore, the undersigned protests against the whole proceedings as illegal and a breach of international law, and demands the innediate delivery of the said negro Charles, that he may be returned to his master.<br>
<br>
"Fugitive slave case," <B>Pioneer and Democrat.</B> September 28, 1860.<br>
<br>
