 - <B>Unsettling Events</B><br>
<h1>Slavery-York</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
Sunday, September 7, 1975, The Sunday Olympian<br>
<br>
Indians Loved The Black Explorer York<br>
by Dorothy McWilliams<br>
<br>
In the autumn of 1805 a small party of explorers reached the Pacific Ocean by land. Their journey had begun at St. Louis, Mo., and ended at the mouth of the Columbia River in the Pacific Northwest. Of all the glorious adventures told of western heroes, no story is more exciting than that of the Lewis and Clark expedition. The "Corps of Discovery," as the group was called, consisted of two leaders, Captains Meriwether Lewis and William<br>
Clark; three sergeants; 23 soldiers; two French interpreters; a woman and her baby; and a Negro, the bondservant of Capt. Clark. The leaders and Sacajawea, the Indian woman, have been remembered in stories and by statues, but it was the intensely black Negro, York, who was the most popular and best remembered by the Indians.<br>
<br>
Although all members of the expedition were liked, none was so royally welcomed by the tribes as York. In a time when many Indians had never before seen a white man, a black man was still more of an oddity. York was young, large and handsome. He was a smiling; understanding, and pleasant person. His popularity was, in part, due to his pigmentation. With moistened fingers, the Indians rubbed his skin, wondering if he was not painted. They yanked his hair to see if it was really his own. Some of the bolder Indians asked him if he had really been born black. But even though he arrived as an oddity, York departed each village as a friend.<br>
<br>
Several times, both Lewis and Clark used the Indians' natural curiosity about a black man to gain help. When the expedition needed horses from the Shoshone tribe, Lewis was able to interest them in a trade only by telling the chief he would be shown a blackskinned man. As it turned out, Sacajawea was the chief's sister, so the trade was easily completed.<br>
<br>
There was more than York's color that made him so successful with the Indians. He, alone, could understand that the patterns by which the Indians lived had great importance to them. He could help the leaders see that Indian ways ought not be trespassed upon by "foreigners" who were just passing through their lands. York had the ability to settle any problems with Indians quickly and quietly by treating them as equals, no more - no less.<br>
<br>
Some historians have called the Lewis and Clark Expedition "The Dancing Explorers" and "The Road Show". It is true that singing and dancing were popular, both with the explorers and the Indians.<br>
<br>
A violin was packed even when food, medicine and guns had to be left behind.<br>

When the camp fiddler struck up a merry tune, York's dancing never failed to please. Once, however, when he performed for the Teton Sioux, York became so carried away by their applause that he, started dancing on his hands. This action made the usually tolerant Capt. Clark frown sternly.<br>
<br>
As a wilderness explorer, York was without flaw. He was an excellent shot, one of the strongest when it came to pulling or carrying, and, so the men wrote, by far the best cook in the outfit. He was often chosen to accompany the leaders when a small group explored a new river. He was with Clark and four others when the Willamette River in Oregon was first explored.<br>
<br>
There is no indication that York suffered any abuse from other members of the party. Each member depended on the others for safety and survival. At times the captains turned the party into a committee-of-the-whole when everyone's opinion was heard. York and  Sacajawea had their say then and were included in the voting, the same as any other member. A replacement for Sgt. Charles Floyd, who died of an apparent ruptured appendix, was elected in this way.<br>
<br>
Not much is known of what happened in later years to some of the expedition members. About York we know even less. This is because writers in the early 1800s had little interest in the accomplishments of a black man. All that is known for sure is that, of all the men among the "Elkskin Trailblazers", York was the only one not rewarded in some way by the U.S.<br>
<br>
In recent times research has been done to try to learn more about York, which is the only name we have for Clark's slave. What has been found may not be fact, but evidence indicates that shortly after Capt. Clark married Julia Hancock, York was given his freedom. The captain is supposed to have bought wagons and mules and set York up in the freight business, hauling goods between Nashville, Tenn., and Richmond, Va. It seems that after a few years, the former slave left the business.<br>
<br>
Some writers say York rejoined Capt. Clark and died in Missouri. Other writers say that rumors brought back to the settlements along the Missouri River told of a black man "having the time of his life" as chief of a Comanche tribe which roamed the Great Plains.<br>
<br>
No matter how the first black visitor to Washington ended his days, the indians here and all along his route affectionately remembered the "Great White Father's" black ambassador, York.<br>
<br>
<br>&#169; Copyright The Tacoma Public Library, 1996 -- All Rights Reserved<br><hr>
