<img src="../unset.gif" align=middle>Tacoma Public Library - NorthWest Reference Databases
 - <B>Unsettling Events</B><br>
<h1>Shanghaiing</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
<B>SHANGHAIING.<br>
</B><br>
<br>
-------------<br>
<br>
Arthur H. Redman, "Shanghaiing times in Astoria," <B>Oregon Coast.</B> (November-December, 1991), p. 57-59. (il).<br>
<br>
Accounts of some kidnappings or attempted ones, including a minister almost taken from his own church.<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
A CAPTAIN USUALLY GOT HIS CREW IN PORT TOWNSEND<br>
<br>
(Lucile McDonald, "A captain usually got his crew in Port Townsend's uninhibited past," <B>Seattle Times.</B> September 9, 1962.)<br>
<br>
A long with its recent efforts at civic rejuvenation, the city of Port Townsend has become shanghai conscious. Not only have road signs advertised that the nefarious traffic once flourished on the water front, but a new book, "Shanghaiing Days," by a San Francisco author, Richard H. Dillon, cites facts and names from Port Townsend's uninhibited past.<br>
<br>
Dillon's source largely was in files of the Coast Seamen's Journal in the 1890s. Several residents of the city still recall incidents of which the author speaks and records in the Jefferson County Court House add the stamp of veracity to the stories.<br>
<br>
A plant in the county surveyor's office shows the waterfront of 1871, with its several wharves extending into the harbor and lodging houses and bars built on the approaches, supported on pilings.<br>
<br>
Some of the brick buildings on the main street had rear exist a little above high tide level on the beach to facilitate moving of cargo rowed ashore from sailing vessels or towed in on scows. If these doors were used for less conventional business, such as the hustling away of stupefied sailors, it was not surprising.<br>
<br>
The practice of shanghaiing was regarded as essential to the manning of ships in a day when going to sea was one of the least pleasant ways of earning a living.<br>
<br>
John Lewis, 77, who was in the shipping business from his youth, lives within sight of the roadstead where vessels used to drop ballast and await crews.  His father, Wyndham Lewis, arrived in Port Townsend in 1888 and became partner in a shipping agency with
Oscar Klocker, Norwegian born vice consul for Great  Britain.<br>
<br>
Klocker is on Dillon's list of those with a hand in the shanghaiing business. Lewis says that Klocker's activities included making deals with his father's business competitors and this reached a point where the partnership had to be broken up.  Wyndham Lewis bought out Klocker's interest.<br>
<br>
The connection, however, gave young Jack Lewis an insight into many aspects of manning ships. Seamen reported at a long counter in the firm's office upstairs in the C.C. Bailey Building to have ship's articles read to them, so that they understood where they were bound and what pay they were to receive.<br>
<br>
"At least ten per cent in those days, went on board without the reading of any articles, " Lewis said. "Sometimes men who did go through the formality were forced into it. Boarding runners carried blackjacks and I would see them on the stairs beating men on the head. We tried to bar the runners from coming up to our office.<br>
<br>
"We lived in the white house below my present home and I remember men arriving at all hours of the night to tell  Father they did not want to go to sea. If he learned they had been shanghaied in Tacoma  or some other port, sometimes he would help them get away to a ranch near Chimacum from which they could find the way home on foot.<br>
<br>
"Many boats from the Upper Sound anchored here until their crews were filled up. Klocker would get out, which he was not supposed to do, and sign on men brought down by other boats. They'd be enticed off one ship with promises only to be shifted to another bark."<br>
<br>
Master practitioners in the shanghai art were Maxwell Levy and Ed Sims, also listed in the Dillon book. One old resident believes they arrived in Port Townsend about 1885 expressly to engage in the boarding house business for the purpose of supplying ships.<br>
<br>
Max kept close watch on the establishment while Ed had other fish to fry. Their boarding house was on the waterfront in a brick building on directly across from the City Hall.<br>
<br>
"I once used that building," related Lockhart. "The water came to the back end of it and a dock went out behind. They didn't need any tunnels to carry men out there. A door went from the basement to the beach, but it was easier to take fellows out to the dock.<br>
<br>
"There were no engines in the small boats that went to the ships. The boarding houses had strong young fellows to pull the oars. They could come and go quietly enough."<br>
<br>
Harry Cotten says early in the morning after his arrival in town in 1903 he saw shanghaiing done in plain daylight. Two men were dragging a third to a boat on the beach. Cotton asked if he were dead and was told, "No, Knockout drops."
"Isn't shanghaiing against the law?" he asked.<br>
<br>
He received a profane answer to the effect that there was no low in this country.<br>
<br>
Cotton appealed to a police man a block away. "He took a big chaw from his tobacco and told me it was none of my business.  Acquaintances to whom I reported this encounter warned me, ' You'd better pay attention to what he said.'<br>
<br>
"There were twenty-seven sailing ships in the bay that day and they were buying sailors."<br>
<br>
Lockhart recalled that runners usually were careful not to pick up town boys in the shanghai net. "But if fellows got a little wild and went to the wrong part of town, sometimes they disappeared and next thing the family would receive a letter from Australia."<br>
<br>
The tale is told of a certain resident who could not resist a drink. One day he went up Water Street on an errand and did not return home for a year. It became a habit with him and for about fifteen more years in the 18802 and 1890s whenever he did get back to Port Townsend, sooner or later he would wake up again on a ship off Cape Flattery.<br>
<br>
Lewis remembers when seventeen saloons were on the harbor side alone of Water Street. Large sections of blocks on the 1891 map were labeled "female houses." The approximately 350 women available to entertain the seafaring element often acted as bait for the unwary. Mariners would leave the parlor houses, cribs, dance halls and saloons with pockets picked, reeling from knockout drops in a drink. The Port Townsend Salmon Club and Cotton's shipyard occupy a waterfront area where Tom Saunders had a dance hall which contributed liberally to the supply  of shanghaied men.<br>
<br>
The Pacific Bar on Union Wharf also was reputed skilled in dispensing deep-sleep liquor. It was a simple matter for a whitehall boat to wait underneath a trap door in the wharf behind the bar for men to be dropped down and taken to the ships.<br>
<br>
Lewis spoke of a man named Gunderson, boarding house runner for Sims and Levy. With him usually was Chilean Pete.<br>
<br>
"One night with binoculars from my house I saw them going up the chains of a British ship lying at the ballast ground and a few minutes later they were coming off the ship," Lewis related. " The captain had given the mate his revolver and told him to go after the boarding house runners, who were promising the crew double money to desert. If the men left the ship that way they sacrificed the pay due them.<br>
<br>
"I heard bang, bang, and went down to see what was going on. The boarding house had stairs leading to the water and when I got there the lower steps were covered with blood and hair. Max Levy was
there and he wanted me to run and get Dr. House and tell him Chilean Pete was shot through the head. Gunderson was shot through the shoulder. Captain Jones had taken strong means to get his crew back out of their hands.<br>
<br>
"My father had fifty-five company contracts to load  ships on Puget Sound and Klocker held his consular job because of the shipping agency.<br>
<br>
"One, when Dad had gone on a trip to England, where he was born, and Klocker was away, I was left in charge. The fellows wee ready to take advantage of me on account of my age, 18 or 19, and  hat is when I learned a lot about Klocker's activities and many other things.<br>
<br>
"At 2 o'clock one morning Max Levy called on the telephone to say he wanted me. There was a mutiny on the British ship <B>Clan MacKenzie.</B> He sent a horse drawn cab to fetch me. I put on a derby hat and tried to look dignified as an acting consul. Max had his whitehall boat and rowers ready to take me out to the ship.<br>
<br>
"A towboat was lying alongside of her waiting to take the ship beyond Cape Flattery, but it was not moving until the mutiny was settled.<br>
<br>
"I climbed the Jacob's ladder and saw sailors walking around on the deck. The captain was locked in his room and the mate was tied in the forecastle.<br>
<br>
"Max announced that the British vice consul had arrived. I went in the cabin and said I'd talk to one man at a time. When the first one came in I asked what was the trouble and reminded him he had signed the articles before me.<br>
<br>
"The big fellow said, " I don't remember getting aboard this ship and here I am going to Durban, South Africa. I need some clothes, too."<br>
<br>
"I told him he had been listed with the boarding house master's association which required an advance out of seamen's pay to furnish clothing.<br>
<br>
"Let's see what you've got!" I said. " He brought his bag and dumped it on the floor. It contained a woman's corset, old women's shoes and other rubbish enough to fill the bag. That was what he had been supplied by the boarding house masters.<br>
<br>
"I told the fellow he was right to object and turned to the next poor devil. He'd been given an old blanket, mismatched shoes, and old hats in his bag. We went down the line of twenty-six men, none of them properly outfitted.<br>
<br>
"When I saw this, I told Max, 'This ship is not going to sail until these fellows are outfitted properly.' They were taken ashore
though it was Sunday morning, and Al Newman, manager of the Red Front Clothing Company, which outfitted for the masters association, and his clerk were called. I stayed until the men were given everything they wanted and warned Maxie not to let it happen again. However it did... many times.<br>
<br>
"The boarding house masters' association was paid ninety dollars for each man it supplied and received twenty dollars advance for outfitting them. There was a temptation to keep all the money they could."<br>
<br>
Lewis, who was in the revenue cutter service in 1906 and 1907 said there was no incentive to conceal shanghaiing activities by any devise as elaborate as a tunnel.<br>
<br>
"Everything was above board. If you shanghaied or brought in opium, that was considered part of your business. I've seen a bunch of men escorted down Front Street with a lodging house fellow to help hold them up.<br>
<br>
"Runners were mighty careful never to shanghai an Indian or the'd have had the federal government after them.<br>
<br>
"I saw one tremendous, awful fight after a big fellow from Butte had been liquored in Seattle, and woke up on board a ship bound for Hong Kong. He appealed to me to get him off, but when I couldn't do anything for him he said he'd get even. Two years later he got off the steamer <B>Alice Gertrude</B> in Port Townsend and went into Patsy Lennon's Pacific Bar and I saw him looking for Sims and Levy.<br>
<br>
Each of them was accompanied by a runner and when the fellow found them, the four pounced on him. I asked the chief of police to interfere in the fight, but he wouldn't. He was said to be getting a rake-off from the shanghai business."<br>
<br>
Shanghaiing thrived when Port Townsend streets were dirt and plank roads. As the town grew, concrete sidewalks replaced wooden ones on stilts. They were shored with concrete walls for support and the space underneath resembled tunnels, with hatches opening from the sidewalks for unloading freight into basements.  That they were useful for shanghaiing is doubted by elder citizens, who say there was no need for concealment under ground.<br>
<br>
Jail records in the sheriff's office from 1891 to 1906 contain long lists of incarcerations for stabbing, robbery, smuggling, assault with a deadly weapon, ship desertion, murder, and insubordination aboard ship.<br>
<br>
Citizens in that rowdy period regarded the port so infested with undesirable characters they wondered why they should object if drugs were slipped in the drinks and the sinners were sent to repent on the open seas.<br>
<br>
Too often the real story was different and it was an unwary
sailor's hard luck to be ashore in Port Townsend in the unsavory years when it was a crimp's paradise.<br>
<br>
(Lucile McDonald, "A Captain Usually Got His Crew in Port Townsend's Uninhibited Past," <B>Seattle Times.</B> September 9, 1961.<br>
<br>
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++SHANGHAIING<br>
<br>
Peter Simpson, "Shanghaiing," <B>City of Dreams, a guide to Port Townsend,</B> Port Townsend: The Bay Press, 1986, p. 242-148.<br>
<br>
Max Levy was a merchant. Although ostensibly a clothier, his real commodity was the flesh beneath the fabric.  With partner Ed Sims, Levy owned a seamen's boarding house, a place where sailors could stay between voyages, where their needs would be met.  They were given a bed, food, and even pocket money for tobacco and liquor.  All on the cuff.<br>
<br>
When the bill came due, as it always did, it was "on the tide.  " When a ship needed a crew, its master would contact Levy or one of the other "crimps" that worked Port Townsend's waterfront.  For a fee of thirty dollars per head, plus up to three months advance on each sailor's wages, Levy would fill the ship's complement with the indebted bodies from his hotel.<br>
<br>
Those who balked were met by Levy's "runners," specialists whose job it was to render sailors compliant.  The ship then sailed out on the next tide.  When business was slow, Levy worked the other side of the fence, running crews off ships so that the master would be forced to buy another.  He once took three complete crews off the ship America before it was able to clear the harbor.  Until the practice was banned after the turn of the century, operations like Levy's were routine, an accepted part of life in every major seaport.<br>
<br>
What was also routine, but considerably less legitimate, was shanghaiing.  When not enough men were available through legal means to fill out a ship's crew, Levy or his competitors Tom Saunders and Limey Dirk would dispatch their runners to the brothels, called cribs, and bars that bordered the waterfront.<br>
<br>
The next morning a fcw hapless farmhands and loggers would probably catch their first view of Cape Flattery's west face.  Their victims were carefully picked: Professional sailors were always the first choice, soldiers next, local residents and Indians were almost always avoided.  The method might be as subtle as a few free drinks or as vulgar as back-alley sapping.<br>
<br>
In recent years, a popular misconception evolved that shanghai victims were carried to the beach and a waiting dory by way of a
series of underground passages.  The shanghai tunnels, as they were called, were said to have been built expressly for the trade.  In reality they were no more than vaulted sidewalks, added to facilitate access to the basements of the downtown buildings.  As 
romantic as the notion is, <B>it </B>scems unlikely that more than incidental use was made of them.  Generally, there was no need for such contrivances.  The greased palm has always been less capital 
intensive than underground  construction, and it involves far less organization.<br>
<br>
By most accounts, shanghaiing usually took place in one of the seventeen saloons or dozen brothels that lined the waterfront.  Most of them had direct water access through their back entrances.  A few, built on docks, had trapdoors for the disposal of garbage.  Through them an unconscious man could easily bc lowered to a waiting skiff.<br>
<br>
The sailors did not always take the abuse and manipulation lying down.  A particularly nasty operation was being run by Limey Dirk at the Pacific Bar on Union Wharf, Dirk was a notorious bully and shanghaier, besides which his food was bad.  The Sailors' Union of the Pacific organized a boycott and, when that was not enough, followed it with a campaign of stone throwing.<br>
<br>
Every night, under cover of darkness, the sailors would gather near the brothels across the street from Limey's and lob rocks through his windows.  Each night Dirk would charge outside, a pistol in cach hand, shooting at anything that moved.  Fortunately, he was a lousy shot and did not hit anyone.  After several days of this guerrilla war, one of the stones hit Dirk on the head, knocking him unconscious.  The sailors thought they had killed him, but the next day he was back at work.<br>
<br>
Peter Simpson, "Shanghaiing," <B>City of Dreams, a guide to Port Townsend.</B> Port Townsend: The Bay Press, 1986, p. 207-08.<br>
<br>
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
SHANGHAIING<br>
<br>
Stewart Holbrook, "Those bodies on the Flying Prince," <B>Wildmen, wobblies and whistle punks.</B> Corvallis: Oregon State University Press, 1992, p. 185-189.<br>
<br>
The time was late in 1893.  The Flying Prince, a big sailing ship of British register, was in Portland harbor, loaded to the gunnals with Douglas fir lumber, and ready to sail except for one thing; her crew, the captain figured, was short twenty-two men.  He put the matter up to Bunco Kelly.  Times were hard, he said, but he promised Kelly $30 a head for any men he could put aboard, before
morning daylight.<br>
<br>
Bunco made the usual rounds, starting at Liverpool Liz' place, going on to Erikson's saloon, then to Mary Cook's.  Next he started for the South End of the waterfront.  It was an evil night.  The driving rain beat down upon the squat, rather sinister figure as it moved along Front Street.<br>
<br>
Just before he reached Morrison Street, where stood the Snug Harbor saloon, he noticed an open trap door in the sidewalk. (Portland neither had nor has alleys such as most cities have; deliveries of merchandise and such things are often made through trap doors in the sidewalks, that lead to cellars.)<br>
<br>
Now, doors such as this should not be left open at night.  And besides, Bunco Kelly was no man to pass up an open door without investigation.  Moreover, a peculiar odor emanated from this particular trap door.  It welled up out of the the blackness beneath, pungent, powerful, strange.<br>
<br>
Bunco Kelly, whose knowledge of chemicals was limited to the ingredients of Kelly's Comforters, a knock-out mixture he had used with great success, thought he had smelled something like this aroma before, but for the life of him he couldn't say where.  He sniffed carefully.  He did not like the smell, but he was a curious man.  He prepared to descend into the dark.<br>
<br>
"In those days," Bunco Kelly later told Spider Johnson, who in turn told me, "in those days, I always carried a small dark lantern under my coat.  I got it out and lighted, and threw a beam below.  I couldn't see nothing but the little ladder disappearing into the darkness." Bunco was game, however, and he went slowly down into what he described as the damnedest reek he ever hoped to suffer.<br>
<br>
He saw at once that the room was not wholly in darkness.  A candle spluttered on a keg, and the scene its dim light revealed to Bunco Kelly was one he never forgot.  "My hair," he related to Spider Johnson, "was pretty thin, but the few hairs I had stood up and pushed my cap into the air."<br>
<br>
On the floor near the ladder lay a man.  He was alive but not in the best of health.  He was gasping, and every little while made as if to clutch at his throat.  "What's the matter?" Bunco asked him.  The man seemed to hear.  He lifted his head a bit, tried to say something, but couldn't.<br>
<br>
Bunco now let his dark lantern play around the room.  Propped against one of many barrels were three men doubtless corpses,
Bunco surmised.  Their mouths were open, and so were their eyes, but they were not seeing anything.  Lying or dropping in odd postures all over the place were other men.  Kelly counted 24 all told.<br>
<br>
Going from one to another, placing his hand on their brows and listening, he came to the conclusion, hurriedly, that at least a third of them still lived.  Still, he could not be sure, for he thought that as he watched one of the men gave a deep heave and died.<br>
<br>
"I was pretty startled at first," Kelly admitted later in something of a conservative statement.  But he got his nerve back quickly.  He turned his attention to one of the barrels, from the bung of which a liquid was dripping.  He caught some of it in his hand.  It was very cold.  He sniffed it and it rocked him back on his heels.<br>
<br>
In fact, the sniff nearly floored him.  He quickly went up the ladder to the street.  The air soon cleared his dizziness, and his usually quick mind, "By God!" he remarked to nobody in particular, as the true significance of the business struck him, "them stiffs has been drinking undertaker's dope."<br>
<br>
It was true enough, too.  Johnson & Sons' Undertaking Parlors were just next door to the Snug Harbor saloon.  These men had broken into what they thought was the saloon's cellar, which happened to be the cellar of Johnson & Sons.  The embalming fluid had proved too stout even for men accustomed to the vilest booze.<br>
<br>
Without stopping to draw a moral from the sardonic tragedy, or even to notify the police, Bunco went into sudden and efficient action.  He closed the big trap door, lest some watchman find it open, and then tore for the North End of town as fast as his short legs could carry him against wind and rain.  He went directly to<br>
<br>
The Mariners' Rest, as he chose to call the old warehouse he had converted into a boarding place for sailors.  From here he sent a boy on the dead run to fetch a cab.  He roused four or five old friends, bar-flies whom he permitted to sleep in his place, and bade them gird their loins.  "No sleep in the house tonight boys," he said.<br>
<br>
Back came the boy with a cab.  Kelly and his crew piled into it and sped away over the cobblestones, stopping at the Fashion Livery & Feed Stable, where Bunco asked for five more cabs to hurry to Front and Morrison Streets.<br>
<br>
It was now well after midnight.  The storm was increasing, which
pleased Kelly; there was not likely to be so much as a cop on the street.  The rain had turned to sleet that stung, for the wind was rising steadily.  It was just the right kind of night for the apex in the professional career of Bunco Kelly.<br>
<br>
Dark lantern in hand, Kelly led his crew down the ladder, advising them to breathe as little as possible.  The stench at first stopped a couple of the helpers, but Kelly threatened to toss them out of his boarding house if they didn't perform like men.  "Briskly, now, lads, briskly," Kelly commanded.  "We'll lift these boys up the ladder and put them into the cabs."<br>
<br>
It was hard work, and it went all too slowly until Kelly<br>
suddenly became generous, "Five dollars in gold to each of you," he told his aides, "as soon as these sailors are aboard ship." The promise proved a fine stimulant.  Heaving with a will, the Kelly men passed the dead and dying up the ladder, and into the waiting cabs.  Up came Kelly.<br>
<br>
He didn't even stop to close the trap but leaped into the first cab.  "Drive," he told the hackman, "as fast as you can to Ainsworth dock." And away went a procession that would have pleased Ambrose Bierce, and E. A. Poe no more than it did Joseph Kelly-sparks from hooves of wheels lighting the night, the dead rolling against the living, the wind howling across the harbor, and the hulk of the Flying Prince, looming darker than the night, standing there at dock, awaiting twenty-two able sea-men.<br>
<br>
By half-past one fourteen corpses and ten men who were very ill had been stowed away snugly in the Flying Prince's forecastle, bound out for China.<br>
<br>
Bunco Kelly had to explain to the skipper, which he did plausibly, how he had come by his men in one batch; and to argue with the skipper that he had asked for 24, not 22, sailors.  The captain was so well pleased to leave with a full crew he did not argue.  "I never saw so many men drunk at one time," he remarked, but he counted out $30 each for two dozen men.<br>
<br>
"Yes, sir," agreed Kelly genially, "they are godawful drunk, and getting them so cost me a pretty penny." Putting the cash into his pocket he bade the skipper farewell.  "And don't forget, sir," he said, "Bunco Kelly is a man who always keeps his promises."<br>
<br>
At dawn the Flying Prince cast off and headed down the Columbia for the open sea.  Long before noon the first mate made the hideous discovery in the forecastle.  The ship put in at Astoria, where the corpses were removed.  Astoria newspapermen soon had the story on the wires.
The sensation following the discovery of the dead men made a great rumpus in Portland.  Preachers remonstrated that the city was in a moral decay.  They attacked the politicians and the police. <B>There </B>was the<B> </B>usual police shake up, with a few cops being moved here and there, and the chief ordered strict regulation of sailors' boarding houses.  Kelly, Sullivan and other Portland crimps were merely questioned about the load of corpses.  Nobody was charged with murder or anything else.<br>
<br>
Stewart Holbrook, "Those bodies on the Flying Prince," <B>Wild men, wobblies and whistle punks.</B> Corvallis: Oregon State University Press, 1992, p. 185-189.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
PORT TOWNSEND AGAIN.<br>
<br>
Gordon Newell, "Maritime events of 1903," <B>H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest.</B> Seattle: Superior, 1966, p. 93.<br>
<br>
Despite the increased success of Andrew Furuseth and the Sailors' Union in gaining recognition for seamen of the American merchant fleet and in reducing the power of the boardinghouse keepers and crimps, there was still much discontent among seafaring men in 1903, as evidenced by the following direct quotation from the Coast Seamen's Journal <B>of </B>April 15 of that year:<br>
<br>
"DOINGS  IN  TOWNSEND"<br>
<br>
"On Sunday, 28 March, there was another good time in Townsend.  The British ship RAJAH shipped a crew from the 'prominent business men,' Sims and Levy.  After the men had signed they were called in to 'square up.' None had been longer in the place than two days, so they at least expected to get some clothing.  In answer to their query on this score, they were punched and kicked and otherwise misused, for daring to presume that they should get any part of the money they each had to work and brave the dangers of their calling for.  It was a sight to see these men going into the boat to go aboard, bleeding and nearly smashed to a jelly.  There is a common supposition among people living in the Northern States that the slaves were abused sometimes by inhuman drivers; yet the fact goes un -noticed that there are people living within the town limits and called 'prominent business men' who abuse other human beings, to wit, deepwater sailors, worse than ever a slave was treated, even to such an extent as to cause people who have seen the treatment these human beings receive  to say that it is impossible to treat them worse.  This country has a society for the preventionof cruelty to animals. I only wish the sailor came under that head,sothat he might get some redress.<br>

(S) P. H. Von Den Berg<br>
<br>
Gordon Newell, "Maritime events of 1903," <B>H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest.</B> Seattle: Superior, 1966, p. 93.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
SHANGHAIING IN PORT TOWNSEND.<br>
<br>
Gordon Newell, "Maritime events of 1906," H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest. Seattle: Superior, 1966. p. 129.<br>
<br>
A story indicative of the type of men engaged in the trade of crimping is told by a classmate of a runners son at Fort Townsend High School.  Upon one occasion when the firm for which he worked was short one body for delivery to an outgoing vessel of such ill repute that all experienced seamen shunned her like the plague, the runner, Charles Gunderson,  went to the school and took his son from class on some pretext, delivering him to the shipmaster to fill out the quota.<br>
<br>
In later years Gunderson shanghaied a cripple with only one arm, who had a steel hook in lieu of the missing hand.  Surviving the voyage, the one armed man returned to Port Townsend, his steel hook sharpened to a razor edge, and proceeded to so maim Gunderson that he spent the rest of his life as a semi-invalid.<br>
<br>
Gordon Newell, "Maritime events of 1906," H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest. Seattle: Superior, 1966. p. 129.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
SHANGAIING<br>
<br>
Denise M. Alborn, "Crimping and Shanghaiing on the Columbia River," <B>The Oregon Historical Quarterly.</B> LXIII(Fall, 1992), p. 263-288.<br>
<br>
Shanghaiing! The curse of these streets it was.  The tunnels swallowed us up like whales.  It took us months to get our sea<br>
legs and years to get back home to find that blasted no-good crimp that got us into this God-forsaken mess.  We swore that when we hit town the dock along Burnside-we'd find him."'<br>
<br>
For at least three decades, beginning in the 1870s, a profitable and quasi-legal racket run by men called "crimps" governed the Portland and Astoria waterfronts.  Crimps rubbed elbows with politicians and important society people; they gave the Columbia
River a vile reputation on an international scale; and they left behind dramatic legends of sailors shanghaied and brutalized.<br>
<br>
A close study of these legends reveals considerable factual evidence of such notorious waterfront pracfices.  And trough as evidence we can begin to understand how the duration and extent of the crimps' power rested on a combination of local and national circumstances, supply and demand, and the prolonged decline of the age of sail.<br>
<br>
The word crimp originated as a British slang term for "agent," but camc to refer specifically to the middlemen who provided sailors to man vessels.  Merchant-marine crimping matured as a counterpart to the British naval impressment and eventually spread to ports around the world.  As the crimps and their recruiting tactics grew morc ruthless, the word gained derogatory implications.<br>
<br>
At best, crimps were opportinists parasitically feeding off the poorly regulated system of seamen's employment, turning maritime wage conventions and desertion laws to their advantage; at worst, they were cutthroat shanghaiers, supplying kidnapped landsmen in lieu of skilled sailors when labor was in short supply.<br>
<br>
The verb shanghai ("to put aboard a ship by force"), according to various authorities as well as common sense, derives from a frequent destination of the ships so manned (the "coast-wise," or domestic, trade never suffcrcd from the shortage of seamen chronic to the deep-sea trade). U.S. law defined shanghaiing as the employment of any sailor who had not signed ship's articles or who had signed unwillingly or unsoberly.<br>
<br>
Contemporaries often applied the terms "crimp," "shanghaier," and sailors boarding house keeper" interchangeably, as many crimps owned boarding houses.  These establishments extended credit to seamen and, in return, reserved the prerogative of "shipping them"-that is, arranging their next berth.<br>
<br>
"If it had not been for the boarding-house, who is going to take care of these people and feed them?" asked a Tacoma keeper at the Merchant Marine Commission hearings.  "They would be on the streets; they would be in jail.  I have no way of getting any money out of them except taking the risk of shipping them"- and then collecting their debtor's wages in advance to cover costs, as well as a finder's fee from the captain (called  blood money by critics).<br>
<br>
Many contemporaries, however, accused the crimps of collecting from the sailors for imagined debts.  "Thcre is no doubt that much of the advance money of $25 a sailor is pretty near all profit to the boardinghouse proprictors," a Norwegian consul told the press; he knew of sailors who had to pay the advance even though "they never spent a day at the boarding house.<br>

In the 1890s two months wages constituted the maximum legal advance.  Alfred Clark, shanghaied from a riverboat party onto a squarerigger in 1891, later recalled exactly how the crimps exploited this law.  A Portland crimp signed him on as an able-bodied seaman, or A.B. (experienced), and took sixty dollars, the two-month advance.<br>
<br>
When it became apparent that Clark had never been to sea before, his employment status changed to ordinary seaman, or o.s., at half the salary: four months at fifteen dollars per month, all of which had gone to the crimp on shore.  The unfortunate Clark docked at Lc Havre, France, with no salary coming to him.<br>
<br>
This account highlights several of the reasons why early seamen's union activists viewed the problem of crimping abuses as a labor-law issue.  For exaniple, maritime law required no proof of a seaman's A.B. status upon employment; nonrelations were permitted to harnest advanced wage allotments and although a law of 1872 decreed that sailors should sign ship's articles <B>in </B>front of an official, inadequate provision was made for enforcement.<br>
<br>
Other statutes left seamen vulnerable to creditors, allowing captains to issue shore leave without pay, to withhold pay for a period after discharge, and to revoke the wages of deserters.  A contemporary assessment maintained that the strapped crewmen, in ports of call turned to creditors "who preyed upon his necessities and who went to great measures to induce desertion in order to have a dependent debtor and another hand to sea to the next ship."<br>
<br>
The problem of desertion was inextricably tied to that of crimping in the contemporary mind.  Union rhetoric maintained that if seamen gained the right to terminate their contracts at any port and collect wages due, they could lodge where they liked, ship when they liked, and the crimps' source of revenue would dry up.<br>
<br>
Failing to change the convention of the round-trip contract, reformers succeeded around the turn of the century in passing laws that forbade unauthorized persons from boarding vessels and enticing men ashore.<br>
<br>
The crux of the matter of desertion, as explained by a British consul in Portland, lay in "the unknown disposition of the sailor, on arrival in port, after months of repression and discomfort," to be eager for shore; to run into excesses, a much-to-be-deplored, yet by no means unnatural propensity."<br>
<br>
The official went on to say that most deserters break even in the long run: "Sympathy is wasted on the larger proportion of men who desert, as by their practice of leaving at every port and reshipping with an advance they forfeit practically nothing." But, the consul urged, the protection of law should bc extended to "the really honest sailor," who, by combined efforts of the captain and crimp, "Is made so uncomfortable on board that he is quite ready
to desert.<br>
<br>
It became almost a waterfront maxim that the captains of ships cooperated with the crimps for their own gain.  A handbill printed by the Portland Chamber of Commerce in 1898 raged that<br>
instead of deserting, all these seamen, with few exceptions, were enticed, decoyed, or by threats and infimidations forced from their vessels by a syndicate of crimps ... and this too often with the knowledge and consent and even the connivance of captains and owners, who adopt these dishonorable means of voiding contracts usually made for three years, and thus profit by the forfeiture of the entire wages of the seamen.<br>
<br>
Norwegian Consul Endre M. Cederbergh charged that the captains profited morc directly, collecting a payoff of $5.00 to  $7.50 for each man they bought from the crimps with the shipowner's money.  "That the captains receive this rebate is no secret," he claimed.<br>
<br>
The skippers themselves, of course, told a different story.  They maintaincd that vast sums of moncy went toward bribing the men off the ships, and while captains tried to stem the tide, Portland was a lawless place that gave them no assistance.  A Captain Morcau informed the chamber of commerce that the crimps promiscd his men thirty-five dollars apiece to desert; only two did so.<br>
<br>
Captains Blair and Toush tried to hire men independently of the crimps, but the latter brooked no such opposition: Men were lured away from the ships; and the crimps warned that unless the independent sailors were fired and replaced by their own men, the whole crew would go, even "If it cost $100 per man to take them."<br>
<br>
Both captains complied, but Toush's crew still got an offer of ten dollars each to leave; they all apparently resisted."'<br>
<br>
Visiting ships could not afford the time and trouble to prosecute for such violations, an often-overlooked fact that rendered existing laws completely ineffectual. Captains, therefore, expected the ports to police themselves, and complained of Portland's failure to do so.<br>
<br>
Whether they had taken bribes or not, deserting seamen did not have the same right simply to quit a job that other men had, according to admiralty law.  In 1897 four men deserted from the bark Arago at Astoria and, when charged with their crime, pleaded that the thirteenth ammendment protected them from involuntary servitude.<br>
<br>
The Arago case went to the U.S. Supreme Court, which ruled that the sailor's contract was an exceptional one and involved the surrender of certain liberties accorded to others.  In return, sea-men became essentiafly wards of the court, which made decisions for them and supposedly protected them: "Seamen are treated by Congress, as well as by the Parliament of Great
Britain, as deficient in that full and intelligent responsibility for their acts which is accredited to ordinary adults.""<br>
<br>
The law did not change until 1915, when all seamen gained the right to break contract undcr certain conditions, and to strike, subject to a judge's interpretation of whether the acts were war-
ranted or mutinous.<br>
<br>
While unions placed crimping and shanghaiing in the context of labor management and civil rights, others saw it as a social issue.  One of the various reform lobbies of the time put blame for the abuses squarely on public and legal opinion, whose "logical" outcome, they argued, was the manner in which crimps and sea captains misused sailors.<br>
<br>
A man resorting to the ships "loses social caste by going to sea, loses the respect of the people with whom he has been associated"; this downward mobility demoralized the work force and kept its numbers short, thus crippling the industry."<br>
<br>
Charities adopted this cause and addressed themselves to the mariner's moral and social welfare, offering an alternative to waterfront accommodation amd entertainment.  The Seaman's Friend Society, chapter in Portland sponsored a boarding house kept a library there, hired a minister, and formed a commission to study the abuse of seamen and to facilitate legal action against abuse.<br>
<br>
Mostly the Seamen's Friend Society hoped to save the "weak and shiftless" mariner, "tossed by every wave of influence," from the "baleful" sailor boarding house:<br>
<br>
It is said as partial excuse for not helping him that the sailor is ... his own worst enemy-which to a great extent is deplorably true ... and hence the imperative necessity for Seamcn's Homes and<br>
Bethels where the worthy seaman may find a home and hospitality.<br>
<br>
The rhetoric of the Seamen's Friend Society at times bore striking resemblance to the language of the Supreme Court's paternal rulings on the seafaring trade as expressed in the Arago decision.<br>
<br>
Thus crimping generated a number of different responses -moral, legal, social, and economic-depending on the perspective of the observer.  Perhaps one of the strongest barriers to the emancipation of seamen was a societal attitude - a fear of @s transient male population - as voiced by one man-on-the-street when asked about crimps stealing advanced wages: "I do not carc how much they take away from [the sailor], as he is only a beast, anyway.""<br>
<br>
In 1898 a Portland Chamber of Commerce report credited one James Turk with the introduction of crimping practices to the Oregon coast about twenty-five years earlier." This British-born
ex-sailor and Mexican War veteran arrived in Portland in the 1870s, opening a large hotel in North Portland and a sailors boarding house on Couch Street between First and Second.<br>
<br>
He also purchased some of the best property in Astoria, where he dabbled in politics and public affairs, even running for mayor once."'<br>
<br>
Besides fathering the Oregon crimping trade, Turk fathered two sons.  One of them, Frank, followed in James Turk's footsteps and operated a sailors boarding house in Astoria.  Frank Turk tried to expand his business westward, moving to Honolulu in 1899, where, in the Astoria Daily Budget's words, the sea captains did not "take kindly to the idea of having Pacific Coast methods of shipping seamen introduced" The authorities pressed charges against the younger Turk for aiding and abetting desertion, and for illegally boarding vessels."<br>
<br>
Frank Turk returned to Astoria to ply his trade, apparently unharried by such legalities.<br>
<br>
James Turk is remembered, among other things, for shanghaiing his other son (whose name, however, is not remembered), as a disciplinary measure for drinking and womanizing.  An account of this rather unusual punishment claims that Turk collected blood money from the skipper for his son, and that the young man returned from sea several months later cured of his delinquency, eventually to become a successful businessman <B>in </B>California.<br>
<br>
The Portland Chamber of Commerce report waxed eloquent on the misdeeds of the elder Turk: "The inhumanity and cruelty of James Turk toward seamen has never been denied by men who knew him-, and the spirit of their progenitor has largely animated his successors in the business, even to the present day. <B>"</B><br>
<br>
Over thirty years later, however, one of those who knew him -an old Portlander named Spider Johnson -told the Oregonian that Turk was a "square-shooter," as no one was ever robbed in his place (though, Johnson admitted, Turk "got a pretty bad reputation" and "may have" shanghaied a few drunk sailors).<br>
<br>
At the same time, Johnson confirmed part of the chamber's report: "This Jim Turk ... was one of the original shanghai boys here."<br>
<br>
Spider Johnson's reminiscences described a busy Portland water-
front- a "forest of masts" from ships docked on the river and an elaborate red-light district both ashore and floating on saloon scows.  "Sailor runners" went about recruiting less-experienced or inexperienced sailors for the boarding houses:<br>
<br>
"Thc genuine A.B.s and skilled mariners never stopped at the sailor's boarding houses unless they wanted to take ship again
right away.  They knew better." But farmers, loggers, or men who had sailed just once or twice before were fair game for the runners' promises of good employment and accommodations on credit.<br>
<br>
"I know one ship that went out of Portland which had two real seamen and around forty plowboys from the midwest.  I know of another ship ... which had a bull-teamster signed on as bos'n," Johnson recalled."<br>
<br>
"Yes, I know there was a lot of bad stuff went on, and a lot of guys were shanghaied, but a lot of them needed it." Instead of just hanging around "waiting for someone to buy them another drink," the sailors benefited from the months of forced sobriety and came back in good physical condition, with money coming to them, according to Johnson.<br>
<br>
"That was not such a bad break." He also told of a man dying of consumption who was cured by a sea vovage after being shanghaied out of Portland.<br>
<br>
Blood money, Johnson said, usually  ranged between twenty-five and fifty dollars, but went as high as one hundred dollars per man.  "Knockout drops " used on occasion and a certain local druggist ... kept his store going from that trade, but for the most part it was hard liquor or cash that shanghaied a man."<br>
<br>
Johnson admitted to signing on a few, men himself, as well as to stuffing ballot boxes in support of the crimps political designs.<br>
<br>
Another feature  of  Portland's waterfront and also figuring  prominently in area folklore-was the network of "shanghai tunnels" running under city streets to the never.  Underground passages opened into saloons and other businesses in the north end and terminated near the present-day Burnside Bridge.<br>
<br>
While mundane uses may have included access to waterlines and cargo loading, some claim that human "cargo" trafficked the tunnels as well.<br>
<br>
Following leads from rumors and local folk memories, historian Mike Jones excavated such tunnels in the 1970s- In these brick-lined passageways that may originally havc been constructed for drainage or flood control, Jones found evidence of human use: intriguing artifacts such as pin bottles, a turn-of-the-century shoe, part of a peg leg, bullets, meat hooks, and, most intriguing of all a man-sized cage.<br>
<br>
Jones identified certain tunnels as escape routes for Chinese gambling and opium dens; he became convinced that others, leading from establishments such as the elaborate Erickson's Hotel on Third and Burnside, provided convenient routes for the <B>crimps.<br>
<br>
</B>Of the known crimps operating in the milieu described by Spider
Johnson and disinterred by Mike Jones, James Turk was perhaps the first, but he was not the most famous.<br>
<br>
A colorful character named Joseph "Bunco" Kelly gained more notoriety than the rest, attracting tall stories that have since been recounted in virtually every magazine and newspaper review of Oregon shanghaiing printed this century.<br>
<br>
According to one of these tales, Kelly earned his nickname "Bunco" in 1885, when he stole a six-and-a-half-foot wooden Indian from the front of Wildman's Cigar Store (at First and Glisan in Portland), wrapped it in a tarpaulin, and sold it as a drunk seaman to a ship for fifty dollars.  After Norwegian fishermen supposedly netted the Indian near Astoria, it eventually returned to Wildman's, where it was chained to the pavement.<br>
<br>
Other exploits credited to Kelly include the shanghaiing of prostitutes (whom he dressed as men) and the defrauding of the bark Rosecranna in 1888, from which he collected $465 for a crew he never delivered.  But the most fantastic story involves the mass shanghaiing of twenty-four dead men.  As the story goes, Kelly happened on a group of dead and dying inebriates in the cellar of Johnson & Sons Undertakers.<br>
<br>
They had broken into what they thought was the cellar of the Snug Harbor Saloon, which stood next door (at Second and Morrison), and mistakenly drank formaldehyde thinking that the wooden kegs held beer.  Kelly, after rounding up help, sold the corpses for $720 to the Flying Prince, which was in the harbor awaiting a crew.<br>
<br>
Originally from Liverpool, Joseph Kelly came to Astoria as a sailor in 1874 at the age of thirty-six.  He eventually opened a boardinghouse at Northwest Third and Davis in Portland, after crimping on the streets for a time.  Besides fraud, he became famous for Keily's Knock-Out Drops, served in drinks.<br>
<br>
Of more interest, perhaps, than the wild stories told about him are Kelly's diaries, written in prison.  Kelly remarked of Astoria, perhaps too innocently, that he found it something inhuman to see the way them sailors were treated.... New Orleans was never in it with the Columbia River crimps.  No wonder we have got the worst reputation of any nation on earth.  Wherever you go, in any part of the world, you are asked by seafaring men, captains, mates and sailors, the first question is: "Did you come from Astoria, the pirate city by the sea?"<br>
<br>
Writing as if from the standpoint of a righteous observer rather than a participant, Kelly described the Oregon crimping busincss: The "boss crimpers" approached newly arrived vessels armed with iron hooks and a rope ladder, like the old-time pirates.  They would throw the ladder aboard and climb over the ship's side with their dosed whiskey and commence giving it out to the sailors.<br>
<br>
When the poor sailor takes one drink, he belongs body and soul to
the crimp.... Sometimes the ship captains allied themselves with the crimps in ordcr to confiscate the sailor's pay."<br>
<br>
The Noddleburn case of 1890 offers a more credible example of Kelly's crimping methods than the anecdote of the shanghaied corpses.  An Idaho logger named Armstrong jumped overboard from the Noddleburn while she lay at anchor in Portland and went to the authoritics to implicate Kelly for shanghaiing.<br>
<br>
Armstrong charged that Kelly had promised him light work at good pay; furthermore, he had personally signed no ship's articles.  But Kelly was taken without a warrant and the case had to be dropped.<br>
<br>
Kelly maintained that competing Portland crimps fabricated the Noddleburn incident because he refused to join their monopoly and raise the local price of blood money.<br>
<br>
Again iiii8g Kelly cried foul when he was tried and convictcd for the murder of George Sayres.  Kelly later wrote: "It is said that I killed him while trying to shanghai the old man.  I am <B>innocent.<br>
</B>On the night of the murder Kelly and another crimp Larry<br>
Sullivan went to jail for fighting. Despite this alibi and his continued not guilty plea the police produced an alleged confession.<br>
<br>
Kelly is quoted as saying:<br>
<br>
"I am being tried not as the person who killed poor old George Sayres.  I am being tried for all the crimes ever committed in the North End.  I am on trial because I am operating a successful sailor's boarding house, the finest on this coast.  I am being tried because I have no influence with the city's politicians.  It is all a frame-up, gentlemen."<br>
<br>
Apparently Bunco Kelly's defense did not fall on deaf ears, for in 1907 Governor George Earle Chamberlain granted him a full pardon in response to a petition that had been circulating for some time.  Kelly returned to Astoria, advising others to give up crimping, become men and go to work because there is a curse on the sailor business.  Beware and take warning, for time flies, and become good citizens."<br>
<br>
The men that Kelly accused of engineering his defence certainly had the wherewithal to do so.  Larry Sullivan, brothers Jack and Peter Grant, and Richard McCarron worked together as a powerful coalition during the 1890s and into the early twentieth century. (Other occasional partners included Billy Smith, Jim and Harry White, and John Betts.)<br>
<br>
As Kelly hinted in his testimony, this coalition had political clout, as evidenced in court decisions, law enforcement (or lack thereof), and even state legislation.  A historian of Portland later enlogized Sullivan as "king of the boardinghouse operators.<br>

Larry Sullivan came to Astoria in the early 1880s, while in his twenties, and made a name for himself as an amateur boxer.  In the 1890s he opened a boarding house at Second and Glisan in Portland he also operated gambling clubs and became a "ward boss" for local elections.  Although he accrued a long police record of minor convictions and dropped charges, Sullivan and his cronies often successfully manipulated the law to stall ships and to punish uncooperative captains, sailors, or rival crimps.<br>
<br>
For instance, once when Richard McCarron came to blows with Astoria crimp Paddy Lynch for encroaching on the coalition's territory, police arrested Lynch for assault and battery but let McCarron go free.  And in 1895, when representatives of the Portland Seamen's Friend Society began laying groundwork for a Seamen's Institute that would house and ship sailors at reasonable rates, the organizers also found themselves facing charges of assalt and battery, trespassing, threatening to kill Sullivan, and using profane and vulgar language.<br>
<br>
Like Kelly had earlier, defendants Matthew Dee and J. P. Christiansen of the Seamen's Friend Society insisted that the affair was a frame-up.  The Oregonian sarcastically remarked that Sullivan's "esthetic mind was rudely shocked by the use of such language as he imputes to Dee.<br>
<br>
"Time and again I have seen poor seamen arrested on trumped-up<br>
charges, simply because they refuse to do what the boarding house masters demand," complained British Consul James Laidlaw.  Captains hiring independently also faced such sanctions, he added, mentioning one who had been charged with kidnapping and another with libel, "on the flimsy pretext of breach of contract."<br>
<br>
Other libel suits brought by crimps <B>in</B>cluded one by Jack Grant against Norwegian Consul Cederbergh, who had claimed that Grant overcharged for sailors, and another by Jim Turk against a party who had accused him of shanghaiing.  Both suits failed,<br>
however.<br>
<br>
Before 1889 transients were subject to debtor's prison in Oregon, and this provided yet another legal tool for the crimps.  E. Quackcnbush of the Seamen's Friend Society described how boarding house keepers "of the Jim Turk stripe" had "fattened upon the sailors" using debtor's prisons.<br>
<br>
For instance: a sailor would contract 50 cents or one dollar actual indebtedness in a saloon, he would finally ship, would be taken from the ship either here or at Astoria upon a claim in the Justice Court of anywhere from $30 to $60, all of which except the onc dollar or less was fraudulent.<br>
<br>
When once on shore he would be discharged, the sailor pirates
running him in and finally shipping him for a second profit, with prospect of a rearrest upon a similarly trumped-up charge, that a third profit might be realized from reshipment."<br>
<br>
Such a chain of events may be the basis for one diarist's assertion that men were shanghaiied out of Astoria jail cells.<br>
<br>
"The boarding-house masters here have a big pull.  It is believed here that they can do anything that they at the courts," came the report on Portland printed in a London journal. In keeping with this claim, Bunfco Kelly's autobiogrpahy tells of a Finn whom Larry Sullivan tried to shanghai out of a dance hall, but having given him too much dope the crimp could not wake the seaman. So Sullivan poured coal oil into his boots and set fire to them. He burnt the sailor's feet pretty near off. The case went to the grand jury but Sullivan paid a thousand dollars to clear his name, according to Kelly. The sailor died a short while later.<br>
<br>
Another of Sullivan's clients lived to tell his own tale: Alfred Clark, just off the farm at the age of twenty-one came to Portland in 1891 and accepted an invitation from a pleasant sort of fellow to the boarding house owned by Sullivan and Billy Smith. From there he joined a riverboat party, featuring food, drink, women and dancing and a three piece orchestra which reveled its way down river to Astoria and docked.<br>
<br>
The festivities continued ashore but not before the ten guests signed a "passenger list" ostensibly to assure their return trip. In Astoria someone offered a of the square-rigger T.F. Oaks, and everyone went aboard -only to be threatened at gunpoint and clapped in irons.  The captain explained to Clark and the others that they had each signed legal ship's articlcs (the passenger list) and thereby agreed to sail to Le Havre.<br>
<br>
Clark's story attests to the general spirit of collaboration in crime along the Columbia River.  Starting out from Sullivan's boardinghouse in Portland, the men were shanghaied out of Astoria; many crimps operated out of both towns rather than one or the othcr, a fact that renders the frequent comparisons between the two towns rather meaningless.  Then Vice-Consul Laidlaw wrote:<br>
<br>
In his report for 1890, my colleague at Astoria makes the statement that the crimps infesting that port had changed to Portland.... The facts are that nearly all the sailors boarding houses have been and are located at Astoria-, that, with one or rwo exceptions, aH the most notorious crimps resided there.<br>
<br>
He went on to say that Portland's higher desertion rate was the result of  Astoria crimps tagging along up river and then hustling the sailors back to the coast.<br>
<br>
Certainly the family ties of Jack and Peter Grant constituted one of the greatest factors in this river wide cooperation. While their
mother, Bridget Grant, owned one of the most successful boardinghouses <B>in </B>Astoria, their brother Nace (short for Ignatius) held influential civic posts ranging from grange master and volunteer hose-team chief to sheriff and chief of police.  Nace Grant resigned from public life in 1918 when he was charged with graft in his capacity as chief of police.<br>
<br>
Bridget and Peter Grant (senior) owned boarding houses on the East Coast and in San Francisco before settling in Astoria in 1876.  The elder Peter drowned soon after, and Bridget single handedly raised her eight children and ran the sailors boarding house at 614 Commercial Street.<br>
<br>
Given to hosting society-page functions, after she died Bridget Grant was remembered fondly by the newspapers as a "pioneer resident." But while she lived, those who knew her from a business standpoint deplored  her as "queen of the boarding-master's fraternity."<br>
<br>
Legend has it that she cleared land on her farm with the help of shanghaied men, detained on the wilderness property, until a ship requircd them.  A captain complained that she builied him out of $150 in 1887 by collecting the debt of some sailors the captain had picked up in Portland, even though these men had never seen Bridget Grant.<br>
<br>
When the captain refused to pay she let them go; but the sheriff later boarded his ship to collect for Mrs. Grant, and the captain had to comply or lose the men to debtor's prison <B>.<br>
<br>
</B>Indeed,  it  seems  that  at  times  Astoria  law  enforcement  cooperated wth the crimps by policy.  When Robert M. Stuart of the Seamen's Friend Society asked the assistance of a police officer in case of a dockside scuffle with crimps, the chief of police later notified Stuart that his men were instructed not to interfere with the boardinghouse keepers.<br>
<br>
"I told him to go to Hades, that I would never ask help from them again," Stuart wrote."<br>
<br>
Bridget Grant retired in 1906, by which time competition-and profit had dropped off sharply for her and for her sons.  Jim Turk died in 1895, and Bunco Keily was in the state penitentiary until 1907, when he emerged a reformed man; Richard McCarron went to California at some point.  Crimping in Portland dwindled to a few individuals: Sullivan, the Grant brothers, and BiHv Smith and his partners Jim and Harry White.<br>
<br>
In 1904- the papers announced Sullivan's impending retirement from the boarding house, taking with him "not a single dollar.  There are no assets, no invested capital, nothing to sell." Sullivan and Petcr Grant went to Nevada as miners in 1905, leaving the shrinking boardinghouse business with Jack Grant; the Whites, who had fought for a foothold against the Grant-Sullivan monopoly, agreed on a
merger at that time.<br>
<br>
In 1916 or 1917 Sullivan reappcared in Orcgon, got in trouble for bootlegging in Clackamas County, and wound up laboring for a Pordand shipbuilder.  "Larry Sullivan Has Joined the Army of Hard Working Men," touted a headline.  "The soft hand that once slid the two-spot from a faro case now wraps its grimy fingers around beams in a local shipyard." A year later, in 1918, Sullivan died of natural causes at the age of fifty-five.<br>
<br>
Larry, Sullivan's oft-quoted boast to a visiting consul that he was "the law in Portland" certainly had some substance, though at this remove it is difficult to gauge the extent of his and other crimps' influence, or to provc allegations made bv contemporaries."<br>
<br>
Sullivan's extensive political involvement surely gave him contacts in high places.  Just before and after his death, the newsmen tallied up Sullivan's carcer: "Destinies of More Than One Politician Swayed by Boarding House Man," was the subhead for an article that called Sullivan a powerful political factor in the state," a denizen of the Joseph Simon faction of the Republican party, "a daring and picturesque fighter in the political arena," and a ward boss; "during the height of his career in the sailor boarding house busincss he was active in all of the election contests and the side he was on usually came out victorious."<br>
<br>
Another paper stated more vaguely that "his political activitics <B>in </B>Portland were numerous and varied."<br>
<br>
Both newspaper stories recalled and election in which Sullivan brandished a shotgun at police who arrived to investigate the polling booth located at his boardinghouse.  When the polling was safely over, police arrested Sullivan, but, as usual, "no serious charge was filed against him." A later account of that election asserted that an entire crew from a Dutch ship had voted: "I think they got two dollars apiece; not one of them could read or speak English. <B>"</B><br>
<br>
Sullivan also made his connections useful in the harbor master's office.  After they had posted Robert M. Stuart at the mouth of the Columbia to collect the complaints of sea captains, Seamen's Friend Society officials insisted they had no recourse in Portland against Sullivan's extortionate fees (fifty-five dollars per sailor, by one report) because the harbor master cc stood in" with the crimps.<br>
<br>
Some of the captains interviewed asserted that the Seamen's Friend Society itself answered to the cnrimps.  Sullivan, the captains said, had shown them a dispatch, written by Stuart and intended for the society's president E. Quackenbush.- Sullivan apparently displayed the intercepted dispatch as proof of his complete control of the port.<br>

After collecting many accusations against the harbor master, Quack-
enbush wrote to the mayor-elect, George Williams, alleging "without reservation" that "not more than 15% of the nearly $12,000 which the city has paid out" to the Harbor Office went toward administering the ofrice's duties; "In other words, the law has not been enforced 15% of the time, nor with 15% of honest intention that it should be enforced.  Over $10,000 has simply been squandered.<br>
<br>
This attention to financial considerations typified the battle against crimping and related graft in Portland.  A chamber of commerce address to the Legislative Assembly of 1899 appealed to the state's wallet first, estimating the 1898 earnings of Columbia River crimps at $51,000; next, the address invoked civic pride; and finally, near the bottom of the page, it cited humanity and sympathy for sailors as "a further ground" for action."<br>
<br>
Perhaps in an effort to draw a wider scopc of concern, the chamber and other interested parties insisted that Orcgon's grain growers lost out in the long run:<br>
<br>
Who pays for this? Not the shipowner, for he can eventually recoup himself through the higher freight.  Not the merchant, who  predi-
cates his buying price on the freight he has to pay, but the produc-
er-the farmer who gets just so much less for his produce.<br>
<br>
Various estimates of the amount fleeced from honest farmers (in addition to the chamber's estimate) appeared in the news from time to time.  Norweigan Consul Cederbergh calculated in 1908 that the individual sailors boardinghouse keeper made $25,000 tO  $30,000 per year, "equal to the earnings of many big businesses."<br>
<br>
When Jack Grant retorted that he and his three partners netted less than $10,000 together, Cederbergh published statistics backing his claim.  In 1911 the president of the state legislature reckoned Grant's annual take at the slightly more modest figure of $20,000."<br>
<br>
Besides soliciting support against crimps with dollars-and-cents ap-
peals, the media dished out blame for the problem.  "It has always been inexplicable why abuses so flagrant and a business so devoid of honor and equity should be countenanced by the business men of a community, and be defended by the press," railed the Oregonian in reference to Astoria:<br>
<br>
"It seemed as if the whole community were willing to endorse this heinous outrage for the sake of the few thousands of dollars that were put in circulation by it." The article came to the pragmatic conclusion that ultimately the defeat of crimps would generate revenue for Astoria by attracting more tonnage to the port (a prediction that became a stock phrase for consuls, though in reference to Portland).<br>
<br>
One of these fiscal arguments were in the interest of new legislation, but for years the more powerful crimps found ways to
manipulate or avoid the resulting laws.  The Astoria City Council neglccted until 1891 to appoint a harbor master, as required by the 1889 state law, and Portland's appointee proved to be a paper tiger.<br>
<br>
A 1903 bill established a state commission to license and monitor the sailors boarding houses; Grant and Sullivan's house immediately obtained the sole license in Portland, for the commission favored a citywide monopoly-as explained when Billy Smith and Harry White were turned down.  The latter sued, and the state supreme court ruled against the monopoly policy; but thereupon the two houses agreed to merge, and a de facto monopoly continued.<br>
<br>
Even down river the 1903 law effectively cut competition.  A boarding house called the "Sailor's Home" closed, insisting that "the new law was formed in the interest of certain Portland people" and citing restrictions and fees that drove smaller operations out of business. Later, Consul Cederbergh stated the same in stronger terms, calling the 1903 bill "the Larry Sullivan Law" and saying that it "was placed upon the statute books through the influence of the notorious boarding house master, Larry  Sullivan and his gang of crimps."<br>
<br>
The first challenge to the authorized crimps came in 1908, when the employment firm of Wisschusen & Jones opened expressly to hire seamen out for the modest fee of ten dollars each.  When Jack Grant, who had taken Sullivan's place as leader of the firm, raised an uproar, the city council revoked Wisschusen & Jones's business twice by special ordinance on the grounds that they had not gone through the boarding house commission.<br>
<br>
However, Mayor Harry Lane vetoed the ordinance, ruling that any employment agency had the right to handle the seafaring as well as any other occupation.  "Sailors must be slaves no more," he expounded.  "Portland has the unenviable reputation of being the only large port in the world where this unfair employment system is allowed.<br>
<br>
In the throes of this dispute, Wisschuscn bitterly declared to the newspapers that "ship owners are as anxious as anyone else to skin the poor sailor"; and that Portlanders, too, seemed content with the crimps' extortions."' Indeed, when the consulates began agitating for legislative action in 1909 the Oregonian twice urged that they "leave well enough alone," calling the new bill "more pernicious than any yet introduced" because it intended "to repeal the law which prohibits crimping."<br>
<br>
That "professional jawsmith" Andrew Furuseth, of seamen's union fame, even came to Salem to support the reform.<br>
<br>
But at the legislative session, House Representative John McCue stalled the bill and prevented its passage, according to Senate
President Ben Selling.  He later charged that McCue worked for Jack Grant; that in 1909 he stole the sailors bill, produced it from his pocket after the assembly adjourned, and waved it in the air yelling, "What are you going to do about it?"<br>
<br>
Another sailors bill was on the docket in 1911 again with McCue <B>in</B> opposition.  The Oregon Journal echoed Selling's suspicions that McCue worked for Grant, and added that "whoever his employer, he <B>is </B>apparently earning his salary.  No lobbyist ... could possibly compete with him.<br>
<br>
This time, however, Grant and McCue's faction could not depend on the community's inertia.  National circumstances intervened and lent urgency to the clean-up of Portland: "Commercial Bodies Want Port Made as Popular as Possible before Panama Canal Is Completed," ran a headline." The new law attempted to divorce completely the employment of sailors from the boarding of them; it imposed heavy fines for charging more than ten dollars per sailor, tightened the shipping commissioner's control, and took steps to ensure that the commissioner had no investment at stake with the shipping business.<br>
<br>
Although Consul James Laidlaw's obituary <B>in </B>1913 hailed him as "the man who wiped out [the] shanghai evil," one must wonder how thor-
oughly he did so: Jack Grant, as head of the Oregon State Shipping Board, still had the shipping business firm in hand when he cued in 1921, and Captain McDonald of the Moshula later confessed that as late as 1927 or 1928 he got a crew through a Portland "man of evil repute" called Shanghai White (perhaps one of the brothers who worked with Billy Smith).<br>
<br>
Frank Earl Hammond of Portland told the Oregonian in 1978 that he was a latter-day shanghai victim as well.  When he got back (perhaps in the late 1920s), "things were different.  Progress was a-coming and those tunnels were destroyed.  Things were so different that even the shanghaiers were out of business.  A few years later they even tore down the waterfront.  I guess I was one of the last to get shanghaied out of Portland.<br>
<br>
Crimping settled on the banks of the Columbia River through the ef-
forts of a few individuals, most of them ex-seamen, all of them familiar with the business from other ports.  San Francisco, New York, Baltimore, New Orleans, and Tacoma, as well as some Canadian and European ports, share a common history of crimping and shanghaiing.  Elsewhere, as in Oregon, crimping consisted of payoffs, politics, organized crime, union bashing, shanghaiing, and, more generally, exploitation.<br>
<br>
And not by coincidence, crimping began to wane all over the country early in this century for on top of local measures opposing crimps
there were larger forces at work.<br>
<br>
"I don't know when or where Bunco died," Spider Johnson told a reporter, but whenever he died, Bunco Kelly died in his time.  Steam was coming in, and that is what killed shanghaiing. When steam came in, it knocked out close to fifty percent of the men needed to man a ship.  When you cut off half a crew, this technological unemployment means something.  That's what steam did."<br>
<br>
Besides halving the crew, the increased efficiency of steam shipping sharply reduced the total number of vessels needed in the industry.  A steamship carried up to twice the freight of a square-rigger and made the voyage in less time.<br>
<br>
This minor industrial revolution arrived late in the United States compared to other countries; American ship owners, clinging to the glory of the clipper era and its leftover vessels, did not spend money modernizing the fleet until foreign competition and foreign wars provided the motivation.<br>
<br>
Not to belittle the significance of state and national legislation or the efforts of millions, it is undeniable that the pace of waterfront reforms closely matched the steamship's progress.  As Spider Johnson said, "There were a lot of what they call crusades against shanghaiing in Portland, and they had some effect, but the steamship is what killed shanghaiing.<br>
<br>
Denise M. Alborn, "Crimping and Shanghaiing on the Columbia River," <B>The Oregon Historical Quarterly.</B> LXIII(Fall, 1992), p. 263-288.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
SHANGHAIIING FOR THE WHALERS.<br>
<br>
Simeon Oliver with Alden Hatch, "Shanghaiiing for the Whalers," <B>Son of the Smoky Sea.</B> New York: Julian Messner, Inc, 1941, p. 106-121.<br>
<br>
Kutan is the next island eastward of Unalaska.  The Whaling Station, where I worked that spring of <B>1</B>922 was on the bay about a mile by water from Akutan village.  It was a busy place at that time of the year.  About one hundred men were employed there and three ships hunted the whales we processed.<br>
<br>
They brought in from seven to ten of the great seagoing mammals daily, and sometimes, when we ran behind, there would be as many as thirty whales lying anchored off the float.  Sperms, sulphur-bottoms, finbacks and humpbacks, they were all grist to our mill.<br>
<br>
We would hook a heavy chain around the tail of one of these monsters; eighty to ninety feet long they ran, weighing
approximately a ton to the foot.  The hoisting engine would be started and slowly the great hulk would slide up the inclined float out of the water.<br>
<br>
When it was securely fastened on the platform we'd attack it with heavy cutting tools.  One man cut into the head, where a great reservoir of hundreds of gallons of free oil lay ready to be barreled.  Others cut through the four-foot layer of blubber, loosening one end of it.<br>
<br>
Then the chain was securely hooked into the tough fat; the hoisting engine was started again and the long, thick slice of dirty white blubber was peeled cleanly off and hauled away to the trying kettles.  Every bit of the carcass was utilized.  The parts which yielded no oil or bone were ground up for fertilizer.<br>
<br>
One of the most valuable parts was the baleen, the sieve of wiry teeth which fills the mouth of a whale.  Through it the water rushes as the great beast cruises slowly along the feeding grounds, and it strains out all but the tiny, cellular creatures which nourish these monsters. His baleen is the stuff of which whalebone for women's corsets is made.<br>
<br>
No sooner was one whale cut up than another was hauled out.  The place hummed with industry and smelled to high heaven.  I tell you we were a tired crew at the end of the long day's work.<br>
<br>
Nevertheless we usually seemed to have energy enough left for a walk over the hills or a trip across the bay <B>to </B>the tiny village of Akutan.  In this little settlement of perhaps seventy-five people <B>there </B>was a dance hall, and in it we would spend harmlessly gay evenings.<br>
<br>
Sometimes in our bunkhouse we would put on a dance ourselves.  Since most of the workers were Norwegians, the music usually consisted of Scandinavian waltzes and polkas, played by a fiddle and accordion.  How the rough boards shivered under the crash of heavy boots, tripping to the fast measures! How the rafters rang when we burst into song.<br>
<br>
The whaling ships, which fought through the roaring seas to bring in the raw material to our factory, were trim little vessels no more than a hundred feet in length.  They were driven by powerful steam engines and could buck the wildest storms, the fastest tides.  A single mast bore a crow@s-nest in which the lookout always perched, swaying dizzily abovc the towering seas.<br>
<br>
At the bow was <B>a </B>harpoon gun manned by an expert gunner, who with dcliberate aim and mechanical precision, performed the task, which used to be done by the hardy lanceman standing up in the plunging bow of a whaleboat under the very shadow of his fearsome prey.<br>
<br>
A crew of ten manned these little ships; and, though they had an
easier life than the whalers of an earlicr day, they had need to be hardy men.  Their quarters were cramped and their work long and arduous.  They must sleep when and where they could, and ever be ready for the kill.<br>
<br>
The toughest part of them had to be their stomachs, for the little ships bounced and gyrated through the waves in a way to make a destroyer seem like a rocking-horse, and the food on them, prepared in a tiny galley with the stove at any angle including the perpendicular, was terrible.  Black coffee by the gallon was the mainstay of life.<br>
<br>
At that it was luxury compared to the ships of even a decade before.  When I was a small boy, the famous whalers of the time would all put in at Unalaska as they followed their prey to the northward when the arctic ice began to drift.  Karluk, Herman and Belvedere, the Beluga and the Fearless commanded by such men as Captains Fred Tilton and Ted Petersen; and the famous Captain Bob Bartlett.<br>
<br>
Splendid names those old ships bore, and fine seamen commanded them; but living conditions aboard were indescribable.<br>
So bad were they that few men would voluntarily sign aboard a whaler and most of the crews were shanghaied from the San Francisco <B>waterfront.  </B>The would be a month from port when they reached the Aleutians, and the pressed crews would be raving to escape.<br>
<br>
To prevent any such attempt the ships would anchor five miles or more from shore and send picked men in their whaleboats to secure essential supplies.  But even this precaution did not always discourage the frantic crew.<br>
<br>
I remember one occasion on which a posse of armed sailors from a whaler came on shore to report several members of their crew missing.  They searched the village and all the surrounding country, but could find no one.  The ship remained at anchor for a week; and all that time the manhunt went on.  In the end she was obliged to sail away short handed.<br>
<br>
It is cold in Unalaska in April.  A man could hardly expect to survive more than a few minutes in the freezing waters of the Bering Sea.  Nevertheless these men had dived overboard and swum the long miles into Dutch Harbor.  There, in a cave in the cliffs on a deserted stretch of beach, they had lain while the posse passed them by.<br>
<br>
They could not go to the village for food lest they be taken.  They dared not light a fire, for the smoke would be seen.  Their sufferings must have been fearful and yet, such was their horror of being taken back to their ship, that they endured all, while gradually, as the long week dragged on, the splendid strength which had enabled them to survive that five mile swim through Arctic seas, ebbed away.<br>
<br>
Months later a native found their bodies huddled in the cave.
Simeon Oliver with Alden Hatch, "Shanghaiing for the Whalers," <B>Son of the Smoky Sea.</B> New York: Julian Messner, Inc, 1941, p. 106-121.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
