<h1>Smuggling</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
KELLY, THE KING OF THE SMUGGLERS<br>
<br>
(Lucile McDonald, "Kelly, the King of the Smugglers, Guemes, Sinclair Islands were headquarters of notorious operator in years long past." <B>Seattle Times.</B> March 29, 1959.).<br>
<br>
The waters of Bellingham Channel between Guemes and Sinclair Islands were once the haunt of the Puget Sound country's most storied smuggler, Lawrence Kelly.<br>
<br>
Tales told about Kelly are more numerous than the known facts. Historians have touched on him vaguely. He is said to have served once in the British armed services and to have ben a sailor on a vessel which called at New Orleans at the outbreak of the Civil War. There he enlisted in the Louisiana Tigers and fought for the Confederacy.<br>
<br>
Kelly arrived in Seattle about 1872 and sometime between that year and 1878 established himself on the southwest point of Guemes Island which today bears his name. He married Lizzie Kotz in 1877.<br>
<br>
Kelly's cabin was in the woods, which only in the past year have been stripped from the point. His bluff commanded a far reaching view of Rosario Strait and of Guemes and Bellingham Channels. This was a definite asset in his chosen profession.<br>
<br>
One historical researcher says of Kelly, "He maintained his part time family life in the cabin on the point and established another base on  Sinclair Inlet."<br>
<br>
Smuggling goods from Vancouver Island to Washington afforded profits tempting to island boat owners. The illicit trade had been going on since the late 1850s. It took a big spurt when Chinese laborers were imported to build railroads and work in the mines.<br>
<br>
With the influx of Chinese came the trade in opium, a product in which Kelly specialized, though he was not above earning an illegal dollar carrying Chinese passengers, Chinese wine or any other profitable commodity.<br>
<br>
A yarn is told about Square Bay, on the northeast corner of Guemes Island. An old resident said he saw Kelly's sloop anchored in the small harbor. The two men chatted a while, then Kelly shouted, " Come out John, he's o.k.," whereupon the tall grass erupted Chinese. There seemed to have been one hiding behind every bush around the bay.<br>
<br>
The first official mention of Kelly in the United States Customs files for the Puget Sound District was December 21, 1882, when his sloop was seized at LaConner with forty cases of red and white Chinese wine on board. he was fined one hundred sixty dollars.
A newspaper that week related:<br>
<br>
"For some months past a systematic course of smuggling has been going on between British Columbia and points in this district. Collector Bush has been indefatigable in attempting to ferret out the guilty parties and on Sunday night last Special Officer Thomas Caine captured a sloop valued at $250 and $400 worth of Chinese wine at LaConner."<br>
<br>
Kelly was in the sloop at the time of his capture but the loss did not discourage him. Records show that on July 8, 1883 he paid another fine of $390 and on the following November 17, $20.00.<br>
<br>
The profits in Kelly's illicit wares were so high that he took great risks. He managed to keep away from the law until Mary 16, 1886 when his Whitehall boat, sail and oars were seized at Tacoma with 567 tins of prepared opium on board. This was equivalent to 364 pounds of the drug.  His craft bore no name, the inspector reported. Newspapers commented that Kelly was "...an old time offender."<br>
<br>
Kelly was bound over to District Court for trial and his bail was set at three thousand dollars. A boatman named Main and a witness named Willis also were required to post bond. Kelly was fined one hundred dollars on July 31.<br>
<br>
The officers continued to watch the king of the smugglers. A February 1, 1889 telegram from a customs officer in Bellingham reported, "Kelly left Bellingham Bay today with stuff for his island"<br>
<br>
However, it was not until March l3, 1891 that Kelly met his real downfall. Special Agent Charles J. Mulkey saw Kelly in the smoking car of a train en route from Tacoma to Portland, a large new russet-colored valise carefully parked at his feet. When Mulkey inquired as to its contents, Kelly answered, "Clothing."<br>
<br>
Mulkey was suspicious and opened the bag. In it he found 65 cans of unstamped opium worth about $450.<br>
<br>
Kelly declared angrily and profanely that no revenue officer ever would take him, but Mulkey was firm and transferred him to a north bound train at Castle Rock. Mulkey took along as witness the man who occupied the seat with Kelly.<br>
<br>
Kelly, taken before the United States commissioner in Tacoma, the same day insisted the bag was not his. He had left his grip on the seat when he went to the wash room he said and on his return he had found that it had been replaced by another.<br>
<br>
"Kelly is an old steam boat man formerly employed on the steamer <B>North Pacific</B>," said a contemporary newspaper account of the case.<br>
<br>
"For several years he had made his home on Cottonwood (Sinclair)
Island near Anacortes. He lately fitted out a new sloop for his cruises. It has no name and is said to be fast and in front of the tiller is a small shelf where Kelly keeps an arsenal of revolvers and pistols.<br>
<br>
"About two months ago, Canadian authorities arrested Kelly at Victoria and fined him $300 for leaving the harbor without clearing. A few years ago he was tried in Tacoma, convicted of<br>
smuggling and served a term in the penitentiary."<br>
<br>
Kelly's bond was set at a thousand dollars.<br>
<br>
Customs officers descended on Kelly's hide out at Sinclair Island two days later and seized the sloop <B>Alert</B>. They charged Kelly with smuggling and entering and leaving foreign ports without proper formalities, alleging he had gone to Victoria without clearing and returned about January 30 to New Whatcom.<br>
<br>
Although the officers could not prove it, they believed Kelly had smuggled in 1880 cans of opium. He went to Victoria again March 4, the officers said, and returned four days later with a large quantity of the drug.<br>
<br>
The <B>Alert</B> was sold at a marshal's sale for $3,221.83. There is no record of how those charges against Kelly were disposed of.<br>
<br>
Sometime before 1906 Kelly was arrested in Seattle and again served a term.<br>
<br>
Fred Splitstone's history of Orcas Island says that in May, 1909, Kelly pleased guilty to another smuggling charge and was sentenced to a year at the McNeil Island penitentiary. On his release he found that going straight meant hard times. He got in touch with the Daughters of the Confederacy and was admitted to a Confederate Soldiers home in Louisiana where he died.<br>
<br>
So ended the 25 year career of one of the most notorious smugglers on the Pacific Coast.<br>
<br>
(Lucile McDonald, "Kelly, King of the Smugglers," <B>Seattle Times.</B> March 29, 1959.).<br>
<br>
TRACKING THE SMUGGLERS<br>
<br>
(Lucile McDonald," Old records tell how Puget Sound customs men went about tracking the smugglers," <B>Seattle Times.</B> July 27, 1952.).<br>
<br>
Smugglers of opium and Chinese furnished exciting activity for the Puget Sound customs officers for twenty years or more. Details of how smugglers were trapped or more often, got away, are revealed in a mass of records recently transferred here from Port Townsend and now being catalogued in the Collector of Customs' office in the Federal building.
By the time headquarters of the customs district moved to Seattle on Jul 1, 1913, Chinese no longer were so much in the news. The Exclusion Act of 1882, designed to suspend importation of Oriental laborers for a ten year period, spurred the smugglers. Until then, coolies had been brought in freely to supply cheap labor for canneries, hop yards, mines and public works. As many as 15,000 were employed in the construction of the Northern Pacific Railroad.<br>
<br>
After the ban was put on the Chinese, Puget Sound was the hole in the fence through which they entered. They continued to arrive in British Columbia from Hong Kong in groups of one to seven hundred on English vessels docking every three weeks. Canada gave them ninety days in which to leave the country.<br>
<br>
The United states had been advertised to the Chinese as the promised land. some years prior to passage of the law this country had done considerable recruiting of Oriental labor. When the door was suddenly closed against the Orientals, they continued to take a chance on getting through.<br>
<br>
No penalty was attached to any Chinese making the attempt and when caught he did not have to pay his expenses back to his starting place. Some  tried so often their faces were familiar to the customs men, who at that time also constituted the immigration service.<br>
<br>
In 1880 statistics showed 3,186 Chinese legally living in Washington. When smuggling commenced the general scheme ws to channel newly arrived Oriental to places where they could be lost among their brethren already in the country.<br>
<br>
Small sailing vessels, ostensibly fishing boats used to lie at anchor at a buoy off the Indian reservation at the entrance to Victor Harbor. Chinese would be taken out to them and transported to a hiding place at James or Sidney Islands. When enough were gathered to make a run advisable, all were picked up from their camp and the sloop made for Dungeness or some place near Port Townsend, arriving after dark and departing in the night.<br>
<br>
The Chinese were instructed how to proceed from the beach to a place of security among their countrymen in a nearby town.<br>
<br>
An opium cargo was a little more difficult because it would not walk to its final destination but had to be carried there by some person.<br>
<br>
A refinery of crude opium existed in Victoria, where the poppy gum was boiled, skimmed and prepared for smoking. It could be imported by paying duty, but evading the tariff by smuggling was more profitable. Another devise was to sweat off the stamps and apply them to cans on which the import tax had not been paid.<br>
<br>
A feature of the illicit traffic was adulteration. A purchaser of smuggled drugs could not squeal. Some revealing entries form the
customs house seizure books read like this:<br>
<br>
"June 2, 1894. New Whatcom--200 cans supposed to contain opium upon examination found to contain a substance resembling tar."<br>
<br>
March 27, 1892--found at Howard and Bryant's wharf, Seattle-five-
tael tins of prepared opium. With them 318 five tael tins containing molasses and flour."<br>
<br>
"June 11, 1892 at Seattle. Four five-tael tins of opium and 349 tins of molasses."<br>
<br>
In July, 1885, more than one hundred twenty pounds of opium were confiscated on Puget Sound. Today the "revenuer" do not pick up that quantity in years. The next month 880 tins or 40 pounds of the narcotic comprised a single haul taken from a sloop at Discovery Bay. The offender, who was apprehended, had among his equipment a revolver, two different types of spy glasses, a call whistle and a bottle of strychnine.<br>
<br>
However, smugglers seldom were caught. The seizure book is filled with entries marked "owner unknown." this was the  case with four trunks containing 1,300 tins found in the Northern Pacific station at Spokane and turned over to the Port Townsend collection.<br>
<br>
Instead of being destroyed, the drug was sold at auction, and the lot brought more than $7,000 a fantastically low sum in terms of present values.<br>
<br>
The seizure book shows frequent losses through cans being thrown overboard or floated ashore. Written in memos are such line as "20 five-tael tins containing salt water mixed with opium and molasses," --double adulteration--and "shipment damaged and leaking water badly."<br>
<br>
The hundreds of reports have a certain sameness. If you put them all together the details fall into a pattern.  Everybody knew about smuggling. The light keeper at Dungeness could see Chinese arriving and being taken ashore in canoes. He saw schooners which always departed by 3:00 o'clock in the morning. When seized, the craft invariably had a fishing net usually rotten and worthless.<br>
<br>
The Orientals landed on the beach. Maybe there was a Chinese garden nearby where the personnel changed frequently. Some nights the dogs at Chimacum set up a mysterious barking. That mean Chinese on the run, trying to reach Port Discovery or some place where friends would push them along.<br>
<br>
Bound books contain telegrams via the Puget Sound Telegraph Company, hand written bearing messages like these:<br>
<br>
"Victoria--Boat leaving tonight for Port Discovery Bay Charley Cook's landing at hotel 400 pounds opium. Probably reach there tomorrow night. Hanson."
"Whatcom--Kelly,(doubtless, Lawrence Kelly of Sinclair Island, most famous smuggler on the Sound in the 1880s) left Bellingham Bay today with stuff for his island. Also another sloop went down the Sound with stuff. W. Wheeler."<br>
<br>
"Victoria--Small sloop about three ton register with white stripes on rail left here 12 o'clock last night for Whatcom l00 pounds on board two men."<br>
<br>
There was money in the business. The Chinese were mostly agriculturists in their homeland. They paid from fifty to one hundred dollars to make the crossing from Victoria and there were plenty of boatmen ready to take the risk. The opium went along with them on the same trip.<br>
<br>
So profitable was smuggling that officials were not above dipping into it, to the scandal of the service. A letter from an agent in Victoria telling of the Canadian Pacific steamer <B>Albany</B> in November 1888 landing a consignment of 6,618 pounds of opium in British Columbia includes this astonishing sidelight on the trade:<br>
<br>
"Singularly enough," the informant wrote, " the well known evangelist Moody appears to be a factor in the suppression of opium smuggling indirectly at least, as h is conversion of Chet Terry, late holding an important position in the custom house in Port Townsend, but who had been in refuge over here form some months, and the restitution by the ex inspector to the United States government of some six thousand dollars through the hand of Moody would prove, I may say, that I know this to be true."<br>
<br>
(Lucile McDonald, "Tracking the Smugglers," <B>Seattle Times.</B> July 27, 1952.).<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
Gordon R. Newell," Smuggling Once Big Business in Tacoma.Huge Ring Smashed By Ledger's Expose," <B>Tacoma Sunday Ledger-News Tribune.</B> November 21, 1954.<br>
<br>
When the Alaska steamer <B>Portland</B> entered Puget Sound on July 17, 1897 she carried a fabulous cargo that was to bring fame to herself and prosperity to the Pacific Northwest. Her cargo, of course, was the legendary "ton of gold" that sparked the Klondyke stampede; the Alaska gold rush. To this day the <B>Portland</B> has maintained her place in western shipping annals as the Alaskan treasure ship.<br>
<br>
Not so well known is the old ship's even earlier history; a history of smuggling, graft and corruption that rocked the nation. Under another name, the famous <B>Portland</B> carried on one of the greatest smuggling operations ever engineered, operating for a ring that included government customs officers, political and financial leaders and even a special agent of the United States Secret
Service. So powerful was the gang of smugglers that its members seemed beyond the reach of the law. . . until a reporter from <B>The Tacoma Ledger</B> stepped into the picture. His one-man crusade smashed the mighty criminal syndicate in a ruin of prison sentences and lost fortunes.<br>
<br>
The <B>Portland</B> was built at Bath, Maine, in 1885, serving as an Atlantic coastal liner for several years under the name Haytian Republic. She retained that name when in the early 1890s she was transferred to the Pacific Coast, operating between San Francisco, Portland and Tacoma for a firm known as Merchants Steamship Company. The firms legitimate shipping activities were largely a front for the smuggling of opium and alien Chinese from Canada into the United States.<br>
<br>
Money In Chinese<br>
<br>
At that time it was perfectly legal to import opium, providing the duty of $12 a pound were paid, but by evading this payment smugglers could make vast profits on the drug. Sums ranging from $100 to $150 a head were being paid for the delivery of "contraband" Chinese from Canada to the United States. The Haytian Republic, along with the Michigan and Wilmington of the same firm, were the carriers of this lucrative freight.<br>
<br>
Small boats, met the incoming liners in the Straits of Juan de Fuca; coolies and dope were quickly and efficiently transferred. Tacoma, the line's Puget Sound terminus, was the distribution point for the incoming cargoes. It was common knowledge that most of the trains leaving Tacoma carried from 10 to 100 pounds of undeclared opium for the firm's southern outlets; that Chinese by the hundreds were being moved out of town by night.<br>
<br>
Everyone seemed to know about it, but no one did anything about it; no one except Nelson A. Bennett, who was then owner and publisher of <B>The Tacoma Ledger.<br>
</B><br>
Bennett called in assistant editor and special writer Stephen W. De Lacy. De Lacy was just back from covering the 1893 session of the legislature at Olympia, where he had done an outstanding job. Bennett felt he was just the man for another important assignment. The conference ended in a well simulated quarrel, and De Lacy stamped out of the publisher's office, loudly announcing that he was "through working for The Ledger."<br>
<br>
From then on he was on his own, picking up his pay and expenses through a bank rather than at the newspaper office. His special assignment was known only to himself and Bennett.<br>
<br>
Begins at Victoria<br>
<br>
Going first to Victoria, where he felt most of the illegal shipments originated, De Lacy conferred with an old newspaper friend, Martin Egan at the office of the Victoria Times. Egan, who
later became a noted Associated Press war correspondent in the Russo-Japanese war, agreed to help him.<br>
<br>
Working together, the two newsmen made several interesting discoveries, among them the fact that a special secret service agent, assigned to break up the smuggling ring, appeared to be one of its leading members. Almost all the customs personnel were either in the deal or going around with their eyes shut. The one exception was an inspector named Coblentz, who met De Lacy secretly, confirmed what was going on, and agreed to keep him supplied with information. But even Coblentz, an honest cop, was afraid to openly testify against the powerful combine.<br>
<br>
Things were stalemated when De Lacy got his big break. The smuggling steamers Michigan and Wilmington were wrecked. The Wilmington losing a valuable shipment of both Chinese immigrants and opium. The syndicate refused to make good the costs of the lost shipment, and a Victoria wholesaler was left holding the bag to the tune of some $15,000, a sizable loss in the 1890s.<br>
<br>
Canadian newsman Egan saw his opportunity. He convinced the unhappy Canadian exporter that De Lacy was a United States government agent who could probably get back at least a part of his lost fortune for him if he cooperated in exposing the syndicate.<br>
<br>
Exporter Tells All<br>
<br>
The Canadian jumped at the bait. When De Lacy denied having any connection with the government, the smuggler merely attributed it to the natural reticence of an authentic secret service operative. He was thoroughly disgusted with smuggling as a profession, desired to clear his conscience, and he wouldn't take no for an answer.<br>
<br>
Trying not to show his elation, De Lacy saw the case breaking Wide open. The Canadian furnished him with a stack of letters, telegrams and receipts from the smuggling syndicate, along with a copy of the key by which all of them could be deciphered.<br>
<br>
It was all the proof he needed. Special officers were dispatched from Washington, D.C., and when the Haytian Republic next entered port she was searched by inspectors who didn't have their eyes shut. Five hundred ounces of opium were found behind the canned foods stacked on the galley shelves.<br>
<br>
Then the coded papers unearthed by De Lacy were published in The Ledger with the key by which they could be translated from the language of legitimate business to the parlance of thieves. Ledger readers had a wonderful time working out the smugglers; code for themselves, the greatest scoops in West Coast journalistic history, and the criminal syndicate was finished.<br>
<br>
Some Fled Country<br>
<br>
The crooked secret service agent got a year in prison and a $5,000
fine, as did a number of ex-customs agents. Others arrested included the U.S. collector of customs at Portland, along with 11 of his staff, the president of the Merchants' Steamship Company, and many of its stockholders. Others, tipped off in advance, boarded Orient-bound ships before warrants could be served on them. Nearly all of those arrested were convicted and sent to prison, while the U.S. Customs Service underwent the greatest shake-up in its history.<br>
<br>
Ironically, the honest cop, Coblentz, met as tragic a fate as any of the guilty. Appointed warden of the state prison at Walla Walla, he committed suicide when minor irregularities were found in the prison accounts - a man who had turned down dishonest thousands becoming the victim of petty graft. The newsman, De Lacy, was appointed United States deputy collector of customs at Tacoma, a position which he held for many years.<br>
<br>
And the old Haytian Republic, seized and sold at auction by the government, became the famed Alaskan liner <B>Portland</B>, bringing a ton of gold and a whole new era to the Puget Sound country. Years later her amazing past almost forgotten; she was carrying ore between Alaska and the Tacoma smelter until her final stranding at the Kalalla River mouth in 1910. So ended the adventurous career of a ship that proved again the truth of the ancient adage:<br>
<br>
Truth is stranger than fiction!<br>
<br>
Gordon R. Newell, "Smuggling once a big business in Tacoma," <B>Tacoma Sunday Ledger-News Tribune.</B> November 21, 1954.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
In Judge Allyn's court February 29, Mrs. Lou Smith and Mrs. Lizzie Lewis pleaded guilty to a charge of smuggling and were fined $50 and costs which they paid.  The two women, each carrying a baby, 
came down the gangplank of the steamer Idaho January <B>31 </B>preceded by one of the boat's men who carried a large valise belonging to them.<br>
<br>
Deputy Collector J.. H. Price and Inspector of Customs J. B. Croake stopped the party and upon searching the valise found it to contain forty-five pounds of unstamped opium.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
Herbert Hunt, "Smuggling opium to Tacoma," <B>History of Tacoma.</B> Chicago: S.J.Clarke, 1916 Chapter 35-excerpts.<br>
<br>
The customs officers had known that opium was being smuggled
through Tacoma and December 11, 1889, they searched the steamer Olympia, just arrived from Victoria.  They found no contraband, but officers detailed to watch saw three row boats passing close to the steamer the next day at daylight.  One of the boats landed near Brown's Point and three men began removing packages to the shore where Inspector Billings confronted them.<br>
<br>

The smugglers had <B>130 </B>pounds of opium.  Billings had captured Jack Powers, Freight Conductor Fisher, on the Portland run, and William Easton, or "Black Bill," one of the most dangerous smugglers in the Northwest and a man who had boasted that the officer did not live wbo was sharp enough and brave enough to put him behind the bars.<br>
<br>
A few days before this, John Sullivan, runner for the Hotel Grandolfo, was standing on the railroad wharf shortly after the steamer Hassalo bad departed when be saw several brown paper-covered packages floating in the water.  Sullivan fished them out.  They consisted of seven packages connected with a cord, each containing twenty five-metal cans of opium.  Deputy Collector Hayden estimated its value at $1,050 and one-fourth of this amount later was paid to Sullivan.<br>
<br>
Herbert Hunt, "Smuggling opium into Tacoma," <B>History of Tacoma.</B> Chicago: S.J.Clarke, 1916 Chapter 35-excerpts.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++SMUGGLING.<br>
<br>
R.H. Calkins, "Days of Puget Sound Smugglers," <B>High Tide.</B> Seattle: Marine Digest, 1952, p. 24-27.<br>
<br>
Bizarre attempts to smuggle opium, Chinese and wool into the United States and how Puget Sound virtually was made narcotic proof by two government officers more than 45 years ago, make up one of the most colorful stories in Pacific Northwest shipping.<br>
<br>
Rear Adm.  W. H. Munter, United States Coast Guard, retired, and Roy L. Ballanger, retired assistant collector of customs in the Washington District, had stellar roles in the successful effort to halt the daring operations of smugglers on Puget Sound.<br>
<br>
It was on May 13, 1905, that the government carried into execution long-studied plans to break up the smuggling of wool from Canada to Puget Sound, which was assuming major proportions.<br>
<br>
Wool was 22c a pound higher in the United States than in Canada and successful smugglers reaped a big profit.<br>
<br>
     
Customs Inspectors Ballanger and F. C. Dean left Port Townsend in an open boat and cruised along the San Juan Islands in the guise of seal hunters.  Dean had been a seal hunter before joining the customs service and knew the captains of the boats in this industry of other days.  Ballanger also was valuable to the govemment as he was reared on a farm, knew wool, and could shear a sheep.<br>
<br>
The two inspectors drifted -in their boat off Port Townsend until after dark and then headed for Canada.<br>
<br>
The boat had two pair of oars and carried a sail, and although<br>
the  progress  was  slow,  she  was  able  to  reach  Sydney,  Vancouver Island.<br>
<br>
Visiting all of the islands in the vicinity of Sydney and several sheep ranches, the inspectors told the farmers they were on a vaca-
tion, seeing the country and doing a little sealing In a short time, they had visited aR of the ranches suspected of being operated by wool smugglers.<br>
<br>
Their pockets were full of skewers-wooden pins used in securing meat to form-and while the ranchers, who were shearing sheep, were not looking, the inspectors placed them in the fleece.<br>
<br>
Ballanger and Dean became acquainted with a man by the name of Burke.  They found him loading wool at South Pender Island and followed him.  He crossed over to Orcas Island of the San Juans at night.  There they found a large quantity of wool in a barn.  It contained the skewers they had placed in the fleece.  The inspectors called Munter and he went to Oreas Island in the little Coast Guard cutter Arcata. (She was decommissioned in 1936, and is now only a memory on the waterfront.)<br>
<br>
The Arcata loaded the huge sacks of wool, which measured about seven feet in length and three feet in diameter.  There was so much wool on the deck of the Arcata that it reached almost to the smokestack.  The wool was landed in Port Townsend, where it was sold at govemment auction.<br>
<br>
Burke was arrested and tried in Seattle on a charge of smuggling, but the judge ruled he was not really seen crossing the border with the wool and he was released because of insufficient evidence.<br>
<br>
These were the days of "Pig Iron" Kelly and Larry Kelly, notorious opium smugglers, when it was lawful to import the drug if the duty of $12 a pound was paid.
There was an opium plant in Victoria, known as the Ly Yuen factory and one in Vancouver, known as the Ty Yuen factory.  Crude opium from India and China was cooked and made into round chunks as big as a bowling ball.  The opium, the gum and the sap of the poppy, was put into a copper pan over a charcoal fire.  As it cooked, it was stirred and skinnned by the Chinese.<br>
<br>
A big traffic in opium developed.  Firemen on ships had pockets in the back of their vests in which they carried the opium.  They wore large box-hanging coats to conceal the drug and carried between ten and twelve cans.  The smugglers, obtaining the opium in British Columbia, made about $5 a pound by avoiding the duty.<br>
<br>
Then came the embargo against opium and the drug reached the coast on ships from the Orient.  The Coast Guard began trailing vessels arriving from China and India as they came up the Sound, and when they shifted from dock to dock, to prevent opium smugglers from tossing the drug overboard to confederates.  Men also were placed in rowboats under the docks.<br>
<br>
Smugglers of Chinese did not stop at anything if they believed they were trapped.  They threw the Chinese overboard when they saw a Coast Guard cutter approaching.  Those who got through were<br>
landed on a lonely beach and walked until the boat operator met a confederate.<br>
<br>
Smugglers usually received from $100 to $500 a head for the<br>
successful delivery of Chinese in the United States.<br>
<br>
Puget Sound now is virtually narcotic-proof, wool-smuggling is just a story of other days, and the smuggling of Chinese seldom is attempted.<br>
<br>
Retiring from the Coast Guard, Admiral Munter "dropped anchor" here and now makes his home in Seattle.  As an active member of the Propeller Club, he keeps in close touch with maritime affairs and his many friends in the shipping industry.<br>
<br>
Admiral Munter came to Seattle in 1938 from Washington, D. C., where he was chairman of the Coast Guard's permanent board, which formulates Coast Guard policy.<br>
<br>
During his long tour of duty, Admiral Munter served 24 years in ships of the old Revenue Cutter Service and the Coast Guard.  He
was a lieutenant in the cutter Grant on Puget Sound during the winter of 1902 and 1903, made cruises in the cutter Manning to Bering Sea and Honolulu, and in 1925, visited Seattle as a member of a Coast Guard board.  He retired April 1, 1944 after nearly 45 years of Coast Guard service.<br>
<br>
Ballanger retired May 31, 1946 after 45 years in the United States Customs Service.  He died April 24, 1950.<br>
<br>
R.H. Calkins, "Days of Puget Sound Smugglers," <B>High Tide. The Big Stories of Seattle's Waterfront. </B> Seattle: Marine Digest, 1952, p. 23-27<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
LARRY KELLY.<br>
<br>
The career of one of the Northwest's most notorious opium smugglers was ended is recalled by a revolver deposited with the Washington State historical society yesterday by Fred E. King of Puyallup.  The gun is a 32 caliber Smith & Wesson made to shoot rifle bullets.<br>
<br>
It was taken from Larry Kelly, for 32 years a successful smuggler, when he was caught by King and his associate, Fred C. Dean, July 18, 1908. He was captured near Anderson island as he was on the way to Olympia with a sloop load of opium for the peddlers who made their headquarters there.<br>
<br>
Said to have had powerful connections which reached even to the higher-ups at Washington, Kelly had for more than a quarter of a century been a thorn in the flesh of the Northwest federal men.  He got by when nobody else could but he came to grief when he failed to recognize a revenue launch which King and camouflaged as a fish boat.<br>
<br>
King, who was stationed at Tacoma, had been detailed by Collector C.W. Ide to look out for Pete Nelson and his partner, small fry smugglers, when he had a hunch that he was on Kelly's trail.  He reported to headquarters and Dean, then connected with the Port Townsend office, was sent to help him run down the clues.<br>
<br>
FIND CONNECTIONS IN OLYMPIA<br>
<br>
King had discovered that Kelly was dealing through a Chinese store at Olympia, running the opium from Victoria in a small sloop.  From
an ambush on Anderson island he watched Kelly's boat come and go and when he was sure of the schedule, sent to headquarters for a launch.<br>
<br>
At that time nearly every resident on the islands had a gas boat with a license number painted on the bow and usually had a log or timber picked up on the Sound towing behind.  When King's launch was left for him at McNeills island it was one of the regulation boats with a "watermelon" top and customs service written all over it.<br>
<br>
The first thing he did was to take the launch to the other side of the island, paint a number on the bow with charcoal, take off the top, and hitch a boom log on behind.  That little strategy turned the trick.<br>
<br>
King and Dean waited a few days longer and one morning saw Kelly's sloop headed down Sound. He had slipped by them and was going back to Victoria for another load.  King figured that he would be back in 10 days and made his plans accordingly.<br>
<br>
KELLY SAILS INTO THE ARMS OF THE LAW.<br>
<br>
Sure enough, 10 days later the federal men saw Kelly's sloop coming through the Narrows and started out to intercept him.  He paid no attention to the launch with a couple of ranchers chugging diagonally toward his course from Anderson island until it was too late.<br>
<br>
Like all the big crooks, Kelly knew when he was beaten and submitted to arrest.  When he turned his gun over he told King he hoded he might have it for his own because it was a "good one."<br>
<br>
Caught with the boat load of opium, it wasn't long before Kelly was serving a twoyear term on McNeil island.<br>
<br>
Because he was a model prisoner, Kelly was able to cut a few months from his term and had been out only a short time when he was back at the old aame.  A little while after a border patrol found him asleep near a campfire with 10 pounds of opium.<br>
<br>
That brought him a year's sentence and for a time after he was released he dropped out of sight.  One day a man was reported apparently very ill in a miserable shack on the beach near Port Townsend and a customs launch was sent to bring him in.  It was Kelly.  The customs men took him to the marine hospital at Port Townsend where de died a few days later, broke and friendless.<br>

<br>
The men with whom he had associated and assisted to make large profits from the illicit opium traffic, and the crooked officials and other grafters who had chiseled into his earnings, all deserted him when they found he could no longer keep out of the law's clutches.<br>
<br>
Of course, nobody having official connection would be expected to verify it, but there is plenty of evidence "off the record" to indicate that Kelly and others of his kind did not operate without sanction from some of those high in authority in Washington.<br>
<br>
It also is not going beyond the bounds of probability to say that certain Northwest business men who held their heads rather high profited from the activities of Kelly and other smugglers.<br>
<br>
In fact, Kelly's first arrest, when he was operating in Oregon, ijas due to an official with whom he had to split.  It seems that Kelly was due to meet this official at a certain time but in some way they missed connections.  The official assumed that Kelly had double-crossed him and turned him in.  A little while later the tables were turned and the official was behind the bars.<br>
<br>
Larry Kelly came to the end which is sooner or later reached by all who think they can beat the law, including the grafters who profit from ill gotten gains.  You just can't beat the game.<br>
<br>
King, retired, lives at Puyallup.  Dean is still in the service and is connected with the Seattle office.<br>
<br>
E. T. Short, "The end of Lawrence Kelly," <B>The Tacoma Times.<br>
</B><br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
SMUGGLING<br>
<br>
Lucile S. McDonald, "A place for smugglers," <B>Making History, the people who shaped the San Juan Islands.</B> Friday Harbor: Harbor Press, 1990 p. 99-103.<br>
<br>
Smuggler's Row, a little bay on the east side of Henry Island, was named for the contrabandists who long ago ran in there for shelter after crossing Haro Strait with cargoes of opium, Chinese or wool.  I suppose it is the place where Deputy Customs Inspector O.H. Culver boarded Jim Kelly's boat Success in May 1889 and found the smuggler asleep, his small son on watch.<br>
<br>
"He came up with a revolver.  I was not prepared for a fight with an armed desperado such as Kelly had every appearance of being,"
Culver reported.<br>
<br>
The inspector uncovered no suspicious evidence; he had no choice but to bid farewell to Kelly.  Some officer better prepared would catch up with the smuggler sooner or later.<br>
<br>
The Kelly name is famed in the San Juans, but Lawrence Kelly, not Jim, was the real celebrity.  Tales told about Larry are more numerous than known facts.  Though his name is a byword, I found the two unrelated Kellys often confused and the written records were lean.  With good reason Larry courted little publicity.  His livelihood required anonyn-dty and seclusion.<br>
<br>
Lawrence Kelly was born in 1845, but records it was in Ohio or Ireland.  The federal census-taker never caught up with him.<br>
<br>
Larry Kelly was said to have begun his career on the coast of Maine smuggling mostly bonded whiskey.  When things became uncomfortable forhim he moved to Alaska and operated there until his profession again became difficult.  He is said to have been a sailor on a vessel which called at New Orleans at the outbreak of the Civil War.  There he enlisted in the Louisiana Tigers and fought for the Confederacy.  He told his children he had been a drummer.<br>
<br>
Kelly arrived in Seattle about 1872 and sometime between that year and 1878 established himself onthesouthwestpoint of Guemeslsland, which today bears his name.  He married Lizzie Kotz in 1877 when she was 16 and he was 32.  They had nine children in quick succession.<br>
<br>
Kelly's cabin was in the woods back of a bluff commanding a far-
reaching view of Rosario Straitand Guemes and Bellingham Channels.  This was a definite asset in his chosen profession.  Hehadalater base on Sinclair Island, half of which he purchased in March 1886.<br>
<br>
A few months afterward he deeded the property to Lizzie, to safeguard it from confiscation in case he had any brushes with the law.<br>
<br>
Smuggling from Vancouver Island to the Washington coast had been going on almost from the beginning of settlement of the San Juans.  The hidden coves and winding waterways, which afforded refuge for deserters from British naval vessels, were similarly encouraging for concealing staple purchases from Victoria.<br>
<br>
Customs authorities complained of "the great and increasing evil" among settlers, some of whom were storekeepers living with Indian women, whom they sent by canoe across Haro Strait for goods.  The
women returned at night with three to five tons of merchandise, landing them in places the revenue men could not reach.  So easy was it to hide contraband in the islands, the Roche Harbor inspector complained in 1897<br>
<br>
"Smugglers waltz up to the customs house in ballast, having left their stuff within easy reach in little harbors.  " After clearing with the officer, they went back and retrieved the hidden goods and continued merrily on their way.  Ordinary wool was a cargo which tempted reputable citizens.  Right after the shearing season inspectors watched for crossings to Henry, Spieden and Stuart Islands with Canadian fleece, which some ranchers took a chance on mixing with their own.<br>
<br>
Smuggler Larry Kelly dealt in more dangerous cargoes -- Oriental laborers, opium and Chinese wine.  It required anotherbrand of daring toengageinhisline.  Hewasthemosthuntedmaninsmugglingcircles in the Puget Sound country for more than two decades.<br>
<br>
The Chinese exclusion act of 1882 made smuggling Orientals a profitable business if one could get by with it.  Chinese in British Columbia willingly paid $100 or more to be put ashore inside the promised land of the Pacific Northwest, where they slipped away to build railroads and work in mines.<br>
<br>
To checkmate the smugglers, an immigration inspector, John M. Izett, was sent to Friday Harbor in May 1882.  In August 1883 the port of entry was changed to Roche Harbor.  Izett, besides his other duties, went out in a skiff and watched the entrance to San Juan Channel early in the morning and late in the evening.  It was a futile and lonely job because he lacked an adequate boat.<br>
<br>
With the influx of Chinese there was a demand for opium and wines the laborers had known in their own country- Kelly, specializing in all three items, was a clever fox, with a hundred hiding places.  One sympathizes with poor Izett, in his rowboat, when he received notification in October 1882 that Kelly had left Victoria in his sloop, with 20 cases of wine.  "Do what you can to take him," were Izett's instructions.  He hadn't a Chinaman's chance.<br>
<br>
The popular belief prevails that Kelly and others of his ilk, if stopped by the revenue service cutters, threw their cargo, live or packages, overboard.  This seems to have been largely a myth.  Official records made no such accusations, nor even hinted at them.  But Chinese evidently wereput ashorebysmugglers on barren rocks, such as Goose Island in San Juan Channel, when a cutter was in pursuit.<br>
<br>
A picnic party camped at Davis Bay on the south side of Lopez
Island in 1885 reported seeing an Oriental brou- ght in, weak and ill, from a barren islet called Deadman Island.  "He seemed to have been abandoned," said the narrator.  "That same day a boat load of his countrymen from the Flowery Kingdom came gliding in, occupying a smart clinker-built boat propelled by white oarsmen.  It soon appeared that a smuggler of Chinese had brought his cargo out of sight ... he pretended to have rescued them from a perilous position."<br>
<br>
A yarn is told about Square Bay on the northeast corner of Guemes Island.    Anold resident saw Kelly's sloop anchored in the small harbor.  The two men chatted a while, then Kelly shouted, "Come out, John, he's O.K., " whereupon the tall grass erupted Chinese.  One seemed to have been hiding behind every bush around the bay.<br>
<br>
The law first caught up with Kelly on December 21,1882, when his sloop was seized at LaConner with 40 cases of red and white Chinese wine on board.  He was fined $160.  Kelly was in the sloop at the time of its capture, but the loss did not discourage him.  On July 3,1883, he paid another fine of $390 and on the following November 17, $20.<br>
<br>
Then in January 1884, customs inspector John M. Izett received a typical communication from the collector of customs, saying: "An English sloop took on board at Cadboro Bay 130 pounds of opium and mostlikely will cross to StuartandWaldron Islands and transfer it to an American sloop.  We think it goes to Whatcom.  The opium is in tin boxes of 15 pounds each.<br>
<br>
A Chinaman at Cadboro Bay appears to be in on the transaction and may accompany the vessel to make the delivery. (Larry) Kelly is at his old trade, running opium and wine.  He had over 80 cases a short time ago.  He has a long black sloop, narrow, with a small house forward. Some time she is in a rowboat.  He says no custom<br>
<br>
house man can take him."<br>
<br>
Kelly managed to remain out of the clutches of the officers until May 16, 1886, when his Whitehall boat, sail and oars were seized at Tacoma.  He had on board 567 tins of prepared opium, equivalent to 364 pounds of drugs.  They cost him another $100 fine, but the profits in these illicit wares were high.<br>
<br>
Officers continued to watch the smuggler king.A February l,1889, telegram from Bellingham reported, "Kelly left Bellingham today with stuff for his island." By then he was a resident of Sinclair, where he bought the homestead of Thomas P. Hogin and became a member of the island school board, as he had several children.<br>

Things went well with him the next two years, but in March l891 he came up against the real thing in enforcement.  Special Agent Charles  Mulkey saw the smuggler riding in the smoking car of a train en route from Tacoma to Portland, a large new russet-colored leather valise carefully parked at his feet.<br>
<br>
When Mulkey inquired as to its contents Kelly answered, "Clothing." Mulkey was suspicious and opened the bag.  In it he found 65 cans of opium, worth about $450.<br>
<br>
Kelly declared angrily and profanely that no revenue officer was going to take him, but Mulkey was firm and transferred Larry to a north bound train at Castle Rock.  Mulkey took along as witness the man who occupied the seat with Kelly.  When Kelly was arraigned the same day, he declared the bag was not his.  He said he had left his grip on the seat when he went to the washroom and on his return found it had been replaced by another.<br>
<br>
A newspaper account of the case stated Kelly had recently fitted out a new sloop for his cruises.  It had no name, was very fast, and its owner kept an arsenal of revolvers and pistols on a small shelf near the tiller.  "About two months ago," it added, "Canadian authorities offested Kelly at Victoria and fined him $300 for leaving the harbor without clearing.  A few years ago he was tried in Tacoma, convicted of smuggling and served a term in the penitentiary."<br>
<br>
Kelly's bond was set at $1,000, but the customs men were not through with him.  Two days later they descended on his hideout at Sinclairlsland and seized the sloop which was sold at a marshal's sale, after his trial, for $3,221.<br>
<br>
The smuggler's luck was running out.  His wife sold portions of his island in 1894 and 1896 and after that he owned no property.  Smug-
gling of Chinese diminished, the British Columbia authorities having tightened their surveillance.<br>
<br>
Lizzie Kelly quit living with her errant spouse in March 1898 and, to support herbrood, was keeping house for a man in Anacortes whose wife was hospitalized.  One day Kelly got drunk and, anned with a<br>
revolver, paid a call on LIzzie, announcing he was about to kill her.  She fled to a neighbor and the town marshal went looking for Kelly, who returned next day, rattled the door and announced he was still out for blood.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Kelly filed a complaint, charging assault with a dangerous weapon and declared Larry had "shown a willful, malignant and abandoned heart."<br>

The case was dismissed by the superior court the following January and Kelly was not heard of again until the customs men received word he was making trips out of Victoria.  It was 1902 before he was picked up in Portland and sent to the county jail for having $800 worth of opium in his possession.<br>
<br>
In January 1905 he was caught in Tacoma with 120 cans of the drug aboard a sloop.  That brought him another term in federal prison.<br>
Kelly learned no lessons from incarceration.  In May 1909 he pleaded guilty to another smuggling charge and once more spent a year at the McNeil Island prison.  It was said that in attempting to escape when taken into custody he jumped off a train and was badly injured.<br>
<br>
On his release he drifted away.  Old and broken, he got in touch with the Daughters of the Confederacy and was admitted to a Confederate soldiers' home in Louisiana, where he died.<br>
<br>
Larry Kelly outlived all of the region's most daring and successful smugglers.  The man so often confused with him, Jim or "Red" Kelly, dropped dead of heart failure at a salmon trap on October 1, 1908.  He, too, served a ten-n at McNeil Island after customs officers lay in wait for him at Kanaka Bay and watched him unload five Chinese.<br>
<br>
Lucile S. McDonald, "A place for smugglers," <B>Making Histroy; the people who shaped the San Juan Islands.</B> Friday Harbor,Washington: Harbor Press, 1990. p.99-103.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
SMUGGLERS AND OTHER GENTLEMEN<br>
<br>
David Richardson, "Smugglers and other gentlemen," <B>Pig War Islands.</B> Eastsound: Orcas Publishing Company, 1971, p. 256-276.<br>
<br>
Thus was the stage set for the golden age of smuggling on Puget Sound, and once again the San Juan Islands -due to their strategic location practically astride the border - found themselves in the center of that stage, playing host to chief actors like Jim "Pig-Iron" Kelly and Larry "Smuggler" Kelly, Bill "Old Man" Jamieson, and Henry Ferguson, better known as "the Flying Dutchman."<br>
<br>
The two Kellys were often confused in newspaper stories, and still are in the legends they left behind.  They were not related, and differed markedly in the way they plied their craft.  Larry was known up and down the Sound as "king" of the smuggling fraternity, apparently because he was heard of the most - the reason being that he got caught so often! Nevertheless, his fame remains such that
whenever the roster of Puget Sound contrabandistas is called, it is his name which generally heads the list.<br>
<br>
Lawrence Kelly was born about 1839, of Irish parents, probably in that country or in England.  As a youth he served a hitch in the British army, later became a deep-water sailor.  After seeing a good deal of the world he chanced to put in at New Orleans just as the Civil War was erupting.<br>
<br>
Kelly left his ship and joined a Confederate outfit, the "Louisiana Tigers," with which he fought up to the moment of Lee's surrender on April 9, 1865.  He then left the South, reputedly vowing he would "never earn an honest living under the stars and stripes," and returned to the sea.<br>
<br>
Later the same year Kelly arrived on the inland waters of the Pacific Northwest aboard the vessel Young America.  Almost immediately he was attempting his first smuggling caper, sneaking a batch of Canadian silks across to the Washington mainland.<br>
<br>
He was promptly caught, and the offense cost him $500 - but without dissuading him from his new-found vocation.<br>
<br>
A decade or so later found Kelly living on the southwestern bulge of Guemes Island, across from Anacortes, with his wife, an Indian woman named Lizzie Kotz.  There he supported himself and his tawny bride with profits gleaned by hauling a miscellany of contraband items from place to place on the Sound.<br>
<br>
Those being the days of scant interference from the undermanned revenue service, Kelly used an ordinary fishing sloop in his work, not even bothering to change the bright red paint job which charac-
terized it - and made it quite visible from a great distance away.<br>
<br>
On those rare occasions when he was spotted by the customs men, he was generally able to outrun his pursuers, or elude them among the Sound's numberless bays and channels, all of which he had come to know like a familiar book.  If all else failed, the outlaw goods were dumped overboard at the last moment, for without them, there could be no conviction.<br>
<br>
Kelly always stuck to sail in his work and has been called the most skillful small-boat handler on Puget Sound.  A crony recalled how the smuggler king would grease his craft with pot black and tallow to cut its resistance in the water.<br>
<br>
Those were the days of the revenue cutter Oliver Wolcott, a
lumbering old tub with a top speed of four knots.  Given any wind at all, Kelly's sloop could sail faster than the Wolcott could steam, and could navigate in passages too narrow, or water too shallow, for the government vessel to follow.<br>
<br>
Eventually, determined revenue officers fitted out one of the Wolcott's small boats with sail, and laid for Kelly.  A witness to the encounter which followed left this account of what happened:<br>
<br>
"The revenue boat was pretty smart before the wind and there was a smart wind and a freshening sea up in the San Juans.  Kelly came bowling down the channel at a great clip.  The revenue boat shot out from the little bay where they were watching for [him].<br>
<br>
"He was pretty close up on the revenue hiding place when the little boat shot out but it never teased him.  He put his helm hard over and swung up into the wind.  He just turned tail like a scared jack rabbit and the way that little sloop of his went flying back toward the north was a sight to see.<br>
<br>
"Kelly had a boat that would sail into the eye of the wind or just as close to it as anything afloat will sail and he knew how to handle her.  She buried her nose in the seas at times till you couldn't see anything but white smother, but she made better weather of it than the revenue boat.  Gradually Kelly drew away and the revenue men sailed back into port, sore all over."<br>
<br>
Kelly's come-uppance came at last one cold, foggy December night in 1882.<br>
<br>
Deputy Customs Inspector Thomas Caine teamed one of the smuggler-king's tricks was to sneak his boat along the shoals of Swinomish Slough, near LaConner, in the early morning.  So Caine staked himself out in the slough and waited quietly.  But the wily Irishman must have suspected something, for as he approached the place where Caine was stationed he slipped overboard into shallow water and began pushing the light boat ahead of him, as soundlessly as possible.<br>
<br>
Caine heard some faint splashing sounds and suddenly the smuggler's craft loomed out of the fog almost in front of him.  The inspector pulled a large service revolver, pointed it and shouted, "I've got you, Kelly!"<br>
<br>
"All right," said the king of smugglers.  "Put up your iron.  I'm your prisoner."<br>
<br>
Kelly's cargo this trip was $400 worth of illegal Chinese wine.  
Worse still, he had a Chinaman aboard, contrary to the months old Exclusion Act.  Fortunately for him, the man was able to convince a judge that he was not a coolie, but a merchant doing business in Portland. Kelly got off with a $150 fine.<br>
<br>
To avoid being classed as laborers many Chinese attached themselves to small businesses, some of which counted their owning "partners" in the dozens was a pittance to Kelly, who was doing so well that a few years later he bought up a 360-acre spread on Sinclair Island, also known as Cottonwood, on the eastem edge of the San Juans.<br>
<br>
The property (prudently placed in wife Lizzie's name) comprised a third of the island, where Kelly - in spite of his profession, ff not actually because of it -was considered a citizen of great uprightness and was even elected to the school board.<br>
<br>
Kelly's place was on the northwest shore of Cottonwood, where he had a commanding view of the Strait of Georgia, and Canada beyond, which helped him keep tabs on the customs vessels.  He was now specializing in the importing of opium, and his usual practice was to haul the drug in relays.<br>
<br>
After purchasing it at one of fourteen licensed refineries in Victoria, he would head for Cottonwood and bury the stuff somewhere along the beach or on his farm.  When the time seemed right he dug up one or more of the caches and headed for Port Townsend, a favorite destination, or Seattle, or elsewhere, and disposed of the drug to an agent for the standard $12-a-pound fee.<br>
<br>
Years later, when he had fallen on hard times, residents of Cottonwood used to see him poking about there, hoping to find in some old hiding place a forgotten packet that could be converted into a few needed dollars.<br>
<br>
Meanwhile, the customs service was becoming decidedly more aggressive in their war on contrabanders.  Gradually, with more manpower and faster boats on the Sound, Kelly and his confreres found themselves being overhauled and searched more and more frequently.<br>
<br>
Of course, they responded by becoming foxier.  Larry Kelly took to tying his opium in a weighted sack and trailing it, submerged, on a line fastened to a ring-bolt under the hull of his boat.  Ultimately inspectors caught onto this stunt, and routinely "keel-hauled" suspected smuggling craft.  Or, if pursued too closely by the revenue cutter, Kelly would sometimes anchor his cargo to a float and return for it when the coast had cleared.<br>
<br>
The cynical mishandling of human contraband became rather
prevalent, with the smuggler-king getting his share of the blame, though there is some doubt whether Larry Kelly went in much for that end of the business.<br>
<br>
Once a band of Chinese were put off "temporarily" on a lonesome rock in San Juan Channel when the revenue boat was bearing down, but the man who collected their fares never came back for them.  They were discovered days later by Reverend T. J. Weekes, emaciated and barely subsiding on clams on a reef which has been called "China Rock" ever since.<br>
<br>
The broad-shouldered Englishman [found by customs agents after they had missed Kelly] was actually Jim "Old Man" Jamieson, another adherent of the Sound's close-knit smuggling fraternity. Jamieson had shipped on square-riggers before he joined the club, and rivaled Larry Kelly in his boat handling ability.  But Jamieson was shrewder, and certainly more audacious, reputedly disdaining to land his Chinese passengers at some hidden, exurban rendezvous: it is said he sailed right into Seattle and discharged his human cargo at Schwabacher's dock, like the other freighters.<br>
<br>
Jamieson always painted his boat green, to blend with the coastline if seen from a distance.  But customs men on the Grant spotted it one bright, chilly February day, just as the Englishman set his course from Victoria to San Juan Island.  He had crossed the boundary line before he discovered the Grant was steaming toward him for all it was worth.<br>
<br>
Jamieson had a near-record load of opium on board and didn't care to get caught with it.  Swinging about smartly he gave the Grant a good race back to Canadian waters, but seeing he wasn't quite going to make it, he began dumping the evidence overboard.  It took fifteen minutes of frantic deep-sixing to dispose of the whole shipment, worth something like $20,000.<br>
<br>
When  Grant came alongside almost as the last tael of opium hit the drink but the relieved and sweating Jamieson was able to get off one of the few great one-liners in the annals of contrabanding: "It's all right, Cap," he shouted up at the Grant's wheelhouse; "I don't need a tow."<br>
<br>
Wool was another dutiable commodity often brought into the country without benefit of a customhouse clearance.  Dean of this branch of the smuggling biz was a diminutive, gray-bearded Shaw Island man named Alfred Burke.<br>
<br>
Burke had a long, slender rowboat stained a dull black color; and during each year's shearing season he would quietly ride the changing tide across Haro Strait to the Gulf Islands - appearing, then, at one sheep ranch after another, offering to trade chickens, tobacco or cash for fleeces.  In his long black coat and slouch hat he became a familiar figure to Canadian islanders, one of whom recalled that he rowed standing up, without feathering his oars,
for fear the sun would reflect from the wet blades.<br>
<br>
Burke easily disposed of the wool to San Juan county ranchers who mixed it with their own output, shipping it to mainland markets at a fine profit: wool was selling for some twenty-two cents a pound more in the States than in Canada then.  The arrangement was thus lucrative to all concerned, except the U.S. Treasury, whose officials became suspicious when they compared the huge figures for wool output in the San Juans with the modest number of sheep.  They knew no flocks in the world could be half so productive!<br>
<br>
The government moved in 1905 to break up what they believed to bc a full-fledged ring of wool smugglers.  On May 13, Inspectors Dean (capturer of Larry Kelly off McNeil Island) and Roy Ballinger left Port Townsend in an open boat, disguised as seal hunters.  Their act was convincing.  Dean had made his living as a sealer before entering government service.  While Ballinger, who had lived in the San Juans (he married a pretty Roche Harbor school-ma'am) had a ranching background and knew wool.<br>
<br>
Under sail and with two pairs of oars, Ballinger and Dean crossed during the darkness to the Canadian islands and began systematic visits to all the sheep ranches they could find.<br>
<br>
"We had our pockets full of skewers, wooden pins used in securing meat in form when roasting," Ballinger recalled years later.  "And when the ranchers, who were shearing sheep, were not looking, we placed them in the fleece.  We would stand around while the men were at work, telling them we were on vacation, seeing the country and doing a little sealing with our boat."<br>
<br>
The inspectors spent a couple of weeks at this, traveling back and forth between the Gulf Islands and the San Juans, where they camped Indian-fashion on the beaches.  Ultimately their rounds brought them to a South Pender Island ranch where their visit chanced to coincide with that of the short, somber-coated fellow from Shaw Island, Alfred Burke.  Ballinger and Dean came upon him as he was loading wool he had bought into his lead colored dory, struck up a conversation, and had their suspicions aroused.<br>
<br>
Toward evening Burke put out into the Strait with his furtive-
appearing craft.  The two inspectors followed at a discreet dis-
tance and as the dory disappeared into the darkness they concluded its destination was Orcas Island.  Ballinger and Dean headed for Orcas too, poked around there and at length located half a ton of skewer-marked wool in a warehouse belonging to the storekeeper, W. E. Sutherland.<br>
<br>

Burke was arrested at his Blind Bay home, tried for smuggling and acquitted on grounds the inspectors hadn't actually seen him cross the border with the contraband.  But the government's efforts were not wasted: the wool was confiscated and sold at auction in Port Townsend so that from Uncle Sam's point of view this particular crime paid - and handsomely.<br>
<br>
Sutherland was not the only merchant in the Islands to benefit from the enterprise of smugglers.  A West Sound pioneer recalled that 0. H. Smaby's store in that community never sold sugar except in bulk - because the sacks all had Canadian labels on them.  Smaby's source for the sugar, and perhaps other commodities, was probably Victor McConnell, son of a pioneer family.<br>
<br>
McConnell's dad having died in a shipwreck off Vancouver Island, Victor lived with his blind, respected mother and five brothers and sisters on the island which bears his family's name, until discovery of his extra-mural activities led them to request that he find another domicile.<br>
<br>
McConnell is said never to have crossed the border empty: hauled everything from apples to shoes to the Canadian side, in exchange for the sugar and other staples "imported" on the return trip.<br>
Somewhat surprisingly, one of the more popular cargoes when Canada-bound was playing-cards - an item made cheaper IYY Yankee mass-production methods in the States than in the land of the maple leaf.<br>
<br>
The activities of men Eke Burke and McConnell, and even the two Kellys, were largely looked on with something between tolerance and admiration by San Juan Islands people, who certainly had nothing to fear personally from any of these entrepreneurs.  But it was another story with Henry Ferguson, the fast-hitting pirate-smuggler-thief whose wide-ranging exploits earned him the nickname, "The Flying Dutchman."<br>
<br>
Ferguson had once been a member of Butch Cassidy's notorious "Hole in the Wall" gang of Wyoming badmen.<br>
<br>
When vigilantes and the U.S. Cavalry finally made things too hot for them there, Ferguson changed his name to Wagner and lit out for the Pacific Northwest.  He arrived in the late 'nineties and promptly embarked on a career of highway and high sea robbery which terrorized island and seacoast dwellers from Vancouver Island to Olympia.<br>
<br>
Ferguson's trademark was the stolen boat.  He used a succession of them, reworking and repainting each one so speedily it would be unrecognizable overnight.  In such craft he sped from place to place on the Sound, smuggling opium and Chinamen, stealing from
fish traps and logging booms, looting stores and warehouses, sometimes commandeering whole cargoes from small Sound freighters.<br>
<br>
Ferguson's home was in his hat, but he had several hide-outs, including a cabin in the San,juans where he hid his money and received mysterious light signals from the Canadian side.  Another retreat was on little Skagit Island, just in the maw of narrow Deception Pass between Fidalgo and Whidbey Islands.<br>
<br>
It was here that sheriff's officers finally cornered him in October, 1901, and captured him after a prolonged shoot-out.  He was prosecuted for a warehouse burglary committed at Stanwood the year before.  So for the next several years his hat had stripes on it, and his home was the State penitentiary at Walla Walla.<br>
<br>
Skagit Island proved to be the stamping ground of Benjamin Ure, once a wealthy Anacortes landowner whose holdings were lost in a real estate panic.  Sheriff Luther Weedin discovered Ure had also been in the customs service at one time, but before that he was a notorious smuggler of fire-water into Camp Pickett during the joint occupation.<br>
<br>
Now he made a business of sheltering criminals Eke Ferguson, making his secluded island available as a way-point for stolen and smuggled goods, and a gathering place for the scum of Puget Sound generally.<br>
<br>
Weedin put Ure out of business but an indulgent parole board returned Ferguson to society after he served a portion of his fourteen-year sentence, and the "Dutchman" promptly picked up his old career with new vigor.<br>
<br>
But Ferguson made the mistake of robbing several post offices, including one at Langley, Washington, for which he was indicted in absentia by a Grand jury.  United States Attorney Elmer Todd got a special appropriation to finance a Sound-wide search for Ferguson, but the effort failed.  Contemptuously, the "Dutchman" again entered the same Langley post office in 1912 and stole not only the government's cash, but the safe that contained it.<br>
<br>
Another costly expedition over Puget Sound waters was authorized but Ferguson remained at large.<br>
<br>
Finally in March 1913, Ferguson and an accomplice were surprised by Canadian constables in the act of robbing a store on Vancouver Island.  One of the officers was killed in the wild shooting affray which followed, but when the dust settled the "Dutchman" was on the floor with two pairs of manacles about his wrists.<br>

A Canadian court tried Ferguson - alias Wagner - for murder and sentenced him to death.<br>
<br>
Ferguson, who had sworn he would never be hanged for his crimes, tried to make good his vow by beating his brains out against the walls of his cell; but alert guards restrained him and on August 28, 1913, after drinking a cup of coffee, he walked unaided to the jail-yard scaffold and paid the penalty for which he had so long been marked.<br>
<br>
"Old Man" Jamieson was another who died violently, stopping a slug from a Treasury agent's pistol in a midnight confrontation near Seattle's Alki Point.<br>
<br>
Jim Kelly, too, was in action almost to his last breath.  In September 1908 Friday Harbor's deputy collector, 0. H. Culver,<br>
spotted "Pig-Iron" crossing from Victoria in a small boat and alerted customs officials, who again missed catching him with the goods on board.<br>
<br>
But Kelly's continuing habit of flashing large sums of money about convinced them that the 60-year-old smuggler had not yet retired from his chosen trade and for the next few weeks they kept a particularly close watch on him.  Thus a customs man may even have been present at supper time on the first day of October when Kelly sat down to table on board a pile driver at a fish trap near Seattle.  After eating this hearty meal Kelly got up, stretched himself and fell over dead.<br>
<br>
His passing, attributed to heart failure, occasioned a telegram from Puget Sound officials to Washington, in which interlinear sighs of relief not un-mixed with a certain note of admiration and regret, sounded clearly through the jargon of formal text.<br>
<br>
Thus ended the prolonged battle between determined government inspectors and the last of the best of the Puget Sound smuggling fraternity.<br>
<br>
But it was only a battle.  The war would flare anew a generation later.  For the ill-starred Volstead Act would plunge the nation into an era of speakeasies, bathtub gin, rum-running and hijacking, in which all the exploits of Puget Sound's smugglers would be as nothing compared to the intrepidity of their spiritual successors.<br>
<br>
David Richardson, "Smugglers and other gentlemen," <B>Pig War Islands. </B>Eastsound: Orcas Publishing Company, 1971, p. 256-276.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
SMUGGLING.<br>
<br>
David Richardson, "The Noble Disaster," <B>Pig War Islands.</B> Eastsound: Orcas Publishing Company, 1971, p. 308-325.<br>
<br>
No one can say that prohibition  was rammed down the throats of the American public.  Landslide local-option votes had spread a patchwork of legal sobriety across the land long before Mr. Volstead put pen to paper on the subject.<br>
<br>
The Eighteenth Amendment was ratified in all states but two, many of the legislatures - Washington's included - voting unanimously in favor.  Such was the overwhenning popular support for what Herbert Clark Hoover caged in his enthusiasm "a great social and economic experiment, noble in motive and far reaching in purpose."<br>
<br>
But local option was one thing; border-to-border abstinence was another.  Many a man who once voted to drive the saloon out of his home bailiwick., secure in the secret knowledge that he himself could slip away and bend his elbow in the other fellow's town when the span was on him, found the universality of the new statute intolerable.<br>
<br>
In such a circumstance he indulged himself to bend the law, ever so slightly, thereby giving secure employment to those who could cheerfully shatter it to bits.<br>
<br>
A goodly share of the shattering took place in the waters of western Washington and British Columbia wherc the San Juans,<br>
as in the bad old days of Chinese and opium smuggling, found themselves center-stage again.  In the Pacific Northwest, "just off the boat" generally meant one's booze had been newly spirited across the salt chuck border in a fast night-time dash through the archipelago's twisty channels.<br>
<br>
Rum-running into Washington State was big business even before national prohibition.  It was relatively safe, then, for the Coast Guard was still trying to patrol Puget Sound and the Straits with the same old, tired boats in which the revenue service had chased the likes of "Pig-Iron" Kelly and Henry Wagner.<br>
<br>
Still there were occasional captures.  The Journal ran a Iocal-
boy-makes-good item once in 1917 when the Scout, whose commander then was the son of a prominent Lopez farmer, overhauled a launch in which 750 bottles of choice liquors were found concealed.  A year later the tables were turned as the Arcata seized $6ooo worth of Scotch and Canadian whiskeys from a boat whose master turned out to be a Friday Harbor merchant, Sam Bugge.<br>

Bugge had represented San Juan County in the State Legislature in an earlier decade, which indicates the stature of some of the men being lured by the profits offered in this fast-burgeoning industry.<br>
<br>
Passage of the Eighteenth Amendment created a vastly increased market, ensuring even greater profits for everyone in the business.  A bottle of the "real thing," costing a mere fifty cents or so in hundred-case lots in Victoria, fetched perhaps $2.25 on delivery to an intrepid American smuggler, the loading taking place at night in some lonesome, prearranged rendezvous.<br>
<br>
The "rummy" paid in cash, of course, then made his bee-line -
without benefit of running lights - for the U.S. side.  There he might dispose of his liquid cargo to a shifty-looking gentleman driving a fast late-model car, and collect maybe $7 the copy.<br>
<br>
Ultimately this same four-bit booze would be dispensed by your<br>
friendly neighborhood bootlegger or hotel "bottle man" for something closer to twelve bucks.<br>
<br>
Apparently no one in government foresaw the enormous enforcement job national prohibition would entail in the Pacific Northwest, which is remarkable considering the vastness of the bootlegging industry engendered by Washington State dehydration alone.  But those carly lessons went unlearned in high places, and it was several years before the pleas of the enforcers for more muscle could be responded to.<br>
<br>
Meanwhile, seizures by the thinlyspread Coast Guard, for example, occurred largely through accident.  Once the venerable tugboat-like cutter Arcata, having anchored off Marrowstone Point in a fog, discovered herself lying a few yards away from a rummy which had heaved to for the same reason.  Arcata's skipper made that seizure (twenty-four cases and the rum vessel itself) with the cutter's longboat.<br>
<br>
On another occasion the harbor cutter Guard confiscated $6,ooo worth of liquor from a speedboat at Afinor Ladge, the deserted shoal east of Smith Island.  The Coast Guard version of the capture has the rummies "stealthly" carrying their contraband across the beach at the time, but the Friday Harbor Journal's contemporary report says the rum-runners had been shipwrecked for two days and were so glad to be rescued they couldn't have cared less about losing their booze. The journal also pointed out it was the Coast Guard's first capture in nine months.<br>
<br>
Eventually, of course, Coast Guard forces were beefed up not only by new 75-fOOt "six-bitters" but through conversion of somc of the confiscated ex-rummy vessels into government patrol boats.  'nese
craft were speedy and carxied business-like armaments, thus driving somc of the smaller fry from the game; while the big fcuows responded with greater speed and cunning, some going so far as to equip their low-lying craft with armor plate.<br>
<br>
One of the major operators, a Tacoma brewer whose manufacture of legal "near beer" constituted an ironically appropriate front, invested in a fleet of twin-engined craft that could make nearly forty knots, outrunning just about anything afloat.<br>
<br>
But the rummies depended on stealth as well as speed.  Often times this meant a cautious exchange of recognition signals before the midnight rendezvous with the Canadian supply boat, at some secluded covc in the Gulf Islands, where a hundred or more<br>
cases of hard liquor were loaded aboard. (Actually the almost universal container was the homely gunny-sack, either the stan-
dard-size bag holding an even dozen bottles or a smaller version in which six were sewn end-to-end, sausage-like, the original six-
pack.<br>
<br>
The gunny-sacks were easier to handle and in case the evidence needed to be ditched hurriedly the sacking would not disintegrate in water.<br>
<br>
Across the way, a confederate on the north shore of one of the San Juans would be scanning the murk for Coast Guard vessels.  Seeing none, hc would flash the "all clear" upon which the rummy poured the coal to twin Van Blerck or Liberty engines and in a matter of minutes the illegal merchandise would be beached near the look-outs feet.<br>
<br>
The empty rum boat would be on its way again in a moment while the partner loaded the contraband into a waiting automobile and departed at top speed for the southern shore, where another fast boat waited to relay it to the mainland.  Islanders learned to ignore those noctural autos speeding hell-bent through the gloom, and warned their children to keep away from the windows if they awoke to hear them roaring by in the night.<br>
<br>
Most of the operators maintained hiding places where their goods could be quickly cached in case of pursuit, and a good deal of ingenuity was displayed in selecting them.  One of the more successful caches was on D'Arcy Island on the Canadian side;<br>
<br>
D'Arcy being a leper colony site in those days, no one risked coming around to investigate!<br>
<br>
Another imaginative cache was at Obstruction Pass on Orcas Island where an enterprising fellow constructed a very special kind of outhouse.  Half of the two-holer was conventional, but the other
half concealed the entrance to a short tunnel where the "merchandise" was hidden.  Very effective, providing one didn't forget which half was which.<br>
<br>
When pursued too hotly, it was sometimes necessary to deepsix the evidence and take one's chances of recovering it later.  Such was the case one dark night off the southwestern Orcas shore when a party of rummies hastily tossed their burlap wrapped cargo into shallow water, moments before being overhauled by the persistent guarders of the coast.<br>
<br>
The pursuers did not observe the dumping operation; but a watchful Orcas Islander did, and when the boatmen returned to retrieve their bottled goods, every bag of it had disappeared.  <B>The </B>rum-runners hunted for days, to no avail; but they were looking in the wrong Place.  They should have been searching the local Deer Harbor speakeasy, where quarts of the finest were on sale with new labels warning customers to destroy the bottles after use, so the rummies couldn't trace them.<br>
<br>
In the Islands, the local speakeasy was usually to be found in the nearest village store.  For reasons that are apparent, hard liquor was easy enough to come by.  But there was trafficking in imported beer, the profits being so much greater with spirits, so most of what was sold was of local manufacture.<br>
<br>
But there were also .... all over the place, and one of them was immortalized in a song parody known to islanders throughout the county:<br>
"We'll build a sweet little still<br>
In old Argyle mill<br>
And let the rest of the world come buy."<br>
<br>
The Argyle mill had no still, the miller having abandoned his obsolescent profession to become a highly-respected officer of the local bank, but the rhyme was too fetching to spoil over such a trifling detail.<br>
<br>
It is of course no secret that some of the very authorities charged with detecting Volstead Act violations were themselves among the violators.  Others, though not actively engaged in the booze traffic, were sometimes willing to look the other way for a consideration.<br>
<br>
One Orcas man used to tell of bringing his small fishing boat alongside an apparently disabled craft he thought needed help.  Tle islander was wearing an old Navy jacket and was mistaken by the skipper - who proved to be a rummy - for a Coast Guardsman.<br>
<br>
"Well, help yourself and let me go," said the rum-runner matter-of-factly, whereupon the Orcas man assumed what he hoped
was an official look, threw a gunny-sack full of Canada's best over his shoulder and departed with all the haste he could manage.<br>
<br>
Figuring ways to con a few free sacks of hooch from the runners -who were in no condition to complain to the law over their losses - was one of the sports that made the 'twenties roar.  Loyal Larson, who spent the bulk of his four score and four years carrying the mail in the San Juans, used to tell of one such episode.<br>
<br>
The plotters learned that a certain liquor carrier was using a deserted stretch of beach on San Juan Island for his "drop" and did not bother actually caching the bottles unless a warning shot, fired by a sentinel on a distant vantage point, warned of approaching danger.<br>
<br>
Posing as customers, the hooch-thieves were able to overpower the sentinel.  They themselves fired the alarm signal and watched patiently as the rum-runner crew scurried to convey the goods into the cache.  Then the rummies hurriedly abandoned the<br>
scene, leaving the enterprising thieves'to collect a considerable haul of free booze.<br>
<br>
The polite term for such activities is hijacking, and anyone who was on the inside of the business in those halcyon days win assure you that the hijacker presented a far greater danger to the rum-trade practitioners than all the law enforcement agencies put together.  It was as much on account of the liquor pirates, if not more so, that the  crews resorted to ever faster boats, thicker armor plate, and more potent weapons for thenisclves as the prohibition years advanced.<br>
<br>
A typical hijack operation occurred one blustery Wednesday in November 1922.  A rum-runner calling himself Harry Talbot, from Los Angeles, cleared Vancouver in the Schooner Daisy with $50,000 worth of liquor supposedly bound for Estenada, Mcxico. Talbot's true destination was some quiet island meeting with an American boat - a rendezvous he did not keep for while  negotiating narrow Active Pass between Mayne and Galiano Islands, he was suddenly overhauled by a faster craft, the crew of which relieved him at gunpoint of his entire cargo.<br>
<br>
Talbot was forced roughly from the Daisy into the hijack boat, which turned and headed for American waters at high speed.  After a good deal of brutal treatment Talbot was given his choice of being thrown overboard, or put ashore on one <B>of </B>the U.S. islands.  It was not a difficult choice to make, and before long he was found scrambling up the rocks to the Turn Point light station on
Stuart Island.  Islanders conveyed him to San Juan, whence he made his way back to Vancouver, battered, boatless, and bereft of his booze, but glad to be wearing most of his original skin.<br>
<br>
Canadian waters, was witness to more than one drama of the sort.  It was on September <B>17, </B>1924, that Chris Waters, keeper of the Turn Point light, noticed a small craft drifting northward up Haro Strait on the morning tide.  Waters figured the boat's engine had broken down and kept an eye on it.  Several hours later the vessel was within a quarter of a mile of Stuart, and still drifting.  Waters decided to row over and lend a hand.<br>
<br>
No one answered the lightkeeper's hail as he came alongside.  Clambering over the rail he made a quick search of the craft and found it deserted.  The anchor chain was down, but the anchor seemingly not grounded.<br>
<br>
Waters returned to Stuart, left the lighthouse in charge of an assistant and went off to get Eric Erickson at Provost.  Erickson had a gas boat, in which the pair overtook the derelict and towed her in.  On closer inspection they found the anchor was not dragging, but gone, the chain having been severed.<br>
<br>
That's not all they found.  Brownish stains on the deck and hatch cover looked suspiciously like blood, while a pencil-size hole in the foc's'le door could only have been made by a bullet.  Going below they found more stains-bunks and bulkheads were splashed with them - and on an opened Adventure Magazine lay a man's cap half filled with the still sticky, reddish-brown goo.  It was enough to make the islanders' own blood drop a degree <B>or </B>two in temperature.<br>
<br>
Papers and furniture scattered over the deck added to the evidence a mortal fight had taken place, no doubt between hijackers and their rum-boat victims.<br>
<br>
Waters notified the Coast Guard, which sent a cutter to take charge of the vessel, the fish-packer Beryl-G, owned by William Gillis of Vancouver.  Gillis and his son, William Jr., were supposedly using the craft to haul cannery supplies.  Both men were missing nor was either to be seen ever again.<br>
<br>
Because of the Canadian registry, provincial police were invited into the case along with U.S. authorities.  The ill-starred<br>
craft ultimately was towed by the Arcata to Friday Harbor where it remained tied up at the customs dock below Spring Street for several weeks.  As the county fair was in progress, the much-publicized vessel became the grisly object of considerable interest, vying with the pickled pears and out-sized cabbages for
<br>
fair-goers' attention.<br>
<br>
First, of course, the boat had been combed for clues.  The most promising item found was a camera containing a partially exposed roll of fihn.  Police had the pictures developed and one of them showed in close-up detail a low, squarish boat, its boiling wake curving away from the photographer.  A bit of the Gillis boat's rigging showed too, proving that the pictured vessel had just left the Beryl-G's side.<br>
<br>
B. C. sleuths identified the pictured vessel as one of the 40-knot speedsters of the Tacoma "near beer" man, Pete Marinoff.  An inspector contacted Marinoff and found him cooperative: he was as anxious as they to see the hijackers put permanently out of business.<br>
<br>
The Tacoman disclosed that Gillis' job was to ferry liquor from the supply ship Comet, standing off Vancouver Island in international waters, to various Gulf Islands rendezvous points where Marinoff's crews took over.  The last pickup from Gillis had been made on the 15th, two days before the blood-stained Beryl-G was found adrift.<br>
<br>
Marinoff also ticked off the names of underworld figures he judged capable of hijacking and murder.  Among them was tall 39-year-old Owen B. "Cannonball" Baker, an ex-McNeil Island irunate.  Baker and an unknown companion had relieved Marinoff before of booze as well as cash money in a Seattle holdup.<br>
<br>
From a Canadian-born laundry worker and sometime rummy, the provincial detective wrung the names of several disreputables who had been pirating liquor in the Gulf Islands area.  One of them was "Cannonball" Baker.  Another was Baker's sidekick, also a McNeil Island alumnus, named Harry Sowash.<br>
<br>
Meanwhile, in Victoria, police were questioning an immigrant fisherman who had commissioned an Oak Bay boatworks to alter the appearance of his fishing boat - just two days after the Gillis hijacking.  The man also had been heard to mutter that he "needed a good lawyer." And a Victoria customs official recaged that a few days before the Gillis had disappeared, he had run into the fisherman - whom he knew personally - in the company of an American introduced to him as Owen Baker.<br>
<br>
Other evidence was amassed implicating the fisherman, who soon chose to unburden himself of a bizarre and complicated tale of deceit, piracy, and murder.<br>

Baker's rather clean-cut appearance inclined him toward the impersonation of law enforcement officers - a technique he had used more than once to pry free booze from hard-working rummies.  But most of his jobs had been small ones, netting mere peanuts.  Finally he had hit on a scheme to make some real money.<br>
<br>
Assuming the identity of a U.S. official, Baker arranged to meet a visiting B.C- police officer in a Seattle apartment.  Claiming he wanted the information in connection with Volstead Act enforcement, Baker asked the Canadian to supply him with whatever data the Provincial Police had regarding the location of liquor caches on the B.C. side of the border.  Poker-faced, the officer obliged with a list of probable locations.<br>
<br>
Baker then gathered some rum-row associates together, chartered a gas boat called the Dolphin, and headed for Vancouver Island.<br>
At Victoria they contacted the immigrant fisherman, whom they hired to accompany them in his vessel, the Denman-II.  They told him their mission was to get actual motion picture film footage of American rum boats in action, at the behest of a Hollywood company which was paying handsomely to use it in a movie.<br>
<br>
Intimating the operation had the blessing of the provincial police, Baker let the Denman's owner observe him enter the<br>
Victoria police station and emerge again clutching a list of places to be investigated.<br>
<br>
The two vessels began visiting these locations, the Dolphin's crew searching each one for hidden booze, but coming up empty handed every time: the savvy Canadian official had fed Baker nothing but misinformation.<br>
<br>
Sowash and Baker, frustrated by the turn of events, now abandoned subtleties for direct action.  In the course of their peregrinations they had several times observed the Beryl-G at anchor.  They decided to knock over the Gillis boat.<br>
<br>
The Denman was chosen for the job.  About <B>10  </B>p.m. on September 15th Baker, Sowash, and a companion named Charlie Morris instructed their fisherman dupe to take them to the east side of Sidney Island, opposite Stuart.  Arriving about midnight they moored near the place where Gillis had been seen earlier, working over his engine.<br>
<br>
Baker and Morris had blue suits on and Morris was wearing a gold-trimmed, official-looking cap.  Baker pulled guns and a pair of handcuffs from a satchel and the two, together with Sowash, got into a skiff and rowed quietly into the night.  The perplexed
fisherman was ordered to bring up the Denman on a flashlight signal.<br>
<br>
A quarter hour passed when sounds of shooting reached the Denman, and moments later a light flashed.  Before the Denman's agitated skipper could decide what to do next, the skiff - with Baker in it - came alongside.  Baker leveled a pistol and ordered the fisherman to "Go ahead!"<br>
<br>
As the fishboat approached the Beryl-G Morris could be seen walking young Gillis at gunpoint across the deck and into the forward cabin.  "We had to shoot the old man a little in the arm," Morris called across to the Denman.  Actually, William Gillis was below, his lifeless body oozing blood into his cap and overflowing onto the magazine he had been reading.<br>
<br>
Baker and Morris transferred the Beryl-G's liquor to the other<br>
vessel while the two craft, lashed side-by-side, headed cast toward little Halibut Island.  There the Gillis boat was anchored and Sowash ordered the younger victim topside.  As he stepped out on deck Sowash struck him a savage blow over the head from behind.  "The cold-blooded murderers!" exclaimed Morris, aloud, as young Gillis crumpled.<br>
<br>
Baker and Sowash shook hands over the boy's silent form and went below to get the older man's body.  The two victims were then handcuffed together and - as a precaution against their bodies floating to the surface -both were ripped open with a butcher knife.  The two killers attached the Beryl-G's anchor to them and dumped father and son overside.<br>
<br>
Brandishing the dripping butcher knife before the eyes of the terrified fisherman, Baker ordered him to takc the Denman to nearby islands where the liquor was cached, then on to Anacortes.  There the hijackers debarked - after a final threat to "Plug" the panic-white fisherman if he ever talked.<br>
<br>
The Denman's skipper headed for the San Juans where he spent a day thinking things over and trying to get a grip on himself.  Opting to keep quiet about the whole affair, he returned to Victoria and saw about getting his boat's appearance altered.<br>
<br>
When the fisherman's tale was told, police rounded up Charlie Morris easily enough, but Sowash and Baker had vanished.  Rewards were offered and a gigantic man-hunt spread across North America.<br>

Locally, authorities spent a month and a day fruitlessly dragging the salt chuck for the Gillis bodies, but swift tides and voracious sea creatures had removed every trace.<br>
<br>
Baker was tracked to the New York waterfront by Seattle detectives who captured him on December 27, 1924.  A month later New Orleans police recognized Sowash, who was netted by chance dozing a routine roundup of transients.<br>
<br>
Sowash, Baker and Morris were tried in Canada and convicted of capital murder.  Morris appealed and got his sentence commuted to life imprisonment, but the others paid society with<br>
their lives.  It is said that Baker's last words, directed to the hangman, were "Step on it, Buddy.  Let's get on with it."<br>
<br>
While police on both sides of the border were relentless in their persecution of outlaws like Sowash and Baker, attitudes toward "legitimate" liquor runners ranged downward from reluctant enforcement through tolerance to actual participation.  For years, the undisputed king of Puget Sound bootleggers was baby-faced Captain Roy Olmstead, boy wonder of the Scattlc Police Department, whose far-flung operation rivaled-in size and organization-that of any Capone or Dutch Schultz.<br>
<br>
But unlike those gangsters, whose hallmarks were the murdered mobster and blinded customer, Olmstead ran an honest shop.  You could always buy a bottle from an Olmstead man and be sure the contents were neither watered, nor would they dissolve the enamel from your teeth.<br>
<br>
Nor would Roy Olmstead permit his associates to resort to gunplay even to "pack a rod." His success at eluding both hijackers and the law depended on careful planning, secrecy, and top-notch operators.<br>
<br>
One of Olmstead's lieutenants, reputedly the most successful rum-runner on Puget Sound, was a short, heavy-set San Juan County man named Prosper Graignic.  Graignic's dad was a French sailor who jumped ship at Victoria in the 1870's, married a native girl and settled down on Waldron Island's North Bay.  The large family they reared there grew up, it would seem, with sea water instead of blood in their veins.  One of Prospers brothers is said to have sailed the family sloop to Victoria and back at the age of seven.<br>
<br>
Another, though deaf, earned his way as a fisherman; his knowledge of local tides and currents is described by island people as "uncanny." Even the girls in the family learned, early on, to be as much at home afloat as on dry land.<br>

Prosper's entry into the rum trade was not auspicious.  Acquiring a 45-foot gas "yacht," the M-846, he had her cabin enlarged and installed twin 300-horse Sterling marine engines.  Leaving Seattle's Lakc Union about noon of a junc day he headed north for Discovery Island, near Victoria; four or five truckloads of hooch were to be boated there from Vancouver and divvied up between Graignic and several othcr operators.<br>
<br>
Arriving at that destination during the night, Graignic and his crewman-companion retired to their bunks for some shut-eye.  But early the next morning Chief Coristable John James Otway Wilkie of the Provincial Police discovered the M-846 illegally moored in Canadian waters, arrested the pair, and turned them over to immigration authorities.<br>
<br>
Graignic was obliged to pay a $400 fine for entering Canada at other than a designated port.<br>
<br>
Upon paying the fine, Graignic's B.C. lawyer approached immigration officers and openly asked them how a U.S. vessel could visit Canada and secure a load of liquor "without getting into trouble." He had thus already violated rule number one, for the Canadians promptly reported the conversation to American authorities.<br>
<br>
Returning to Discovery Island, Graignic found his boat adrift and had to hire a launch to chase it.  When the M-846 was recovered, eight miles away near Hein Bank light, the Waldron Islander headed home empty and entered the United States legally, according to the book - at Port Townsend.  But officials at that port, who knew exactly what he had been up to, seized the vessel on grounds it was "being used in foreign trade."<br>
<br>
Graignic paid another $500 fine to get his boat out of hock.<br>
But Prosper Graignic survived the novice stage of his career and in the long run his knowledge of local waters and unerring skill at boat-handling enabled him to land load after load of burlap wrapped Canadian spirits on the American side, virtually at will, thus contributing heavily to the estimated two hundred cases a day being delivered to Olmstead in Seattle.<br>
<br>
Graignic's forte was the ability to navigate in weather neither<br>
the Coast Guard nor Sound pirates would dare face.  Time after time when vicious southeasters tumed the Straits to boiling foam and monster waves drove every other skipper on the Sound to anchor in the lee of the nearest island, Prosper would pile sack on sack of booze into the Baby Bottleman, the Elsie -named by Olmstead for his wife - or some other craft and head unchalIcnged for the U.S. side.  And he always got there. (Except for the day in 1924 when the high-performance engines of the Elsie caught fire, burning the
<br>
boat to the water, and Graignic barely escaped with his life.)<br>
<br>
For the rare occasion when Graignic was about to be overhauled he had a slick device for getting rid of the evidence in a hurry.  Sacks were tied together at intervals on a line passing over rollers to the stern of the boat.  Cutting one line would cause the rope to pay out and the whole load to be dumped.<br>
<br>
If his pursuers didn't look sharp, they would never see it happen.  And by picking shallow water to dump in, Graignic could always come back later and retrieve every sack.<br>
<br>
Of course the truth about Captain Olmstead's extracurricular activities was bound to come out-it was Seattle's worst-kept secret anyhow-but even his dismissal from the force simply enabled the pleasant-mannered ex-cop to devote himself more fully to his private endeavors.<br>
<br>
And his vast connections within all levels of officialdom weren't hurting him, either.  The stacks of money just grew and grew in the old clothes hamper he carelessly called "the bank."<br>
<br>
Some of this money he invested in Seattle's pioneer radio broad-
casting station, KTCL, partly for fun and partly as a hedge against the future.  There is an undying legend in the Puget Sound country that Olmstead used the station to transmit, in the guise of bedtime stories for children, intelligence information about the movements of Coast Guard vessels; but there is no proof that this was ever done.<br>
<br>
Actually, there was no need to, for Olmstead conversed quite openly with his employes by telephone, safe in the knowledge that wire-tap evidence had been outlawed in Washington State.<br>
<br>
Federal authorities tapped his phone anyway, but even this was used to Olmstead's advantage.  Calling an employe from home he would give detailed instructions for a booze pickup.  "I got you the first time, Roy," the fellow would say breezily.  Then Olmstead could go to a pay phone, call back and give a different set of instructions.<br>
<br>
Prohibition agents spent many a wet night at some phony rendezvous, while the actual hand-over of liquor took place far, far away.<br>
<br>
Desperate for a conviction, prohibition agencies built a case on conspiracy to violate the National Prohibition Act, rather than actual violation of it, and got Olmstead and ninety members of his organization indicted in November I924.  Graignic was to be among the defendants at what the Seattle papers were calling the biggest
liquor trial in U.S. history.<br>
<br>
"Whispering wires" evidence, though technically illegal, was by various devices introduced at the classic trial, which drew as observers awed law professors from the nearby University of Washington.  Ohnstead was convicted, sold his radio station to pay the lawyers, and did time on McNeil Island before receiving a pardon from President Franklin Roosevelt.<br>
<br>
The wiretap aspects of the case led to its review by the U.S. Supreme Court, and to a landmark decision holding such evidence is not barred by the Constitution's fourth ammendment.<br>
<br>
Prosper Graignic, like many another of those indicted with Olnistead, jumped bail and fled to Canada, where Graignic had a brother working in a Sooke, B.C. cannery.<br>
<br>
A few weeks after the historic trial Olmstead, who had put up the collateral for Graignic's forfeited bail bond, himself participated in a two-nation scheme to net his former associate.  Driving to Vancouver, B.C., Olmstead and Deputy U.S. Marshal A. B. McDonald boarded the steamer Princess Victoria, Seattle-bound via the British Columbia capital.<br>
<br>
Meanwhile Canadian immigration officers obligingly arrested Graignic for improper entry ordered him deported, and placed him on board the Princess boat when it arrived in Victoria.<br>
<br>
Deputy Marshal McDonald remained in seclusion while Olmstead hunted up his ex-associatc and the pair occupied a stateroom together until 6 o'clock the next morning, when the steamer was in American waters off Port Townsend.  At this point McDonald burst into the cabin, placed Graignic under arrest, and had him up before a Seattle judge later the same day.<br>
<br>
Graignic promoted $7,500 for bail and went to plying his accustomed trade until the last weeks of 1927, when the law's arm finally got him into a courtroom to face a file of damning evidence.  The Waldron Islander drew three years and a day on that grim little island south of Tacoma.  He served half of the sentence, was paroled, and lived a thoroughly circumspect exist-
ence thereafter.<br>
<br>
Between the determined prosecution by Prohibition forces of organizations like Olmstead's, and vastly multiplied patrol activ-
ities by the Coast Guard, the torrent of booze flowing through Washington's inland sea had by the close of 1924 slowed to a persistent but puny trickle.  "Puget Sound is drying up" reported the Friday Harbor Journal, quoting "the booze men themselves.." While according to the Bellingham American, as many as twenty@
relentless Coast Guard crews now guarded Puget Sound waters against the transcursions of foreign spirits.<br>
<br>
Those rummies who persisted in the game were obliged to resort to elaborate new tactics, such as the false-compartmented boat.  But even so, sharp-eyed Coast Guard crews often found them out.  One such vessel, the Alice, was spotted off Upright Head, Lopez Island, in 1926.  J. L. Gunderson, in command of the CG picket boat 2354, thought it odd that the 50-foot Alice was floating so low in the water, with no cargo apparent on her deck.<br>
<br>
He whistled her down for an inspection, which turned up no evidence of liquor - or any other explanation for the sparsity of freeboard.<br>
<br>
Smug faces on Alice's crew turnd to dismay when the determined Coast Guard officer drove the suspect vessel up on the beach for a thorough look-see.  At length the hiding place was uncovered: 22-foot-long, narrow compartments had been built into each side of the hull below the waterline, just wide enough to receive the liquid cargos one sack at a time.  The sacks were attached by ropes to an iron ring at the opening, to facilitate their removal at journey's end, the whole apparatus being concealed during the trip by a board nailed over the opening.<br>
<br>
Gunderson's men seized 115 cases of ilicit potables and Alice herself, an ex-Navy motor-sailer, was confiscated and pressed into the anti-booze service.<br>
<br>
Such were the dying gasps of the rum trade through San Juan waters, as elsewhere.  But the prohibition experiment too was terminal: mounting public revulsion over the mood of gangsterism, official corruption and grass-roots scofflawry rampant in a turbulent and agonized society spoke death to the Great Test, the efficacy - if not the nobility - of which was by then almost universally in question.<br>
<br>
Then the Wall Street humpty-dumply toppled and as the minions of financial empire scrambled vainly to reassemble the debris, the bread-line crowd howled for the right, at least, to its liquid solace.<br>
<br>
In 1932 Franklin Roosevelt, besides declaring against the face of fear, pledged an axe to the Act of Mr. Volstead; but Congress beat him to it by pulling the budgetary teeth of the Coast Guard and other enforcement agencies.  Prohibition was dead, the cadaver to be buxicd the following year upon ratification of the Constitution's twenty first amending.<br>
<br>
In the San Juans as across the nation, the demise of the Noble Experiment was feted with many a high-held toast, and usually to
the self-delusory tune of Tin Pan Alley's latest: "Happy Days Are Here Again!"<br>
<br>
David Richardson, "The Noble Disaster," <B>Pig War Islands.</B> Eastsound: Orcas Publishing Company, 1971, p. 308-325.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
SMUGGLING<br>
<br>
Jo Bailey Cummings and Al Cummings, "Wild and Woolly,"  <B>San Juan: The Powder Keg Island.</B>  Friday Harbor: Beach Combers, 1987,    p. 168-177.<br>
<br>
To be sure the Island of San Juan has always been reckoned as a choice place for sheep raising and smuggling.<br>
<br>
As a matter of fact, in 1906 a farmer named M.A. Ward boasted that he gleaned 21 1/2 pounds of wool from one sheep.  Noted in the Islander of June 9th that year, two farmers with spreads near Kanaka Bay claimed they averaged over 150 pounds of wool per sheep.<br>
<br>
The Customs Inspector expressed grave doubts about that crop-since wool smuggling was rampant on the west coast of the Island-and most sheep do well to grow seven to 10 pounds of wool annually.  But, with no evidence to take to the sheriff, he had to accept the word of the apparently reputable landowners.<br>
<br>
In her diary Winnie Lightheart wrote of an inspector telling her father that he had discovered a large cache of wool near the family barn.  Mr. Lightheart remembered that a fellow Islander, whom he "didn't particularly like," had a fast boat and sometimes off-loaded wool on the shore near the Lightheart property.  She wrote:<br>
<br>
the man . . . had to make a quick job of getting the wool off his boat and our place was the closest.  He was likely being pursued by the Revenue boats.  In those days money was hard to come by on the farms and this particular farmer owned a fast sailing sloop so he bought wool on the Canadian side and brought it across to be sold later with his own wool.  He had a lot of sheep.  My father felt apparently he should protect him as he was a fellow farmer trying hard to earn a living.<br>
<br>
Winnie "pressed the feelings of a number of upstanding citizens.  Smuggling was regarded only as a "somewhat" questionable cottage industry.<br>

Americans living close to the 49th parallel found it hard to believe that unlicensed commerce betw@n them and their Canadian neighbors represented any threat to the country's economic well-being.  Besides, duty-free rum was one of the staples of an Island homeowner, and the British were good customers of the San Juan farmers.<br>
<br>
During the Civil War years of 1861-65, liquor, blankets and wool were the principal "imported" cargo of many fast boats that darted in and out of the coves of the west side of the Island.<br>
<br>
When Chinese workers were imported to help with building railroads on the West Coast, opium became a lucrative commodity.  It could still be brought into the country legally, but the duties were extremely high in order to limit its use.<br>
<br>
In the 1880's laws were passed to restrict the immigration of Chinese because they were a cheap source of labor that threatened white working men.  The law was countered by the creation of a marine "Underground Railway.  " The going price for putting an illegal Chinese on shore in the U.S. was about $100-a princely sum.<br>
<br>
Orientals were carried on board sewed up in potato sacks, hidden in the dangerous shaft-alleys of steamers or in the anchor chain lockers.  Often the "Celestials" were put ashore on uninhabited islands, such as Sucia, or on barren rocks, awaiting a chance to sail by small boat to the mainland.  There are tales about unscrupulous smugglers throwing illegal Chinese overboard when Revenue boats appeared.<br>
<br>
San Juan Island's first minister, the Rev.  T. J. Weekes rescued some Chinese who had been abandoned on a rock in San Juan Channel in the 1880s.  They had been dumped there by smugglers when a "revenue cutter" bore down on their boat.<br>
<br>
The unfortunate Chinese were found by the parson some days later, "emaciated and barely subsiding on clams on a reef which has been called 'China Rock' ever since," according to historian Bryce Wood.<br>
<br>
it would be impossible to estimate the number of Chinese who died of exposure or drowned in these forays.<br>
<br>
The saga of the wily and often-dangerous outlaws who plied the inland waters of Washington and British Columbia, can be drawn around several colorful characters.  There were two men named Kelly: jim "Pig Iron" Kelly and Larry -Smuggler" Kelly who marauded at about the same time, although there is no record they ever met.  Two others were William "Old Man" Jamieson and Henry "Flying Dutchmm" Ferguson.
Lawrence Kelly was an ex-Confederate Army soldier who went to sea.  Arrested for the first time in Puget Sound for trying to smuggle Canadian silk, he was fined $500.<br>
<br>
In the 1880's, he and his Indian wife set up a center of operations on Guemes Island, near Anacortes.  He had a fast red fishing boat and he could be nonchalant about the law because the only Revenue boat in the area was the stodgy old tub, oliver Wokott with a top speed of 5 knots.  Even though he was often spotted, he usually outran his pursuers. if he avoided failed, - he dumped his cargo overboard and thus prosecution fined $150.<br>
<br>
He was caught in  1882 with a load of contraband wine, although his staple commodity was opium.  Lawrence Kelly was reportedly the smugglers who stranded the Chinese on a windswept rock in San Juan Channel.  Unable to swim ashore, they nearly starved to death until the Rev.  T. J. Weekes plucked them from the rock nearly a week later.<br>
<br>
Kelly was sent to jail or fined heavily many times, but he always returned doggedly to his lifess work when he was free.  He finally retired in 191 I when he was 70 and went back to his native Louisiana.<br>
<br>
The other Kelly, "Pig Iron," began his  career  selling  Liquor illegally to natives in Alaska.  He arrived in the Northwest in the late 1880s and earned his nickname by stealing most unusual items: iron ingots.<br>
<br>
He had friends on both Vancouver Island and San Juan Island, since whenever he came to the area he dried a full cargo of illegal liquor to share with his buddies.  Officials hunting for him were frustrated by his frierios' warning and hiding him from the law.<br>
<br>
His luck finally ran out in 1902 when he was intercepted carrying a half dozen Chinese in a long-boat.  He went to prison for a year.<br>
<br>
It was common knowledge in the San Juans that "Pig Iron" continued his activities, but thqe is no record of his arrest after the 1902 incident.<br>
<br>
Alfred Burke was one of the smugglers who made it possible for San Juan Island sheep-men to sell 150 pounds of wool for each animal
in their flocks.  It was nearly 10 years before he was caught after almost a decade of smuggling by a couple of clever inspectors.  Fred Dean and Roy Ballinger made it a personal quest to trap the elusive Mr. Burke.<br>
<br>
They knew he bought his wool from a number of farmers in the B.C. Gulf Islands, so they went "on vacation" to those islands and traced him.  They caught up with him on South Pender Island.  Claiming to be just "tourists" they watched a farmer shear sheep as Burke stood by.  They had with them a number of small wooden pegs which they had made.  When they had a chance, the inspectors pushed the pegs into the bales of wool.<br>
<br>
The Customs men traced Burke to a warehouse on Orcas Island owned by W. E. Sutherland.  When they inspected nearly half a ton of wool, they found their pegs and arrested Burke.<br>
<br>
Burke was tried for smuggling but got off on the technicality that the Inspectors did not see him actually cross the boundary line.<br>
<br>
The ingenuity of smugglers was unbounded.  A story in the Seattle Post Intelligencer in 1903 told about a group of Indians who joined the trade.  They picked up Chinese in the British Columbia waters and put them in canoes.<br>
<br>
On the way to the U.S. the  Chinese were bundled into women's clothing and disguised as squaws.  When the canoes landed in the States, the Chinese went ashore and mingled with squaws until they had a chance to change back to their own clothing.  The price for this masquerade was from $50 to $150 each.<br>
<br>
Agents from the Revenue service said although they thought the operation was managed by white men, some old hands who knew Indians well believed they did not accept help from whites-they were perfectly capable of devising the scheme by themselves.<br>
<br>
Although Chinese illegal immigrants usually came thmugh British Columbia where the laws were more tolerant, returning them was not easy.  The British required detailed expense vouchers for each returned Chinese.  The paperwork was lengthy, the repayment from the British uncertain.  Adding to the difficulty, the Canadians refused to accept the Chinese unless the U.S. paid a $50 per capita tax for them.<br>
<br>
It is little wonder that the U.S. government was less than enthusiastic about the efforts of the Revenue Service to halt the illegal importations.<br>

Jo Bailey Cummings and Al Cummings, "Wild and Woolly," <B>San Juan: The Powder Keg Island.</B> Friday Harbor: Beach Combers, 1987, p. 168-
177.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
THE END OF PROHIBITION.<br>
<br>
Marion Parker and Robert Tyrrell, "The End of Prohibition," <B>Rum Runner, the life and Times of Johnny Schnarr.</B> Victoria: Orca Book Publishers, 1988, p. 216-222.<br>
<br>
The way things were going, we all knew that Prohibition was coming to an end.  We didn't know exactly when it would be over at first, but we knew that it couldn't last much longer.<br>
<br>
I continued to run out the west coast to pick up my liquor from the Chief Skugaid.  With the larger boat I was now hauling for up to five different customers each trip.  On the way down into Puget Sound I might make one stop on the south side of Edmonds, one just north of Seattle, and a third one about fifteen miles the other side of Seattle.  Then on the way back out I might make two deliveries on the other side of the Sound.<br>
<br>
If I was lucky and the weather was good and all of the pickups were right there to get their loads as soon as I arrived, I would be back home in Telegraph Bay by four or five o'clock in the morning.  That, of course, was if everything went just right, which it didn't often do.<br>
<br>
The fourth and last time that I had to stay over on the American side all day was with the Revuocnav.  I was bringing a load in from the outside when it started blowing from the southeast.  Joe Fleming was crewing for me on that trip.  In no time flat we were facing right into a terrific wind.  The wind hit gale force when we were still out around Port Renfrew.<br>
<br>
It didn't let up at all.  We bucked into that blow all the way down the Strait.  For most of the trip you could hardly see the boat, there was so much water on the deck.  The waves were steep and short and every one of them was coming aboard.  We had to slow down to deal with it.<br>
<br>
In those conditions I knew that we didn't have time to go all the way down to Seattle and be clear before daylight, so I started thinking about some place to hide during the daylight hours of the next day.<br>
<br>
Normally I would have headed for a small channel between two islands on the east side of the Discovery Group.  It offered a perfect spot to tie up that was wen protected from the wind and seas.  There was a sheer rock watt on one of those islands that I
could get right next to on any level of the tide.  I could tie right up to the rocks, put a old tire between the boat and the cliff face and ride the tide up and down in comfort with no worries at an.<br>
<br>
The problem was that at this time the Imperator had been particularly active, patrolling the waters at the southern tip of Vancouver Island regularly.  I decided that it would be safer to spend the day on the American side of the border.<br>
<br>
We fought our way past Discovery and bucked across Haro Strait to San Juan Island.  On the southeast tip of the island, just around the corner from Cattle Point, there was a tiny cove that offered good protection from the weather.  The bay was only about a hundred feet wide and two hundred deep.  There was a piling in the middle of the bay and we tied up to that and sat there for the rest of the night and all the next day.<br>
<br>
As it happened the farm above the cove had been homesteaded by Joe Fleming's father and his half-brother was still working the land.  When it got light, Joe went up to the farm to visit his relatives and make new arrangements for the delivery of the load the following night.  I stayed on the boat.<br>
<br>
I felt pretty safe being out in the San Juans the way we were - the chances of a Coast Guard patrol being out there were slim - but I didn't like to leave the boat when it had a load on.  The day passed uneventfully.  The storm blew itself -out and we had no problem making the delivery the next night.<br>
<br>
I kept on hauling liquor right up to the end of Prohibition.  I made my last run on the night of April 2, 1933 - I delivered two hundred and fifty cases down to Seattle.  Prohibition ended on April 4, 1933.<br>
<br>
It's so long ago now that it is difficult to recall the way I felt<br>
when the whole thing came to an end.  I'm sure I looked onthe repeal of the Volstead Act with a good deal of sadness.  After all, it put me out of work.  Prohibition had provided me with a very good income, an interesting lifestyle and a good deal of adventure and excitement.  I can't say I was happy to see it end.<br>
<br>
But it didn't end overnight, and we all knew that it had to eiw sometime.  When I look back on it, it is much easier to remember the good points than the bad, the thrills and satisfactio@s than the disappointments.  All in all the era of Prohibition in the United States was very good to me.<br>
<br>
As I've said all along, I couldn't help but think of myself as a pretty lucky guy.  I had twelve years of doing something that I
really enjoyed.  And I was always well paid for it.  Sure, it was illegal as far as the Americans were concerned, but that never bothered me too much.  I couldn't see where I was doing anything terribly wrong.<br>
<br>
When it came right down to it, I never actually bought or sold any liquor; all I did was haul it.  I think that history has shown that the Prohibition laws were made to be broken.  But I'm not making excuses.  At the time I knew exactly what I was doing.  I knew I was breaking the law.  I knew the risks I was taking.  And I knew the penalties I would face if I got caught.  I guess that was why the pay was so good.<br>
<br>
During the time that I was rumrunning I had four or five different people come to me - all from the American side and ask me to run dope for them.  They made offers as high as $25,000 dollars to take a suitcase full of dope and land it on the other side.  I turned them all down flat.  I wanted nothing to do with that.  I didn't see it as the same business at all.<br>
<br>
But I think as much as anything else - the money and the excitement and all - I enjoyed the challenge of the whole game that was involved in the rumrunning.  The challenge of not getting caught.<br>
<br>
In looking back on it, I'd have to say that that challenge of staying out of reach of the authorities meant as much to me as anything else.  I certainly wasn't in the business just for the money.  I could have made a lot more money than I did, if that was my prime motivation.  I could have paid my crews a lot less than I did, that's for sure.  I never did change my practice of equal shares all around.<br>
<br>
It was always one-third for my crewman, one-third for me and one-third for the boat.  If I took two crew with me, then the split was in quarters.  And many times I took a second man along even though I did not really need him.  And I always did more of the work than any of my crew.  No, I sure wasn't in the rum trade just for the money.<br>
<br>
I thoroughly enjoyed my life during the Prohibition years.  I loved working on and around the water.  I took a lot of pride in my work, even if it was against the law.  During my years of rumrunning I made over four hundred runs; I delivered to ten different buyers, and made landings in thirty-six different locations along the coastline of Washington State.<br>
<br>
I never missed a spot where I was told to make a delivery; yet I never had any instruction in navigation.  Usually I would be shown a new dropoff site simply by someone pointing it out on a map.  
They might say, "Right about here in this bay." And I would go in there in the dark, flash a light toward the shore and nearly always get an answering flash right away.  Looking back on it now, it seems hard to believe that I never had more trouble than I did, making all of those deliveries at night, often in bad weather.  Most of the places I delivered to I have never even seen in the daylight, even to this day!<br>
<br>
I like to think I was lucky.  I had to be to stay out of trouble the way I did.  There weren't too many who did.  But the thing was I also felt that I made my own luck.  I was always careful.  I never took any unnecessary risks.  And I always made sure that I had the best equipment available.  I spent an awful lot of money making sure that I always had a boat that could outrun the opposition easily.<br>
<br>
I was always confident that I could do what I set out to do.  I never really felt that I was taking anY unnecessary risks at all - It didn't always seem that way when the bullets were flying, of course, but you couldn't prepare for everything!<br>
<br>
And looking back on it now, I realize that what I was doing was not at all bad for the Canadian economy at the time.  If you consider an average of about one hundred and fifty cases per trip, I freighted at least sixty thousand cases of liquor across to the United States.  That would have amounted to over four minion dollars of revenue that I brought into Canada.  And that was no small sum in the Thirties!<br>
<br>
The worst of it all was that, when Prohibition ended, I found myself with a very specialized boat, one that was far too expensive to operate for ordinary travel.  There weren't a lot of people around interested in buying the gas to fill those two six hundred gallon tanks and feed those eight hundred sixty horsepower engines! Nobody could afford it! It didn't take long for me to decide that I couldn't afford to keep the Revuocnav.<br>
<br>
There was just no way to use that boat to make it pay for itself.<br>
In fact, there was really no market for the boat as it was.  I finally decided to sell the engines separately.  And even at that I had to practically give them away.  I sold one to a mining company up north somewhere for $900.<br>
<br>
They wanted it to operate an electric generator for their camp.  That Packard would be able to light a lot of bulbs for them!<br>
I sold the Revuocnav to a group of millionaires that had a lodge up in Princess Louisa Inlet at the head of Jervis Inlet.  I think I got about $1500 for the boat.<br>
<br>
When I finished the rumrunning, I had maybe $10,000 dollars in the
bank.  That was a fair amount in 1933, but it didn't make me rich.  I could have made a lot more if I had been a better businessman, but that wasn't my way.  I put a lot of money back into boats and engines.  I spent something like $75,000 on my various boats.  In those days that was a lot of money.  But maybe that was what kept me out of jail!<br>
<br>
And I did build what was considered a fairly nice house at the time.  We lived well and travelled in good circumstances for quite a number of years.  I really enjoyed many of the people that I met in the rum trade.  Captain Charlie Hudson and Carl Melby were fine people and there were plenty of others as well.<br>
<br>
After Prohibition, of course, I had to find another line of work entirely.  I went logging for awhile, first north of Victoria near Ladysmith, and then out on the west coast of Vancouver Island up in Nitinat Lake.  I never got too far away from the water.<br>
<br>
Eventually I ended up making my living as a commercial fisherman out of Bamfield on the west coast of the island.  I bought my first boat, the Eljo from Joe Fleming.  Later I went over to Vancouver and bought a thirty-four foot fishboat.  I used that boat, the Margaret N, right up until the time I retired in 1969.<br>
<br>
I enjoyed the twenty-five years of fishing out of Bamfield up in Barkley Sound.  It wasn't as exciting as the rumrunning, but I was still my own boss, and it was good, healthy work.  And the funny thing was I never had a problem with seasickness when I was fishing.<br>
<br>
My fishboat was round-bottomed and, even though I went through plenty of terrible storms out on the open Pacific, I was never bothered by seasickness.  But everytime that I had gone out in the open in a V-bottomed boat I had been sick.  I was almost seventy-five years old when I finally retired.  I felt I could have fished for another eight or ten years, but my second wife was not in very good health at the time, and I thought it would be better for her to be in Victoria, closer to a good doctor and the hospital.<br>
<br>
Looking back on my life, I realize that I was indeed a very lucky person to have lived during such an unrestricted period in our history.  Although my childhood was hard, I was blessed with a strong body and a good mind which made it possible for me to overcome most of the difficult situations that I encountered.  For the most part I enjoyed my work, no matter what it was.<br>
<br>
My life wasn't without its hardships.  I was pretty hard hit when my little Johnny died very suddenly when I was working up in the Nitinat shortly after Prohibition ended.  And my first marriage was not very successful, and it ended not too long after our son died.
But I was lucky enough to meet a terrific woman later in my life, and we had twenty-seven wonderful years of marriage.  My second wife died of a blood disease at the age of seventy-seven.<br>
<br>
And now, having been retired for over seventeen years, I think it's safe to say that the twelve years of rumrunning were the most exciting years of my life.  I was young and eager, and I really enjoyed the thrills and adventure of that period.  And I've often thought back to the time I was in Seattle buying the engine for my first boat, when the fortune teller predicnd that I would be very successful in the "adventure" I was going into.  I guess I'd have to say he made a believer out of me!<br>
<br>
Marion Parker and Robert Tyrell, "The End of Prohibition," <B>Rum Runner, the life and Times ofJohnny Schnarr.</B> Victoria: Orca Book Publishers, 1988.  p. 216-222.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
SMUGGLING AND BOOTLEGGING.<br>
<br>
Norman Clark, "A booze baron's flamboyant reign," <B>Seattle Magazine.</B> I (September, 1964) p. 14-18<br>
<br>
At two o'clock on the morning of March 22, 1920, a gang of Seattle rumrunners was unloading a tugboat on the beach of Brown's Bay, just north of Edmonds.  Suddenly lights, shouts and gunfire interrupted their work.  Prohibition agents, who had waited for days in the woods, were crouching behind a roadblock and firing wildly at the boat and the bootleggers.<br>
<br>
The gang's leader leaped into a car and went roaring through the brush around the barrier, but the agents were able to identify him before he escaped.  Behind him on the beach he left the largest shipment of liquor ever seized in the Northwest.<br>
<br>
The gang's leader turned out to be, of all things, a Seattle police lieutenant.  His name was Roy Olmstead-and his subsequent arrest failed to deter him from pursuing a notorious career during Prohibition times which remarkably contrasts with the peaceable, redemptive life that he leads today<br>
<br>
During the twenties, newspapers hailed Olmstead as though he were a latter-day Robin Hood.  They called him "the booze baron," "king of the rumrunners" and even "the good bootlegger [who] served a
social purpose." These sobriquets suggest why Olmstead was one of the popular heroes of the day; he grossed over $200,000 a month for several years as chief of an intricate rui-nrunning empire, and he scrupulously safeguarded the integrity of his products by refusing to adulterate the liquor that he brought from Canada.<br>
<br>
The wealth and respectability that Olmstead earned by dodging Federal law reflect not only the loose political texture of that period but also the moral cynicism that prevailed during the whole dry decade.<br>
<br>
Eventually, Olmstead's exploits were to take on even broader significance.<br>
<br>
After his downfall as a rumrunner, the case of Olmstead v. the United States moved through three levels of the Federal judiciary and spotlighted a distinctly modern problem-wire tapping by law enforcement agents.<br>
<br>
However, only the most farsighted prophet would have predicted that Olmstead's career would take these curious-and sensational-turns.  At the age of 20, he had been outspokenly moralistic.  Disgusted by the labor unrest that beset the Seattle shipyards where he had been working, Olmstead upped and joined the Police Department.<br>
<br>
This was in 1906, and his superiors promptly pegged him as keen, responsive and highly competent.  From then until 1920, Olmstead rose quickly through the ranks, and, as the city trebled in population, he had a unique vantage point for watching it grow.<br>
<br>
Olmsted was a sergeant by 1910 and he gained his lieutenancy in 1916 which was the year when, after a statewide vote. Washington began its own ill-fated experiment with prohibition.<br>
<br>
Bootlegging and rumrunning be both popular and profitable and Olmstead noted the increasingly vicious competition between two rival gangs. One was headed by Jack Marquett, a former policeman who was a chum of Olmstead's, and the other by two brothers, Logan and Fred Billingsley, whose younger brother, Sherman, later opened a New York speakeasy that became today's Stork Club.<br>
<br>
Rivalry between the two gangs led to a shooting war which left its dead and wounded on Seattle's streets.  The war, in turn, exposed the weaknesses of both groups and helped police break them up.In all this, theorganization structures, the international connections, the futile competition, they were valuable insights for Roy Olmstead.<br>

The eclipse of Marquett and the Billingsleys left the Northwest's rumrunning trade in total disarray. Then in January, 1920, the National Prohibition Act, usually called the Volstead Act made the Treasury Department responsible for enforcing the constitutional provisions against the manufacture, sale, or transporation of alcoholic beverages.<br>
<br>
The appointment of Federal   prohibition agents sharply increased the risks of entrepreneurship, but the rewards for success went up too.  This was especially so for a leade@ho had administrative talent and who knew the business in its full scope-from the wet<br>
gunny sacks in the bottoms of speedboats through the garages in back alleys to the offices of law enforcers.<br>
<br>
Olmstead was 34 years old in 1920 the youngest lieutenant in the Seattle Police Department.  He was considered such a paragon of efficiency and virtue that when, in court, he recommended probation for certain offenders, judges often followed his advice.<br>
I n due course, he came to realize that his influence with judges was worth money, and Olmstead began striking bargains that brought him tidy profits.<br>
<br>
Then, in keeping with his character and the times, he sought high-risk investment that would turn these profits into a burgeoning bonanza.  Rumrunning was an irrestible choice.<br>
It was that choice which had led him to the beach near Edmonds where prohibition agents intercepted an Olmstead haul and spotted him making his getaway.  He was arrested at home the same afternoon.  From then on, the "baby lieutenant" with the "brilliant career," as Seattle's newspapers called him, was a sought-after celebrity.<br>
<br>
Olmstead pleaded guilty to violating the Volstead Act and was fined $500.  Immediately dismissed from the police force, he was now able to devote all his time and energy to the liquor business.<br>
Olmstead had gained enough experience in rumrunning to form an accurate estimate of its potential.  He quickly found I I investors who would stake $ 1,000 each.  He retained an attorney and hired a staff of boatsmen, navigators, loaders, dispatchers, bookkeepers and salesmen (including some former Canadian policemen), then he began a shrewd and vigorous economic war against his competitors in the Pacific Northwest.<br>
<br>
To evade the export duty of $20 per case that Canada was charging for all liquor signed for the U.S., Olmstead had his ships cleared for Mexico.  After each had been loaded in Vancouver, B.C., with from 2,000 to 4,000 cases they rendezvoused at D'Arcy Island, a lonely spot of forest in Haro Strait northeast of Victoria that was well out of the main steamer lane.<br>
<br>
There, the cargo was secretly unloaded to await transportation by
small, swift boats to U. S. ports on Puget Sound.  Because other rumrunners paid the Canadian duty without protest, this ruse helped Olmstead undersell them by a wide margin.<br>
<br>
His tactics caused confusion and chaos among his competitors.  Many quit the business, some turned in bitterness to piracy, and others joined Olmstead.  Thus his empire mushroomed into what the New York Times called "one of the most gigantic rumrunning conspiracies in the country."<br>
<br>
By 1924 his organization was functioning so smoothly that Olmstead went almost entirely into wholesaling.  This brought him still greater profits, and he took his place in Seattle's grand society.  He bought a spacious colonial residence in the Mount Baker district.  He became president and owner of the American Radio Telephone Company, the very first local broadcasting station that later became KFOX and is now KOMO.<br>
<br>
His select private customers for illicit liquor included William E. Boeing and the exclusive Arctic Club.  Among leading Seattleites, it became a mark of distinction to remark casually, "As Roy Olmstead was telling me today. . . "<br>
<br>
In large measure, Olmstead's prestige stemmed from his audacity, which touched everything he did with cheerful excitement.  He sometimes brought his boats to the docks in downtown Seattle, where the cargo was unloaded in broad daylight into trucks marked "Meat" and "Fresh Fish"-and Olmstead would shake with laughter as, once again, he eluded the law.<br>
<br>
Even more than this, his unique code of ethics endeared him to thirsty citizens.  People could trust his merchandise.  He never allowed his men to bear arms, and he sternly lectured them that no amount of money was worth a human life.  For most Seattleites, it was simply impossible to regard Olmstead as an authentic criminal.<br>
<br>
The city police were a hazard to other rumrunners, but not to Olmstead, who could find a friend by telephoning any police station at any hour.  According to wire-tap evidence that was later in-
troduced in court, this was precisely how Olmstead operated.<br>
"Roy phoned the police station," testified one Federal agent.  "M. came to the phone and said, 'Hello, Roy, what's on your mind?'Roy said, 'One of your fellows picked up one of my boys.' M. replied, 'Who is it?' Roy replied that it was B. 'I don't give a damn what they do [said Olmstead] but I want to know before he is booked.' M. replied, 'I'll take care of it for you, Roy.' "<br>
<br>
To meet the hazards presented by Federal agents, Olmstead depended on his own wit and daring, plus what he regarded as the mediocre
personnel in the office of the Prohibition Administration.  One wire tapper, himself a member of that staff, was to repeat Olmstead's judgment: "Those sons of bitches are too slow to catch cold."<br>
<br>
They had indeed been slow in the beginning, but by 1924 political pressure forced them to greater vigilance.  Commanding the agents was William Whitney, who, as legal advisor in Seattle for Lhe Prohibition Administration, had active charge here, and he began chartering high-speed boats to pursue rumrunners.  The nighttime sport became a grim and unrelenting contest which, for Olmstead, vastly increased his overhead.<br>
<br>
At about this time, he was approached   by   Richard   Fryant,   a  free lance wire tapper who had six years experience in industrial espionage as a tapper for the New York Telephone Company.  According to Olmstead, Fryant showed him a transcript of conversations which had been conducted on Olmstead's office telephone over a period of several weeks.<br>
<br>
The transcript was for sale, Olmstead later alleged, for $10,000.  Olmstead claimed to have replied that he knew something about the rules of evidence, that such a transcript could never be used in court against him, that wire tapping was against state law and that Fryant could go to hell.<br>
<br>
Olmstead had the telephone company remove the tap-it was found in the ladies' room of the Henry Building, down the hall from his office-but he knew there would be others.  His caution, though, was only minimal.  Still trusting his estimate of the rules of evidence, he suppressed only those calls that might lead Whitney and his men to a productive raid.<br>
<br>
The tap even had advantages.  Some of Olmstead's most jubilant moments came when he telephoned false directions to his men about the landing of boats.  Then he sauntered casually to the street, where he used a public phone to give correct directions, confident that Whitney would spend the night on a lonely beach clutching a heavy revolver and (he hoped) shivering in the rain.  One night Olmstead's men left a lighted yellow lantern on Whitney's car as a jeering symbol of their ridicule.<br>
<br>
However, in October, 1924, Whitney had a valuable windfall when Canadian officials seized Olmstead's boat, the Eva B., on a customs charge.  Aboard were a three-man crew and a cargo of 784 cases.  Olmstead's hirelings talked, and as Whitney sifted the evidence, he kept two agents constantly manning the phone tap.<br>
<br>
In November, Whitney led a raid on Olmstead's home and arrested Olm-
stead, his wife Elsie and 15 guests who were entertaining themselves
by reading children's bedtime stories over Olmstead's radio station.  Whitney was jubilant, for he was convinced that he had enough evidence for a grand jury.  The next night, he and his superior, Roy Olmstead had left them to contemplate, lit it and ran it up the flagpole that topped their office.<br>
<br>
Olmstead and his attorney, Jerry Finch, cried loudly that their civil liberties had been violated, but, on January 19, 1925, a Federal grand jury indicted Olmstead and 90 other defendants for conspiring to violate the Volstead Act, and this set in motion what promised to be the biggest trial yet held under the Eighteenth Amendment.<br>
<br>
Olmstead's reaction to the indictment and to the publicity that ensued was characteristically direct: he posted bail, then went back to his office, tightened up his table of organization, placed orders in Canada for more liquor, and set his boats and trucks in motion again.<br>
<br>
Meanwhile, some of his co-defendants panicked.  A few fled in haste to Canada.  Others went to Whitney and pleaded guilty, agreeing to testify for the government in return for promises of leniency.  A dozen more banded together and hired George Vanderveer, the famed "counsel of the damned," who began to prepare the acid rhetoric which would make a national issue of wire tapping by Federal agents.<br>
<br>
In January, 1926, the trial opened in Seattle before Judge Jeremiah Neterer.  Prosecuting the case was Thomas P. Revelle, a former Methodist minister who was U.S. District Attorney here.  Among the parade of government witnesses were Canadian officials, Olmstead employees, William Boeing and the steward of the Arctic Club.<br>
Then, to bind together all the defendants and to prove-as Revelle charged in his opening statement-that Olmstead was Seattle's unofficial police chief, Whitney and other agents took the stand to tell what they had heard over Olmstead's tapped telephone.  Transcripts of those conversations were never offered in evidence, although govemment witnesses were allowed frequent looks at "the book" to "refresh their memories."<br>
<br>
Vanderveer howled indignantly because the court refused to let him examine "the book." He cited a Washington State statute adopted in 1 909 which made wire tapping illegal.  Law, insisted Vanderveer, cannot sanction a violation of law as a means of obtaining evidence. (A double irony was involved: not only had a Federal law encouraged disrespect for law itself but so had the methods that the government used to enforce it.)<br>
<br>
Olmstead watched and listened as his fate unwound, confident that a higher court would uphold Vanderveer.  He was also impressed with
the deep irony which escaped the attention of those less intimate with the details than he.<br>
<br>
Olmstead roared with laughter as some of the phony phone calls-the products of his own humor-were brought in evidence against him, and he <B>griii</B>ned good-naturedly at the U. S. Attorney's young assistant, whom he had supplied-and was continuing to supplywith top-notch Canadian whiskey.<br>
<br>
The conclusion, though, was never really in doubt.  On March 9, 1926, Judge Neterer fined Roy Olmstead $8,000-he had been convicted with 22 co-defendants-and sentenced him to four years at hard labor in a Federal penitentiary.<br>
<br>
In March, 1927, after the Circuit Court of Appeals refused to reverse the verdict, Olmstead began serving his term at McNeil Island.  Ten months later, he was released on bail as the U.S. Supreme Court agreed to review his case-specifically, "whether the use of evidence of private telephone conversations . . . intercepted by means of wire tapping, is in violation of the Fourth and Fifth Amendments."<br>
<br>
The case was heard in February, 1928.  In a five-to-four decision, the Court ruled against Olmstead.  The majority opinion was written by Chief Justice William Howard Taft, but far better remembered is the ringing dissent by Judge Louis Brandeis.<br>
<br>
"Every unjustifiable intrusion by the Government upon the privacy of the individual, whatever the means employed, must be deemed in violation of the Fourth Amendment," wrote Brandeis.  "If the Government becomes a lawbreaker, it breeds contempt for the law ... it invites anarchy . . . Against that pernicious doctrine this Court should resolutely set its face."<br>
<br>
Public opinion supported Brandeis, but this was small comfort to Olmstead, who was remanded to McNeil Island amid a swirl of controversy.  The decision against him by the Taft majority, complained the New York Times, 'made universal snooping possible."<br>
While Olmstead languished at McNeil, an enormous change was taking place in the world outside.  Faith in the Eighteenth Amendment was rapidly dissipating as attention shifted to the Great Depression.<br>
Olmstead's exemplary conduct behind bars won him release after serving 35 months of his four-year sentence.<br>
<br>
By now, the dry forces were in full retreat, and a bill before the State Legislature would soon repeal all state prohibition laws. (Another bill, introduced by State Senator Ed Benn, would make wire tapping a far more serious crime than it had been in the days when Olmstead was convicted.)
But the greatest change for Roy Olmstead was a personal one.  After having ,,pent many months in the prison library, he saw Seattle in 1931 with the eyes of one profoundly impressed with the grandeur of spiritual and civic law.  Turning away from all offers of wealth -from a night club, from a liquor distributor-he chose to dedicate himself to the principles of the Church of Christ, Scientist.<br>
<br>
Soon the U.S. repealed the Eighteenth Amendment altogether.  In 1933, Dr. Nicholas Murray Butler, president of Columbia University and a leading Republican critic of prohibition, spoke analytically about the dry decade.  Among the "moving influences" which hastened repeal he listed bootlegging, corruption of officials and, not least, the Supreme Court's decision in the Olmstead case-a decision which, said Butler brought "revulsion and revolt."<br>
<br>
On Christmas Day, 1935, Roy Olmstead received an impressive document.  "Whereas it has been made to appear to me that . . . Roy Olmstead, since his release from imprisonment, has been conducting himself in a law-abiding manner, and that he is unable to pay his fine and costs: Now, therefore, be it known that I, Franklin D. Roosevelt, President of the United States . . . do hereby grant the said Roy Olmstead a full and unconditional pardon . . . "<br>
<br>
Not long afterward Olmstead, then 49, began crossing Puget Sound again to preach Christian Science to the prisoners.  They frequently asked if he was really Roy Olmstead, "King of the rumrunners," and he had a stock reply.  "No," he told them firmly, "not any more,. The old Olmstead is dead.":<br>
<br>
Norman Clark, " A booze barons' flamboyant reign," <B>Seattle Magazine.</B> I (September, 1964) p. 14-18.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
The King <B>of </B>the Rumrunners Describes His  Redemption<br>
<br>
Shirley Elder."The king of the rumrunners describes his redemption," <B>Seattle Magazine.</B> I (September, 1964) p. 18.<br>
<br>
The preceeding article tells how the skullduggery he committed during Prohibition landed Roy Olmstead in jail.  He has been out now for 30 years, leading a life that is startlingly different from his old one.  Seated in his comfortably furnished apartment on Capitol Hill, Olmstead eagerly tells all comers about his metamorphosis, which began while he was serving time on McNeil Island.<br>
<br>

Says Olmstead, who is a big, cheerful, square-faced teetotaler of 78: "I started asking myself questions like, 'When did you break the law?' The answer was, 'All day long.' Then a little voice asked, 'How long did this go on?' and I answered, 'Till they locked me up.' The voice asked whether I liked it here.  I said, 'I don't.  This is my last trip.'<br>
<br>
"Then I got to thinking and I wondered one day how evil got into man.  I didn't believe in God, but rather that every man makes his own heaven and his own hell, and that didn't seem to explain much."<br>
So Olmstead, seeking further light, holed up in the prison library.  First he read all the books there about psychology, but, says Olmstead, "They didn't have the answer." Then he read all the works he could find by a half-dozen vaunted philosophers, and, he recalls, "They didn't have the answer either."<br>
<br>
He had pursued his search for a year or so when, at last, a celimate handed him a copy of Science and Health, with Key to the Scriptures, by Mary Baker Eddy, the founder of Christian Science.<br>
That book, which, according to Olmstead, propounds the concept that "man rules the universe through spiritual law," made such a tremendous impression on him that he gaily told himself, "This gal's got it, Jack."<br>
<br>
As Olmstead speaks of his conversion, the words tumble out in profusion:<br>
<br>
"I had to learn to live my life over in order to be more useful instead of trying to regulate people.  I knew the law.  I saw temptation ... easy money.  I began to see that tainted money was counterfeit."<br>
<br>
When he was released from prison, Olmstead turned down several "good deals" that would have brought him new wealth - among them, the legitimate importing of alcoholic beverages.  The reason he gave was simple: "I said 1 didn't need the money."<br>
<br>
In truth, however, Olmstead, who had once handied money by the fistful, was broke.  He took whatever jobs he could find, working off and on as a peddler and a construction laborer, then for several years as a real estate agent.  All the while, Olmstead was pursuing his studies of Christian Science.<br>
<br>
"People came to me for help," he says.  "I would pray for them, and they would be healed."<br>
<br>
One day, toward the end of 1948, a friend urged him to go into
business as a Christian Science practitioner.  After giving the proposal careful thought, Olmstead agreed to do so.<br>
<br>
Many of those who now seek him out have had trouble with the law, and Olmstead feels uniquely suited to give them help.  Among his regular duties are weekly trips to the Seattle jail, where he talks with prisoners in a language they can readily comprehend.<br>
<br>
His mission, says Olmstead, is to help the inmates understand, both emotionally and spiritually, why they got there.  "When they realize this," he adds, "they never go back."<br>
<br>
Despite his age, Olmstead spends three days a week in a downtown office and maintains another office in his apartment.  When his phone rings, as it repeatedly does, he answers it with a courteous "Good morning," "Good Afternoon" or "Good Evening" - never just "Hello." The advice he gives is offered with the comforting assurance that, somehow, Olmstead knows exactly what he's talking about.<br>
<br>
"You getting those cracked places straightened out?" he asked one caller.  "Just keep trying," he told another, "and I'll be by to see you in the morning."<br>
<br>
For those who, as did the younger Roy Olmstead, stray not only inches but miles from the law, Olmstead urges special consideration.  "They need compassion," he insists.  "Just because a man makes a mistake, why should we condemn him?"<br>
<br>
In the 20's, Olmstead made plenty of mistakes, but today, the last thing he needs or asks for is compassion for himself.  Olmstead has such a storehouse of it that he is prescribing it-much the same way that he once bootlegged booze, wholesale.<br>
<br>
Shirley Elder, "The King of the rumrunners describes his redemption," <B>Seattle Magazine.</B> I (September, 1964) p. 18.<br>
<br>
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++BOOTLEGGING<br>
<br>
Lynn Ove Mortenson, "Black nights and bootleg booze," <B>Peninsula Magazine.</B> VIII (Summer, 1993) p. 40-43.<br>
<br>
The gravelly crunch of footsteps on a dark, lonely beach, an occasional flicker from a flashlight, a muffled voice carried on the wind.  In the morning, no evidence would remain of the hasty transfer of precious liquid cargo from boat to powerful roadster. 
But another load of booze had been safely delivered to its Peninsula destination.<br>
<br>
On January 16, 1920, responding to more than 30 years of lobbying against the evils of "John Barleycorn" by Carrie Nation, suffragettes, and churches, the Volstead Act propelled the country into a moralistically driven experiment in abstinence from alcohol.  While plenty of people hailed Prohibition as a triumph of good over evil, still others saw it as an opportunity to turn a tidy profit.<br>
<br>
Because the restrictions of Prohibition didn't extend across the border to Canada, easy money could be made ferrying spirits to thirsty Yanks.  A case of whiskey that cost $20 in Canada was routinely sold for  $200 on the American market.  Located a mere 20 miles across the Strait of Juan de Fuca from Victoria, British Columbia, the Olympic Peninsula was a convenient target for the adventuresome rogues who came to be known as "rumrunners."<br>
<br>
Of course, their stock in trade consisted of much more than rum; all manner of alcoholic beverages, from imported whiskeys and rare brandies to the finest champagne, were deposited on Peninsula shores.<br>
<br>
In the beginning, folks of all sorts tried their hands at the new game.  But stray acts of hijacking, including a murder-not to mention high-speed U.S. Coast Guard "revenuer" armed with one-pound guns soon weeded out the fainthearted.  British Columbian whole-
salers grew to monopolize the booze brokerage from Victoria and Vancouver, completely legally under Canadian law.<br>
<br>
They contracted with reliable carriers to tote the goods.  Some simply cruised to the U.S.-Canadian border and transferred their loads to American receivers; others, more daring, delivered directly onto U.S. soil.<br>
<br>
Among the most successful was Johnny Schnarr.  Born in Chehalis, Schnarr spent much time on the B.C. coast as a young man.<br>
<br>
Realizing the potential profits, he had taken on rumrunning as a full time occupation by 1921.  Schnarr was a natural mechanic who had an eye for fast boats.  With no formal training, he could carve a model, take it to a shipyard, and produce a boat that was hard to beat.<br>
<br>
Schnarr's boats were typically sleek-long, low, narrow, and painted an inconspicuous dark gray-and each could hold up to 250 cases of liquor, stowed on deck for easy off-loading.<br>
<br>
Besides other inland water ports, Schnarr made semi-regular deliveries for Consolidated Exporters out of Victoria to at least nine drop-off sites along the northern coast of the Peninsula,
earning $11 per case.  Like his fellow rumrunners, he averaged four or five trips per month in the fall, winter, and spring, when dark nights and stormy weather provided the best cover from patrolling revenuer.<br>
<br>
Early in his career, Schnarr headed out to deliver a load at a small bay about a mile east of Port Angeles.  By the time he approached the designated rendezvous point in his boat, Moonbeam a sudden gale was whipping the waves up to 20 feet.  Not caring to brave the ele-
ments twice in one night, he agreed to the suggestion of his contact, Barney Sampson, that they lay over at the government wharf in Port Angeles.<br>
<br>
Only after the Moonbeam was safely tied to the dock did the harbor master mention that the 85-foot Coast Guard cutter Arcata was berthed on the other side.  While the hospitable wharfinger thoroughly enjoyed his role in putting one over on the Coasties, an anxious Schnarr snuck back out of the harbor before dawn, as soon as the wind abated.<br>
<br>
While on board the Miss Victoria II, during a delivery to liquor lord Carl Melby on Dungeness Spit, Schnarr ran into a different kind of problem.  Though the weather was fair with only a light swell running, the tide change caused huge breakers to form near the sandy shallows.  Responding to the usual flashlight signal, two shorts and two longs, Schnarr's assistant, Griffith, piled a load of hooch into the flat-bottomed skiff and headed toward land.<br>
<br>
Near shore a wave caught him, overturning the boat and tossing him ashore unconscious.  Griffith was revived, every bottle was recovered unbroken, and Schnarr and Griffith eventually climbed back aboard the Miss Victoria-but not before another rogue wave once again sent them bow-over-stern.<br>
<br>
However lucrative, waterborne deliveries comprised only half of the rumrunners' business.  To realize the greatest profits, contraband liquor had to be transferred from drop-off points to metropolitan markets.  Shoreside authorities' physical and mental mettle was put to the test as they chased moonshiners by day and rumrunners by night.<br>
<br>
Jefferson County Sheriff Phil Chase was well known in the area as the "scourge of the Volstead violators." Relentless in his pursuit of offenders, Chase rounded up operators of stills with capacities ranging from one pint to 100 gallons.  The stills themselves were donated to the Women's Christian Temperance Union so they could receive the proceeds from the recycled copper.<br>
<br>
The enterprising sheriff also made headway against the land-based
rumrunning operations of Port Angeles, Dungeness, and Blyn by setting up roadblocks near Port Discovery, where a sharp turn in the road offered natural cover to the police.<br>
<br>
Despite tip-offs by locals, including an alert network of phone operators, one successful blockade snared three high-powered cars and 50 cases of liquor valued at $3,000.<br>
<br>
The unfortunate auto rumrunner Arlie Seifort met his match when he was pulled over near Mount Walker while driving a truck belonging to W. J. Wallace of Des Moines.  At first, the officers weren't at all interested in his cargo of potatoes. It was only when Seifort jumped from the running board, falling 200 feet from the bridge embankment into the Quilcene River canyon, that they because suspicious.<br>
<br>
Fifteen cases of Johnny Walker Red were discovered hidden under the pile of spuds, and Seifort was apprehended the next morning as he climbed back up the bank.<br>
<br>
In local newspaper stories, which were all but buried amidst the excitement over the proposed <B>Olympic </B>Loop Highway, Sheriff Chase complained about the public's apathetic attitude toward his crusade.  Even while recounting his successes reporters tended to write in a joking manner about the <B>rum</B>runners' escapades, and the local citizenry seemed to entertain a good deal of sympathy for the scoundrels, often showing them hospitality and offering aid.<br>
<br>
Doris Hufford, who lived on Protection island, recalled a boat running aground there on its way back to Victoria after a booze run.  Though the "guests," as she referred to them, had guns and "binocular cases stuffed with wet money," they were courteous and helpful.  The grounded boat floated away, but was later located in Discovery Bay by Hufford's father and the culprits continued their escape over the border.<br>
<br>
When caught, transgressors of distilling and rumrunning were routinely fined $250 plus costs, with <B>am </B>occasional 30 to 60 days in jail for repeat offenders.  The confiscated liquor, however, may have been too tempting for some to pass <B>up.  </B><br>
<br>
After reports of the smashing of 40 cases of <B>fine </B>whiskey, beer, and champagne at the Port Townsend city dump rumors circulated about an "enormous, bold and ferocious ghost white rodent, without parallel in the history of ratdom."<br>
<br>
Nameless participants in the romance of rumrunning suffered even worse luck.  Boating at night without lights in the nastiest weather the strait could produce was dangerous at best.<br>
<br>
One stormy February night, <B>a </B>resident of Beckett Point on the east side of Discovery Bay, heard a crash.  The next morning, he found the wreck of a "neat little cabin cruiser" thought to be a rumrunner
abandoned on shore.  <B>On </B>another occasion, Captain Lonsdale of the Areata fired on a boat off Port Townsend, seriously injuring a crew member.<br>
<B><br>
In </B>1924, frustrated with the ineffectiveness of their older boats, the Coast Guard launched a new fleet of 75-foot rum chasers powered by 200 horsepower Sterling engines, these "hooch hounds" could achieve speeds of tip to 18 knots, posing a new threat to the rum trade.<br>
<br>
Though many of his competitors were forced out of business, Schnarr rose to the occasion replacing his old engines with 300 horse power airplane engines, bumping his speed up to 30 knots. Soon he was commissioning ever larger and faster boats.<br>
<br>
One December night in the late 1920s Schnarr set out to make a delivery halfway down Discovery Bay. But the revenuer had been tipped off and were waiting along the dark shore as he entered the enclosed harbor.  Luckily, Schnarr's excellent night vision was able to detect the phosperescence from the cutter's bow wave.<br>
<br>
Schnarr hit the throttle, split the boat around and tore through a volley of machine gun fire and tracer bullets, tearing past five more revenuer before hitting open water.  Later, he learned that ten cutters had been sent out and a $25,000 reward offered for the capture of his boat.<br>
<br>
With the onset of the Depression rum running slowed as demand diminished.  The few folks who could afford liquor at all began to switch to moonshine.  Meanwhile, anti-prohibition sentiment was gathering momentum; opponents cited overbearing government power and increased crime.  More importantly the ban had eliminated jobs and reduced tax revenues.<br>
<br>
During the presidential election of 1932, the Democratic party and its candidate, Franklin D.  Roosevelt, endorsed the repeal of prohibition.  <B>On </B>April 4, 1933, the country's most ambitious moral experiment came to an end.<br>
<br>
And the rumrunners? Most sold their highly specialized boats wherever they could and resumed normal lives. Even the often sought but never caught Schnarr was forced to piece out his last boat.<br>
<br>
After a spelling at logging, Schnarr fished commercially off the west coast of Vancouver Island, retiring at the age of 75. And down on the Olympic Peninsula, dark, stormy nights were once again peaceful.<br>
<br>
Lynn Ove Mortenson, "Black nights and bootleg booze," <B>Peninsula Magazine.</B> VIII (Summer, 1993) p. 40-43.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
SMUGGLING.<br>
<br>
Peter Simpson, "Smuggling around Port Townsend," <B>City of Dreams, a guide to Port Townsend.</B> Port Townsend: The Bay Press, 1986.<br>
p. 249-251.<br>
<br>
Two boys had been patching a derelict skiff for days, picking up remnants of oakum from the boat yard and stuffing them into the cracks and crevices that lined the old hull.  They were close to a launching but needed some pitch to top the seams.  They searched around the many piers that dotted Port Townsend's water front in the <B>1920S, </B>hoping to find some roofing tar hidden among the accumulated debris.<br>
<br>
At the end of the line, near UNION WHAPF, one of them found a large, tightly sealed can.  On prying it open, they discovered a dark sticky substance that appeared to be just right for the job.<br>
<br>
They carried their find to the old boat and built a fire.  Before long they were covering the dinghy with a hot goo.  There was a familiarity to the odor that drifted down the beach.  By time the old sailors had tracked it to its source, the boys were somewhere beyond incoherent.  They sat in a stupor contemplating their labor, a worthless rowboat caulked with five pounds of opium.<br>
<br>
October was unusually cold in 1979.  The cruising season was two months gone, and except for commerciai <B>traffic, few boats ventured </B>into the twisting channels that separate the San Juan Islands.  Of those that did, one was under special scrutiny.  Drug Enforcement Agency (DEA) men had been watching a particular island for a long time.  They had expected the boat and knew why it had come.  It was dark when the agents went ashore.<br>
<br>
In the ensuing confusion, the boat managed to slip its moorings and escape, heading south.  It was fast and powerfull, a good match for the Coast Guard cutter that pursued it.  They followed by radar as it cleared Cattle Point and headed across the Strait of Juan de Fuca.  By the time they reached Point Wilson, it had vanished from their screens.<br>
<br>
The morning after the unsuccessful DEA raid, a Discovery Bay resident reported finding a large plastic bag full of tightly wrapped plant material.  Via citizens I                                                                                          band radio, word spread fast.<br>
<br>
When the Coast Guard cutter Point Bennett raced around the eastern end of the strait picking up bale after bale of "Thai stick," the shore near North Beach was being scoured by interested citizens and local police.<br>
<br>
A local gillnetter informed the Coast Guard by radio that he had picked up several kilos and would deliver them to Seattle.  In all,
more than two million dollars worth of marijuana was recovered, much of it still on the smugglers' boat, which was found abandoned off Whidbey Island.  The helpful fisherman never arrived in Seattle.  Twelve days later he put out a distress call.  He was found drifting <B>in</B> his boat south of Smith Island.  Due to lack of evidence, no charges were filed against him.<br>
<br>
When the DEA made its raid in 1979, the boys who had caulked their boat with opium were more than sixty years old, but over the years the game had changed very little.  Even the basic commodities remained the same.  Smuggling on the Olympic Peninsula began as soon as there was a border to cross.<br>
<br>
At first it was done with relative impunity.  In the early 1850s, the customs district headquarters were located in Olympia, a comfortable spot, but too far away from the action to be an effective deterrent.  When the port of entry was moved to Port Townsend, the level of risk increased slightly, but important contraband flowed like water through a sieve.<br>
<br>
Until Victor Smith took over customs duty <B>in 1861,</B> <B>" </B> smuggling was a truly democratic institution, practiced by each according to want.  Smith took the radical approach that even in territories laws were to be accorded a certain respect.<br>
<br>
His first act was to come down hard on the importation without taxation of Canadian whiskey.  By increasing the level of difficulty, hc also increased the degree of specialization necessary to overcome it.  By the cnd of the Civil War, smuggling was a well-established trade in the Northwest.<br>
<br>
With restrictions on <B>CHINESE </B>immigration and the inception of the Chinese Exclusion Acts, an element of grotesque cruelty was added to the scene.  Chinese, desperate to get into the country, would sign on with unscrupulous smugglers.  Herded on board ships like cattle, they were shackled on deck to an anchor chain.  If the ship were approached by a customs boat, the anchor would be cut loose, sending the evidence to the bottom of the strait.<br>
<br>
Like other outlaws of the time, a cult of personality surrounded the smugglers.  They were both reviled and revered as Robin Hoods.  While their deeds were often widely known or at least surmised, lack of sufficient evidence kept most from jail.  Those that were appre-
hended generally received light sentences.<br>
<br>
The most notorious, men like James Jamieson and Larry Kelly, were a continual topic in Puget Sound newspapers.  The blame for enery unsolved crime in the region would invariably find its way to their doorstep.  A few, like State Legislator Ed Sims, even managed to turn their notoriety to political advantage.<br>

Since the turn of the century, smuggling on Puget Sound has waxed and waned with the fashions of law and society, its profitability increasing in proportion to the measures used to halt it.<br>
<br>
Peter Simpson, "Smuggling around Port Townsend," <B>City of Dreams, a guide to Port Townsend.</B> Port Townsend: The Bay Press, 1986. p. 249-
251.<br>
<br>
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
O. S. Vanolinda, "Dope," <B>History of Vashon-Maury Islands.</B> Vashon,  Washington: The Vashon Island News Review, 1935, p. 84-87.<br>
<br>
Some thirteen years after the first settlement was made on Vashon, in the summer of 1891, to be exact, J. E. Mace bought a ten-acre tract of wild land In what was then known as the "Vermontville" settlement, now (1935)) the Glen Acres district.<br>
<br>
Thirteen years seems almost a life-time, perhaps, to a youngster of that age, but it wasn't really much time in those days when homes had to be carved and grubbed from the virgin forest, the popular tools being the axe and grub hoe and our islands were still something above ninety-eight per cent timber land.  In those days, too, everything which came to the farmer's meat-house was meat.  In other words, Vashon farmers made use of every available thing which came to hand and wasted little.<br>
<br>
Mace, at heart a pioneer, had few resources and almost every Sunday would see him combing the beach, where he picked up quantities of lumber and often other articles of which he could, and did, make use.<br>
<br>
Thus it happened that he was taking his usual stroll on the beach one fine Sunday morning in the early spring of 1895 and came upon a strong canvas sack which contained something very heavy.  He dragged it a little way up from the tide and carefully cut the strong cord with which it was tied-the sack would come in handy at "tater digging time," whatever its contents might be-and found a number of small tin cans, eighty of them when he counted them, they about one pound each and each very neatly and carefully wrapped in oiled paper, but with no label or mark of any nature to disclose what they might contain.<br>
<br>
He cut open the top of one of the cans with the large blade of his pocket knife and found it filled with a yellowish brown, pasty mass which had little odor and he was no wiser than when he had first found the sack.<br>
<br>
He carried the sack of cans up off the beach a short distance on the south side of Dilworth Point, hid it under a large log and, taking
the can he had opened, went up the hill to the home of a neighbor, John Hopkins and asked him if he knew what queer kind of putty it was.<br>
<br>
Hopkins was an Englishman, widely travelled and of education and experience.  He took one glance, at Mace's "Putty" and told him that it was opium.<br>
<br>
Mace knew that there "was a law," but he didn't know a thing as to its details.  He went back and carried the sack of dope up the hill and showed his find to Asa Start, an old friend and neighbor who lived directly across the road from his own place.  They buried the stuff on Start's place, making a rough map and marking the spot where it was hidden so that it could be easily found again.<br>
<br>
This map Mace gave to his wife, telling her to give it to anyone who might come around looking for the stuff-if such should happen and he took the next morning boat for Seattle to learn his rights and duties in regard to it.<br>
<br>
Two strangers had been for several days roaming over the island, ostensibly looking for a tract of land to suit them, but in talking with the farmers, invariably bringing the conversation around to the subject of smugglers and dope running.<br>
<br>
They put in an appearance at the Hopkins place on the very<br>
morning on which Mace left for Seattle and, after some small talk, asked Hopkins if he had ever heard of any dope showing up on the island.  He told them of Mace's find of the day previous.<br>
<br>
They lost no time in getting up to the Mace place and exchanged knowing glances when Mrs. Mace told them that Mr. Mace was "not at home." After considerable questioning they finally told her they were officers looking for opium, which was supposed to be in Mace's possession.<br>
<br>
She said she knew nothing whatever of it, but showed them the map which he had given her.  ' They wasted no more time in conver-
sation, but at once resurrected the dope and carted it off to Seattle.<br>
<br>
Returning- home that evening, Mace learned what had taken place, then back to Seattle the next morning to put in his claim at the Customs office, but it availed him nothing.  The man in charge told him that he had had no part in assisting them and furthermore, that both he and Start were under suspicion and the less they had to say the healthier it might be for them. Mace didn't even get his "tater sack" out of the transaction.<br>
<br>
So he returned to his grub-hoe and stumps, a little Poorer, but.
much-very much-wiser.  He conveyed the impression to his neighbors by the use of numerous lurid adjectives, not really naughty, You understand, as he was a good , but forcible, satisfying and to the point, that next time, if any, things would be decidedly different.<br>
<br>
History repeated itself so quickly in this instance that it might almost be said to have stuttered.  Three weeks after his first adventure in the suppression of the dope evil, M<ace was again devoting himself to the business and pleasure of combing scantlings  and other flotson and Jetson from the beach when he came upon another heavy canvas sack, identical with his first find.<br>
<br>
This time he carried it up into the timber and quickly and skillfully concealed it, doing it, as he said, " with one hand so that even his other hand didn't know what was going on," and he took counsel with no one.<br>
<br>
The following morning he disturbed the slumbers of his son, Ed, at an early hour with orders to row him down to Vashon Landing in time for him to catch the Iola/  Just Off the south side of Dilworth Point he had his son beach the boat where he carried aboard one heavy canvas sack, which might have contained clams, so far as the son knew, but it really was something vastly different from clams.<br>
<br>
On reaching Vashon Dock the sack was transferred to the little steamer, to Seattle and then up to the Customs Office, where he turned it in and made his claim for the reward allowed by law in such cases.<br>
<br>
Owing to the, to them, suspicious circumstances surrounding their very recent contact with Mace, the customs officers "put up an argument" and held the case up for several weeks but finally on a court order by Judge Hanford in June, 1895, Mace received one hundred and seventy-five dollars for turning in his "brown putty." It was reported at the time to have sold for $564.00.<br>
<br>
The federal officers, however, were far from satisfied as to Mace's exact status.  Months passed.  Ed Mace married, built the present home, put in a little saw mill and was working it one day when two men with guns and dogs stopped to talk with him.  They volunteered the information that they were hunting grouse and presently one of them asked what were the chances of borrowing Ed's cap, as his "hat was a damned nuisance, following the dogs through the brush.<br>
<br>
Ed let him have the cap and the men went into the woods to the north a distance of about half a mile to a trail which they thought was being used by smugglers. Here they gave the dogs the scent of Ed's cap and vainly endeavored to get them to lead them
back to the little sawmill.<br>
<br>
The dogs, no doubt, saved Ed a heap of trouble as it as later discovered that the men were government detectives and the dogs bloodhounds.<br>
<br>
O. S. Vanolinda, "Dope," <B>History of Vashon-Maury Islands.</B> Vashon, Washington: The Vashon Island News Review, 1935. p. 84-87.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
SMUGGLING.<br>
<br>
B. H. Scribner, "A wine smuggler spills all," <B>Seattle Magazine.</B> V(November, 1968) p. 11-14.<br>
<br>
Three months ago, this magazine published a brief commentary about three physicians who had been convicted of smuggling wines into Washington State from California [Publisher's Page, August, 1968].  I am one of those physicians, and I am writing this article both to explain why I felt compelled to break Washington's liquor law and to suggest some ways in which that law might b@ changed.<br>
<br>
I first became interested in wines in 1957, when I was granted a year's sabbatical from my teaching position at the U. of W. During that year, my wife and I lived in London, and though neither of us had even a rudimentary knowledge of wine (color perception was our only means of differentiating between red wine and white), through a combination of dining in some of London's better restaurants and taking occasional side trips to France we soon discovered the exciting world of wine tasting.<br>
<br>
By the time we returned to Seattle, we had both developed such a strong liking for fine wines that I resolved to start collecting great vintages of one particular variety-namely, Bordeaux rouge, or claret, as it is called in England.<br>
<br>
Why red Bordeaux? First, because I happen to like the taste of the wine better than that of red Burgundies or any of the white wines.  More important, among "still" wines-that is, wines which have not been fortified with alcohol-Bordeaux is the one most suitable for collecting because aging in the bottle enhances its quality.  Most white wines should be drunk fairly soon after they are bottled, and even the best red Burgundies reach their peak of perfection within 5 to 10 years.  A truly great claret, in contrast, should not be opened for at least 20 years, and may be kept in the bottle for as long as four or five decades.<br>
<br>
In theory, at least, it is possible to enjoy great wines simply by purchasing a choice vintage whenever the mood strikes you. 
However, this practice is exorbitantly expensive, since the demand for a great wine always far exceeds the supply.  The result is that the price of the important vintages increases rapidly with the passage of time. (For example, a case of 1961 Lafite -
Rothschild purchased as soon as available in 1964 has now more than doubled in value.)<br>
<br>
In addition, on-the-spot purchase is usually impractical because of the very limited number of really good wine merchants with adequate cellar capacity for prolonged storage.  Besides, wine collecting makes wine drinking much more exciting.<br>
<br>
A truly great wine has a life of its own, perhaps not in a biological sense, but certainly in terms of processes that are going on all the time in the bottle: sedimentation, aging, the gradual improvement of flavor and bouquet.  Therefore, the enjoyment of vintage wines is enhanced by selecting them soon after they are bottled, letting them age in your own cellar and then, many years later, sharing them with a son-or even a grandson.<br>
<br>
Moreover, I enjoy the challenge of distinguishing a great wine from a lesser one by comparing the wines in my cellar to learn for myself whether all that is said about a given vintage is true.  These things require the maintenance of a sizable cellar.<br>
<br>
In Washington, I soon discovered, it is impossible to build up a good wine collection by buying through the state liquor<br>
stores,  simply because  these  stores  are  not set up to  handle fine wines. No  state  store  I have ever seen, for  example,   has  a wine cellar; instead, the wines usually are placed upright on a shelf .<br>
<br>
While this sort of treatment is not injurious to most alcoholic beverages, fine wines require considerably more care. When bottles of wine are stored upright, their corks dry out and allow air to enter, which creates the possibility of spoilage.  The same result can be produced if the room temperature fluctuates too far above or below the ideal level of 55 to 60 degrees. (Wines obtained by special order through the Liquor Control Board, I might point out, are shipped with the regular boxcar loads of other beverages-and they often sit on a siding under the hot sun for hours at a time.)<br>
<br>
Another obstacle to procuring good wines through the Liquor Board, I found, is that the Board has no means of learning what the good wines are.  It does not employ a single knowledgeable wine buyer, and even if it did, the Board lacks the direct purchasing connections necessary to obtain first-rate foreign wines.<br>
<br>
A customer wishing to buy, say, a fine Bordeaux must be able to
tell the Board which importer handles the wine he desires, and he must then pay the importer's regular retail price, plus the Board's markup of 76.64 per cent. (Incidentally, the local retail stores that handle good wines also have to buy through the Liquor Control Board.  Because they have liquor licenses, they do not pay as high a markup as individuals pay, but they still have to tell the Board what importer to buy from, they still have no control over methods of shipment, and quite often they are not permitted to order wines in the quantities they desire.)<br>
<br>
Perhaps the greatest handicap to procuring fine wines through the Liquor Board, though, is the well-known rule which prohibits their employees' offering the customer any advice at all.  This, of course, places a great burden upon the collector, who needs to be apprised of many details about the wines (the idiosyncrasies of the chateau, the characteristics of the "year") before making his selection-a service unthinkable to the Liquor Board.<br>
<br>
Small wonder, then, that I finally decided to bypass the Board completely and to build my wine collection from out-of-state sources.<br>
<br>
My first break came in 1959, when a famous restaurant in San Francisco went out of business.  A close friend of mine was in charge of the wine cellar there, and he agreed to sell me his entire Bordeaux collection at cost.  With this bounty as a nucleus, I gradually built up my collection by ordering wines through a San Francisco importer who, as a result of his yearly trips to France, was able to give me expert advice about which wines to buy.<br>
<br>
Because of the Washington liquor law, I could not have the wine shipped directly to Seattle, so whenever I drove down to San Francisco, I would load a few cases in the back of my station wagon and haul them back up the coast.<br>
<br>
In those days I did not think of this practice as "criminal." Though I knew I was breaking a law, I had been given to understand that in matters of this sort the law was winked at.  "As long as you don't sell the stuff," a member of the Liquor Board had told my attorney in 1962, "and as long as you're not out to beat the system by bringing in the stock items we handle, it's okay.  "<br>
<br>
I understood, of course, that this pronouncement was unofficial, but it was not until this past Spring that I discovered how " unofficial" it really was.  In early May while my wife and I were attending a medical conference in Atlantic City, N.J., Liquor Control Board officers who we learned with a search warrant entered my home through an unlocked door and Confiscated every bottle of wine they could find that was not normally stocked in the state liquor stores.  Each item they took was carefully noted
on an inventory sheet which they left conspicuously on my coffee table.<br>
<br>
When I got back from the East Coast and discovered what had happened, I couldn't believe it.  Even after I had called my attorney, it didn't sink in for hours that this was really serious-that I had actually committed a criminal offense, for which I could get sent to jail.<br>
<br>
The following day, though, I turned myself in at the county jail, where I was booked, photographed and finger printed (a procedure which I found degrading, to say the least), and on May 22, I appeared <B>in</B> court.  After being found guilty, I was given a six-month suspended sentence for "possession of illegal alcohol," and in addition, I was fined $250.<br>
<br>
After the criminal prosecution was over, my attorney and I started negotiations with the Liquor Control Board for return of my wine.  We indeed were lucky that there was any wine left to negotiate about, since the ,Board's usual practice is to destroy the loot immediately upon confiscation.  In my case, somehow they sensed that destroying my beautiful collection of claret would be like destroying a collection of fine stamps or paintings.<br>
<br>
The negotiations led to the opportunity to repurchase the collection by paying 76.64 per cent of the original retail purchase price.  Because of the immense cost, I bought back only as much as I could afford, and several of my wine-loving friends got together and purchased most of the remaining bottles.<br>
<br>
All things considered, the Liquor Control Board treated me quite well.  They had been forced to seize my wines oft a complaint from a spiteful informant, and I think they felt genuinely dismayed at having to prosecute me.  Even so, I still find it difficult to recall the experience with equanimity.  The fact remains that I was convicted of a gross misdemeanor, that I received a good deal of unfavorable publicity, and that, because my case concerned illegal alcohol, I now have " mug shots" and fingerprints on file with the F.B.I.<br>
<br>
These things resulted not from my having done anything which I consider morally wrong, but rather from my having broken a state law designed to protect Washington "wines" which, to my palate, are undrinkable.  In my opinion, this law should be changed, and I propose three ways to do it.<br>
<br>
My first suggestion-first because it would solve the problem for the wine connoisseur, and because it is the simplest-would be to modify the existing laws to exempt "still" wines from state control, just as beer is now exempted.  If this were done, anyone
who was interested could become a wine merchant. (Frederick & Nelson, for example, with its buying connections in Europe and else-here, could really go to town with its wine department.) Moreover, California wine merchants would be able to sell directly to Washington residents.<br>
<br>
To be sure, the wine would still have  to  be  taxed  at  a  fair  rate, just like everything else, but at  least  it  would be readily available here.<br>
<br>
Another reason to support this course of action is that removing still wines from Liquor Board control could (depending on how the out-of-state wine tax is structured) expose the Washington wine Producers to the beneficial effects of world competition.  Far from being ruinous to this local industry, such competition could lead to a vast improvement in the quality of Washington wines.<br>
<br>
It has been demonstrated conclusively that if proper production methods are used, it is possible to produce good wines from Washington-grown grapes-wines of such quality that they could compete with those from New York and California, as well as those from foreign countries, indeed, if the law were changed, Washington might well become as famous for its wines as it is for its apples and its airplanes.<br>
<br>
A second possibility-difficult for a state run operation but still feasible-would be for the Liquor Control Board itself to become a sophisticated wine merchant.  This would require hiring a knowledgeable person to run the wine division; having several well-stocked retail outlets with proper temperature-controlled cellars; setting up lines of communication to deal directly with shippers in Bordeaux, Burgundy, Germany and elsewhere; and permitting the wine store employees to recommend vintages.<br>
<br>
It would be a sweeping change, but if it could be worked out, the Liquor Control Board could probably compete quite well with private wine merchants-perhaps even in price.<br>
<br>
The third alternative would be to permit each wine lover to purchase his own wine openly, arrange for its shipment under proper conditions of temperature and storage and then pay the Liquor Control Board a 'air amount for the privilege of doing so.<br>
<br>
One simple way of doing this would be for the supplier automatically to send a copy of the invoice to the Washington Liquor Authorities, who would then bill the customer for the taxes due.<br>
<br>
Perhaps none of these alternatives is entirely acceptable, but certainly something has to be done. Now that collecting fine wine
is  clearly established as a criminal offense, it is obvious that most collectors simply will abandon this fascinating hobby because of the most unpleasant possibility that they could end up in jail.<br>
<br>
More important is the fact that the residents of the State of Washington are being denied the opportunity to explore the world of fine wines.<br>
<br>
B. H. Scribner, "A wine smuggler spills all," <B>Seattle Magazine.</B> V (November, 1968) p. 11-14.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
SMUGGLING.<br>
<br>
"Cigale smuggling case continues in court," <B>Marine Digest.</B> LIX (November 8, 1980) p. 22.<br>
<br>
PORTLAND - The nearly three-year-old Cigale marijuana smuggling case came to life again last week when Tommy Tindale, 35, of Virginia, went on trial in U.S. District Court here on charges of conspiracy, importation and possession of illegal marijuana.<br>
Two other men, Thomas Gerald Marengo, 30, of Connecticut, and Richard Scacchetano, 30, of New York, pleaded guilty to the charges.<br>
<br>
Authorities are looking for eleven others, seven of whom are fugitives, to face similar charges.<br>
<br>
The Cigale is a 126-foot ex-yacht which landed on a lonesome beach near Bandon, OR, on Dec. 31, 1977, with 17,000 pounds of marijuana.<br>
Federal, state, county and Coast Guard agents were lying in wait and raided the landing party, capturing 17 men, of whom 12 were convicted and sent to prison.<br>
<br>
The ship was brought to Portland and ultimately sold at auction to Bert E. May, for $203,000.  May converted her for black cod fishing, but with a poor-paying season he now has the vessel up for sale at Metakatla, AK, to an Alaskan Indian corporation.<br>
<br>
Federal authorities said the last group of 14 men are still facing smuggling charges.  Seven are fugitives, two pleaded guilty, one will have a separate trial, and one is awaiting disposition on
other drug charges.  One man died in Massachusetts of an apparent overdose of drugs.<br>
<br>
"Cigale smuggling case continues in court," <B>Marine Digest.</B> LIX (November 8, 1980)  p. 22.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
SMUGGLING.<br>
<br>
Nicholas E. Davis, "Some notes on Puget Sound smuggling," a paper written for Professor Michael Allen, University of Washington, Tacoma, as an intern at the Tacoma Public Library, 1994.<br>
<br>
"After the Treaty of 1846 settled the issue of the Canadian American border it resulted in opportunities to move goods illegally between the two countries without paying duty.(Keve 64)" Thus started one of the most lucrative smuggling operations in North America: illegal trade in various goods between British Columbia and the state of Washington, usually by boat through the waters of Puget Sound. Profitable items to smuggle included rum, Canadian whiskey, British woolens, opium, and illegal aliens.<br>
<br>
The late 1800s saw a dramatic increase in the amount of smuggling between Vancouver Island and Washington state. "Smuggling goods from Vancouver to Washington afforded profits tempting to island boat owners.(McDonald Seattle Times 29 Mar 59)" The boat owners were hauling Chinese laborers who would later work building American railroads. The Chinese also sparked the smuggling of Opium, a product they consumed.<br>
<br>
Lawrence Kelly was one  smuggler in both Chinese laborers and opium. Kelly was able to establish himself as a successful smuggler and avoid customs officials until "May 16 1886 when his Whitehall boat, sail and oars were seized at Tacoma.(McDonald 29 Mar 59)" The cargo of Kelly's craft consisted of "567 tins of prepared opium or the equivalent of 364 pounds of opium.(McDonald 29 Mar 59)" This was not  the last time that Lawrence Kelly was caught and fined by the customs service.<br>
<br>
Kelly earned the nickname the "King of smugglers" from both his peers in the business and the local press. Kelly continued to smuggle until 1909  as his "25 year career as one of the most notorious smugglers on the Pacific Coast came to an end  he then retired to a Louisiana soldiers home where he died.(McDonald 29 Mar 59)".<br>
<br>
The individual smuggler, like Lawrence Kelly also competed with larger smuggling operations on Puget Sound. The smuggling syndicate that operated out of Tacoma  in July of 1897 included
"government customs officers, political and financial leaders and even a special agent of the Secret Service"(Newell 11/21).<br>
<br>
The syndicate in Tacoma smuggled opium and Chinese laborers from British Columbia on the ship "Haytian Republic(Newell)", which also loaded legitimate cargo along with the contraband. The smugglers  used the Haytian Republic as a mother ship for smaller vessels sailing into Canadian waters to pick up the opium and Chinese. This operation involved dozens more people and a larger numbers of boats than the traditional single boat operation more common in Puget Sound.<br>
<br>
The Tacoma smuggling ring came to an end in "1898 when special investigators arrived from Washington D.C. to look into reports of government involvement in illegal trade.(Newell)" The smuggling  ring was destroyed, its perpetrators sentenced to  prison, and investors  never received a return  on their investment in the smuggling trade. Several customs officials were also arrested or released from their posts for failing to stop the smuggling that was only lightly concealed from authorities.<br>
<br>
A far smaller smuggling operation that also involved federal assets, indirectly, was conducted by  Jimmie Jones on his mail carrying duties on Puget Sound. Jimmie Jones was responsible for carrying the "United States mail, weekly, between Olympia and Victoria and all intermediate ports.(Huggins 9 Dec 1900)" This was a smuggler's dream-- entering and leaving the various ports along Puget Sound carrying the mail and all the extra contraband you could carry on your vessel.<br>
<br>
In fact, Jimmie Jones was finally arrested for smuggling and for "disregarding revenue laws of the United States(Huggins 9 Dec 1900)." Yet Jimmie Jones never made it to trial--he took his boat the "Jenny Jones" and bypassed the Customs House at Port Townsend. "The Customs House representative, who was on board, made all manner of threats to turn back to Port Townsend.(Huggins 9 Dec 1900)" Jimmie Jones released the customs agent after  the Jenny Jones had cleared Port Townsend never to be arrested again for smuggling on Puget Sound.<br>
<br>
The smuggling trade continued on Puget Sound into the twentieth century, with a new focus on Canadian Whiskey. The Prohibition amendment passed Congress in 1919, calling for abstinence from liquor. Needless to say there was still a market for good liquor despite government action to make the nation "dry". "In 1916, after a statewide vote, Washington began its own ill-fated experiment with prohibition"(Clark 15).<br>
<br>
Yet, the smugglers continued to risk federal prosecution by running whiskey between wet Canada and the  dry United States. A Seattle police lieutenant, Roy Olmstead, became partners with the very people he was charged to arrest. Roy Olmstead was the ring
leader of group of Seattle bootleggers. "During the twenties, newspapers hailed Olmstead as the booze baron"(Clark 14) due to Olmstead's claim to deliver only pure Canadian liquor, not the watered down variety  many smuggling operations used to stretch profits.<br>
<br>
It was not until 1920 that Olmstead was arrested and fined 500 dollars for violating the "Volstead Act"(Clark 16) and was dismissed from the police force. After being dismissed from the Seattle Police force Olmstead was able "to devote all his time and energy to the liquor business"(Clark 16).<br>
<br>
The smuggling operation, run by Olmstead, continued to grow through the early twenties until his reputation was became one of a "modern day Robin Hood"(Clark 14). This popular label among the people of Seattle stemmed from Olmstead's "unique code of ethics"(Clark 16) that included the idea that no amount of money was worth a human life and that his men never carried firearms while smuggling. "For most Seattle dwellers, it was impossible to regard Olmstead as an authentic criminal"(Clark 16).<br>
<br>
Despite his dismissal from the police department, Olmstead, was able to use his connections to obtain information and ask for leniency for his employees caught smuggling. By 1924 Olmstead's luck ran out and he was again arrested for conspiracy and smuggling,  making national headlines. Federal agents obtained information on Olmstead through a series of wire taps. Olmstead knew the taps had been placed but was able to use "public phones to give directions and orders to his men"(Clark 17).<br>
<br>
Arrested on January 19, 1925 "Olmstead and his attorney cried loudly that their civil liberties had been violated"(Clark 17), due to the wire tapping. Olmstead was able to make bail and, despite  a lengthy court battle, "he placed an order to Canada for more liquor and set boats and trucks in motion again"(Clark 17). Thus, the legend continued that Olmstead would not let even the Federal government interfere with his booming business, however illegal the transactions.<br>
<br>
The court battle continued and ended in "March 1926 when Roy Olmstead was fined 8000 dollars and sentenced to four years at hard labor"(Clark 17). It was not until March of 1927 that Olmstead demanded the issue of the wire taps be reviewed by the courts as an invasion of privacy. "The United States Supreme Court agreed to review Olmstead's case and whether the use of evidence of private telephone conversations was unconstitutional"(Clark 17).<br>
<br>
The New York Times reported the case on page one when the Supreme Court ruled that evidence from wire taps could indeed be used in court. The New York Times complained that the Supreme Court's decision would "make universal snooping possible"(Lyon 1a). With
the courts decision came the end of another smuggling career with Olmstead serving his time at McNiel Island Federal Prison. The case served to illustrate the growing problems with prohibition and its enforcement.<br>
<br>
There was growing public opinion that prohibition should be repealed, however, that would take several more years. But, Roy Olmstead, a Seattle bootlegger was the first to seriously challenge the unpopular policy.<br>
<br>
The last smuggler I want to discuss in this paper was by no means the most well known, or the best. Howard Elmer Fisher was caught several times in Port Angeles for smuggling Canadian whiskey. Yet despite his shortcomings, he was the reason I wanted to research smuggling in Puget Sound because he was my great grandfather. I started my research in his hometown of Port Angeles Washington where on a clear day you can see across the Straits of Juan de Fuca to the source of Canadian whiskey, Vancouver Island.<br>
<br>
The records I found were enlightening to say the least. The first thing I found was that he had an uncle by the name Frank Fisher who was the Customs Officer for the port of Port Angeles. This was the same man responsible for ensuring ships had the proper registry and had paid the necessary fees for cargo. Thus I discovered an early conflict in the chosen profession of his nephew Howard Elmer Fisher, a bootlegger.<br>
<br>
I discovered two court records pertaining to Howard Elmer Fisher, both for bootlegging Canadian whiskey. The second violation states that Howard Fisher was fined 100 dollars,  which he paid promptly, and appeared in  court the following week. This court record was dated November 15 1926 and goes on to say that the defendant never made his court appearance and thus forfeited any chance of getting any of his money back. The Port Angeles Evening News reported, on November 18 1926,  that Howard Fisher forfeited his bail to the Clallum County sheriff by failing to appear in court.<br>
<br>
Howard Fisher smuggled rum for two years and at the same time  used the mail boat, which he worked aboard, to run the rum into Port Angeles past his uncle working the customs house and into town for dispensing. This caused considerable strain on family relations, according to his daughter(and my grandmother) Joanne Matson, she related the following story to me about one smuggling incident that "had been talked about while she was growing up."<br>
<br>
The Port Angeles public dock during the mid 1920s had an area set aside for seized contraband. In this particular case the items on the dock were barrels of Canadian whiskey. Howard Fisher took his small boat and rowed under the dock at high tide. Then he proceeded down the dock until he was directly under the barrels of seized whiskey.<br>

By using a hand drill he was able to tap the barrels and empty its illegal contents into his waiting barrels on the rowboat. According to my source, this was  successful several times until Howard Fisher started to make his own smuggling runs into Canadian waters for larger profits.<br>
<br>
The authorities finally caught up  with Howard Fisher. However  he never served time in jail, as he left Washington state with the merchant marine and took up residence in California. The bootlegger may have been forced out of Port Angeles by his own uncle, who would later be promoted, and who retired as the senior customs agent in Port Angeles.<br>
<br>
The smugglers profiled thus far all used maritime traffic as their mode of smuggling goods over the Canadian and United States border. I should  note that there was a large demand for smuggling "Prohibition Brew"(Fish 198) through the use of domestic stills. In the fall of 1929 one family member recalls "the Christmas the still blew up"(Palmer 25). Although the profits for such home distilleries were high, imprisonment and physical damage to the home were not unusual.<br>
<br>
The home brew usually consisted of various fruits mixed with sugar and yeast to create a "mash that should stand seven to eight days and then run the mixture through the still to condense into a high alcohol liquid"(Fish 198) that was then suitable for distribution through the smugglers various methods.<br>
<br>
Thus, the origin of the contraband sometimes varied but the smuggling conducted within the Puget Sound region fell to an individual or a group of individuals who  smuggled goods in hopes of making a profit without getting into trouble with the law. The line between the criminal and the enforcer of federal laws was not always clear with human greed muddying the proverbial water of justice.<br>
<br>
The Volstead Act was enacted to try and enforce a standard for moral conduct. The failure of prohibition placed the standard of morality  in the private realm and not that of the federal government. Only history can judge the impact the bootlegger had on the eventual failure of prohibition. The fact remains that the market for illegal  liquor was large enough to warrant the activity of the bootlegger which in itself is a symptom of societal morality.<br>
<br>
Nicholas E. Davis, "Some notes on Puget Sound smuggling," a paper written for Professor Michael Allen, University of Washington, Tacoma, as an intern at the Tacoma Public Library, 1994.<br>
<br>

++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
LAWRENCE KELLY<br>
<br>
Marge Davenport, "Irishman most famous smuggler, " <B>Afloat and Awash in the Old Northwest.</B> Tigard, Oregon: Paddlewheel Press, 1988, p. 129-131.<br>
<br>
For more than 20 years, Lawrence Kelly, a genial Irishman and the most famous smuggler in Northwest history, led officers a merry chase.<br>
<br>
Kelly, who made his home on Sinclair Island in the San Juans, was a skillful sailor.  He had one of the fastest sloops in the San Juans and he knew every channel and reef.<br>
<br>
It was reported that Kelly's operations ranged from Alaska to Hawaii, but he evidently enjoyed most the chases that he gave officials as he carried opium, liquor and Chinese from Canadian Ports through the maze of island and reefs to Puget Sound points.<br>
<br>
The San Juan islands are located ideally for smuggling.  They are between two countries where the prices of commodities often were much higher in one than the other, and where restrictions varied radically, and there was great inducement to evade customs and immigration officials.<br>
<br>
Probably the first real illegal activity in the San Juan hole-
in-the-wall came before Kelly got into business.  It was in wool when wool was cheap in Canada and comparatively high in the States.<br>
<br>
For all appearances, it was wool raised on San Juan Island, but if it was there must have been "supersheep" because one farmer shipped more than 30 tons of wool to Port Townsend in one year from his few head of sheep.  At the time, wool was bought on Vancouver Island at 10 or 12 cents a pound and sold in Port Townsend for 30 cents a pound.<br>
<br>
When the San Juan Islands were put under the American flag in 1872, the smuggling business picked up.  The contraband became opium and Chinese.  The profit margin also increased.<br>
<br>
Kelly, who was a veteran of the Civil War, came west about this time, married and settled on Sinclair Island in 1877.  Shortly thereafter, he went into the smuggling business, and for the next 20 years he made it a battle of wits with customs and immigration officials and the U.S. Coast Guard.<br>
<br>
At first, the custom authorities were rather pathetically equipped to catch smugglers.  They started out in rowboats, then they got a
steam-propelled boat that traveled about 4 miles per hour.  This was known to the smugglers as the "Black Pup." Later, when they obtained speedier boats, these often were lured onto reefs by the wily Kelly and wrecked.<br>
<br>
The standard fare for putting a Chinese on U.S. soil in the 1800's was $50.  There were lurid tales about smuggling that tell of Chinese being thrown overboard in weighted wool sacks to drown when the Coast Guard threatened, but Kelly always emphatically denied that he ever drowned any of his human contraband.  He did admit to some of his friends that if officials threatened he sometimes simply put back to Vancouver Island and landed the unlucky Chinese there, letting them believe they were now in the United States.  Not even a Chinese could tell the difference on a dark, rainy night.<br>
<br>
Because he knew the islands so well, and had many well disguised secret coves and hiding places, there were many stories that still persist about Kelly's escapades.  His friends said Kelly really enjoyed the excitement and the smuggling game and considered it a battle of wits.  Those who knew him well added that he took good care of his family, loved to have friends over and make clam chowder for them and enjoyed social gatherings.  To officials, though, he was a desperado and a terror.<br>
<br>
After chasing Kelly over the years and never catching him, the local officials finally admitted themselves defeated and asked for help.  A Treasury Department expert, famed for running down smugglers in the East, was dispatched, and Kelly finally was caught.  He pleaded guilty in May, 1909, and spent a year at the Federal Penitentiary on McNeil's Island.  When he was released he was about 60 years old and he said he would go straight the rest of his life.<br>
<br>
But he found the going tough.  He was admitted later to a Confederate Soldier's Home, where he died.<br>
<br>
Another famous San Juan smuggler was Victor McConnell, who had McConnell's Island named for him.  He, too, knew the local waters well.  McConnell's specialty was Chinese, and he had a fast boat.  When he finally gave up the smuggling business, he opened a filling station near Seattle.<br>
<br>
When prohibition was passed, other smuggling gave way to rum-running.  This was an even more hazardous occupation because, by then, the Coast Guard had faster boats that were well-armed.  The rum-runners had speedy boats, too, and they used all the islands in their games.  There were dozens of hiding places used for caches of liquor enroute to Seattle and other points.  Most rum-runners operated in connection with a big ring in Seattle that used meat and vegetable trucks for deliveries for years.<br>
<br>
Rum-running flourished until the repeal of prohibition.  Today, customs and immigration officials keep a tight check on boats moving between Canadian and American ports and occasionally there is a report of some smuggling activity, but the colorful days of
smuggling in Puget Sound along with those who were actors in the drama of contraband have passed.<br>
<br>
Marge Davenport, "Irishman most famous smuggler, " <B>Afloat and Awash in the Old Northwest.</B> Tigard, Oregon: Paddlewheel Press, 1988, p. 129-131.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
LAWRENCE KELLY.<br>
<br>
Marge Davenport, "Smuggler Operated 20 Years," <B>Fabulous folks of the old northwest.</B> Tigard, Oregon: Wagonwheel Press, 1986.  p. 45-47.<br>
<br>
For more than 20 years, Lawrence Kelly a genial Irishman and the most famous smuggler in Northwest history, led officers a merry chase.<br>
<br>
Kelly, who made his home on Sinclair Island in the San Juans, was a skillful sailor.  He had one of the fastest sloops in the San Juans and he knew every channel and reef.<br>
<br>
It was reported that Kelly's operations ranged from Alaska to Hawaii, but he evidently enjoyed most the chases that he gave officials as he carried opium, liquor and Chinese from Canadian ports through the maze of islands and reefs to Puget Sound points.<br>
<br>
The San Juan islands are located ideally for smuggling.  They are between two countries where the prices of commodities often were higher in one than the other, and where restrictions varied radically, and there was great inducement to evade customes and immigration officials.<br>
<br>
Probably the first real illegal activity in the San Juan hole-in-the-wall came before Kelly got into business.  It was in wool when wool was cheap in Canada and comparatively high in the States.<br>
<br>
For all appearances, it was wool raised on San Juan Island, but if it was, there must have been "super-sheep" because one farmer shipped more than 30 tons of wool to Port Townsend in one year from his few head of sheep.  At the time, wool was bought on Vancouver Island at 10 or 20 cents a pound and sold in Port Townsend for 30 cents a pound.<br>
<br>
When the San Juan Islands were put under the American flag in 1872, the smuggling business picked up. The contraband became opium and Chinese.  The profit margin also increased.<br>
<br>
Kelly, who was a veteran of the Civil War, came west about this
time, married and settled on Sinclair Island in 1877.  Shortly thereafter, he went into the smuggling business, and for the next 20 years he made it a battle of wits with customs and immigration officals and the U.S. Coast Guard.<br>
<br>
At first, the customs authorities were rather pathetically equipped to catch smugglers.  They started out in rowboats, then they got a steam-propelled boat that traveled about 4 miles per hour.  This was known to the smugglers as the "Black Pup." Later, when they optained speedier boats, these were lured onto reefs by the wily Kelly and wrecked.<br>
<br>
The standard fare for putting a Chinese on U.S. soil in the 1800s was $50.  There were lurid tales about smuggling that tell of Chinese being thrown overboard in weighted wool sacks to drown when the Coast Guard threatened, but Kelly always emphatically denied that he ever drowned any of his human contraband.<br>
<br>
He did admit to some of his friends that if officials threatened he somtimes simply put back to Vancouver Island and landed the unlucky Chinese there, letting them believe they were now in the United States.  Not even a Chinese could tell the difference on a dark, rainy night.<br>
<br>
Because he knew the islands so well, and had many well disguised secret coves and hiding places, there were many stories that still persist about Kelly's escapades.  His friends said Kelly really enjoyed the excitement and the smuggling game and considered it a battle of wits.  Those who knew him well added that he took good care of his family, loved to have friends over and make clam chowder for them and enjoyed social gatherings.  To officials, though, he was a desperado and a terror.<br>
<br>
After chasing Kelly over the years and never catching him, the local officials finally admitted themselves defeated and asked for help.  A Treasury Department expert, famed for running down smugglers in the East, was dispatched, and Kelly finally was caught.  He pleaded guilty in May, 1909, and spent a year at the Federal Penitentiary on McNeil's Island.  Vaen he was released he was about 60 years old and he said he would go straight the rest of his life.<br>
<br>
But he found the going tough.  He was admitted later to a Confederate Soldier's Home, where he died.<br>
<br>
Another famous San Juan smuggler was Victor McConnell, who had McConnell's Island named for him.  He, too, knew the local waters well.  McConnnell's speciality was Chinese, and he had a fast boat.  When he finally gave up the smuggling business, he opened a filling station near Seattle.<br>
<br>
When prohibition was passed, other smuggling gave way to rum-running.  This was an even more hazardous occupation because, by then, the Coast Guard had faster boats that were well-armed.  The rum-runners had speedy boats too, and they used all the islands in
their games.  There were dozens of hiding places used for caches of liquor enroute in Seattle and other points.  Most rum-runners operated in connection with a big ring in Seattle that used meat and vegetable trucks for deliveries for years.<br>
<br>
Rum-running flourished until the repeal of prohibition.  Today, customs and immigration officials keep a tight check on boats moving between Canadian and American ports and occasionally there is a report of some smuggling activity, but the colorful days of smug-
gling in Puget Sound along with those who were actors in the drama of contraband have passed.<br>
<br>
Marge Davenport, "Smuggler Operated 20 Years," <B>Fabulous folks of the old northwest.</B> Tigard, Oregon: Wagonwheel Press, 1986.  p. 45-47.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
SMUGGLING<br>
<br>
Gordon Newell, Maritime Events of 1913, H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest. Seattle: Superior, 1966.. p. 218.<br>
<br>
A remarkable feat of navigation, though one looked upon without enthusiasm by Canadian authorities, was accomplished in July with the arrival at Bella Bella, B. C. of a 60 foot Japanese sampan.  Eleven Japanese were put ashore by the captain, who immediately put to sea again.  The small fishing craft, with 27 men aboard, had come from Japan in 70 days, the only navigating equipment being an ancient compass, merely a needle balanced on an upright pivot, and a six - inch - square map of North America.<br>
<br>
The skipper told Bella Bella villagers that he was bound for Alaska and thence back to Japan "looking for herring." Eight of the sampan's passengers were picked up by immigration officials when they arrived at Vancouver by steamer, and held for deportation.<br>
<br>
They said they had paid the sampan skipper from $ 50 to $ 100 each to bring them across the Pacific and land them somewhere near Seattle.  The William Jolliffe was dispatched to search for the wayward sampan, but there is no record of its ever having been apprehended. Gordon Newell, Maritime Events of 1913, H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest. Seattle: Superior, 1966.. p. 218.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
SMUGGLING.<br>
<br>
Roy Franklin Jones, "Early Smugglers," <B>Boundary Town, early days in a northwest boundary town.</B> Vancouver, Washington: Fleet
Printing Company, 1958. p. 234-253.<br>
<br>
I had heard the tales of smugglers and knew that the father of my school friends, Larry and Will Flanigan, had been a Customs Officer and with passing of time I learned more and more of some of the interesting events.  I heard so much about "Cowboy Jake Terry" that he was a living legend, a sinister one which kept cropping up from time to time until that day I joined the crowd to view his body, stretched out in the showcase of Gillies Swanson.  Now that I have looked up the record of those days<br>
<br>
I've found many details which had us puzzled at the time.  Some of the officers have been friends of mine and so I have been able with good fortune to put their stories together, to check one against the other and the records, thus revealing dramatic scenes and the thread of the stories which occasioned so much local rumor and conjecture.<br>
<br>
The coming of the railroads brought passenger and freight traffic and the beginning of large scale smuggling operations.  There was good money in smuggling Oriental silks.  Some stores in Whatcom and Seattle found it convenient to stock up on silks at attractive prices and not to question the manner of importation.  The large numbers of Orientals brought into Canada to work on the railroads required a steady flow of Oriental foodstuffs and other supplies.  One of the items desperately required there and among the Orientals in our country was opium.<br>
<br>
In the states, by the Tariff Act of 1897, there was a duty of six dollars per pound on smoking opium.  Crude opium was admitted at one dollar per pound; the sulphates and alkaloids, which included morphine, were dutiable at one dollar per ounce.  In 1909 the 61st Congress raised the duties about fifty per cent, but also, in response to an awakening public interest, passed an act prohibiting importation for other than medical purposes.<br>
<br>
There were large sections in some of our shipping centers occupied by Orientals and called "Chinatown".  On the Pacific Coast, Vancouver, B. C., Seattle and San Francisco had the largest numbers.  The demand for opium was very strong.  The Orientals risked their lives to get it.  The degenerate white, who was crafty enough to outwit or outrun the few Customs men at our borders, found a Bonanza in opium smuggling.<br>
<br>
The smuggling in of Chinese nationals themselves was another source of revenue.  Sumas was in a position destined to be the scene of much smuggling activity.  We, who lived in town, heard many rumors but the long thread of the stories, buried, as they needed to tell in official discretion, only came out when one of the actors in the drama was caught or met his end.<br>
<br>
Now, the message of time makes possible the recounting of some of these interesting events.
Laurence J. Flanigan, always known locally as "Larry", was our first U. S. Customs officer, serving from 1891 to 1897.  He must have been making it pretty hot for some of the early smugglers.<br>
<br>
One day he boarded the train at Sumas and after checking passengers and baggage thoroughly on the way to Wickersham, he ordered the conductor to hold the train a few minutes while he checked the undercarriages.  He had received confidential information that a shipment of opium was aboard.  When he saw a package tucked in over the trucks he grasped it eagerly and ran to the freight shed.<br>
<br>
"Well, I've got the dope!" he confided breathlessly to the station agent as he cut and tore the many wrappings to get into the box.  It didn't lift or shake like five tael tins, the usual container for smoking opium.  Maybe it was gum opium and then again, maybe it was morphine.  As the wrapping fell aside, Larry's hands shook with excitement.  At last he got down to the shoe box, opened the lid and found ' - a box of horse manure.<br>
<br>
Larry turned the tables just a few months later.  "Cowboy" jake Terry had come to Sumas to operate early in the nineties.  For about fifteen years he was to pester Customs men, during the times when he was out of jail.  He was quite a slicker and always believed he could outsmart any man he could not intimidate or buy off.  He was a great teller of stories and made himself right at home in any company.<br>
<br>
Terry had been using an old logging road, back on Barker Hill to get his stuff across the line.  Sometimes he used trails east of town or the Telegraph Road.  Once across, he carried opium in suitcases or a blanket roll or had a confederate do it for him.<br>
<br>
Then he could board the train as a passenger at Clearbrook or Nooksack and thus outwit the Customs men.  For a number of years Larry Flanigan held down the office alone.  An additional man was added later and an Immigration Inspector detailed to work under the local Deputy Collector of Customs.<br>
<br>
One night Jake had a load and hung around the Customs House talking to Larry to get the lay of the land.  He confided that, since the trails were dry, he wouldn't mind taking the back road route so as not to embarrass Flanigan.<br>
<br>
"I'll be coming through after midnight and nobody will know the difference, Larry.  You might as well get a good sleep.  You could sure use a little sleep better than a slug of lead in your guts, couldn't you?"<br>
<br>
"Ye-ah.  I could use a little sleep, but about that other, sometimes lead flies both ways."<br>
<br>
In the evening Larry sauntered around town, spent a little time in
a card game at the "U.S.", then went down to the Mount Baker bar.  There he saw Schumacher and accepted his invitation to have a glass of beer.  When the barkeep was out of listening range, Larry spoke quietly.<br>
<br>
"Schu, I've got a job to do tonight and I'm going to have help.  I've got a right under the law, to deputize any citizen when I have reason to believe that a felony is going to be committed and I need assistance.  I'm deputizing you as a Customs Officers for tonight and I want you to meet me about fifty rods south of the roundhouse at one o'clock and be double dam sure nobody sees you getting there.<br>
<br>
Make a wide circle, bring your six shooter.  I don't want to be seen talking to you any more tonight.  See you fifty rods south, be sure!"<br>
<br>
Larry went home, fussed around a bit, blew out the light and instead of going to bed, went out the back door, trailing his shotgun.  He hit for the ferns back of his place, crouched and waited to see if he could spot the skulking form of Jake Terry coming around for the check-up. Jake didn't show in the next half hour so Larry took off, walking west of town, crossing the bridge by the mill, then back on the creekside trail.<br>
<br>
One o'clock found him in position on the track and Schumacher came puffing up from the road to the east.<br>
<br>
The two men planned their work together.  Larry was sure that Jake took him for a sucker and believed that he would take a trail.  Instead, Larry figured that Jake was going to come down the railroad track with a handcar, catching the law off balance.<br>
<br>
The officers "borrowed" a speeder from the roundhouse and then went far down the track to the first gentle curve and when<br>
out of sight of the straightaway they blocked the speeder and went back a short distance toward town and waited.<br>
<br>
Occasionally Larry went up on the tracks, dropped to his knees and put his ear to the steel rail.  In an hour or so he heard the first faint rumble.  It grew louder and louder and in a few minutes they could hear it while standing up.  Then the sound revealed that it was a heavy laden handcar grinding away on the rails as it rolled south.<br>
<br>
When the travelers were near enough to see by the cloudy night that there was an obstruction across the track, there arose a lot of sharp cackling of Chinese voices and the voice of Jake Terry.  "Shut up, you yellow bellied fools!"<br>
<br>
just then two men rose from the grade at the side, ran alongside the handcar, with shotgun and pistol trained on Terry.
"Hands up, you all! Federal officers! Jake Terry, you're under arrest," yelled Flanigan.  "As soon as the car stops I want you to step out in front.  Keep your hands up!"<br>
<br>
Flanigan must have done a first class job, for Jake Terry, often called "Terrible Terry", who had the reputation as a cold killer, didn't even get his gun in hand.  He was manacled as soon as the car stopped rolling.  His load of four Chinese were docile coolies who accepted the will of the gods fatalistically.  They cheerfully pumped the handcar back to town, towing the speeder after them.<br>
<br>
Schumacher got the marshal out of bed and the five culprits were locked up in the city jail.  After due process, Terry the wise guy, went to San Quentin for another jail stretch.<br>
<br>
About three years previous to this incident, another Jake Terry episode had occurred.  It took place near the towns of Sedro and Woolley, the two places later becoming the present town of Sedro-Woolley.<br>
<br>
The Bellingham Bay Express, on July 28, 1891, printed the following interesting account of the battle in the woods.<br>
<br>
"One Man Killed, Another Wounded.<br>
Deputy Sheriff Poor, of Seattle, Is the Dead Man.<br>
Cowboy Terry Is Not Expected to Live."<br>
<br>
"Sunday night, about eleven o'clock, a tragedy occurred about one and a half miles from Woolley . . . Sunday morning Inspector Beard, of Seattle, telegraphed Collector Reilly (New Whatcom) that a party of Chinamen had been smuggled across the border near Sumas and asked that an inspector be sent on from here to meet him in Sedro and help with the case."<br>
<br>
"Inspector Buchanan was accordingly ordered to the scene of action and lie and Beard went to work to locate the contraband Mongolians.  During the afternoon they located the road that was to be used and, after dark, went out there and sat down in the bushes to wait for the smugglers."<br>
<br>
"About eleven they heard a band of men coming and, as they came opposite, Beard stepped out in the road and found in front of him a band of about fifteen Chinamen, accompanied by either two or three white men."<br>
<br>
"To the command of 'halt' the white man in the lead replied that he was a Deputy United States Marshal and was taking the Chinamen to Seattle as prisoners.  He also displayed his badge as proof."<br>
<br>
"Beard considered this a ruse and ordered the man to throw up his hands.  Which one reached for his gun first is a disputed question, but one thing is sure, they both got them out and both fired, Beard's shot striking the supposed smuggler in the body and killing
him instantly."<br>
<br>
"About this time the other white man had got his gun into action, and Buchanan had also appeared on the scene and opened fire.  A shot from the second smuggler's gun whistled through Beard's hair scraping his scalp in a manner that was impressive, but a moment later the smuggler fell with a bullet in the groin, and the battle was over."<br>
<br>
"In the meantime the Chinese had . . . scattered in all directions and not one has been seen since."<br>
<br>
"The dead <B> man </B>and his wounded companion were taken to Woolley.  There it was shown that the dead man was Poor, a (deputy sheriff <B>and deputy </B>U. S. Marshal of Seattle, while the wounded man proved  to be Terry, who has had charge of the Kellytown townsite near that place.<br>
<br>
He was found to be dangerously wounded and the doctor says it is impossible for him to live.  His ante-mortem deposition was taken.  In it he stated that, hearing of the smuggling of the Chinamen, he had telegraphed Sheriff Woolery of King County, that if he had assistance he thought he could capture them.  In reply to this Woolery had sent on Poor and another man named Holden.<br>
<br>
The three of them had captured the Chinamen and were taking them to Woolley where they were to be put in a box car and taken under guard to Seattle."<br>
<br>
"Next morning . . . Holden was also arrested.  The coroner's jury returned a verdict of manslaughter against Buchanan and Beard, who were at once taken into custody."<br>
<br>
"Holden claims he came on ahead to make arrangements with the railroad officials for a car . . ." (He had witnesses to say he was drinking beer in a saloon at the time of the shooting.)<br>
<br>
"Sheriff Woolery was telegraphed and he came to Woolley last evening and at once went to view the dead man, though how he has expressed himself is not yet known."<br>
<br>
"The men must have had iron nerves as the shooting was started at such close quarters that their guns were almost touching each other, and the shot which killed Poor went right through his body and was found in the back of his coat."<br>
<br>
"People who afterward visited the scene of the shooting say that the fusillade must have been terrible . . . Later developments go to show that the shooting was not much of a mistake, but will be the means of breaking up a big smuggling combine."<br>
<br>
"Sheriff Woolery says that Poor had asked leave of absence, but he did not know where he was going.  Holden, who is an Inspector of
Customs, left Seattle without authority and Terry, the third man of the party, bears a reputation that is not altogether as savory as it might be.  He has served several times in jail, has been separated from his wife, whom he treated so badly that news of his approaching death caused her to smile, and he has been <B>more </B>or less mixed up in rascality all his life."<br>
<br>
"There is an air of mystery surrounding the whole affair Inspector Beard is a Seattle man, but was formerly a policeman at Blaine (border town), where he had worked with Inspector Buchanan.  Both are known as reliable men and good officers.<br>
<br>
Poor, the man who was killed, was known in Seattle, where he lived, as a whole-souled genial, honest man.  He was an enthusiastic member of Seattle Chapter No. 3, Royal Arch Masons, and belonged to the First Baptist Church.  He has been a prominent figure in Seattle society.<br>
<br>
For a time he was steward of the Olympian and was afterwards appointed Customs Inspector, but did not retain his position long.  Last year he started in the jewelry business and remained at that till Sheriff Woolery was elected, when he was appointed deputy."<br>
<br>
The Express on 'July 30, 1891, carried more news under the headline, "Both Men Go Free".<br>
<br>
"Beard and Buchanan Are Discharged From Custody.  The Evidence Shows They Acted in Good Faith."<br>
<br>
"Inspector Holden's Resignation Demanded in 24 Hours."<br>
<br>
"Woolley has attracted More Attention in the Last Few Days than any place in tlie Sound Country . . ."<br>
<br>
"The preliminary examination of Beard and Buchanan took place yesterday.  Both gave their evidence frankly and in straightforward manner.  Both swore that Beard had called upon the Chinamen and their escort to surrender three times, and the answer they got was three shots in quick succession.  Then all blazed away.  Beard fired his last shot before Poor fell.  He then rushed up to him and in stooping over to feel his face, rubbed off his false whiskers."<br>
<br>
"Terry testified that he had no revolver, and that the Inspector fired first, but his character is such that his evidence carried no weight with the court.  When Holden saw Beard after the shooting he had on a different hat from the one he wore when he came to Woolley and Beard claims that if his first hat can be found, it will have some mark on it to show that he was in the fight.<br>
<br>
Deputy Collector Alexander testified that Holden  had not acted under instructions, and another witness swore that Terry was a smuggler."<br>

"This is the evidence and after the attorney's got in their work, Justice J.Y. Terry said it was apparent to him that the defendants<br>
had acted in good faith.  He dismissed both.  As the last words were spoken by the justice, a loud shout of applause went up from the crowded hall and Beard and Buchanan were congratulated by everyone who could get near them."<br>
<br>
"Terry is lying between life and death, with no very pleasant prospect before him.  He will either die or go to jail as a smuggler."<br>
<br>
Collector Bradshaw, head of the Customs district, with headquarters in Port Townsend, had demanded the resignation of Holden when he came to Woolley to investigate.  Later, from his Port Townsend office, he demanded the resignation of Beard, also, on the ground that Beard was spying on the activities of another officer without notifying the Collector of his activities.  Deputy Collector Reilly, however, who sent help to Beard, on request, was the direct representative of the Collector in the Whatcom area.<br>
<br>
On the same day that the above news was released, the Express announced the appointment of Thomas Hopp, publisher of the Sumas Index, as a Customs Inspector.<br>
<br>
In 1897, S. P. Conner succeeded Flanigan and had as assistant, Inspector Stenger, who had to spend part of his time in Whatcom.  During this time Jake Terry was planning his future in San Quentin prison but there were plenty of others on the scene.  "Cap" Conner had a flair for getting into local politics and drew bitter criticism and perhaps a bit of "framing" from his opposition.<br>
<br>
He aired his resentment and made counter charges in a series of pamphlets which he called "Kum-tux I, II and III." At any rate, as a federal officer in politics, he was vulnerable and was succeeded by Deputy Collector Lockbaum in 1905.  At that time there were three major smuggling rings, known to be operating at Sumas, Blaine, and the salt water routes of the sound, from Canada.<br>
<br>
There were two officers rating Deputy Collector at Sumas in 1903 the U. S. Immigration Service began to function as a separate organization and they occupied the new Immigration Station, built at the boundary line west of the N.P. Depot.  Sumas was the designated Chinese Port of Entry.  With a force of thirteen men, one a Chinese interpreter, the new federal men were integrated into the community.<br>
<br>
Shortly after the opening of the station a band of about forty Hindoos were being led across the line, at night, on a trail back on Barker Hill.  At the bottom of the trail, where it joined the settlers' road on the south side, the Immigration men were waiting.  George Manning, the Immigration Guard, had his hands full that night.  The barred windows of the station framed interesting faces,
mostly oriental, Chinese, Hindoos, occasional Japanese and Russian, and sometimes for temporary safe keeping, the smugglers caught by the Customs men.<br>
<br>
The newspapers of the area found some choice items in the happenings at Sumas.  One of the most bizarre incidents which drew keen public curiosity at the time was a murder mystery which occurred right under the noses of the Immigration Officers, and in fact, within the Immigration Detention Station.<br>
<br>
Included among the detainees at the station had been one Chinese dignitary, named Li Wing Wah.  Li had a beautiful wife who was detained with him.  They occupied a room together.  She well might have been a Chinese princess or a scion of one of the most honored families in China.  She had a graciousness that aroused interest among all who saw her.  Her education     had been broad and she spoke excellent English.  Her tiny feet, incased in jeweled slippers, and her exquisitely embroidered and fitted silk garments added to her charm.<br>
<br>
To pass away the time while awaiting entry requirements,<br>
she made excellent translations of various Chinese letters and labels for the immigration people.  But for all her education and elegant bearing the word got out that she was, in reality, <B>only </B>a slave girl, having been acquired by the elder Li for his comfort and companionship, or possibly to be turned over to another merchant prince once he entered the United States.<br>
<br>
Imagine, if you can, the consternation that filled the Immigration Station and which gave oriental mystery headlines to the papers, when on a morning early in 1908 the morning check of the detainees disclosed the beautiful girl lying lifeless on the floor of the cell, her throat opened by a terrible slashing with a razor.<br>
<br>
The people of the county waited with consuming curiosity, and a degree of horror, for the story detailing the motive, and any possible defense by Li Wing Wah.<br>
<br>
On June 3, 1908, Li was found guilty of murder and condemned to death but he uttered no words to defend himself or explain away the mystery.  He "saved face" as much as he could by refusing to release whatever tale of anguish he might have had in his breast.  The story hung suspended, a thing of endless wondering, but the public learned no more.<br>
<br>
On one fine summer day Mrs. George Handley and daughter, Myrtle, hurried to get their housework done and then set off to go blackberry picking with Mrs. Albert Stell and Walter.  The little wild blackberries were prized highly and the picking provided enjoyable outings in mid summer.  On this occasion they walked out the road, east of Sumas River, to the vicinity of McClure's place, near the boundary line.
As they trudged along happily they were alarmed at seeing a group of men get up hastily from the fern beds along the bank of the stream.  Their fears mounted when they saw the pigtail queues of Orientals.  Some of the men ran for cover in the bush  others stood cynically.  There appeared to be about a dozen.  The berry pickers turned and ran back down the road for home.  Berry picking would have to await another day.<br>
<br>
Fred F. Strickling was an accountant who had lived in South Dakota.  He came to Seattle and took the Civil Service examination for the position of U. S. Customs Appraiser.  He had no thought of, or ambition to become an enforcement officer.  He made an enviable grade in the test, but instead of getting the appointment in Seattle, he was asked to go to Sumas for a "temporary assignment".<br>
<br>
There he found himself on a job where he was expected to put in a day of routine work and to spend many nights hiding on trails, looking for dangerous outlaws.  For a man of purely academic interests his role here was far from his choice.  When Deputy Collector Samuel P. Conner handed him a service pistol he considered turning back his badge.  Then he decided he would give it a try but he would leave his firearms at home.<br>
<br>
This worked all right, for a smuggler would not suspect that the officer had no firearm.  With no flash of weapon there was no provocation.  But he had some narrow squeezes.  Take the time Fred and Harry Blee were waiting on a dark night at the bridge at Clear brook.  The smuggler appeared in the early morning hours carrying a heavy suitcase.  As he walked across the bridge the officers stepped out.  Strickling said, "Stop, you are under arrest!"<br>
<br>
The fellow stepped back and coolly surveyed the situation.  "Under what authority?" he said cautiously while stalling.<br>
<br>
Strickling showed his badge, "U.  S. Customs," he said.  "We'll go over there on the porch of that store where there's a light and we'll open the suitcase for inspection."<br>
<br>
As they walked over, the smuggler became cooperative, anxious to talk and to open his baggage.  Before he got the straps off, Fred was convinced there was something wrong.  "No, fellow," he said,<br>
<br>
"I'll open that myself.  You stand over there by that officer."<br>
As the lid came open the first thing apparent was a loaded automatic pistol.  Under it he had forty-five pounds of opium.  Back at the detention station the prisoner became bitter.  He told Fred, "If I could have gotten that pistol, there would have been two funerals instead of me going to McNeil."<br>
<br>
On one quiet day Fred went out to check on a smuggler's trail a couple of miles east of town.  It led across a marshy place near the
border, where there was a footlog.  Fred walked the log and as he reached the far side he steadied himself by placing his hand on a tree trunk. just then there was a sharp thud by his fingers and lie heard the bark of a rifle behind him.  A high powered bullet had passed through the tree by the tips of his spread fingers.<br>
<br>
One aspect of the border which added to the enforcement difficulty was the way the boldest smugglers worked on the train men.  Some were bribed to keep quiet, others were fearful.  One railway mail clerk, a postal employs, was discovered to be actually abetting the activities of a notorious smuggler.<br>
<br>
While Conner was still in charge, in February of 1905, he had his men, Lockbaum and Strickling, with the support of Immigration Inspectors Pink and George Manning out, making a maximum effort to catch the persistent smuggler, Larry Kelley.<br>
<br>
Kelley shifted his operations along the border and, when running Chinese, used a power boat.  He was reputed to be one of the first runners who used the swift and boiling waters of Deception Pass.  He boasted that he had a system for getting rid of his human cargo in case he was overtaken by a Coast Guard cutter.  Some said that he carried them in weighted sacks, sewed up at the neck, ready to be rolled over the side.<br>
<br>
Kelley had been caught in 1887 while smuggling four thousand dollars worth of opium and at that time served two years in the penitentiary.<br>
<br>
Again in March of 1891 he had been captured on a train between Tacoma and Portland, by Treasury Agent C. J. Mulkey and Inspector C. B. Cox.  He had in his possession 65 five-tael tins of the finest Tai Yune opium.  The opium had been processed and packed by the manufacturer at Victoria, B. C., and was sold at Victoria for $8.00 per pound.<br>
<br>
He had used his four-ton sloop to transport the contraband to a point near Olympia, then he hiked overland and boarded the train at Tenino, but little did he expect to find that treasury men were already aboard.<br>
<br>
A short time previously he had been fined $200 by the Canadians for not properly clearing his vessel.  When the Canadians pointed out that the American officers were likely to catch him he ha(l made a remark which was the cause of many a wry smile along the border.<br>
<br>
"No - - - - - of a Customs House Officer will ever take me."<br>
<br>
On this dark February night the federal men were spotted at various points.  Strickling rode the engine from Sumas and kept out of sight at Nooksack.  However, from his spot of concealment, he was sure he saw an active man with heavy suitcases going toward the train when
it came to a stop.<br>
<br>
When they pulled out of the station Fred asked the engineer if any passengers came aboard.  "Oh, I think there was some old man, farm hand, no doubt." At Deming when the train started up again, Fred boarded the first coach and soon spotted the conductor.  "Yes, I think there was one at Nooksack.  Some old fellow.  I haven't been back there yet.  He's in one of the rear coaches."<br>
<br>
Strickling started to walk through as the train pulled out of the station.  He took it slowly as the train gained headway, then continued more briskly, checking every face and hiding place.  When he came to the last car he spotted Kelley and walked quickly to his seat.<br>
<br>
"Open up your baggage for inspection, Mr. Kelley," said Fred, showing his badge.  Kelly got up and tried to walk out in the aisle.  "I don't know as I have to," he said.<br>
<br>
"If you don't open it, I'll examine it, as unclaimed, and if you're wrong I'll hold it and you, too," said Fred.  He turned to get a good look at the two heavy suitcases, heard a shuffle behind him, then ran to catch the fleeing Kelley but failed to grasp him until he reached the platform and jumped.<br>
<br>
Strickling pulled the emergency cord and the train slowed down.  The conductor came puffing into the coach.  Fred had checked the suitcases and found them loaded with opium, one hundred twenty tins, his count later showed.  He ordered the conductor to stop the train and to back up to the point where the passenger jumped.<br>
<br>
As the train reached the spot the officer saw his man lying prone in the cinders.  He jumped off and finding that Kelley was unconscious, took the occasion to shackle his arms behind him and to remove from his pocket a .41 caliber Colt pistol.  He had no sooner done this than Kelley revived and looked around.<br>
<br>
Kelley was a sight.  He had hit on his feet, off balance, then bounced on his head so violently that his head and one shoulder plowed into the cinders.  The black, *egged bits of cinder had<br>
torn his face and shoulders and were imbedded in the flesh and under the skin.<br>
<br>
They got him back aboard the train.  Strickling deputized Harry Vanderhoof, the mill man, to assist him with the prisoner.  He ordered the conductor to back up to Deming.  The station agent phoned a local doctor who got out of bed and came down to pick out as much of the cinders as he could see and feel on the gory man, beneath the torn flesh.  He packed the head to stop the bleeding.<br>
<br>
The men took the next train back to Sumas, plus one notorious prisoner and one hundred twenty tins of refined opium.  Arrived at the home station, they locked Kelley up in the Immigration strong
room, by permission of Edsell, the Immigration Inspector in charge.  Then Strickling called Doctor Clark.  Clark dug more gravel and cinders out and Kelley pleaded for whiskey.<br>
<br>
Clark warned him that whiskey could easily kill him since he might have concussion.  If he drank whiskey it would be his own election and not prescribed.  Kelley wanted whiskey and he wanted something to eat.  Strickling looked piteously at the wretched creature and Kelley felt he had a friend.<br>
<br>
"Ye-ah, go ahead, officer.  Get me a bottle of whiskey and something to eat."<br>
<br>
Strickling knew there would be no question of recompense, for Kelley had in a wallet on his person at the time of search eight hundred fifty dollars in gold.<br>
<br>
Fred went across the line to the Huntingdon Hotel and then to the U. S. Saloon and soon came back with a roast duck and a bottle of whiskey.<br>
<br>
Lockbaum and Strickling called next day to take their prisoner down to Bellingham for arraignment before U. S. Commissioner H. B. Williams.  As George Manning, the Immigration Guard, opened the door, Lockbaum said, "How have they been treating you since you have been in custody, Kelley?"<br>
<br>
"Never was treated better in my life," he said.<br>
<br>
Occasional incidents broke the routine around the station.  Railroad men rarely gave any information but one day as Strickling walked through a baggage car the conductor came in, hesitated a moment at the side of the officer and murmured, "take a good look at that dog."<br>
<br>
A lady passenger had crossed the border on other occasions.  This time she brought with her a large shaggy haired dog.  He was tethered in the baggage car and he was scratching continually.  Fred took the leash and led him into the customs office where he and Lockbaum began the examination.<br>
<br>
The itching proved to come from some razor slits in the skin of the back of the dog.  Tucked beneath the skin was a shipment of large diamonds.<br>
<br>
On another occasion the conductor stopped in the coach aisle and curiously watched Fred taking out some screws from the side casing of a window.  "Well, officer, have you quit your usual job and are you now starting to work as a car repairman?"<br>
<br>
"Just wait a minute, conductor." When the casing came off there was revealed, in the double wall, forty neatly stacked tins of opium.<br>
Strickling the accountant, who had no yen for enforcement work, was a handy man to have around.  Being on temporary assignment, he could
<br>
be spared to go checking on rumors or he could be sent to a spot to stake out with instructions to come back when he had the answers.<br>
<br>
"Fred, I've got news for you," Lockbaum said one day.  "You know the reports we had about the trail crossing the border somewhere north and east of Mount Baker.  Well, now I've got a letter from the Collector,-says to send Strickling out, have him make a report on what's going on there.  You are to bring back prisoners if its a job one man can handle and if you catch them smuggling.  Otherwise, the Collector would like to know who is using the trail.  He says to send you during a quiet period at Sumas.  Well, this is as quiet as any, right now, anyway, so you might as well get camping gear together and prepare to stay a week, if necessary."<br>
<br>
Fred got his outfit together, hired a horse and set out early next morning.  Confidential reports indicated the trail was regularly used, crossed tlie boundary, running diagonally to the southeast from the origin southeast of Cultus Lake.<br>
<br>
Not too many trails led off the Mount Baker county road and Fred had a few landmarks to go by.  There was Church Mountain, which stuck up like a sore thumb, and there was Tommyhoy.  Having started early, noon found him on the trail.  As lie neared the boundary he tethered his horse and walked on along the side of the trail so as to conceal his footprints.<br>
<br>
The trail led on for several miles, with no indication as to its utility.  An occasional pony track revealed that it was used by pack horses, that was all.  In a spruce and hemlock shaded ravine he passed along a tumbling little stream.  Suddenly there was a different smell in the woods and he peered cautiously ahead with every step.<br>
<br>
Then he saw the roof of a cabin.  No doubt there would be a dog to sound warning.  Fred tested the wind direction and listened for any sound.  He saw no smoke.  By inching along he felt he would soon have the answer and he could still withdraw.<br>
<br>
Next to appear was a contraption in the creek and a long bed of freshly worked gravel. it was evidently a gold rocker, but what could it be doing on a smuggler's trail? Fred stood for many long minutes, waiting for a sound.  There was no dog, no horse, so not likely any sleeping men.  He went forward with great caution, finally stood inside the cabin.  There was no smell of moonshine mash, no evidence of imported goods.  It looked more like a blacksmith shop than anything else.  There was a small furnace which looked like it was used for reducing ore.<br>
<br>
Strickling looked on in amazement.  He looked back at the prospector's cradle in the creek.  If this was a gold mine, why the secrecy@ All was quiet in the timber.  The operators were apparently-on a trip to town.  He was in luck.
He went further inside and on a bench, near the furnace, he saw some kind of a mold.  It appeared to be a mint.  By looking closely he saw the clear imprint of a U. S. twenty dollar coin and a similar ten dollar.  He gather up some clay, made a clay model, found a tobacco tin, placed his model inside, packed it gently with moss and set off back up the trail.<br>
<br>
Strickling's foray in the hills resulted in a hurried conference of American and Canadian officials.  The Canadians raided the place and arrested two operators.  An investigation followed.  The facts uncovered were that they had been successfully counterfeiting American money and placing it in circulation in Vancouver, B. C., where the spurious character was not recognized.<br>
<br>
There it found its way to the banks, which in turn, exchanged the coins with American banks.  In the states some of the coins had been detected.  The only way they were found was by weight, the counterfeited coins being heavier.  On test it was found that the spurious coins contained more gold than the American minted currency, since there was lacking the usual quantity of alloy.<br>
<br>
After weeks of study as to whether the men were punishable under Canadian law, the case was lost track of by the Sumas officers.  There was more pressing business for them.  The cat came back.<br>
Deputy Collector Lockbaum reported to Collector Clarence W.  Ide at his headquarters in Port Townsend in October of 1905: "Sir: One "Cowboy" Terry has been making his headquarters here for a number of months past and I am convinced . . ."<br>
<br>
Again in the spring of 1906, he wrote: "Sir: I learn from good authority that 'Jake (Cowboy) Terry is again on the coast, having arrived at New Westminster junction yesterday."<br>
<br>
In the Bellingham Reveille of July 17, 1906, under the heading: "Taken With the Dope on Him", was the following story:<br>
<br>
"A tall, dignified appearing and well dressed man, with iron gray hair, a black beard and shifty gray eyes, who gives his name as Thomas Morton.... was arrested at Mount Vernon by Customs Inspector George Hubbard, after a search of his baggage revealed eighty pounds of opium, valued at $1000.00. . . . Jake Terry, as in all smuggling cases, is reported to be one of the agents on the Canadian side."<br>
<br>
In the summer and fall of 1906 Jake Terry found a special personal interest in Sumas.  There was a fight about a woman.  A lot of public indignation arose when he threw Gus Linday out of his own house.  Finally he was arrested by the sheriff, but he was out on bail promptly and then made his headquarters in the Huntingdon Hotel, just across the boundary line.<br>
<br>
After he forfeited his bail there was a warrant out for his arrest but he was safe in Canada and he could come over to fight Gus Linday or shoot up the town, then go back across and laugh at the uproar.<br>
Frank Myers, the town marshal, was really on the spot.  He probably
<br>
could have caught Jake if he had tried hard enough.  The town was divided on whether or not Myers should take a hand.<br>
<br>
Terry was a smuggler and it was really up to the Customs Officers to catch him again.  Besides, as Frank's friends pointed out, Frank's house was on Harrison and very close to the boundary line.  He had a good wife and four or five children.  If Jake Terry found that Myers was going to try to arrest him, the house would surely go up in smoke some windy night, while Terry was prowling around.<br>
<br>
It wasn't a simple thing to take Jake.  He seemed to get wind of any plans to cause his downfall.  Besides the chances were pretty high that somebody would be killed.  Frank Myers received a salary of fifty-five dollars per month and the government was offering no reward for the apprehension of this federal law violator.<br>
<br>
Father shook his head, sadly,  "I  don't  know,  I  don't  know."<br>
<br>
Roy Franklin Jones, "Early Smugglers," <B>Boundary Town, early days in a northwest boundary town.</B> Vancouver, Washington: Fleet Printing Company, 1958. p. 234-253.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
SMUGGLING.<br>
<br>
"Smuggled celestials, a big bogus certificate scheme unearthed," <B>The Tacoma Daily Ledger.</B> May 6, 1891.<br>
<br>
Bradshaw's Deputy Suspected of Complicity and Suspended Pending Investigation - A Port Townsend Lawyer in the Toils - Chinese as Witnesses.<br>
<br>
The "big ring," whose operations in smuggling both Chinamen and opium into this country have long puzzled the customs officials, and whose "bosses" are supposed to be prominent citizens of this state, is on the verge of being entirely exposed to judge from present appearances.<br>
<br>
It is well known that of late the ring has transferrd its principal attention to the smuggling of Chinese across the border, but in what manner was unknown.  Treasury Agent Mulkey assisted by Inspector Coblentz, has been at work on the matter, for some months and have, they think, located the missing link of testimony.<br>
<br>
It appears that certain parties in Port Townsend have been engaged in the wholesale trade of preparing bogus certificates for Chinamen to return on and and sending them across to British Columbia to the purchasers.  With the "rings" usual foresight, it secured some catspaws in the customs service.<br>

Charles B. Wood, Collector Bradshaw's chief deputy, is strongly suspected to winking at the passage of Chinamen on bogus certificates.  A private dispatch from Port Townsend last night announced that he had been suspended pending a full investigation of the fraud.<br>
<br>
John Trumbull, a lawyer in Port Townsend, is accused of being the chief manufacturer of the certificates, and the same dispatch announces that he has been arrested.  The matter was brought to a focus Monday by Messrs. Mulkey and Coblenz arresting Yee Long and Wong-Uny-Sung on the City of Seattle when she landed here.<br>
<br>
The "Ledger" became aware of the fact, but agreed not to mention the case Tuesday, as the officials said the ends of justice would be served by saying nothing for a day or two.  Both of the Chinamen had certificates suspected of being false, but it now looks as if Yee Long is all right.<br>
<br>
The two Chinamen were detained in a room in the Brooklyn house Monday and Tuesday awaiting orders from Mulkey, who with Coblentz went to Port Townsend immediately after the arrest.  Chief of Police Ellis, acting under a mistaken impression, attempted to put the Chinamen in the city jail, but as they are for the present United States prisoners, Inspector Kane in whose charge they are, would not allow him to do so.<br>
<br>
Lee Bing, a highly educated Chinese merchant from Portland, came over yesterday from that city to assist in securing the release of Yee Long, whose certificate he signed in Portland.  It is probable, however, the two Chinamen will be held as witnesses until to-day anyhow and perhaps later.  Messrs. Mulkey and Coblentz will arrive this morning and will dispose of the prisoners as they think best.<br>
<br>
The certificates prepred by Trumbull were offered for sale in Victoria for $30 to $90 each.  Trumbull was taken before United States Commissioner Swan at Port Townsend, yesterday morning, and examination was postponed until Monday next.  Trumbull was released on $200 bail.  Ah Tom, who was arrested for smuggling opium, is said to be an accessory to the smuggling of Chinese.<br>
<br>
"Smuggled celestials, a big bogus certificate scheme unearthed," <B>The Tacoma Daily Ledger.</B> May 6, 1891.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
SMUGGLING.<br>
<br>
Robert C. Nesbit, "Smuggling in Puget Sound," <B>He Built Seattle, a biography of Judge Thomas Burke.</B> Seattle: University of Washington, 1961, p. 168-69.<br>
<br>
The captain of the United States Revenue Marine Cutter, in his report to the governor in 1884, called attention to the difficulty
of enforcing the Chinese Restriction Acts:<br>
<br>
"On the matter of the needs of the Customs Service of the Territory I can only say that the force employed to carry on the work of 'Protecting the Revenue' in this Collection District is ridiculously small, in no place, are such facilities offered for violation of Law as on this frontier, and in no place is such a large extent of Territory guarded or supposed to be guarded by so few men.<br>
<br>
There have been in this District so many avenues open for the smuggler, that it was impossible to guard them all, and since the enforcement of the Chinese Restriction Act, is entrusted to the Customs Official, the smuggler has but little difficulty in pursuing his nefarious calling.<br>
<br>
Complaints are frequently made that the Restriction Act is not enforced by the Customs official, that Chinamen are crowding into the Territory, without hindrance etc-I ask your attention to some of the obstacles encountered by the Revenue officer, in this matter<br>
<br>
"First, there is nothing to deter the Chinaman, from making the attempt.  No penalty attaches to him, he even is not required to bear his own expense in returning to the port from whence he came, consequently he keeps trying until he succeeds.  Some of them have been detected, and sent back so often, that their faces are quite familiar to the Customs authorities.<br>
<br>
The facility with which white men escape the penalty for aiding the Chinese, encourages dozens of worthless characters to engage in the business.  If caught, unless actually engaged in stepping from the boat to the shore, which occupies but a moment of time, they are acquitted.  There are thousands of Chinamen just without the border, waiting for an opportunity to get in.<br>
<br>
Plenty of worthless characters are ready to assist them, and all passenger steamers ready to carry them, provided it can be done without risk.  The facilities offered for smuggling Chinamen as well as dutiable goods by way of the San Juan Archipelago, are well known.<br>
<br>
These islands are inhabited by farmers and sheep raisers and while a large majority are honest, industrious men, there is no lack of confederates to assist the smugglers in concealment until a favorable opportunity to complete his voyage.  Indeed some of them openly declare themselves smugglers, and defy the law.<br>
<br>
"The proper enforcement of the Chinese Restriction Act would alone require more men, than now constitute the entire force of the Customs Service in this district, yet with all this additional duty, and the increasing commerce of the District the Customs force, with possibly one or two additional men remains the same as before the Act went into affect.<br>
<br>
The Collector of the District has been greatly embarrassed in his
efforts to get additional help by the Treasury Agents who have visited the District from time to time.  Knowing that 'Economy' is an ever popular cry they affect to disbelieve the accounts of smuggling, and oppose any increase in the Service.<br>
<br>
The fact is well established that Chinamen, and large quantities of opium are being brought into the Territory in violation of Law and that it will continue until a large increase in the Customs force in the District." Captain C. L. Hooper to Gov.  Squire, October 15, 1884, Governors' Papers, Washington State Archives, Olympia.<br>
<br>
Robert C. Nesbit, "Smuggling in Puget Sound," <B>He Built Seattle, a biography of Judge Thomas Burke.</B> Seattle: University of Washington, 1961, p. 168-69.<br>
<br>
