<h1>Stagecoach Robberies</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
STAGE ROBBERS<br>
<br>
Arthur Amos Gray "Stage coach robbers and other citizens," <B>Men Who Built the West.</B> Caldwell,Idaho: Caxton Printers, Ltd, 1947, p. 195-201.<br>
<br>
With cattle rustling and horse stealing went the robbing of stages.  After the discovery of gold the miners usually sent their gold in stages to the nearest town where there was a bank or a large iron safe, kept in buildings having doors and windows that were covered with heavy iron shutters at night.<br>
<br>
At the mines gold was put into a strong box, bound with heavy iron bands and made secure by a big lock.  This box was carried under the driver's seat, or inside the stage under the back seat.  The box was often chained securely to the stage.  If the stage carried a large amount of gold, guards, who were heavily armed, went along.  One sat with the driver, and one rode inside with the passengers.<br>
<br>
Two kinds  of  stages  ran  in  the  West.  One  carried  chiefly<br>
passengers. It did not always have a strong box. The other was the fast express, and in it were usually carried large amounts of gold.  These stages ran on schedule, and the robbers usually knew just about where they were on the road.<br>
<br>
To stop the stages the robbers selected a narrow place in the road, or a place where there was a sharp turn.  At such places the drivers had to slow down, and the robbers then easily stopped the horses.  Also, where trees and bushes grew along the sides of the road, or where the stage passed by large high rocks, the robbers hid and quickly drew their guns before they could be seen.  Stage robberies nearly always occurred in some isolated place, far from town.<br>
<br>
One of the most noted stage robbers was Charles E. Boles.  He was known as "Black Bart," because he always signed his name that way when he left a note saying anything about a robbery that he had committed.  Alone he robbed twenty eight stages in six years, and he never carried a loaded pistol.  He was finally caught and sent to the penitentiary.  Upon his release from prison, it is said, he was employed at a good salary by the company whose stages he had held up for so many years, on condition that he would not rob any more stages.  Having a good job, "Black Bart" had no further desire to rob stages.<br>
<br>
One man rarely tried to rob a stage alone.  There were generally three and sometimes five or seven men in the group.  As the horses slowed down at a sharp turn or where the road was rough, usually two men, one on each side of the road, jumped out quickly in front
of the horses to stop them.  At the same time another man drew his pistol on the driver, while another "covered" the passengers.<br>
<br>
The driver was forced first to climb down from his seat.  He was then disarmed and made to stand with his face close to the side of the stage, with both hands held upright.<br>
<br>
Next came the passengers.  As they climbed out of the stage, they were lined up by the side of the road and compelled, at the point of a gun, to hold their hands high in the air.  Sometimes they were required to hold the long whip of the driver above their heads; and no one was allowed to drop his hands.<br>
<br>
As these people stood helpless in the road, one of the robbers passed along the line and turned every pocket inside out, letting everything drop to the ground.  While this was going on, another searched the inside of the stage for hidden money and for jewelry.<br>
<br>
And if a strong box were found, it was dumped out in the road.  Sometimes each person was forced to take off his shoes.  In these paper money was often hidden.  The linings of the garments were also frequently examined.<br>
<br>
When all the pockets had been emptied on the ground, the people were put back into the coach, and the driver mounted his seat.  He was then required to drive on slowly.  This was done to give the robbers plenty of time to get away.<br>
<br>
Quickly the robbers gathered up everything in sacks.  They broke open the strong box, if the stage carried one, jumped upon their horses, and rode away.  All this took place in a few minutes, unless the strong box was hard to break open.<br>
<br>
Each robber had a good horse.  It was sometimes several hours, or even a day, before the officers of the law heard of the robbery; and by that time the robbers were usually many miles away.  Then there were no telephones, and the sheriff did not know of the affair until the stage arrived.  It was often too late then to catch the robbers.<br>
<br>
Stage robberies occurred almost daily.  The owners of the stages did not know what to do.  It was believed that some of the drivers were members of the criminal gangs.  One man in Idaho was so sure this was true that he decided to drive his stage himself in order to see if he would be stopped.  He put a good six-shooter in each hip pocket, and placed a shotgun between his knees.
While crossing the mountains, some men jumped into the road and yelled, "Throw up your hands!" Instantly he dropped his lines, and just as he snatched up his shotgun, the robbers opened fire.  He never had a chance to shoot.  The robbers used a shotgun with heavy buckshot, and the driver's hands were shot almost completely from his wrists.  The mangled hands had to be cut off, and he was never able to work again.<br>
<br>
At another time  the  owner  of  several  stages,  Ben  Holla-<br>
day was robbed of everything he had, and the strong Express, was<br>
box was carried away.  A small safe, which contained  valuables and jewelry, was also taken.  In the belt which Holladay wore the robbers found several thousand dollars worth of gold dust; he also had some paper money, which he carried in his pockets.  No one was killed in this robbery.<br>
<br>
it was frequently reported that Indians held up stages.  They did sometimes.  But investigation often showed that the robbers were white men, dressed and painted as Indians.  They imitated the war whoop of the red men and used arrows to deceive the driver and passengers.  These men usually help up the express stages that carried few or no passengers.<br>
<br>
Many stage robberies took place when gold dust was being carried from Montana and Idaho.  One fatal robbery occurred near Pocatello, Idaho.  In the stage were seven passengers and they had about $50,000 in gold dust, which they had worked hard to get.  In a strong box was an equal amount of gold being transported by the company for other miners.<br>
<br>
As the stage passed through some thick brush, five men jumped out on each side of the road and began firing at the driver and the passengers.  All but two of them were instantly killed.  The robbers carried the strong box into the brush and broke it open.  The driver was then ordered to go on.<br>
<br>
One of the passengers, to escape, acted like the opossum.  He pretended to be dead, and while the robbers were opening the strong box, he rolled over the bank along a river and hid himself in the brush.<br>
<br>
The stage company hunted for these robbers for a long time.  All @ of them were finally caught.  The last man was located in Mexico City, and while he was running away from the officers, he was shot and killed.<br>
<br>
Near the place of this robbery another occurred not long afterward.  The stage carried $60,000 in gold.  Three passengers
were killed.  The robbers escaped with the gold and much jewelry taken from the passengers.  This gang was <B>headed by the </B>notorious Jim Locket. None of the robbers was ever captured, but it was proved that the driver of the stage had told the gang of the trip, because he was one of them.  However, he was caught, tried, and hanged some time after the affair.<br>
<br>
Year after year the robbers in the West became more numerous and more dangerous.  They drifted from one mining community to another, always going where things were new and where few or no officers of the law lived.<br>
<br>
As soon as the state governments were established, courts were set up and sheriffs were elected.  But even after this for many years the disregard for the law was very common in many places, and murder continued.  One county had forty-four murders in a little more than a year, and only one person was tried; and in one state more than five hundred persons were killed by outlaws in less than a year.<br>
<br>
At times the people became aroused and organized committees that helped to catch the most dangerous characters.  The capture of one man often led to the arrest of others.  This happened with an outlaw named George Ives.  He was captured on the plains, and a hundred people attended the trial.  A jury of twenty-four men was chosen to try Ives.<br>
<br>
He was found guilty, and the crowd was divided as to whether he should be hanged or sent out of the country.  Those wishing him to hang were in the majority, and so in a few minutes he was swinging in the air dead.  Before he was hanged, Ives confessed to other crimes and gave the names of several men who belonged to his gang.<br>
Among the names was that of Henry Plummer, who was then a sheriff in a county in Montana.  People said the accusation could not be true; but upon investigation Plummer was found to be the chief leader of a large criminal gang.<br>
<br>
This discovery greatly aroused all good citizens in Montana.  They organized committees and scoured the country to find these desperate bandits.  More than a thousand men assisted the officers of the law in hunting for them.<br>
<br>
Plummer was caught.  He had formerly been in the mines in California, and had lived in Montana only a short time.  He was found guilty and hanged.  In his pocket was found a list of names of eighty-five men who belonged to his gang. <B>Within three</B> months, from December, 1863, to March, 1864, some twenty cut-throats in the mining sections of Montana were hanged.
One of the men executed was Joseph Slade.  He had been a superintendent of the Pony Express Company at Julesburg, Colorado, a few years before.  He was a notorious character.  When only thirteen years old, he had killed a man in Illinois by throwing a stone at him, because the man was trying to stop a fight between two boys.  After this Joseph's father took him to Texas, where he became a cowboy and, later, a soldier in the Mexican War.<br>
<br>
During the time that he acted as superintendent for the Pony Express at Julesburg, Slade had many quarrels with the employees.  One of these was Jules Reni, commonly known as "Old Jules," after whom this town was 'named.  Jules shot Slade with a shotgun and then ran away into the mountains.  Slade went to the hospital in St. Louis to get the shot removed from his body, and, when he returned, he hunted everywhere for Jules, intent on killing him at first sight.<br>
<br>
One day they met, and Slade shot Old Jules, crippling him badly.  Then Slade tied him to a post and shot him to death.  Not satisfied, he cut off his ears, it was said, and kept them as souvenirs.<br>
<br>
Slade was a most dangerous man, especially when under the influence of liquor.  After he was discharged from the Pony Express Company for cheating the riders out of their pay and for other crimes, he went to Fort Bridger, Wyoming, and in 1863, to Montana.  He found work in Virginia City.<br>
<br>
Slade was a fine horseman.  He had a habit of galloping into a town, yelling at the top of his voice, and shooting into the air.  Riding his horse into a store or saloon, he threw articles on the floor, destroyed merchandise, and threatened to kill the owner.<br>
<br>
His chief sport was shooting bottles of liquor from the shelves in the saloon, or shooting out the lights in stores and along the streets.  It was said that at one time he tried to make his horse drink a bottle of wine.<br>
<br>
After one of Slade's shooting sprees, a sheriff went to arrest him.  He tore up the warrant which the sheriff gave him, and then said that he would shoot the sheriff and the judge if they tried again to arrest him.<br>
<br>
The people of Virginia City had heard what a bad man Slade was, and everybody was afraid of him.  It was reported that he had killed twenty-six men before he arrived in Montana.  The insults that Slade heaped upon everyone, and his robbing and shooting aroused all good citizens.  They organized six hundred men, and,
with the aid of the sheriff, arrested Slade.<br>
<br>
When Slade was arrested, he asked to see his wife, who was many miles away.  Learning of his arrest, she made a long, hard ride on horseback in an effort to save him, only to arrive too late.  While she was racing to Virginia City at lightning speed, Slade was hanged.<br>
<br>
Slade was like many another bad man of the Far West.  He was tall, strong, fearless, and an expert on a horse.  He was one of the most dreaded men in all the West during his time; he was a perfect shot.  But when sober he was courteous and agreeable; he dressed well and was polite in the presence of others, unless he was out to rob and kill.<br>
<br>
Throughout the entire West at different periods desperadoes committed many crimes.  Settlements were far apart, and the officers of the law had great difficulty in catching these bad men.  But when they did, little sympathy was shown, and many were hanged without a trial.  In Wyoming the following words were found pinned to the body of an outlaw who had been hanged:<br>
<br>
Process of law is a little slow,<br>
So this is the road you'll have to go<br>
Murderers and thieves, BEWARE!<br>
<br>
Such affairs as these show you that the Far West once was a country full of excitement and adventure.  But we must remember also that the majority of the people were civil, industrious citizens.  At the same time that these crimes were common, schools and colleges were started, and every small community had one or more churches.<br>
<br>
The teachers and the preachers were just as devoted and as faithful to their work as teachers and preachers anywhere else in the<br>
world.<br>
<br>
The ministers went into the wild cowboy towns and into the wicked mining camps and never flinched where there was danger.  They often preached while standing on barrels or boxes that were placed in the streets.<br>
<br>
They rode horseback miles and miles through the storm and zero weather in the mountains and on the plains.  When the snow was too deep for the horses to go through, these good men went on snowshoes to preach to the people and to bury the dead.  Their pay, as well as that of the teachers, was always a mere pittance.<br>
<br>
Arthur Amos Gray, "Stage coach robbers and other citizens," <B>Men
who built the west.</B> Caldwell, Idaho: Caxton Printers, Ltd, 1947, p. 195-201.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
