<img src="../unset.gif" align=middle>Tacoma Public Library - NorthWest Reference Databases
 - <B>Unsettling Events</B><br>
<h1>Aerospace workers Strike of 1948</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
THE BOEING 1948 STRIKE.<br>
<br>
John McCann, "The 1948 Boeing Strike," <B>Blood in the water, a history of District Lodge 751 of the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers.</B> Seattle: District Lodge 751, 1989. p. 105-108, 114-130.<br>
<br>
Informal talks between Union and the Boeing Airplane company began on January 29, 1947.  Formal negotiations started on March 16.11 In April of 1947, the Union accused the company of not negotiating in good faith, and filed a notice of intention to strike as required by the War Labor Disputes Act (Smith-Connally Act).<br>
<br>
The Act required a thirty day cooling off- period prior to a strike vote.  The Union offered to submit unresolved articles of the contract to impartial arbitration. The company demanded veto power over the choice of arbiters, and demanded that the entire contract be submitted to arbitration.  The Union refused.<br>
<br>
Both Union and company met with the United States Conciliation Servicel3, but talks stalemated on seniority, wages and hours.  On May 10, 1947, 751 called a general membership meeting, which authorized continued negotiation for two weeks, and called for a strike vote after the two-week period.  The membership met again on May 24, rejected the company's final offer and authorized a strike. 751 leadership informed the company and asked the IAM for strike sanction.<br>
<br>
Further negotiations took place between Union and company with the help of the Conciliation Service.  Harvey Brown, IAM President, came to Seattle in late June.  According to Hansen, Boeing President AHen "informed Brown that the basic trouble existing between the parties arose out of the fact that the (75 1) union officers were not 'labor statesmen.'<br>
<br>
His support for this statement was that 'the officers had made an attempt to sell the company's proposal to the membership.'<br>
<br>

The IAM refused to grant strike sanction to 751 on the grounds that:<br>
<br>
1) The differences between company and Union had not been submitted to arbitration as provided for in the 1946 contract.<br>
<br>
2) The 1946 agreement included a no-strike clause.<br>
<br>
3) The 1946 contract remained in force and effect until a new agreement has been reached by the two parties either through
negotiation or arbitration."<br>
<br>
The no-strike clause and the fact that the 1946 contract remained in effect until a new agreement was reached meant that the company 
could stall negotiations  indefinitely. 751 had agreed to the contract remaim in full force and effect until a new agreement Was signed.<br>
<br>
Hansen quotes District President Harold Gibson as saying that "this clause was inserted in the contract because during the interval between the expiration of the old contract and the signing of the new one, rival unionism reared its head.<br>
<br>
Apparently the AFL carpenters, plumbers, etc., were attempting to invade this industrial Structure. (The IAM had withdrawn from the AFL in 1945 due to the inability or unwillingness on the part of the AFL Executive Council to resolve jurisdictional disputes between the Carpenters and the IAM in the IAM's favor.) The "full force and effect" clause returned to haunt the District.<br>
<br>
Negotiations continued sporadically between June and December of 1947.  The company submitted a revised proposal tO 751 on january 6, 1948, and intensive negotiation followed.  On March 15, 1948, the Union again offered to submit unresolved articles to arbitration.  The company took the same position as before; it wanted veto power over choice of arbiters; it wanted to submit the entire contract to arbitration.  Again, the Union refused.<br>
<br>
Prelude lo the 1948 Strike<br>
<br>
In the meantime, the Taft-Hartley Act had been enacted into law on June 23, 1947, by a Republican Congress over President Truman's veto.  The passage of Taft-Hartley considerably complicated an already complex situation.  Among other provisions, provisions which in total prompted organized labor to label TaftHartley a slave labor law, the Act required a 60 day notice prior to a strike.16 Taft-Hartley also required union authorization elections prior to union shop agreement.<br>
<br>
The NLRB conducted an authorization election during the week of March 26, 1948.  "About - 12,800 employees voted in the election, and more than 12,000 voted to authorize Lodge 751 to negotiate a union shop agreement with the company."18 Negotiations continued, centering on the seniority question, wages and the date of retroactivity of increases, and the method of selection of an arbitration panel.<br>
<br>
Agreement staged on the date of retroactivity and the amount of the wage increase. (The Union wanted wage increases to be retroactive to January 1, 1947.  The company insisted upon the date of the beginning of formal negotiations - March 16, 1947.) On
April 13, 1947, the District Council established a deadline of April 16 for the reaching of a settlement regarding choice of arbiters.<br>
<br>
Following this deadline, the Union submitted another proposal to the company, providing for selection of arbiters and submission of wage demands to arbitration.  The company refused.<br>
<br>
On April 20,1948, the District Council m@with "some 350 shop committeemen" Present, and voted to strike on 12:30 AM of April 22, 1948.  The Union submitted a final proposal to the company on April 20.  The company refused the offer.<br>
<br>
The District Council met again on April 2l. According to Hansen,<br>
Grand Lodge Representative Cotton addressed this meeting and cautioned the members as to possible consequences of such strike action, reminding them of their weak strategic position, and informing them that the advice of the Grand Lodge was to stay on the job.  However, emotions were running high and he was booed 
from the platform.<br>
<br>
On April 22, 1948, the membership of District Lodge 751 struck, and remained on strike until September 13, 1948.<br>
<br>
"Let's forget about the Union. Let's concentrate on community, country, company and ourselves.  "<br>
<br>
Boeing President William Allen addressing a mass meeting of non-strikers and scabs during the 1948 strike.<br>
<br>
The strike came as no surprise to Boeing.  "As early as the summer of 1947, almost a year before the strike, Mr. Allen outlined to the supervisors the plan of action they should folloW.112 When the strike did come, Allen was prepared.  From the beginning, Allen and Boeing used tactics designed to isolate 751 leadership in the eyes of the membership and the community.<br>
<br>
Allen made adroit use of Taft-Hartley and Dave Beck of the Teamsters in his attempt to break the strike and the Aero Mechanics Union.  The following telegrams between Allen and Harvey Brown, IAM President, were the first salvo:<br>
<br>
April 22, 19484:48 P.M.<br>
<br>
To:    Harvey Brown, President<br>
International Association of Machinists From: Wilham M. Allen, President<br>
Boeing Airplane Company<br>
<br>
     At 12:30 A.M. today Local 751 of the Intemational Association of Machinists caused its members to strike at the Boeing Airplane Company's Plant in Seattle.  Our operations are being
picketed today.  Please advise by return wire if this action was sanctioned by the International Association of Machinists.<br>
<br>
Washington, D.C., April 23, 1948 11:10 A.M.<br>
<br>
To: William M. Allen From: Harvey Brown<br>
<br>
International Association of Machinists'Executive Council did not sanction strike at the Boeing Airplane Company's Plant in Seattle.<br>
<br>
April 23, 1948  10:50 P.M.<br>
<br>
To: Harvey Brown From: William M. Allen<br>
<br>
Appreciate your wire stating you did not sanction strike.  I wish to point out that no notices were given by Local 751 which would constitute compliance with Section 8D of the National Labor Relations Act; that individuals represented by Local 751 are engaging in a strike in violation of this section; that these individuals have therefore lost their status as employees of this Company; and as a consequence Local 751 does not at the present time constitute a collective bargaining agent under the National Labor Relations Act.<br>
<br>
In telegrams which followed, Brown and Allen agreed to a meeting between Boeing officials and a subcommittee of the IAM Executive Council in Seattle.  AJ.  Hayes, IAM General Vice-President, tells what happened next:<br>
<br>
I telephoned Mr. Allen of the Boeing Airplane Company at approximately 1:45 P.M. on Tuesday, April 27, 1948, for the purpose of arranging for the time and place for a conference to be held for the purpose of attempting to settle the strike of District #751 of the Intemational Association of Machinists at the Boeing Company Plant.<br>
<br>
I told Mr. Allen that there would be six persons in our group.  Mr. Allen immediately inquired as to the identity of the six.  I explained to Mr. Allen that our group was composed of Vice-Presidents Joseph McBreen, Roy M. Brown and myself; Grand Lodge Representatives Jack Bentley and Garry Cotton; and Harold Gibson, President of District #751.<br>
<br>
When I gave Mr. Allen this information, he immediately objected to meeting anyone other than the subcommittee of the Grand Lodge Executive Council (Vice-Presidents McBreen, Brown and Hayes)....
Mr. Allen stated further that he did not intend to meet with the subcommittee ... for the purpose of negotiating any provisions of an agreement and that he would not meet with any representatives of District #751 of the IAM.  He stated in substance that he intended to meet with the subcommittee of the Executive Council only for the purpose of discussing:<br>
<br>
1)     What the Grand Lodge of the IAM intended to do about those in District #751, IAM, who were responsible for violating the labor contract and the Taft-Hartley Act.<br>
<br>
2)     To explore the possibilities of establishing a bargaining agency on a basis which would give the Company definite assurance that there would be no further violations of an agreement or the Taft-Hartley Act.<br>
<br>
3)     To discuss matters related to damages incurred by the     Boeing Company as a result of the strike.<br>
<br>
I told Mr. Allen that the subcommittee did not come to Seattle to discuss his allegations with reference to violations of the Taft-Hartley Act, but that we came to Seattle in the hope that we could be helpful in resolving the issues which caused the strike.  I explained to Mr. Allen that ... it was not Mr. Brown's intention to send a committee to Seattle for the purpose of discussing the matters Mr. Allen had previously mentioned to me.<br>
<br>
During the discussion of this phase of the question, Mr. Allen said that he had no objection to our bringing our attomey to the conference but that he would not meet representatives of District #75 1. Since Mr. Allen did not deviate from his position, no con-
ference was held.<br>
<br>
Faced with Allen's refusal to bargain with District 751 leadership present, the IAM belatedly <B>granted</B> strike sanction on April 28, 1948.  By refusing to bargain with 75 1, but agreeing to meeting with the IAM subcommittee, Allen had attempted to create the appearance of division within the International.<br>
<br>
Clearly, Allen desired a union at Boeing more to the liking of management - a more pliable, reliable union - a union led, perhaps, by a "labor statesman.<br>
<br>
Allen found his "labor statesman" in Dave Beck, Vice President of the Intenational Brotherhood of Teamsters.  With the Aero Mechanics on strike, Beck moved in.  At first, he claimed only to be interested in exercising jurisdictional rights over about 5,000 warehouse workers, parts and transportation department employees.6 An Aviation Week article of 6/7/48 explains the situation well:
The (Boeing) company has insisted from the start that it can no longer rely on the Aero Mechanics' leadership and has hinted that it wished to deal with a new union, one with 'responsible' officials.<br>
<br>
Beck's rationale for the raid on the Aero Mechanics is explained in the same Aviation Week article:<br>
<br>
Several thousand men and women, who properly belong to our organization, are today out of employment because of a labor dispute with which this union has no connection whatsoever .... As a direct result of this dispute, a vast amount of work, upon which they have a right to depend in the future, has been transferred elsewhere and may never return to Seattle.<br>
<br>
Beck's statement contained two kernels of truth.  The AFL had granted the Teamsters jurisdiction over some workers at Boeing.  "On May 28, (Beck) announced in his union newspaper, the Washington Teamster, that the Teamsters would seek jurisdiction at Boeing on the grounds that it had been awarded them by the 1937 AFL convention.<br>
<br>
A Business Week article of 9 / 25 / 48 provides further explanation:<br>
<br>
Some years ago the AFL Executive Council awarded conditional jurisdiction at aircraft plants to the IAM, which was at the time affiliated with the AFL.  The object was to block CIO organizing drives in aircraft plants.  The Council stipulated that after plants were safely- organized, the Machinists must recognize jurisdiction of craft unions.<br>
<br>
The IAM didn't do so before leaving the AFL, and it's not likely to do so now that it's out of the Federation.<br>
<br>
Perlman notes that "Beck, it should be added, got at least a limited endorsement from the AFL executive council - but this was at a time when AFL President Green was trying to pressure the IAM to negotiate with the AFL."'(The IAM was out of the AFL at the time.) Beck's statement that vast amounts of work had been transferred out of Seattle perhaps never to return had some truth also.<br>
<br>
Aviation Week said on May 24, 1948, that Boeing "transferred several million dollars of work to Wichita and to subcontractors in Oregon and California. A much greater threat alluded to in Beck's<br>

statement were rumors circulating to the effect that  the Air Force intended to move all defense plants inland to place them out of range of Soviet bombers.  The Air Force did, in fact, have such a plan, which they formally announced in 1949.  But the Air Force later backed off, and the plan to move all Boeing production to
<br>
Wichita never materialized.<br>
<br>
It soon became clear, however, that Beck and the Teamsters intended to capture the entire membership of 751.  The fiction of asserting jurisdictional rights over a limited number of employees (rights which were disputed by the IAM) became apparent when Beck organized Aeronautical Workers and Warehousemen Helpers Union Local 45 1, and opened a hiring hall to recruit workers for Boeing.12 Moreover, Beck and Allen had a deal.  Samuel Bassett, an attorney on the Teamsters' staff during 1948, had this to say:<br>
<br>
I was requested to meet (at) ... the Washington Athletic Club with representatives of Boeing and a small committee appointed by Dave Beck.  At that time, I met Mr. Allen for the first time, and I was also introduced to Mr. Logan, who I believe was Boeing's labor relations manager.<br>
<br>
At that meeting a course of action for ending the strike was discussed.  Thereafter the Teamsters union sent organizers through the picket lines at the Boeing plant to solicit membership applications from employees who had returned to work and from new (workers) who had been recruited by the company.  The Teamsters union chartered a new local union designated as Aeronautical Workers, Warehousemen and Helpers Union Local 451, and this local established ari employment office and recruited employees to replace the strikers.<br>
<br>
(After the strike) ... and during the strike, on several occasions a committee from the Teamsters union, which I was requested to accompany, visited Boeing's labor relations office to discuss the recruiting and organizing efforts of the Teamsters union.<br>
<br>
.... I am sure that Mr. Allen will not deny that he came to Dave Beck's office and requested him to assist in breaking the strike of the Aero Mechanics' Union.<br>
<br>
Beck, with the collaboration of Allen and Boeing, recruited scabs through much of the period 751 was on strike.  Boeing actively recruited scabs in its own right through extensive newspaper and billboard advertising.  Company sponsored billboards read, "Boeing has a job to do; Boeing has a job for you.-14 According to Aviation Week of May 31, 1948,<br>
<br>
Boeing continued to advertise for workers willing to cross the picket lines and made it more tempting by granting a 15 cents an hour wage increase to all hourly employees.  Allen claims the increase makes Boeing personnel the best paid aircraft workers in the world.  At present the boost affects about 1000 workers, but
would apply to all Union members should they all decide to retum to their respective jobs.<br>
<br>
Excerpts from accounts of the time show a growing presence of non-751 workers in the Boeing plants.  This quote is from Aviation Week of June 7, 1948:<br>
<br>

<B>Any Person Crossing This Picket Line Is a Scab!</B><br>
<br>

<B>Don't Be a Boeing Scab</B><br>
<br>
Aero Mechanic Union members-over 14,000 strong-ore on strike against Baeog Air. plane Company to win a living wage and retain adequate working conditions.<br>
<br>
Picket lines are around all Boeing plants 24 hours each and every day.  Any person crossing this picket line. whether to work in a job formmy held by a Union man or to fO any pos@. is labeled as a scab and a sfnle-breakerl<br>
<br>
The Aero Mechan;cs Union is offiriafed with fhe huge International Assockwm of Ma. chinists-on infernational Union with members in every state in the United States.  HawaiL Canada and the Canal Zone.  These hundreds of thousands of members and the rest of a huge army of American Union people will remember forever the ident*y of scalm Amd here's the definition of a SCAB as found in Webster's Unabridged Dictionary:<br>
<br>
"A mean, dirty, peltry fellow; specifically in contempt, a workman who refuses to join in a strike, and one who continues at his work as usual; one who takes a striker's place . . .<br>
<br>

<B>No Real Man or Woman Ever Becomes a Scab</B><br>
<br>
The Teamsters, according to the rival Aero Mechanics, have 12 organizers working on Boeing employees and already have signed up about 200 employees normally represented by the Mechanics.<br>
<br>
The Teamsters have not been observing the picket lines at Boeing.  Neither have members of the engineers' union.  In addition, the back-to-work move is growing.  Total employment (author's note: includes all employees - not just hourly employees) last week was put at near 5000 and was increasing I 00 per day.<br>
<br>
On June 28, 1948, Aviation Week said, "Total hourly employees now is 3650, including 926 retumed strikers." By July, according to Hansen, "the Teamsters'campaign became a serious factor as housewives, 19-year olds, and rural residents moved into Boeing.1118 And by July 20, 1948, according to the New Republic,<br>

<br>

... <B>it </B>appeared that the company was succeeding.  Retuming strikers and new workers flocked into the plant, and Boeing claimed to be within 5000 of its needed workforce.<br>
<br>
But despite the pressure of company blandishments, Lodge 75 I's members are continuing an excellent job of holding out.  Less than 3000 of them have returned to work.<br>
<br>
Included in the Union's ranks are a large number of first-time unionists, school teachers and farmers who had flocked to Boeing during the war, and some 500 Negroes, who had worked on permits during the war and have been admitted only recently to IAM membership.  All of them are still marching on the picket line.<br>
<br>
By late July of 1948, it had become clear that District Lodge 751 could remain on strike no longer.  Boeing refused to bargain.  Boeing, in association with Beck and the Teamsters, was actively recruiting strikebreakers.  Given more time, Boeing would be able to replace striking Aero Mechanics with scabs.<br>
<br>
Too, the Taft-Hartley Act provided that only employees actually at work in the Boeing plants were eligible to vote in NLRB representation elections. By late July 751 leadership knew that the Union would be facing an NLRB representational election against the Teamsters.  An NLRB trial examiner's ruling of July 20 came just in time.  This ruling ordered Boeing to reinstate striking 751 members.<br>
<br>
A complex series of NLRB hearings and court cases took place during and after the strike.  The NLRB essentially supported 751's claim that Boeing was engaging in unfair labor practices due to refusal to bargain with 751.  The NLRB requested a District Court injunction requiring Boeing to bargain with the Union.<br>
<br>
In June of 1948, the District Court refused, citing the contract extension clause, the contract no-strike clause and the lack of 60-day strike notice as required by Taft-Hartley.  In addition, the Court held in its June, 1948, ruling that the company was "not required ... to bargain collectively with Lodge 751 or to recognize Lodge 751 as the collective bargaining representative of the presently striking employees of (the) ... Company.<br>
<br>
NLRB hearings continued.  An NLRB trial examiner found on July 20, 1948, that:<br>
<br>
1) The contract extension clause "could not contemplate perpetuity<br>
<br>
2) The Union had adequately complied with the 60-day notice provision.<br>
<br>
3) The Union "was and is the exclusive bargaining representative of
employees in the appropriate collective bargaining unit.<br>
<br>
4) The Boeing Company was engaging in unfair labor practices by refusal to bargain with the Union.  The NLRB trial examiner ordered Boeing "to cease and desist from refusing to bargain collectively with Lodge 751 " and to reinstate "all employees who went on strike on April 22, 1948, to their ... positions without prejudice.<br>
<br>
According to the New Republic,<br>
<br>
Lodge 751 immediately accepted Spencer's (the NLRB trial examiner) 
findings in full and applied to retum <B>its </B>members to work on the NLRB recommendations.  The company, committed to its new employees and involved with Beck's Teamsters, could do nothing but refuse.  On August 1, five days after Lodge 751's application, Boeing was liable to pay $172,000 daily in defaulted wages should the NLRB and the courts uphold Spencer's findings.<br>
<br>
But Bill Allen and Boeing seem willing to take the chance.  His determination to prove the strike illegal apparently unshaken, Allen announced he would cany the case all the way to the Supreme Court.<br>
<br>
Boeing held out in defiance of the NLRB trial examiner's ruling until September.  On September 13, 1948, the strike ended.  Aviation Week summarizes the reasons 751 returned to work:<br>
<br>
... the Aero Mechanics hurried back to work on September 13 after being out 140 days.  The new (Teamster) union was one reason for the return.  Others: IAM worry over cost of strike benefits, more than $2,000,000; defection of about one-third of AMUs (Aero Mechanics Union) original 14,000 members.<br>
<br>
The NLRB trial examiner handed down the reinstatement order on July 20, 1948.  Allen ignored it until September 13th.  ABen's reasons for agreeing to abide by the trial examiner's ruling include two possibilities: first, he may have counted on the NLRB or the courts overturning the ruling.<br>
<br>
In the meantime, however, Boeing incurred penalties of $172,000 per day; perhaps Allen and Boeing decided the stakes were getting too high.  Second, and the more likely reason: Business Week of 9/17/49 says, "The walkout ended only after high military officials intervened.-27 Seeing the Cold War heat up, the Armed Forces became deeply concemed with production delays of the B-50 Superfortress bomber, for which Boeing was the prime contractor.<br>
<br>
In any event, the longest strike in 75I's history ended.  It is more
accurate to say that the strike was broken.<br>
<br>
Boeing and Allen had little to lose by complying with the trial examiner's ruling, for when 751 members returned to work, they retumed without a contract and under the company's terms.  Four factors forced them back: Allen's refusal to bargain, the Teamster raid, the ability of Boeing and the Teamsters to recruit strikebreakers, and the TaftHartley Act.<br>
<br>
The New Republic, in an article of August 30, 1948, says, "Today some local leaders, sympathetic to the strike, feel that inexperienced Union leaders were unwise to act so abruptly.1128 Looking back with always-clear hindsight, this seems true, but the District was a democratic union, the membership did endorse the strike, the entire seniority system was at stake, and 751 did try to reach agreement.<br>
<br>
When 751 members retumed to work, they retumed without a contract, and hearings and litigation continued.  An NLRB ruling of November 22, 1948, upheld the decision of the trial examiner.  Boeing appealed the NLRB ruling to the courts.<br>
<br>
A ruling on May 31, 1949 by the Circuit Court of Appeals of the District of Columbia struck down the NLRB ruling, saying virtually the same thing as the previous District Court decision of June 1948:<br>
<br>
The strike was illegal, as the contract's no-strike clause had been violated.  The Union had not complied with Taft-Hartley.  The Union had lost the right to engage in collective bargaining on behalf of Boeing employees.<br>
<br>
On July 31, 1949, 751 petitioned the NLIP for a representation election to determine which union had the right to engage in collective bargaining with the company.  Tippett explains the situation:<br>
<br>
The strike had been over for almost eleven months when the Circuit Court's adverse decision came and the District's petition for an NLRB election was filed.  In the eleven months' interim, although the Aero Mechanics were working in the plant, they had no contract with the Company and no protection.<br>
<br>
They were mixed in with Teamsters members and with non-Union employees... It was this total group of Boeing workers that would be eligible to vote in the representative election.  They, as a whole, would determine the issue.  A majority of them had to vote for the Aero Mechanics in the coming election.  How to be assured of that majority was the major concem of the Aero Mechanics in July 1949, as they waited for the NLRB to process their petition.<br>
<br>

The NLRB set the election for November 1, 1949.  The ballot provided for a choice between District Lodge 751, the Teamsters" Local 451, and "no union" - as required by Taft-Hartley.  With the election date set, 751 mobilized, briefed and organized Union members, directed personal letter campaigns at all Boeing workers, made house calls on each worker, established a speakers bureau, held mass membership meetings and special Local and District meetings, and aimed extensive radio, billboard and newspaper advertisements at Boeing workers and the labor community.<br>
<br>
John McCann, "The 1948 Boeing Strike," <B>Blood in the water.</B> Seattle: District Lodge 751, 1989 p. 105-108, 114-130.<br>
<br>&#169; Copyright The Tacoma Public Library, 1996 -- All Rights Reserved<br><hr>
