<h1>Aerospace Workers Strike of 1965</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
THE BOEING STRIKES OF 1965 AND 1977.<br>
<br>
John McCann, "The  Boeing Strikes of 1965 and 1977" <B>Blood in the water, a history of District Lodge 751 of the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers.</B> Seattle: District Lodge 751,<br>
1989. p.<br>
<br>

But neither the 1965 nor the 1977 strikes were as <B>significant </B>in the history of District Lodge 751 as the 1948 strike, the representational battle with the Teamsters or the 1962 contract negotiations.  The very survival of the Union depended upon the outcome of those battles.<br>
<br>
By contrast, the 1965 and 1977 strikes focused on incremental change in collective bargaining agreements.<br>
<br>
Major issues in 1965 were Performance Analysis, union security and dependent medical coverage.  Since the strike took place under the IAM Boeing corporate agreement, all IAM members at Boeing struck nationwide.<br>
<br>
Two months of negotiations preceded the strike.  The strike itself lasted nineteen days.  The Union won minor modifications in union security provisions, and won review of the Performance Analysis system by a Union-company committee.<br>
<br>
According to Bill Walkama (Interview, 3 / 3 / 88), the Union made gains in dependent medical coverage.  The Union retained the right to strike over the Performance Analysis issue.  Performance Analysis negotiations continued through April 1966.  Performance Analysis was replaced by a system called "Seniority Ability Control."<br>
<br>
Seniority Ability Control was Performance Analysis under a different name, but according to the Aero Mechanic of 4/25/66, the IAM won improvements in seniority provisions, and in grievance and arbitration procedures.<br>
<br>
The 1977 strike lasted from October 4 to November 17.  This strike also took place under the IAM Boeing corporate agreement.  Major issues were wages, retirement, cost of living adjustments, and health and welfare benefits.  The most important issues were wages and cost of living adjustments.<br>
<br>
The company's proposal offered a 3% general increase on base wage rates, not increases based on the base rate plus folded-in COLA'S. (See Aero Mechanic, IO/ 13/77.)<br>

According to Bill Walkama (Interview, 3/3/88), the Union won "substantial improvements in the pension program and in some wage inequities and fringe and health and welfare benefits."<br>
<br>
The 1977 strike, according to Walkama was "a strong, stable strike.  It was well organized, well put together."<br>
<br>
John McCann, "The Boeing Strikes of 1965 and 1977," <B>Blood in the water.</B> Seattle: District Lodge 751, 1989.<br>
<br>
<br>&#169; Copyright The Tacoma Public Library, 1996 -- All Rights Reserved<br><hr>
