<h1>Railroad Strike of 1873</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
RAILROAD WALKOUT OF 1873.<br>
<br>
"Death of E.S. Smith," <B>The Tacoma Ledger.</B> January 3, 1886 p. 4.<br>
<br>
"Mr. Smith was a man for an emergency and when in the autumn of 1873, Jay Cooke failed and the contractors of the road from Kalama to Tacoma were unable to pay the men, and it was necessary to meet the requirements of Congress to complete the road to Tacoma before the close of the year, the railroad company put the work of completion into his hands.<br>
<br>
"Sixteen miles of road remained unfinished, and this it was necessary to construct within a few weeks. A force of three hundred men wee encamped under arms at the end of the road, refusing to work until paid, and threatening to fire on anyone else who should attempt to work on the road.<br>
<br>
"But Mr. Smith went out with other gentlemen and aided in inducing the men to resume work without a collision, the road was completed within the time required. It was large through his efforts that the railroad company was induced to build the road up the Puyallup Valley to the Wilkeson coal mines in 1887.<br>
<br>
"Death of E.S. Smith," <B>The Tacoma Ledger.</B> January 3, 1886, p. 4.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
North Pacific History Company, "Edward S. Smith," <B>History of the Pacific Northwest, Oregon and Washington.</B> Portland: North Pacific History Company, 1889, p. 563-65.<br>
<br>
When, in the autumn of 1873, Jay Cook failed, and the contractors on the road from Kalama to Tacoma were unable to pay the men, and it was necessary to meet the requirements of Congress to complete the road to Tacoma before the close of the year, the railroad company, through the individual efforts of Captain Ainsworth, put the work into his hands.<br>
<br>
Sixteen miles of road remained unfinished;  and it was necessary to construct them within a few weeks. A force of three hundred men were encamped under arms at the end of the work refusing to work until paid, and threatening to fire on anyone else who should attempt to work on the road.<br>
<br>
Mr. Smith went out with others to the men and was principally instrumental in inducing the men to return to work.  Under his direction, the railroad was completed within the time required by the charter.  The authority for that important work was contained
in a letter from Captain Ainsworth of a few lines, and which was a veritable carte blanche as to mode of work.<br>
<br>
North Pacific History Company, "Edward S. Smith," <B>History of the Pacific Northwest. Oregon and Washington.</B> Portland: North Pacific History Company, 1889, p. 563-65. (excerpts).<br>
<br>&#169; Copyright The Tacoma Public Library, 1996 -- All Rights Reserved<br><hr>
