<h1>Railroad Strike of 1922</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>

RAILROAD STRIKE OF 1922.<br>
<br>
Leonard Painter, "The Big Strike of 1922," <B>Through fifty years with the Brotherhood of Railway Carmen of America.</B> Kansas City, Missouri: Brotherhood of Railway Carmen, 1941, p. 158-172.<br>
<br>
Brotherhood leaders and officials of other railway labor Organizations were in a difficult position in this momentous year of 1921.  Comparatively little space has been given the war years in this history; under federal control the Brotherhood made many gains for its membership, wide employment kept everyone at work and there were few threats of any sort to bettering conditions.<br>
<br>
Now the situation had reversed itself.  The abnormally high cost of living had made increased wages insufficient ... and now the wage reduction of July 1, 1921 and other losses including a second wage reduction threatened to return the railway worker to worse conditions than existed before the war.<br>
<br>
Brotherhood leadership had hoped to hold fast to standards of wages, hours and working conditions as stipulated in the National Agreement, in a belief that somewhat decreased living costs would result in that agreement providing fair remuneration . But the first wage reduction was followed by a decision on August 11, 1921, dealing with overtime, eliminating time-and-one-half for Sunday and holiday work and modifying other sections of the overtime agreements.<br>
<br>
The effect of this decision was electrifying.  To the Brotherhood membership it was a piecemeal decision on one part of the National Agreement indicating what was to come as other decisions were handed down.  Moreover, these actions in Washington were<br>
directly responsible for an increasingly hostile attitude toward workers on the part of railroad management, particularly local subordinates, who appeared to adopt a manner of treatment calculated to stir the workers to drastic action.<br>
<br>
The executive council of the Railway Employees' Department caged several divisional executive boards into conference . . . at the same time urging every precaution against unauthorized suspensions of work,. which would have Placed the workers in a defenseless position with practically all the rules yet to be decided by the Labor Board.<br>
<br>
At the joint conference the action of the Labor Board was condemned and the conferees declared against any other than a complete decision on Ar rules.  Six representatives from each organization were authorized to tour the country and urge members at federated meetings in all important centers to adhere strictly to the policies adopted.
Another serious and widespread development was the farming out on contract of railroad repair work "for the double purpose," said General President Ryan, "of increasing the profits of the outside companies in which they (the railroads) were financially interested, and of forcing labor to submit to their open-shop program."<br>
<br>
When the Railway Employees' Department presented the matter of contract work to the Labor Board and urged a speedy decision, even the chairman of the board declared this was the most important matter before the Board, and added: "If the conduct of the carriers in those cases is lawful, the ground is cut from under the Labor Board and the vitals are cut out of the Transportation Act."<br>
<br>
Under the contract system piecework had been restored in some<br>
of the shops in spite of employe protests.  It was, as the General President later pointed out, a pathetic situation that long ex-
perienced employees were turned out of railroad employment en-
tirely and given over to contractors, losing all of their seniority rights and pass privileges for themselves and families . . . a reversion on the part of railroad management to practices of the long-ago past!<br>
<br>
Although one of the last acts of Director General McAdoo had been to forbid piecework except by the majority wish of organizations of employees, this work-method was not to disappear from railroad practices.  The railroads appealed to the Labor Board for permission to reinstate the piecework system, but the Board denied them that right except where labor organizations preferred it.  After the strike, the piecework system was revived.<br>
<br>
These serious situations confronted the June, 1922, convention of the Railway Employees' Department convention in Chicago, where the prevailing opinion was that prompt and drastic action must be taken to halt the Labor Board in its surrender of long fought-for railway labor rights.  As a result, the submission of three strike ballots was authorized, (1) dealing with the rules (2) dealing with piecework and contract work; and (3) the recent further reduction of wages by 7 and 9 cents per hour.  The ballots were ordered returnable by July 1, and again the various memberships were cautioned against any impulsive action prior to an authorized strike.<br>
<br>
At the time of submission of the ballots, General President Ryan addressed the Brotherhood membership with an appeal to support the Railway Employees Department's request for funds to be used as strike benefits for certain classes of workers not participating
otherwise in authorized benefits ... and this Brotherhood raised $15,000 for that purpose.  In another appeal to the membership, the General President urged that every member vote his own convictions, and that the final vote represent the biggest possible majority opinion.<br>
<br>
Before July 1, when the balloting was to be completed, the executive council of the Railway Employees' Department made a final effort to prevent the strike.  The council addressed a letter to the chairman of the Association of Railway Executives Placing the responsibility for developments squarely on that association by pointing out that although the Transportation Act provided machinery for negotiation and adjustment of disputes, the carriers had refused to employ it from the outset.<br>
<br>
The letter pointed to other indications that railway management had ruthlessly ignored means of adjustment.<br>
<br>
"There is, however," the letter concluded, "one benefit which may come to the carriers and their employees, and to the general public, from the fact that there are national spokesmen of the conflicting interests who might be able to halt a nationwide strike in the railway service, if the withdrawal of men from employment<br>
railway executives sincerely desire to avoid this consequence of their previous course of action.<br>
<br>
For this reason, in behalf of and by the authority of the executive Council of the Railway Employees' Department, I am informing you and through you informing the responsible heads of the various railway systems in the United States, and also the Pullman Company, most of which are represented in the Association of Railway Executives, that unless an immediate arrangement can be made (to adjust the three points in dispute) a sanction of withdrawal from employment on July 1, 1922, as voted by the employees, wig be unavoidable."<br>
<br>
The tenor of the reply from the railway executives was not unexpected.  After presenting the case of railway management and declaring that wage demands of the labor organizations would put an unjust burden on the public, the reply waxed eloquent in this conclusion: "If the just authority of the <B>Government</B> is to be successfully defied and the Government is to be rendered helpless to protect its citizens in their peaceful and lawful pursuits, if patriotic and loyal obedience to Government authority is to be denied, the act and the responsibility must be yours.<br>
<br>
It shall not be ours.  If you strike it will be against an order of a <B>Government</B> tribunal-it will be a strike against the Government of the United States."<br>
<br>
The Association of Railway Executives now turned patriots for the moment and unmindful of the "unpatriotic" and frequent violation of
Labor Board decisions by ninety member railroads ... thus closed the door on any conciliation or adjustment efforts.<br>
<br>
Meanwhile, the flood of strike ballots was rolling in!<br>
<br>
It should be recorded here that the organized railway workers had reached such a stage of impatience in the dispute with the railroads and the Labor Board, some factions felt that the cautious moves of the executive council of the Railway Employee' Department were signs of surrender . . . and a distrust of the council stood in the way of a strike, and would never permit a strike to be called.<br>
<br>
It is very apparent, from the viewpoint of today, that the council was wisely and patiently cautious ... for the good name and integrity of railway workers generally.<br>
<br>
However, the suspicion reached a point that some lodges had returned the packages of ballots unopened and unvoted with the comment that balloting was useless in the face of that "attitude" of the executive council.  Because of these things, the ballots were tabulated by a committee appointed from the memberships.<br>
<br>
The result was a vote almost unanimous in favor of the strike ... 97 per cent favorable, to be exact.  And the three issues involved in the strike again should be recorded: First, the establishment of unjust wages by decisions of the Labor Board; second, the establishment of unjust working conditions through amendments by the Labor Board of certain rules of the National Agreement; third, the contracting out of shops and work by a large number of railroads as a means of evading the application of the law to their properties.<br>
<br>
In an attempt to halt the strike the United States Labor Board on June 29 cited labor organizations and railroads to appear at a hearing in Chicago the next day, directing that the status quo be maintained until the hearing was completed.<br>
<br>
In the meantime, on the same day-June 29, 1922-this telegram went to every local union affiliated with the organizations: "In compliance with the strike vote, all shop crafts employed below the rank of general foreman are hereby granted sanction to suspend work 10:00 a. m. July I on all railroads and Pullman shops in the United States.  Notify all outside points.  Wire number responding and number remaining at work."<br>
<br>
The executive council of the Railway Employees' Department refused to appear at the hearing of the Labor Board, filing a communication that stressed the need of labor executives remaining 99 on the job" to counsel the men in a peaceful strike.  It denied the right of the Labor Board to intervene, saying "a compulsory limitation upon the
right to control one's own labor is not within the power of the Government, because this right is a natural right and is protected by the thirteenth amendment of the Constitution."<br>
<br>
The communication asserted that "there is no more important concern than to safeguard the freedom of labor upon which alone can enduring prosperity be based."<br>
<br>
At 10 o'clock the morning of July 1, 1922, history records the greatest stoppage of work ever occurring at one time in the history of American organized labor.  It was from 95 to 100 per cent effective.  All over the land the shop crafts laid down their tools.  The great strike of 1922 was on.<br>
<br>
It was almost at that moment, strange to say, that what has now come to be known as the infamous company-union setup was introduced and sanctioned by the Labor Board to make the strike ineffective.  All the forces against labor were augmented by government itself in the ruthless strangulation of labor that was attempted in the weeks to follow.<br>
<br>
The first move of the Labor Board was a resolution authorizing railroad companies to organize the strikebreakers.  Such company organizations of classes of workers, the board said "...will be desirable, if not a practical necessity." Company associations sprang up in a hurry on a great many of the railroads most of which required the applicant for work to sign an agreement which prevented him from joining any other labor organization except on penalty of being discharged.<br>
<br>
The transportation brotherhoods and orders signed a complaint to the Labor Board, and the American Federation of Labor passed a resolution not only condemning the Board's action and declaring the Board 69 unworthy of public trust," but added: "The American Federation of Labor win take all appropriate Steps to obtain from the congress which created the Labor Board such legislation or declarations of public policy as may check this unamerican effort to destroy the freedom of labor to organize to bargain collectively and to act in concert for the general welfare."<br>
<br>
There was no doubt that railroad operations were seriously crippled by the strike, in spite of frenzied effort to recruit strikebreakers with few questions asked as to qualification-and the assistance of the Labor Board in these efforts.<br>
<br>
Let there be no doubt that labor's opposition was united! State and federal officers and the courts were called on to intimidate and coerce the men on strike.  In many places the militia was caned out without warrant.  Federal injunctions were issued in almost every
federal court district in the land.<br>
<br>
Thousands of striking shopmen were arrested following these injunctions; in nearly every instance where trials were not before juries, the men were convicted and sentenced to fines and prison terms.  In one instance, the counsel for employees was threatened with contempt proceedings if trial by jury were demanded!<br>
<br>
The President of the United States ... President Harding ... issued a proclamation forbidding interference with interstate trans-
portation and the carrying of the mail, which drew a letter from the executive council of the Railway Employees' Department to the chief executive pointing out that the railroads and not the workers had violated the Labor Board decisions ... that railway management had refused all possibilities of adjustment . . . and the labor organizations stood ready to cooperate in such ail effort at any time.<br>
<br>
The executive council met with the President July 28, and later the same day the President conferred with the chairman of the Association of Railway Executives.  Out of those conferences the President conveyed to each side the terms for uniting preliminary to calling off the strike.  But, as pointed out to the President by the executive council after a conference with the policy committee of ninety men, the terms required surrender on the part of labor on the very points over which the strike had been called.<br>
<br>
However, to show their fairness, the shop craft leaders declared magnanimously that "we accept reluctantly, but commit ourselves to carry out the terms of settlement in utmost good faith."<br>
<br>
Their reluctant acceptance was of no use.  The railroad executives rejected the proposal, largely over the one point that all employees would be returned to their former jobs with full seniority rights.  Said the executives: "The striking former employees cannot be given preference to employees at present in the service without doing violence to every principle of right and justice involved<br>
in this matter and without the grossest breach of faith On the part of the railroads to men at present in their service.<br>
<br>
A second attempt by the President to adjust the differences was rejected by both sides. In this attempt, the President asked the labor organizations to resume work and leave the matter of<br>
seniority to a decision of the Labor Board ... the chairman of which already had expressed his opinion that the railroads were right in their viewpoint of seniority!<br>
<br>
It  must  be  recorded  that  among  those  who  attempted 
mediation efforts were executives of railroads not affected by the strike...executives who conferred with government officials and with executives of railroads involved in the strike in attempt to find a solution.<br>
<br>
Those railroad executives did everything in their power to affect mediation of some sort.  Also, following the rejection of the Presidents second proposal, the chief executives of railroad labor organizations not on strike asked the President to use his offices to bring about a settlement on the basis of his first proposal.<br>
<br>
It is noteworthy that  the  leaders  of  the  striking  organizations showed every desire to settle the dispute fairly and it is equally obvious that railroad management was being  ruthlessly stand-pat to break the ranks of organized labor.<br>
<br>
DAUGHERTY AND HIS INJUNCTION<br>
<br>
Unfortunately shop organizations could not have chosen a more inappropriate time to strike than this Post-war period when reactionary forces were in charge of all branches of the government.  A period a decade before had been called the "Age of Property" . . . but it had been the mere shadow of Such an age, compared with the audacious exhibition of government fighting labor in behalf of the entrenched interests.<br>
<br>
Harry M. Daugherty was the next spokesman for the railroads<br>
and he wielded a vicious injunction in this government attempt to break the strike.  It was an injunction without parallel, going so far as to enjoin the officers of the striking organizations from using organization funds and from communicating with members of their organizations "in aid of or to permit or encourage the doing any of the matters or things here in before restrained and enjoined."<br>
<br>
That the effect of the injunction was demoralizing is not to be questioned, for without doing anything unlawful the officers and leaders were subject to arrest.<br>
<br>
Daugherty ... and this act was before he was driven in disgrace from the office of attorney general for what was considered the worst case of corruption in the government's history ... slipped into Chicago September 1, 1922, without any notice of his intentions, and applied for the injunction before Federal Judge James H.     Wilkerson.  His bill of complaint was largely an appeal for the open shop, saying he would use the "power within his control to prevent labor unions of the country from destroying the open shop." The bill pledged all the power- of the government to the railroads.<br>
<br>
With very slight modifications from the bill, the federal judge granted a temporary restraining order.
The injunction had a devastating effect on the strikers.  It brought home to the railway labor organizations the fact that against them were arrayed every power of the financial world, every power of government, every power of capitalistic reactionaries.  Hundreds of men were in prison.<br>
<br>
"Litigation of a stupendous magnitude immediately confronted the organizations," declared General President Ryan.  "It was necessary to employ innumerable lawyers in all sections of the country.  The burden of expense was tremendous and practically beyond the ability of the organizations to meet; all of which, no <B>doubt</B> was the aim of the attorney general.  The result of our ex<B>perience</B> cannot soon be forgotten."<br>
<br>
That matter of litigation cost entered even into defense plans against a permanent injunction, and the leaders of the striking the organizations were compelled to direct their attorneys to with draw from any further defense, saying: "It is useless for the men who labor to match purses with the railroads and the government."<br>
In spite of that withdrawal, government attorneys went into a lengthy trial, the permanent injunction was granted . . . and the of<br>
defendants presented a bill $13,356.70 for court costs! After Daugherty had been removed from  office because of corruption,<br>
the Department of Justice reduced those costs to  $3,421.25 aid the bill was paid.<br>
<br>
Other litigation was piling up, such as a San Francisco suit against the craft organizations in which default judgment was given the railroad for more than 9 million dollars! And there even were suits by such individuals as a foreman who claimed he had had to abandon his employment as a result of the strike, and sued t@ recover $100,000 damages!<br>
<br>
With  every  force   of   management   and   government   against   them with   necessary    expenditures    draining    every    organization treasury almost to the vanishing point ... the plight of the strikers was serious.<br>
<br>
THE BALTIMORE AGREEMENT<br>
<br>
The leaders   of   the   railway   labor   organizations   had   continued their efforts toward settlement, and as late as August 25 had held one of a series of conferences with the Association of Railway Executives.<br>
<br>
It was apparent that the executives disagreed among themselves.<br>
<br>
One so-called "hard boiled" group was headed by Atterbury and Loree, the former and his Pennsylvania Railroad being one of the prime movers for many years in the company-union policy.  They were not agreeable to any kind of a settlement acceptable to the men.  But
Daniel Willard and S. Davies Warfield were leaders of another group that favored some sort of conciliation.<br>
<br>
Willard and Warfield and A. H. Smith, president of the New<br>
York Central Lines, met with representatives of the shop crafts in Baltimore and an agreement was reached, and early in September the strike was settled on the B. & O., the Milwaukee, the Chicago & Northwestern, the Seaboard, the New York Central, the Southern, the Mobile & Ohio and the Carolina, Clinchfield & Ohio.<br>
<br>
The terms of the agreement included restoration of as many men as possible, at prevailing wages, to the same jobs and at the same points as of june 30, and set up a <B>commission</B> composed of six representatives of management and six representatives of labor to pass on disputes arising out of this settlement.<br>
<br>
The executive council of the Railway Employees' Department, and officers of the latter, gave long consideration to the matter of agreement, and against much criticism approved it because of the general situation of increasing hardship, vanishing finances and the futility of hoping for a national agreement of any sort.  Rather, it was believed wiser to make this agreement in the hope that other railroads would join the movement immediately.<br>
<br>
A few of them did . some railroads were several months in adopting it ... and even after two and one-half years the Pennsylvania and Long Island Lines strikes still continued.<br>
<br>
In the weeks that followed, the railroads signing the agreement did not live up to the seniority rule . . . which also remained un-
settled at the time of the 1925 convention.<br>
<br>
The strike had had scarring effects on the participating organi-
zations, including this Brotherhood.  It had opened up the channel for the formation of company unions, which were to be a labor stumbling block for many years to come.  It caused loss of life, and suffering among those who were sent to prison under autocratic power.<br>
<br>
And it caused a breach in the membership, largely among those recent "joiners" who never had been disciplined to the serious and far-reaching purposes of the Brotherhood ... and who now were enemies to organization within the ranks of the Brotherhood.  The strike and its ending created several such major problems that put this organization face to face with the vital need of "beating back" to its previous standing and prestige.<br>
<br>
Leonard Painter, "The Big Strike of 1922," <B>Through fifty year.</B> Kansas City: Brotherhood of Railway Carmen, 1941, p. 158-172.<br>

