<h1>Typographical Union Strike</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
FOUNDING OF THE TYPOGRAPHICAL UNION.<br>
<br>
Randolph Radebaugh, "Founding of the typographical union," <B>The Tacoma News Tribune.</B> September 9, 1922. Number twenty-one in a series.<br>
<br>
City Editor Had Reputation Brought From East<br>
As Scrapper; Later Wrote Valuable Manual<br>
Used Today as Reference<br>
<br>
This is the 21st of a series of articles written for The News<br>
Tribune by R. F. Radebaugh, veteran editor of the Ledger, which he<br>
founded in 1881. In this article Mr. Radebaugh tells of the early<br>
newspaper making in Tacoma and of the incident which preceeded the<br>
last signature written by President Garfield before he was fatally<br>
shot.<br>
<br>
(NOTE: The first part of this article describes the people in<br>
a picture that can be found on page 5 of the September 9, 1922<br>
issue of the Tacoma News Tribune.)<br>
<br>
The above half tone represents very nearly all of the employees<br>
of the Tacoma Daily Ledger, posing at the front of the brick Ledger<br>
building on the west side of C Street (now called Broadway), erected four years before. The photograph was made in 1887--35 years ago, and includes all of the employees at that time except l A. Maulsby, foreman of the composing room; one reporter, and the boys who delivered the papers.<br>
<br>
The men stood in front of the business office, on and near the<br>
north end of the narrow platform which was built of consequence of<br>
cutting the street down to the grade established by the city, about<br>
three feet below the first floor of the building.<br>
<br>
The platform remained until the Ledger office was moved to 10th Street, in 1892, when it was torn away, a new floor laid on a level with the sidewalk, and two storerooms substituted for the old offices.<br>
<br>
In the lower room, from left to right are--C. H. Bell, printer;<br>
Ceorge Boothroyd; Phil Rummel, printer; Frank W. Beach, pressman; --- Jones, printer; Clarence Barton's little daughter; Fred Baker, now makeup on the San Francisco Examiner; ---McGrath, printer; Ed. Moabus, printer; Edward Herriff, printer. In the upper row, left to right, are: Chris Holz, errand boy; ---Toy, printer; Walter Whitney; E. M. Beach, job foreman, now in San Francisco; William Watson, printer; R. P. Milne, printer; Clarence Barton; E. L. Gruener; Morton Ramsdell; ---Porter, printer; Ed Lamb, printer; C. R. Wyland, printer; George Arkley, bookkeeper; Will Sutherland, city circulator.<br>

There are about a dozen printers tiring their legs and bodies<br>
by standing before the case, picking and setting type as through<br>
hundreds of years agone--for Mergenthaler had not yet arrived on his feet--and, when the little stick was filled, dumping and resuming the snail's pace for other and still other similar, small grabs; thus continuing the night of immense tedium until the paper was "up" to be followed the morrow by the equally tedious operation of 'throwing in, or distributing, ... the same type in the cases, preparatory to the next issue.<br>
<br>
When mere reminiscence of it seems wearisome there is hardly room for wonder that the practice turned so many to strong drink.<br>
<br>
Organized in 1883<br>
<br>
The local typographical union was about four years old when the<br>
picture was taken, a published announcement of the organization,<br>
recording the date as of September 30, 1883, about three weeks after the driving of the last spike on the Northern Pacific. The last spike event ushered in numerous and important changes in Tacoma and throughout the territory, and this was one of them. Through rail traffic with the East was deemed to have warranted all manner of developments and expansions.<br>
<br>
After promising appropriate remarks concerning "The Art of Arts<br>
Preservative," customary on such occasions, announcement stated that "the members of the typographical art in New Tacoma being of sufficient number to warrant the formation of a union, and being fully cognizant of the benefits to be derived therefrom, resolved to take the necessary steps toward the formation of such an organization, and, accordingly, as prearranged, the members of the craft in this city, to the number of 15, met in the composing room of the Ledger office on the last Sunday (September 30), at 2 o'clock p.m. with that object in view.<br>
<br>
The purpose and object of the meeting were stated to those present, after which Mr. D. A. Maulsby, foreman of the Ledger composing room, as temporary chairman, called the meeting to order.<br>
<br>
"All present then signed the roll and the names were as follows:<br>
D. A. Maulsby, S. H. Condon, W. A. Berry, Frank Baldauf, Marshall Fell Jr., Oliver Waller, S. H. Herin, George G. Ashbaugh, Hugh Glenn, M. D. McCaslin, E. L. Gruener, George Anderson, E. M. Beach, T. W. Beach, T. D. Powell.<br>
<br>
"The following officers were then chosen: President, S. H. Herin;<br>
vice president, W. A. Berry; recording and corresponding secretary, T. D. Powell; financial secretary and treasurer, Marshall Fell Jr.; sergeant- at-arms, S. H. Condon; board of directors, W. A. Berry, E. L. Gruener and D. A. Maulsby.<br>
<br>
The name adopted for the organization is the 'Tacoma Typographical Union.' Application will at once be made for a charter from the
International Typographical Union, at Washington, D. C., and the local union will meet at the call of the directors."<br>
<br>
Randolph Radebaugh, "Founding of the typographical union," <B>The Tacoma News Tribune.</B> September 9, 1922. Number twenty-one in a series.<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
