<h1>Wilkeson Strike of 1919</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
WILKESON STRIKE OF 1919.<br>
<br>
Nancy Irene Hall, "The Wilkeson Strike of 1919," <B>Carbon River Coal Country.<br>
</B><br>
The miners at Wilkeson joined the ranks and the mines shut down on October 31, 1919.  The men wanted a 14% raise in wage and other working conditions changed.  In December, the mines were still shut down.  Two of the main operators in the Carbon River area threated to open the mines on an open-shop basis.<br>
<br>
Besides the strike, on October the 28, 1919, state wide enforcement of the 'bone-dry law' went into effect.  It was up to the Department of Internal Revenue to see that the law was carried out.  Immediately they descended upon Wilkeson and arrested two local men and hauled them off to jail with a stiff fine and the threat of imprisonment.<br>
<br>
Such were the conditions the men coming home from the war faced, when they arrived home to Wilkeson.  It was a changed place, and it would never be the same from that day on. The 'boom' was over.<br>
<br>
<br>&#169; Copyright The Tacoma Public Library, 1996 -- All Rights Reserved<br><hr>
