<body>
<img src="../unset.gif" align=middle>Tacoma Public Library - NorthWest Reference Databases
 - <B>Unsettling Events</B><br>
<h1>Wilkeson Strike of 1921</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
Nancy Irene Hall, "The Wilkeson Miners Strike of 1921," <B>Carbon River Coal Country.<br>
<br>
</B><br>
The men had gone back to mining and managed to reach an agreement with the mine owners.  Suddenly the mine companies notified the men, that they were going to roll back the price of coal and the wages of the men to the rate which was in effect before the strike of October 31, 1919, The contract the men were working under was not due to expire until 1922.  When the news came the miner's Union became enraged.<br>
<br>
On March 15th, in 1921, the cut in wages and prices went into effect.  The cuts ran: skilled coal digger's cut from $10.00 per day down to $8.50, semi-skilled coal-diggers from $8.25 to $5.29, common underground labor from $7.55 to $5.20 and common above ground labor from $7.00 to $4.65.<br>
<br>
The miners struck.  On March 31st, the miners walked out on strike.  The Companies gave the men a deadline.  If they did not go back to work they were to leave the Company owned homes.  The Union officials stood firm and the men were not even allowed to vote, to see if the majority of the miners would accept the new rates.  This was a period of tremendous strife.  The Union men were forced to leave the Company owned homes.  Some went to South Prairie and Union Hill was established.<br>
<br>
The miners put up tents on the hill and tried to wait out the strike.  They were sure an agreement would be reached and soon they could return to Wilkeson and the mines.  Others left the area, as they could not afford to wait out the strike.<br>
<br>
The Companies retaliated against the striking miners, and they opened the mines under the open-shop method.  They brought other men into the 'Up-town' section and reopened the mines.  Ad's were put in all the local newspapers soliciting men to come to work at the mines, under the new rates.<br>
<br>
The people, who lived 'Down-town' were luckier in some respects.  They owned or rented their homes and the Company could only take their jobs away and not their very homes in which they lived.  "Up-town' and 'Down-town' became hated enemies.  Each day at a certain time of the day all the people from 'Down-town' would walk to the mine areas and curse the new miners, who were at work.  The Company stood pat and so did the miner's Union.  There was not a chance of reaching                                          any agreement.<br>
<br>
The strike lasted, almost two and one-half years. The men were starved out.  They lost their Union.<br>

<br>&#169; Copyright The Tacoma Public Library, 1996 -- All Rights Reserved<br><hr>
