<h1>Tacoma Narrows Bridge</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
<B>PART ONE-SUICIDES FROM THE TACOMA NARROWS BRIDGE.</B><br>
<br>
(Files checked  include Tacoma. Suicide.<br>
Tacoma. Bridges. Narrows 1953-1965.)<br>
Tacoma. Bridges. Narrows.1980-    .<br>
1952  March 14.<br>
<br>
<B>GADBAW, WILLIAM J.</B>  (First on Tacoma News Tribune list).<br>
<br>
William J. Gadbaw, 36, of Olympia was believed to have leaped from the bridge. His car was found abandoned on the span about 2:00 p.m., Tuesday. Oldtimers in the city recalling that the bodies of very few persons who have been lost in the cold waters of the Narrows have ever been found expressed doubt that further search would be of value.<br>
<br>
If Gadbaw leaped from the span, his is the first known suicide on the bridge since it was opened October, 1950. The bridge floor is 213 feet from the water at the spot where Gadbaw is believed to have jumped. (Tacoma News Tribune March 14, 1952).<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
1953 JUNE 18<br>
<br>
<B>BARKER, CECIL</B>  (Fifth  on the Tacoma News Tribune list.)<br>
<br>
Cecil Barker, 49, formerly of Tacoma and in recent years an automobile dealer in Olympia started east over the Narrows Bridge at 3:00 p.m. Wednesday, stopped his new car in the center, got out and climbed over the south railing, hung by one hand for a brief moment and then plummeted 187 feet to the cold water and his death.<br>
<br>
The body was found floating one hundred fifty feet south of the center span. The body was buoyed by air pockets in the shirt and slacks he had on. (Tacoma News Tribune June 18, 1953).<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
1953 JULY 30<br>
<br>
<B>NICHOLS, ROBERT G</B>   (Sixth on the Tacoma News Tribune List).<br>
<br>
<B><br>
</B>Robert G. Nichols a 33 year old Bremerton War veteran died in the
<br>
Pierce County hospital three days after he was found semi-
conscious after a one hundred fifty foot leap off the Tacoma Narrows Bridge.  The county coroner's office has listed the death as a suicide bringing to six the number of suicides off the bridge. He died from multiple fractures and a punctured lung. When first found on the beach at the west end of the span he said he was unable to provide a good home for his wife. (Tacoma News Tribune July 30, 1953).<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
1954  October 22<br>
<br>
<B>STEVENS, GERTRUDE L</B>   (Eighth  on the Tacoma News Tribune List).<br>
<br>
The swirling waters of the Tacoma Narrows claimed another victim Friday when a woman identified as Mrs. Gertrude L. Stevens leaped to her death from the center of the bridge.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Stevens left her coat on the bridge railing and her  purse on the sidewalk. In the purse she left a note to her family in explanation of her action.  Mrs. Stevens is the eighth person who has leaped from the span since its completion. (Tacoma News Tribune October 22, 1954).<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
1956  June 16<br>
<br>
<B>MEYERS, DORIS L</B><br>
<br>
A 37 year old woman plunged to her death from the Tacoma Narrows Bridge about 3:00 p.m. yesterday. Three witnesses told police they were dirving toward Tacoma when they noticed a parked unattended car near the west pier of the bridge. Then they said they saw Mrs. Myers standing on the south bridge rail, hanging on to the supporting cables.  She pushed herself away from the cables and fell two hundred feet below to the water as she was approached.  The body was picked up at Point Evans. (Tacoma News Tribune June 16, 1956).<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
1956  November 10<br>
<br>
<B>STARNES, CHARLES C</B><br>
<br>
"NP wire chief dies in leap from Span," <B>Tacoma News Tribune.</B> November 10, 1956<br>
<br>
Ignoring the plea "For God's sake, man, don't jump," the wire
chief for the Northern Pacific Railway yesterday plunged to his death from the west end of the Narrows Bridge.<br>
<br>
Charles C. Starnes, 68, of 3606 South Thompson Avenue, apparently was killed instantly when he struck the base of a concrete pier 200 feet below the Gig Harbor end of the span.<br>
<br>
Starnes, employed by Northern Pacific for fifty years, had been on a leave of absence since September 4, because of illness.<br>
<br>
Sgt. Mark Hamilton, Washington Toll Bridge Authority, tried to talk Starnes out of leaping after he saw the veteran railroad employe leave his automobile on the bridge and walk to the railing.<br>
<br>
"He acted as if he didn't hear a word I said," Hamilton told investigating officers.<br>
<br>
A note to Starnes' wife, Helen, was found in the car. In it Starnes said he "couldn't stand" his illness any longer. There was a list of persons to be notified of his death and a quit claim deed turning his property over to Mrs. Starnes, dated November 1.<br>
<br>
Starnes left his overcoat and wrist watch on the car seat.<br>
<br>
A Coast Guard vessel took Starnes' body form the pier following an on the scene investigation by Dick McCreadie, Jim Phill and Tom Dunlapa, all of the Pierce County Sheriff's Department.<br>
<br>
Starnes went to work for the firm October 15, 1906, as an apprentice telegrpaher. Except for brief periods at outside jobs, he had been with the railroad continuously as a telegrapher or agent in the Tacoma area.<br>
<br>
In 1944 he was promoted to assistant wire chief for the Tacoma division of the telegrpah office. And in 1948 he became wire chief.<br>
<br>
Starnes was on the board of directoes of Northern Pacific Hospital. He was a member of Royal A. Gove Lodge, F & A M, and the Holy Communion Church, and he was past worthy patron of White Clover Chapter, OES.<br>
<br>
Mr. Starnes was a native of Lincolnton, North Carolina. Besides his wife, he is survived by a son, C.M. Starnes of grants Pass, Oregon, and a daughter, Mrs. Don Sherrod of Portland.<br>
<br>
("NP Wire Chief dies in leap from span," <B>Tacoma News Tribune.</B> November 10, 1956.).<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
1961 JUNE 26
<B>MCGOWAN, EDWARD A</B>   (13th on the Tacoma News Tribune list).<B><br>
<br>
</B>Instantly killed in a jump from the Narrows Bridge today the 13th jump victim since the birdge was built was recovered in less than thirty minutes by two men in a small boat about two miles north of the bridge.Tentatively identified as Edward A. McGowan, a worker at Carling Brewery the man passed the bridge toll plaza in his car about 10:25 this morning and headed westbound for the peninsula. Near the easternmost tower the occupant of the car (Mr. McGowan) jumped out and dived over the railing to the water about 185 feet below.<br>
<br>
The death was the first suicide leap in twenty months. The last once occurred October 8, 1959 and claimed the life of Mrs. Eugene Dixon of Tacoma. (Tacoma News Tribune June 26, 1961.).<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
--------------------------------------------------------------<br>
1962 JANUARY 27<br>
<br>
<B>REAPE, MARGARET</B>  (14th on the Tacoma News Tribune list).<br>
<br>
A 47 year old women plunged to her death from the Narrows Bridge yesterday afternoon. He body was recovered from the water near Point Evans by men from the Narrows Marina.  The woman leaped unseen from the bridge shortly after 2:00 p.m. January 26, 19162. The coroner said her car was left on the bridge but no note was found. She died from a broken neck and internal injuries.<br>
<br>
A passing motorist who noticed the automobile about three hundred feet west of the east pier informed bridge authorities. (Tacoma News Tribune January 27, 1962).<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
1963 JUNE 23<br>
<br>
TAYLOR, MICHAEL D.<br>
<br>
The county coroner's office today identified Michael D. Taylor, 30, of 1651 South 35th Street as the man who died after jumping from the bridge Wednesday. Taylor was still alive when passing boaters pulled him out of the water, but he died before reaching shore. (Tacoma News Tribune June 23, 1963).<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
1966 AUGUST 17<br>
<br>
<B>BACKER, ELWIN.</B>     (Number 17 on the Tacoma News Tribune list) 
("NP Official dies in leap into Narrows," <B>Tacoma News Tribune.</B> August 17, 1966.).<br>
<br>
A sixty-six year old Tacoma railroad official plunged to his death Wednesday morning from the Narrows Bridge.<br>
<br>
The apparent suicide victim was identified as Elwin Backer, of 1212 North K Street, district claims agent for the Northern Pacific Railway.<br>
<br>
His body was recovered from the Narrows just north of the bridge a short time later.<br>
<br>
There were at least two eye-witnesses to the jump<br>
<br>
Bill Kepler, a Tacoma auto salesman who lives in Bremerton said he was crossing the bridge at 8:20 a.m. when he saw a car stop and a well dressed man get out and head for the railing.<br>
<br>
"I hollered at him: "Stop! Don't do it, Think it over!" Kepler said. "He had one foot up on the railing, looked back at me for a moment then just kept going. He went over head first.<br>
<br>
"He had kind of a wild look in his eye."<br>
<br>
Another motorist  C.A. Peterson of 1306 Mountain View Avenue, watched Backer jump and then called authorities from one of the newly installed emergency telephones on the bridge.<br>
<br>
The Coast Guard was alterted but the body was recovered by Ervin Runolfson of the Sixth Avneue Boathouse, using a small boat. He took the body to the boathouse for inspection by Cornor Larry Amundson. The body was naken to the Gaffney Funeral Home.<br>
<br>
No note was found in the Backer car, which was driven off the bridge by Officer Glen Alexander, police said. Then wife, Mrs. Elizabeth Backer, an employe in the office of the Tacoma Public Schools, said her husband had been morose and apparently on the verge of a nervous collapse but that he had not indicated that he contemplated suicide.<br>
<br>
The leap was the 17th known Narrows Bridge suicide and the first in more than two years.<br>
<br>
("NP Official dies in leap into Narrows." <B>Tacoma News Tribune.</B> August 17, 1966.).<br>
---------------------------------------------------------<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
1967 FEBRUARY 20<br>
<br>
<B>LARSEN, JUDITH </B>   (Number 18 on the Tacoma News Tribune list)<B><br>

</B>The mother of five small children ended her life early Sunday in a leap from the Tacoma Narrows Bridge. Killed in the 200 foot plunge was Judith Larsen. Her body was recovered by the Coast Guard shortly before noon on Sunday after a fisherman found it floating near Point Evans. Mrs. Larsen's empty car, its lights burning and motor running was found parked on the bridge about a block west of the east tower.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Larsen was the 18th person known to have jumped from the second Tacoma Narrows Bridge since it opened in October 1950.<br>
(Tacoma News Tribune February 20, 1967).<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
1968. JANUARY 13<br>
<br>
<B>MITCHELL, THYRA B.</B> 1968.   ( Tacoma News Tribune LIST NUMBER 19).<br>
<br>
"Woman used ladder in death leap," <B>Tacoma News Tribune.</B> January 13, 1968.<br>
<br>
A fifty one year old Belfair woman leaped to her death from the<br>
Narrows Bridge Friday afternoon.<br>
<br>
She was identified by Pierce County Coroner Larry Amundsen as Mrs. Thyra B. Mitchell, of 170 South Shore Raod, Belfair.<br>
<br>
Amundsen ruled the death a suicide.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Mitchell carried a six foot stepladder onto the bridge about 12:30 on Friday afternoon. She apparently placed the ladder on the walkway on the north side of the bridge's east tower, climbed the ladder and jumped over the rail.<br>
<br>
She landed on the concrete tower pier 210 feet below the walkway.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Mitchell's car was found parked near the east end of the bridge. Her wallet and other personal effects were found in the car by Tacoma Police officers.<br>
<br>
Amundsen said Mrs. Mitchell had left a note for her husband, Neal Mitchell. Amundsen said the woman had been in ill heath for some time.<br>
<br>
The body was taken from the pier by men from the Tacoma Coast Guard cutter <B>Point Glass</B>. The death is the 19th suicide from the bridge.<br>
<br>
She was a native of South Prairie and lived in this area all her life. She was a member of the Westminster Club of Seattle, Seattle Fine Arts Club, past president of the Toastmistresses Club, Chapter of Seattle, Camp Fire Girls Board of Directors of
Seattle, and the Presbyterian Church.<br>
<br>
Survivors include her husband, Neal M.; two brothers, Lawrence and Kenneth G. Brown and Puyallup and several nieces and nephews.<br>
<br>
Services were announced by Powers, Wrigley Clements Funeral Home, Puyallup.<br>
<br>
("Woman used ladder in death leap," <B>Tacoma News Tribune.</B> Jan 13, 1968.).<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
1975 APRIL 23<br>
<br>
<B>UNIDENTIFIED WOMAN</B>  (32nd in the Tacoma News Tribune lst.).<br>
<br>
<B><br>
</B>An unidentified woman leaped form the Narrows Bridge this morning. Her body was recovered ninety minutes later by a Tacoma Fire Department scuba crew from the tide swept waters near Point Defiance.  Horrified motorists told sheriff's deputies they saw her park her 1967 Mercury sedan near the center of the bridge about 6:40 a.m. and "run across the road and leap over the rail."  The car was reportedly registered to a Tacoma address but there was no identification on the body. She is the 32nd victim of the bridge. (Tacoma News Tribune April 23, 1976.).<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
1974 JULY 10<br>
<br>
<B>STEWART, ERICKA ROSE VIOLA<br>
<br>
</B><br>
The body of a women who jumped to her death from the Narrows Bridge on Monday has been identified as Ericka Rose Viola Stewart of Tacoma.  The woman, a former Western State Hospital, patient committed suicide. Her body was found sprawled on the concrete base supporting one of the bridge towers by police who said she carried no identification.<br>
<br>
Her abandoned car was found on Fairview Drive, a short distance from the bridge. (Tacoma News Tribune July 10, 1974).<br>
<br>
