-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<B>KENNEDY, DAVID.</B>   1986 DECEMBER 10.<br>
<br>
("Gig Harbor man, 21, found dead under bridge," <B>Peninsula Gateway</B> December 10, 1986.).<br>
<br>
The body of a twenty-year old Gig Harbor man was discovered on the north side of the west pier of the Tacoma Narrows Bridge by a passing fisherman about noon Monday.<br>
<br>
David Kenney, 21, of Gig Harbor, apparently jumped off the bridge sometime Monday morning, according to police reports. A Sheriff's Department official said Kennedy was "despondent over a female."<br>
<br>
Pierce County Sheriff's District 13 office at noon recieved a call concerning the body and dispatched an officer to the bridge.  Sgt. Bill Seewer said a vehicle registered to Kennedy was found parked near an underpass at the west end of the bridge.<br>
<br>
Kennedy's body was recovered by the Sheriff's Department marine unit from Day Island. A Tacoma fire boat also responded to transport the man's body to the Day Island marina, where a coroner was waiting.<br>

Traffic in the Tacoma bound lanes of State Route 16 was delayed slightly during the noon hour as police responded to the bridge. However, authorities said use of the Tacoma fire boat helped prevent major traffic problems which often occur when police or medical personnel must respond to an incident on the bridge.<br>
<br>
("Gig Harbor man, 21, found dead under bridge," <B>Peninsula Gateway,</B> December 10, 1986.).<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
1988 February 07<br>
<br>
MYGATT, DAVID H<br>
<br>
An air and water search Saturday failed to locate the body of a 21 year old man who jumped from the Narrows Bridge "for sport" and failed to meet up with friends on the shore. The Fort Lewis corporal reportedly jumped from the 200 foot high center span at 3:00 a.m. on Friday. The search was concentrated in the waters off Fox Island where a fisherman reported spotting a floating body Friday afternoon off Point Gibson. (Tacoma News Tribune February 7, 1988).<br>
<br>
A body believed to be a Fort Lewis man who jumped off the Narrows Bridge "for sport" was recovered Sunday off Alki Point in Seattle, about twenty miles away, authorities said.<br>
<br>
The man's identify was witheld pending final identification, said Paige Olson of the King County Medical Examiner's Office. However, other authorities previously identified him as David H. Mygatt, who was assigned to the 2nd Battalion, 47th Infantry.<br>
<br>
Cpl. Christopher W. Raabe, 21, who accompanied Mygatt to the bridge told authorities he and Mygatt had planned to leap from the 200 foot high center span of the bridge in the middle of the night and swim to shore. Mygatt jumped but Raabe changed his mind. (Tacoma News Tribune February 8, 1988 p. B-2).<br>
<br>
