++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
1990  July 11<br>
<br>
<B>UNIDENTIFIED MAN<br>
<br>
</B>An unidentified man ended his life by leaping from the Tacoma Narrows Bridge at about 5:00 p.m. on Sunday according to Pierce County deputies. The body was not recovered. The man was thin, about six feet tall, wearing blue jeans and no shirt.  Some people in a sailboat beneath the bridge heard the body hit, but said it sank. The man is said to have jmped from the north side of the west bound lanes. (Gateway. July ll, 1990).<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
1991  April 13<br>
<br>
GABRIEL, VANCE<br>
<br>
Bruce Rushton, "Broken elevator thwarts rescue of bridge jumper," <B>Tacoma News Tribune.</B> April 14, 1991.<br>
<br>
While would-be rescuers tried to get a broken elevator on the Narrows Bridge to work a twenty-six year old Tacoma man spent nearly three hours atop the bridge's eastern tower before jumping to his death Saturday afternoon.<br>
<br>
Tacoma firefighters and state troopers climbed the tower to reach the man but he jumped shortly before 2:00 p.m. when the first would-be rescuer reached the top of the tower said a dispatcher with the Tacoma Fire Department.<br>
<br>
A nearby boater pulled the body from the Narrows Tacoma police said. The Pierce County Medical Examiner's Office identified the dead man as Vanc Gabriel.<br>
<br>
During most of his time on the tower, Gabriel was lying down and could not be seen from the ground. At times, he stood up and looked over the tower's railing at the traffic below.<br>
<br>
Authorities at the bridge said he apparently reached the tower's top by climbing a diagonal support that links the bridge deck with the top of the tower.<br>
<br>
The rescue attempt was delayed while firefighters and Tacoma Police tried unsuccessfully to use an elevator to reach the top of the tower.<br>
<br>
The elevator had been broken for a week said Dennis Ulmer, bridge maintenance supervisor with the Department of Transportation.<br>
<br>
He said he hopes to have the elevator fixed within a week when a
custom made part is expected to be ready.<br>
<br>
The State Patrol did not close the bridge during the drama, but traffic was delayed at times as motorists slowed to watch rescuers on the bridge deck.<br>
<br>
(Bruce Rushton, " Broken elevator thwarts rescue of bridge jumper," <B>Tacoma News Tribune.</B> April 14, 1991. p. B-1.).<br>
<br>
(Obituary of Vance Guy Gabriel, <B>Tacoma News Tribune.</B> April 15, 1991. B-4.).<br>
<br>
Vance Guy Gabriel, 26, died April 13, 1991. Vance was born January 9, 1965. He was the beloved son of Bill and Thelma Gabriel. Vance was born in Tacoma and lived here all of his life. He was a graduate of Foss High School and Central Washington University.<br>
<br>
He is survived by his mother and father; brothers, Bill and wife, Jean Gabriel of Cerritos, California and Kelly Gabriel of San Francisco. aunts, uncles, and many cousins. Vance was preceded in death by his brother, Leonard Gabriel.<br>
<br>
(Obituary of Vance Guy Gabriel, <B>Tacoma News Tribune.</B> April 15, 1991. B-4).<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
AUGUST 7, 1991.<br>
<br>
DAVID FOSTER.<br>
<br>
A 32 year old Gig Harbor man who leapt to his death from the Tacoma Narrows Bridge was identified Thursday as David Foster.<br>
Tacoma police did not know why Foster jumped from the bridge about 2:30 p.m. Wednesday. According to a police report, a motorist saw the man climb over the rail of the bridge, "throw up his hands and disappear."<br>
<br>
A short time later the man's body was discovered floating face down about a quarter of a mile from Titlow Bach. The police said they found a can of chewing tobacco and a package of gum in his pants, but no suicide note.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
EATON, DENNIS.<br>
<br>
Anthony K. Albert, "Tacoma Narrows Bridge reopened following
man's suicide jump," <B>The Tacoma News Tribune.</B> January 7, 1997.<br>
<br>
A man died Monday morning after jumping from a five hundred foot high tower on the Tacoma Narrows Bridge.<br>
<br>
But Dennis Eaton never hit the chilly waters of Puget Sound. A stiff, cold breeze blew the 36 year old Bonney Lake man back over the bridge. He landed on the roadway 300 feet below the top of the west tower Tacoma police said.<br>
<br>
The Pierce County medical examiner's office will perform an autopsy today on Eaton, medical investigator Bob Bishop said. The Tacoma police are investigating the incident said Sergeant Mike Taylor.<br>
<br>
A motorist called 911 operators shortly before 9:00 a.m. to report seeing a man walking up the catwalk toward the tower.<br>
<br>
Tacoma police and the Washington State Patrol troopers shut down the entire bridge at 9:00 a.m. Eaton was on the south side of the tower facing Steilacoom when he jumped at about 9:15 a.m.<br>
<br>
"We didn't get an opportunity to negotiate with him," Taylor said.<br>
<br>
The officer watched Eaton fall back through the cables onto the roadway less than twenty feet from where Taylor was standing.<br>
<br>
The strong winds carried one of Eaton's shoes about 2,000 feet north of the bridge before it landed in the water.<br>
<br>
Shortly after Eaton jumped troopers opened one eastbound lane, allowing traffic to trickle over the bridge toward Tacoma. Blankets covered Eaton's body; emergency vehicles shielded it from curious passers by.<br>
<br>
All four lanes were reopened by 10:30 a.m.<br>
<br>
Anthony K. Albert, "Tacoma Narrows Bridge reopened following man's suicide jump," <B>The Tacoma News Tribune.</B> January 7, 1997.<br>
<br>
