-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
TWO SCORE KILLED IN STREET CAR WRECK<br>
<br>
("Two score killed in street car wreck, frightful plunge over a high bridge sends a happy Fourth of July crowd into eternity and saddens many homes," <B>Tacoma Daily Ledger.</B> July 5, 1900.).<br>
<br>
Nearly a hundred persons, passengers on a car bound for this city were plunged down a gulch at 26th and C streets shortly after 8:00 o'clock yesterday morning. Those who were standing on the platforms dropped off only to be crushed and wounded by the heavy body of the coach while others inside were killed or maimed before they knew what had happened.<br>
<br>
The car jumped the track and was smashed into kindling wood in the bottom of the chasm over a hundred feet below. The dead will number more than two score, for there are many of the injured who will never recover and who are expected to die at any moment and there are at least sixty of the passengers of the car now in the various hospitals or under the care of their own physicians.<br>
<br>
Death Interfered<br>
<br>
It was one of the most appalling accidents that has ever occurred in the Northwest, and it came at a time when people, residents of the nearby towns, South Tacoma, Lake View, Parkland, Hullhurst, Lake Park and other places, coming to Tacoma full of joy and patriotism to spend the Fourth of July.<br>
<br>
Their journey was nearly at an end when death interfered, and claimed them as his own in a most frightful manner. He gave no quarter. Neither man, woman nor child was spared.<br>
<br>
Crushed and mangled the unfortunates were dragged from beneath the wreck of the car and tender hands ministered to them until
conveyances could be had to carry them to hospitals and to the homes of their friends. The dead were laid on the gras, but there were few in the crowds of spectators and rescuers who gathered at the scene at that time who knew who were dead and living.<br>
<br>
Such a spectacle of battered mutilated humanity has scarcely ever been seen. A former member of the First Washington Volunteers, who has played a part in many battlefields in the Philippines said he never witnessed such a sight before.<br>
<br>
Spectacle of carnage.<br>
<br>
It was a spectacle of carnage such as is scarcely ever observed in war for car wheels and trucks and heavy timbers make more horrible wounds that bullets and shells. And the agonizing cries of the wounded and the ding as they lay on one side of the gulch and in the bottom or where held down under the heavy timbers that once formed a part of the wrecked car, could be heard for blocks away.<br>
<br>
There was help at hand a few moments after the accident occurred. Citizens, post men firemen, guardsmen, ex-volunteer and women and children aided. The sides of the gulch are steep in fact so steep that a goat would scarcely be able to descend them, but the cries of the wounded made men forget for they plunged downward without regard to their own safety.<br>
<br>
Ropes were quickly procured and the victims of the wreck were drawn carefully to the top of the gulch and their wounds attended to as fast as it was possible for the physicians to work. Every doctor in the city was called on for his advise. The Fanny Paddock and St. Joseph's hospitals were soon crowded with patients who but a few moments before wee in the enjoyment of their health.<br>
<br>
Hacks, express wagons, and all sorts of conveyances were pressed into service, but there was another vehicle that was in use too. It was the wagon of the dead. It came to take away the last evidence of the destruction caused by the wreck. It made journey after journey and it was always full. Boys and girls, and men and women were its freight. The morgues of the various undertaking rooms were scarcely large enough to hold all.<br>
<br>
Searching for Friends.<br>
<br>
And then when the dead had been sorted from the living, and the last one had been removed from the wreck, excited men and women and children besieged the morgues searching for missing friends. Some wee successful in their sad quest, and others who wee not successful turned away with every evidence of joy on their faces.<br>
<br>
Thousands of people visited the bridge where they accident occurred during the day. They watched the men at work clearing
away the debris of the car, and looked curiously at the red stains ont he grass and the tattered pieces of clothing that hung from the bushes.<br>
<br>
They glanced too, at two women who wandered about all day, one with a babe in her arms, and the other leading a small boy by the hand. The charges of these women were foundlings of the wreck. Nobody had come to claim them.<br>
<br>
Perhaps their mother and their father as well were dead. But they have found friends, and if nobody asks for them, their foster mothers will probably see that they do not want. Then there is a little girl of four and a girl babe at the Fanny Paddock Hospital. They seemed to e deserted but it is probably that some relatives will look after them.<br>
<br>
The Fated Car<br>
<br>
The car, which carried its human freight into the deep ravine instead of to the city was No. 116. It left South Tacoma at 8 o'clock in charge of F.L. Boehm, motorman, and J. D. Calhoun, conductor. The car which is one of the big box-like affairs was crowded to the doors and every inch of space on the platforms was taken. Men hung on to the railings and were glad to be able to get a ride to the city, for like those inside they were anxious to arrive early so as not to miss any of the independence day exercises.<br>
<br>
The car ran merrily along, the passengers chatting with each other, for they were nearly all acquainted and everything was pleasant until it reach the apex of the hill just beyond Tacoma Avenue. From this point the stories differ. One is that the motorman, after starting down the hill, turned on his current instead of shutting it off and when the car had gained such a momentum as to threaten to get away from him he turned off the current, but it was then too late, for the car was going at lightning speed and there was nothing to bring it to a standstill for the incline is steep.<br>
<br>
Passengers on the front platform, who saw the sharp curve on the bridge as it leaves Delinn Street, endeavored to jump. Several of them succeeded in reaching the ground in safety, but others were as badly injured as they might have been had they remained on the car to the bottom of the chasm.<br>
<br>
Another story is that the motorman lost control of the car when it left the hill and was unable to bring it under control again.But whatever the story the car went over the bridge and there is sorrow in over one hundred families in this city and in the neighboring towns.<br>
<br>
The curve which leads to the bridge comes from the southwest. Besides being partly on a hill it is very sharp as it touches the bridge.  On either side of the tracks on the bridge are guards a
foot high which were placed in position for the purpose of preventing a car from jumping off the bridge. These guards are of heavy timber topped with railroad iron.<br>
<br>
The guard on the right side of the track looking north was not even marked after the wreck yesterday. The can had evidently jumped over it. A  young man who was thrown from the front platform just before the bridge was reached said he believe that the rapidity of the descent of the coach caused it to leap over this obstruction and plunge over the side of the bridge.<br>
<br>
Another spectator said he believed that the car struck the guard and toppled over but there are no marks on the guard to show that it came in contact with anything. Then there are deep ridges worn in the wooden ties on the other side of the guard which plainly show that the car wheels passed over them.<br>
<br>
It is possible and probably that the can did turn over in its descent. Nearly all those who were killed were injured about the head and all the occupants of the coach must have been jammed in one mass at the bottom of the car when it struck the bottom of the gulch, and only released when it feel to pieces.<br>
<br>
Horrifying Spectacle.<br>
<br>
The scene five minutes after the accident occurred was one that would make the stoutest heart break down. Strewn from the bridge for a distance of about one hundred yards up the hill toward Tacoma Avenue were a score of people, writhing in agony, while in the gulch lay the wreck of a car, its framework scattered on the sides of the declivity and dead and dying and wounded lying all about.<br>
<br>
The shrieks of the injured were heartrending. the beautiful green of the grass was stained here and there a deep crimson the life blood of the passengers on the doomed car.<br>
<br>
The crash of the car as it plunged from the bridge to the bottom of the gulch over one hundred feet below could be heard for several blocks. Thee was a creaking of timbers and a rasping of wheelers and then a terrible thud as the car struck the bottom.<br>
<br>
Residents of the vicinity rushed to the scene from every direction and soon willing hands were at work on the steep sides of the gulch endeavoring to rescue the wounded. the car had been smashed into pieces and those who escaped were indeed fortunate.  For a half an hour after the accident occurred a diligent search was made for any person who had escaped without injury but none could be found. It is very probably that every one in the car was more or less injured.<br>
<br>
Help at Hand<br>
<br>
The first comers on the scene were so paralyzed by the scene that
for a time they were helpless. Then somebody turned in a call for an ambulance. When the ambulance arrived, those in charge of it quickly took in the situation and a call was sent to the fire department for help.<br>
<br>
Several engines and a hook and ladder truck responded and the fireman ran down the sides of the gulch recklessly and aided those who were there before them to draw out the injured and dead from under the wreckage.<br>
<br>
Torn and bruised men, women and children were carried to the street above. Some died as they were being placed in hacks to take them to the hospital. Others pleaded for their fathers or mothers or for their children. The sward was red with their blood.<br>
<br>
Little girls who a few moments before had been all decked out in their finery, little boys, their brothers in many cases, lay dead on the grass. Men and women with wide open, staring eyes lay with faces upturned, never to breathe again while horrible gashes on their persons told how they had come to their end.<br>
<br>
Tearful Parents.<br>
<br>
Here a mother, pale and tearful, cried for her children as kind hands endeavored to place her in a cab; there a child sat dazed and moaning and all about lay the dead.<br>
<br>
W.A. Wering stood with a happy smile on his blood stained face, holding in his arms his almost infant daughter, while two other daughters stood beside him. The girls had been in the wreck, and had escaped with some wounds, but none of a serious character. Mr. Wering praised God fervently for his children's fortunate escape.<br>
<br>
George Bott, proprietor of the Monogram saloon, was injured about the head and lower limbs. He told all he knew of the accident as he lay in the ambulance.   He said that he left his home on the car line at about 8 o'clock and managed to get on the rear platform. The car was crowded. He believed there were more than one hundred on board. They were mostly excursionists coming to Tacoma to view the Fourth of July parade. There were a few workmen and other passengers in the car. Women and children occupied about half the seats.<br>
<br>
Dashed Through the Bridge<br>
<br>
When the car reached Tacoma Avenue it seemed to gain speed. In a short time it was going down the hill with frightful rapidly. The men on the rear platform seemed to realize their danger for several of them dropped off. Then there was a rush to leave the car. Mr. Bott jumped just before it reached the bridge and fell on his side in the road. He lay there until he was helped to the ambulance. He thought at least twenty jumped before he left the
car.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Lee had five children with her on the car. She was badly injured and when she was carried out of the wreck she discovered her son, Lyman. He was also injured. She could not find the others and then her condition was such that she was gently compelled to enter a cab and go to the hospital. She sat on the seat with her boy in her arms.<br>
<br>
Her Children Killed.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Moser of South Tacoma, had three children with her when she entered the car. One, Herman, was saved and the other two were killed. The woman was too crazed with grief to give their names or ages. She was taken to the hospital.<br>
<br>
Joseph Longerman, his daughter, Berdene and his son Roy were all injured.<br>
<br>
("Two score killed in street car wreck, frightful plunge over a high bridge sends a happy Fourth of July crowd into eternity and saddens many homes," <B>Tacoma Daily Ledger.</B> July 5, 1900.).<br>
<br>
LIST OF THE INJURED SWELLS<br>
<br>
("List of the injured swells the total number of victims to over one hundred, thrilling stories of survivors," <B>Tacoma Daily Ledger.</B> July 5, 1900.).<br>
<br>
The girl declined to go until she saw her father and brother in a hack.  Little wounded children, separated from their parents, who were perhaps dead, were tenderly cared for by women and men living int he neighborhood. Many turned their eyes away as the victims were drawn from beneath the timbers of the car which had pinned them to the ground.<br>
<br>
Kind hearted people placed handkerchiefs over the faces of the dead until the undertaker's wagon came down loaded with coffins.  Then when the last body was carried away and the wounded were all being cared for at the hospitals or by physicians elsewhere the work of removing the wreck was begun.<br>
<br>
Passenger Told To Hold On<br>
<br>
The car ws one of the Tacoma Railway and Power Company's cars, leaving South Tacoma t 8:00 a.m. with Motorman F.L. Boehm and Conductor J. D. Calhoun.<br>
<br>
O.G. Brollar, a passenger, was on the front platform and escaped with a broken arm and a dislocated shoulder. He says there were about seventy-five or eighty passengers from Edison, Lake Park, Parkland and Lakeview.  Coming down the hill the car gained speed
rapidly and some passengers proposed to jump but were told to stay on and the speed was slacked a little.<br>
<br>
Then it against suddenly gained frightful headway, apparently being beyond control, and before the frightened passengers had hardly time to realize the situation the car went over the bank with a frightful crash and the victims were buried beneath the wreck.<br>
<br>
Working to Save Life.<br>
<br>
The car lay on the side of the hill, over one hundred feet from the track above and twenty or thirty feet from the bottom. Scores of men worked with an almost super human strength to raise the pieces of wreck and to lift out the bodies of the dead and dying. Boards from the car and pieces of cloth or carpet furnished a few stretchers which were used to carry away the dead and injured.<br>
<br>
The ascent from the bottom to the top of the hill was so steep that men could not climb it without the aid of ropes yet in some manner that the workers could not describe now, they staggered up the include with the bodies of the dead and in some cases with the living in their arms. From the top men rushed down to assist them and the bodies wherever possible were carried to the top and laid out in the tall wet grass.<br>
<br>
On both sides of the road lay the dead in groups. friends too busy then at the work of rescue to look for the dead or attempt identification. Tenderly the faces were covered with clothing and the dead lay there awaiting the coming of the wagons which would carry them to the morgues.<br>
<br>
Morgue at Pumping Station.<br>
<br>
Down in the gulch runs a stream of water, a foot deep in some places and five or six feet in width. About three hundred feet above the bridge is the city pump station. Here and there fallen logs furnished a natural bridge across the small stream and  boards have been laid to furnish other crossings.<br>
<br>
To use the pumping station as a temporary morgue and hospital seemed best. Scores of physicians every one in the city would could be summoned at once were working at the scene of the accident and a corps was sent to the pumping station to take charge.<br>
<br>
Fireman, policemen, and volunteers carried the dead and dying to the temporary morgue. Women, men and children, for the most part, bore up with heroic fortitude or were screaming with the awful pain of internal injuries and broken bones.<br>
<br>
It was a frightful trip to contemplate and a terrible one to endure. Rescuers could not do more but the rough and broken gulch bottom, the lack of supplies it was impossible to furnish more
carrying the victims a hard and difficult task.<br>
<br>
Men tried to be tender as they picked up bruised and maimed. Four lifted carefully at broken and bruised arms, legs, and bodies, careful always to support every part of the body that appeared to be injured, but the journey was one that made comfort impossible.<br>
<br>
The rescuers could not walk on the narrow bridges across the gulch and at every few steps someone was plunging into the icy waters, then struggling up to carry the injured to a resting place. The rescuers forgot the water and overlooked the frail bridges.<br>
<br>
They plunged into the stream, crossing it three and four times to reach the pumping station, or wading its length because the bottom was more level and it seemed merciful to give the injured the benefit, though the rescuers were suffering.<br>
<br>
Up to the pumping station the great engine and pump room was quickly cleared of all furniture and everything that interfered with the physicians. In the office on the floor of the engine room, between the mighty pumps that were forcing water into the city reservoir and stand pipes, in the furnace room, and outside on the bare cold ground the injured were tenderly laid.<br>
<br>
Nurses Give Aid<br>
<br>
Nurses from the Fanny Paddock hospital, priests from nearby Catholic Churches, physicians and volunteers made the injured easy. Wherever possible their injuries were dressed or the injured were temporarily relieved for the ride to the hospitals. The dangerous cases received more extended attention, one or two physicians devoting their entire attention to those whom it appeared could only be saved by prompt attention.<br>
<br>
Now and then a victim would throw back his head, a "gurgle" would come from his throat and another victim had been added to the growing list of the dead. Out in the grass near the running stream, almost in the water itself, the row of dead at the temporary morgue were laid.<br>
<br>
Women seemed to predominate here, but there were men in the roy who had passed beyond the aid of the medical staff.<br>
<br>
Taken to Hospitals<br>
<br>
A wagon road comes down the steep grade back of the pumping station. Down this road dashed hose wagons, the city ambulance, patrol wagon, express wagons, and carriages. Into these conveyances the injured were placed for the ride to the hospitals. It was in many instances a case of life or death to get patients where medical treatment could be given and wagons and carriages dashed up the hill with loads heavier than it had
ever been intended by their builders they should carry.<br>
<br>
The city ambulance, constructed for one patient carried three; the patrol wagon carried a man on a stretcher and a volunteer sat on a seat holding a severely injured man on the seat opposite.<br>
<br>
The victims of the disaster rode off quietly. There was little moaning or crying among the injured. Many were still unconscious while others bore the pain with a look of resignation on their faces that indicated they were prepared for any contingency.<br>
<br>
A young girl with a terrible injury drove away with a smile on her face and a small boy only asked to be turned on his face so he could bear the pain of internal injuries more comfortably. A man suggested he could probably ride easier on his side, but did not complain of the legs that hung limp, indicating they were broken at the ankles and the two broken arms hanging by his side.<br>
<br>
Last Body Taken Out<br>
<br>
The last of the injured had been sent to the hospital before 9:00 o'clock, just a few minutes after the rescuers had taken the last body from the wreck. This was the body of G. McMillin who was found well forward and half the car had to be moved before he could be reached.<br>
<br>
Then the removal of the dead began. The bodies were loaded into express wagons, carriages form the morgues and in some cases placed in wooden boxes and laid aside for another load of the express wagons. One express wagon moved to the morgue with nine bodies as its share of the load of death.<br>
<br>
Out of the wreckage came some who could help themselves, but these were few. O.M. Park escaped with only a slight bruise to his leg and a small baby and a four year old by were picked up badly frightened but not severely injured.<br>
<br>
Strange Baby Found<br>
<br>
A baby apparently six or eight months old was found suffering from bruises about the head. It had been discovered lying under a broken seat in the wrecked car. A blow on the head of not much force had shattered the little one's senses and it was picked up tenderly and carried to the top of the hill. The babe was handed to Mrs. Dick, who lives at 2413 1/2 Pacific Avenue.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Dick carried the little one in her arms for a short time and then delivered it to her sister, Mrs. Simmons who lives at the same places. Mrs. Simmons tried to summon a physician but none could be reached. They were all too busy at the hospitals. For a time she tried to care for the babe herself but later she sent it to the Fanny Paddock Hospital. Mrs. Dick accompanying the infant.<br>
<br>
No one knows the name of the little child. During all the time it
remained with the two women it showed no sign of returning consciousness. Only once did it open its eyes and then they were immediately closed again. No means of identification were found.<br>
<br>
Three Year Old Boy Uninjured<br>
<br>
A little three year old boy was rescued. He had miraculously escaped injury and a tailer, whose name was not known to the rescuing party handed the boy a dollar and turned him over to Mrs. E.C. Austin who lives at twenty-sixth and C Streets. Mrs. Austin took the lad home but he could not give his name.<br>
<br>
As nearly as it could be understood he is a Neeman, but his stories of himself differ. The boy is about three years of age, light complexioned, wears a white blouse with a navy blue coat. The coat is lined with red and the lad wore a red tie. His broad-
brimmed straw hat had a red band. His trousers, stockings and shoes were black.<br>
<br>
The boy may belong to one of the injured. Down among the group of injured and dying with a dead girl lying by her side, H. L. Hansen saw a women, looking about in a dazed manner and inquiring for her boy.  He had been seated on her lap at the time of the accident and she stated she heard her son call "Mamma" just as the car took its awful plunge. Then darkness came and when she had revived her boy was gone. The woman was carried away and Mr. Hansen lost track of her.<br>
<br>
Saw the Accident<br>
<br>
A seven year old son of John Deal stood on the banks of the gulch when the car leaped from the bridge. He had been playing near the scene and saw the car coming down the hill. He stood as if petrified while the car came sweeping down the street and followed its flight over the guard rail and into the gulch with staring eyes. The lad tells an interesting story of the disaster.<br>
<br>
He says the motorman was vainly trying to check the speed of the car as it came down the hill. "A man up on top," he explains, was trying to bring the car to a standstill. Then the car reached the fateful curve, men leaped from the platforms or were  hurled into the air to fall into the gulch beneath.<br>
<br>
The lad says the car seemed to give a bound, spring over the twelve inch timber at the side of the track, and after turning over twice struck with a terrific crash at the bottom of the gulch. Shrieks of the victims as the car made the plunge startled him and he sped away from the scene.<br>
<br>
All the eye witnesses claim the car turned over and this is the theory of the street car company. Mrs dick and her husband were standing at their window on Pacific Avenue as the car came down the hill and saw it leap into the gulch. They state the can
turned over before it struck the ground. Then came the cries of the victims and they hurried away to give all the relief possible.<br>
<br>
Had a Narrow Escape<br>
<br>
A passenger who escaped injury by almost a miracle is Frank Halverson, of Parkland. He was thrown from the front platform of the car just before it reached the bridge and was slightly bruised about the face.<br>
<br>
He boarded the car at Edison junction. At that time it was crowded to the doors. The front and rear platforms were crowded and he managed to find a place on the front steps. When the brow of the hill south of the bridge ws reached Halverson says the motorman turned on the current and then seemed to lose control of the car.<br>
<br>
It began to gain speed and several men attempted to jump off. Two men, however, prevented them from doing so and the car swung along at a frightful speed.  When Tacoma avenue was reached the speed ws terrific. As the car passed the water tank Halverson felt it give a sudden jerk and the next instant he was pitched from the car head foremost. He landed on his hands and knees and when he realized what had happened his head was buried in some berry bushes.<br>
<br>
The car continued on its wild journey. Halverson saw a man jump off just before the bridge was reached and strike a log and then roll over. Others followed him from the car.At the bridge the car seemed to pause a moment while those on the front platform dropped to the gulch below and then the front wheels feel on the unfortunates and the car broke in two and followed into the gulch. The other half of it rolled off the bridge almost instantly afterward.<br>
<br>
Halverson shut his eyes when he spoke of the scene of horror  that he saw afterward. He said it caused him to feel faint.<br>
<br>
Motorman did his duty.<br>
<br>
D.H. Seacon, of San Francisco, was on the ill fated car. He had just come up to Tacoma to renew acquaintance with some of the members of the old First Washingtons whom he had known in Manila, where he was a member of Company H. First Montana.<br>
<br>
He had been on a visit to Mrs. G.W. Flemming, and was accompanying her and her children to Tacoma to see the parade. He was on the rear platform and jumped off before the car struck the bridge and escaped unhurt.<br>
<br>
"I heard the motorman try his current three times," he said, "and
then I heard the fuse blow out. The car was running at a frightful rate of speed and I realized that the man at the brake had lost control.  I have heard since the accident that the motorman was drunk, but I do not believe it, and you can say for me that I think he did everything a mortal man could do to stop his car. The fuse blew out and that is all there is to it.<br>
<br>
Heroism of a woman<br>
<br>
"I served six years in the regular army and spent over a y ear in the Philippines, but I never witnessed such a bloody sight as I saw in that gulch after the car went over. I was for several years on the wrecking train on the Southern Pacific in California and in all my experience I never saw a more total wreck. As ssn as I could pull myself together I hurried to the wreck.<br>
<br>
" I suppose I must have been somewhat stunned by the fall I got, as all I remember about it is that I worked as hard as I could pulling men, women, and children from under the debris. As long as I live I will never forget the splendid heroism of a dark little woman who was one of the first on the scene. She worked hard and directed the efforts of the men in the coolest manner imaginable. I would like to learn her name, so that I could tell her what I think of her."<br>
<br>
Mr. Seacon says he is going back to San Francisco today, as his visit has been soiled and he is half sick from the gruesome sights he saw in the gulch.<br>
<br>
Leaped for Life.<br>
<br>
John Wedemeyer, superintendent of the Tacoma cemetery was fortunate enough to escape serious injury. He leaped from the car just before it reached the bridge and although he is painfully injured he is thankful to have escaped so easily. He boarded the car at Edison and secured a place on the front platform near the motorman<br>
<br>
The latter he did not know, although he is a patron of the road. Mr. Wedemeyer said that there had been so many changes in the employees of the road recently that he had grown timid and was always watchful.<br>
<br>
When the car near the bridge yesterday morning  he saw that the motorman had lost control of it and he urged the men on the steps to leap. Two of them followed his advise and then he jumped himself. Before this the conductor rang the bell violently to stop and the motorman endeavored to obey the summons, but was unable to control the car, and it dashed off the bridge while Mr. Wedemeyer lay on the ground.<br>
<br>
Bridge is Closed<br>

After the disaster the bridge was immediately closed to all traffic by Chief of Police William Fackler and special policemen were stationed at each end to enforce the chief's orders. Later in the morning City Attorney W.P. Reynolds made an inspection of the bridge and found one of the bents had been injured. He instructed the chief of police to keep the bridge closed until the city engineer could make an investigation.<br>
<br>
City Engineer Taylor was out of the City yesterday and Owen Wood, the Tacoma Railway and Power Company's engineer, made an inspection of the bridge and track. He declared the structure was safe. Officials of he railway company and officers of the city went over the track and found none of the rails had been injured. The railway company then made application to have the bridge reopened.<br>
<br>
Mayor Louis D. Campbell, Councilman Holgate and General Manager Mitchell of the railway company made an inspection of the bridge yesterday afternoon. The party went direct to the injured portion of the structure and stood on a beam carefully examining the broken support. A voice from above order them away. No attention ws paid and then a rock was hurled dangerously near the party and again a command was given to move.<br>
<br>
Would arrest the Mayor<br>
<br>
Mayor Campbell looked in the direction of the voice and again turned to examine the wreck. Then J. W. Kendall moved out into sight and warned the party if it did not move immediately he would arrest them all and "...he did not care who they were."<br>
<br>
Mayor Campbell ordered Kendall not to interfere and then he cam down. He explained when he learned the identity of the party that Sheriff Mills, on behalf of the coroner, had taken charge of the wreck and placed Kendall and a man named Nellis in charge.<br>
<br>
Two cars were sent across the bridge and it did not appear to show any signs of weakness. the broken support was a part of the old wagon road bridge and had no connection with the street car company's bridge. Arvid Rydstromws sent down to examine the supports and upon his recommendation Mayor Campbell permitted the street car company to use the bridge.<br>
<br>
Coroner in Charge<br>
<br>
Coroner Hoska will remain in control of the bridge and the wreckage until the inquest is held. A coroner's jury will be summoned this morning. The jury will view the bodies and may adjourn until a later day before hearing the testimony of witnesses. The bodies will be delivered to relatives for burial as soon as the jury has seen them.<br>
<br>
The coroner's jury will make a thorough investigation into the accident and attempt to fix the responsibility definitely.  The
coroner is determined to learn the cause of the disaster and it may be some investigation will be made into the safety of the bridge and the track at that point.<br>
<br>
Mayor Louis D. Campbell will called the attention of the council to the accident tonight  and it is probable he will suggest a committee be appointed to make an investigation. The authority of the city is limited. The council may investigate and learn if the speed requirements of the city ordinances were observed and if the tract and bridge are in good and safe condition.<br>
<br>
As soon as City Engineer Taylor returns to the city he will be instructed to make an investigation of the roadbed and the bridge to determine whether the track is safe and cars should be permitted to operate on the line.<br>
<br>
Pathetic Scenes<br>
<br>
The scenes at the hospitals and morgues were pathetic at all times and there were times when it seemed as though the spectators' hearts would break with those of relatives and friends. Mothers swooned at the morgue in front of the bodies of their sons or daughters, wives broke into tears and men wept without restraint as they gazed upon the distorted and mangled features of friends or relatives.<br>
<br>
Children that were left fatherless, parents who were bereft of their children, friends who had waited for acquaintances to come to the city, relatives who were drawn to the morgue by a premonition that evil had befallen those they had dearest, sobbed out their grief that was only expressed by staring eyes, ears that heard not a sound that was made about them,voices that spoke without understanding and a general appearance of numbness that could not be shaken off.<br>
<br>
It was the most pitiful of all griefs, for there is a relief in tears while the harder sorrow cannot be alleviated.<br>
<br>
At the hospitals it was a long wait for tidings from within. The operating room door kept hidden the secret that anxious friends and relatives would know. There were loved ones there whose lives hung by the slender thread that might be snapped at any time.<br>
<br>
Over their beds bent nurses struggling to keep the life blood flowing while outside friends waited with a dull feeling of dread until the silent watchers should give them word. Many were too seriously injured to be seen and it was only occasionally that word of their condition could be had.<br>
<br>
Searching anxiously at the hospitals first, then at the morgues and later at the homes of residents near the scene, where many who had expected friends on the car. they could not find a trace of the ones they sought and their position was even more painful
than those who had found the ones they were seeking. It was a long strain, too, for on a day like yesterday, it was a hard matter to locate another.<br>
<br>
Scene at St. Josephs<br>
<br>
The scene at St. Joseph Hospital as the loads of injured were brought up from the wreck was a pitiable one. Mingled with the moans and groans of the injured were the cries of relatives and friends trying to locate loved ones. Drs. McKone, Case, Libby, Parks and Rummel, with white aprons on and sleeves rolled to the elbow worked hastily by systematically, separating the seriously injured from those who had escaped more fortunately. The severe cases wee hurried to the operating room and the busy attendants carrying the wounded on stretchers formed a seemingly never ending procession.<br>
<br>
As fast as the wounds were dressed the  patients were carried to the wards and then the work of the nurses began. Their work was done silently and well. They brought order out of chaos, stilled the cries of the wounded, and with deft fingers ministered to their wants. A sister visited the different wards and soon had a complete list of the injured giving the name, residence and occupation, when it could be obtained.<br>
<br>
The sister in the children's ward is especially adapted for that work. In a short half hour after the wounds of the children had been dressed she had them in such good humor that several of them wee sitting up in bed propped up by pillows.  In the afternoon thoughtful women brought great bunches of roses, and these were distributed among the children.<br>
<br>
Working at Fannie Paddock<br>
<br>
The scene at the Fannie Paddock hospital, where forty of the wounded were taken was the same as at the other hospital. The attendants took hold the work with trained minds and soon had all the wounded in bed and as comfortable as possible.  Dr. McCutcheon is on Coney Island, but Mrs. McCutcheon took personal charge of affairs and the doctor himself could not have done the work better. She directed the corps of willing assistants in quick sharp commands and then wounded were handled expeditiously and well.<br>
<br>
Late in the afternoon Mrs. McCutcheon received a telegram from the doctor from Coney Island, expressing his horror at the terrible calamity and regretting that he could not be at home to assist.  Dr. H. Allan, surgeon for the Northern Pacific, had charge of the wounded, and he was able assisted in dressing the wounds by Drs. Wagner, Coleman, Armstrong, Shaver, Harrison and Misner.<br>
<br>
Druggist Cole ws of immense assistance to the newspaper men and friends of the patients to call at the hospital. In a remarkably
short time he had a complete list of all the wounded in the hospital with a brief description of their injuries and after the first rush of attending the injured was over, he assisted materially in assigning them to the different wards. The nurses all worked hard and kept at it all night long.<br>
<br>
Cried for her baby<br>
<br>
Mrs. Louis Dinger was the object of much attention from her friends and neighbors as she lay on her cot at the St. Joseph Hospital, almost unconscious from several broken ribs, a sprained ankle and a bruised hip. The dead body of her husband ws taken out of the bloody gulch. Her sister, Miss Effie Roberts lies just across the aisle, suffering from severe injuries.<br>
<br>
When the car went down Mrs. Dinger had her six months old baby on her lap and after the wreck the rescuers found the two bodies far apart. Mrs. Dinger was taken to the St. Joseph Hospital while the baby was taken to the Fannie Paddock as during the hurry of the rescue work there was no means of knowing to whom the baby belonged.<br>
<br>
All yesterday afternoon Mrs. Dinger tossed and moaned on her bed of pain, but her one thought seemed to be of her baby. She called out constantly for it and stretched  out her arms yearningly.  The soft spoken nurses had their hearts touched by the piteous pleading of a mother for her baby and did everything they could to relieve her mind.<br>
<br>
A kind hearted neighbor from Lakeview, where the Dingers live, told the stricken widow that her husband was killed, but she seemed too stunned from her own injuries and her anxiety to clasp her baby in her arms once more to realize the full significance of it. She did not mention the name of her husband once, while she called for her baby a hundred times.<br>
<br>
Mr. Dinger was engineer at the Lake Park rolling mills and left an insurance policy of a thousand dollars. Mrs. Dinger's parents in Oregon were telegraphed for.<br>
<br>
Wanted Firecrackers<br>
<br>
Little Willie Campbell, aged five years, was stunned when he arrived in the Hospital but after the nurses had washed up his bruises and he had a few hours sleep, he could not understand why he should stay in bed longer. He astonished the quiet nurse at the door by bounding out into the hall and wanting to know when he was to have "...the bunch of fire crackers."<br>
<br>
The little fellow knew that he had started out to celebrate the Fourth of July and could see no reason for further delaying it. The wreck of the car and the cries of the wounded and the blood bespattered bodies lying around had passed completely from his youthful mind.
The sister took the little fellow in her lap and answered his many questions with marvelous patience. Presently friends  came and took the little fellow home.<br>
<br>
Richard Sanburg died at the St. Joseph hospital about noon. He was unconscious when brought in, but revived presently and called constantly for Robert Rigney.  It was learned that the man worked for Mr. Rigney at Lkewview and in his partially delirious state he seemed to think that if Mr. Rigney would only come he would be able to do something to relieve his intense suffering.<br>
<br>
He talked almost up to the last breath and his last words were "Send for Robert Rigney." He bore up bravely under what must ha e been intense pain from horrible internal injuries.<br>
<br>
Got the Conductor's Cap.<br>
<br>
J.F. Calahan and seven year old son were on the rear of the car with the conductor who was killed when the car went over. The boy escaped with slight injuries an d in the rush at the St. Joseph's Hospital when carriage after carriage dashed up with its load of maimed and bruised bodies, Mr. Calahan was stored away in the basement. It was not until afternoon that room could be found for him. He lost his hat in the wreck and came to the hospital wearing the cap of the conductor.<br>
<br>
Birdena Lingerman and Tena Schweirow and sister left the St. Joseph hospital during the afternoon and went to the home of friends. A brother of Miss Lingerman was killed in the wreck and her father is badly injured. The wife and mother arrived during the afternoon and sat beside her husband. Although she clasped the body of his dead boy in his arms on the lawn in front of the hospital Mr. Lingerman did not seem to realize the fact as he talked to his wife. His one inquiry was to know "What has happened?"<br>
<br>
Artigis Pistolesi, a young Itanlan had his face crushed to a pulp and he seemed to have suffered terrible internal injuries. He cried like a baby while being carried into the St. Joseph Hospital and his cries could be heard all over the building.<br>
<br>
While the nurse was absent from the room for a moment he fairly writhed from his bed and the blood spouted out of his mouth, making a large dark spot on the carpet. He would have fallen on his face had not the nurse caught him. He lapsed into unconsciousness during the afternoon and it was only when some of his friends arrived that his name could be learned. He called for his mother, speaking Italian. It could not be learned where he lived.<br>
<br>
Eastern Men Hurt.<br>
<br>
John Lyberg, whose home is in Minneapolis, F.T. Startzell, who lives in Washington D.C. and Francis O'Hara, all young machinists
in the car shops were standing together on the rear platform when the car went down. Lyberg was taken to the St. Joseph Hospital and his two friends were taken to the Fanny Paddock. Lyberg said he realized that the car was running away, but that he could not reach the stops to jump off. His first intimation of the real danger, however, came when he saw the bridge looming up before him, and then came the leap through the air and when he woke up he was in the hospital with his head bandaged.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Charles O. Lee and two children, a boy and a girl are at the Fannie Paddock. Mrs. Lee lives in South Tacoma and her husband is a traveling man. She was bringing her five children in to see the parade. None of them sustained serious injuries though all are bruised and cut somewhat.<br>
<br>
Richard, seven years old, was killed outright and Lyman, his twin brother, and his sister are at the Fanny Paddock. Roscoe, another brother, was taken to the St. Joseph but was not hurt much. The baby, a year old, is missing, but is said to be with a family in the Sixth Addition. Mr. Lee was in Medford, Oregon, last night on his way home, and he telephoned his brother, H.M.Lee that he would reach Tacoma tonight.<br>
<br>
Fleming Children Are Found<br>
<br>
The two Fleming children have been found. The little girls, Deil and Berje were missing after the wreck until late last evening when they were found at home, where some of the neighbors had taken them. They are now at the home of their uncle at 733 C Street and are doing nicely. They have several slight bruises, but nothing of a serious nature. They were on the rear platform when the car went over, and none of them fell off the bridge.<br>
<br>
Miss Lizzie Patterson daughter of ex-Councilman Patterson, of South Tacoma and Miss Ethel Withers were together in the car when it went over the bridge. Miss Patterson was uninjured save for a few scratches and the result of shock and was driven home in a carriage. Miss Withers did not escape so fortunately as she is at the Fanny Paddock hospital with several cuts about the head and face.<br>
<br>
A Pathetic Incident.<br>
<br>
One of the most pathetic incidents of the disaster was witnessed at the entrance of St. Joseph Hospital when a carriage was driven up containing J.B. Lingerman of South Tacoma, and his son, aged about sixteen. The father was able to walk when he alighted form the carriage, but the boy was  dead. He had passed away on the way to the hospital but the father did not know it.<br>
<br>
When the dead lad was removed from the carriage and laid out on the green lawn near the entrance the father fell upon him and had to be almost literally torn away from his son so strong was his
embrace of the dead boy.<br>
<br>
Even then he did not realize that the boy was dead and talked in a dazed sort of way about his boy and asked repeatedly whether he did not have his daughter with him. The dead boy is Roy Lingerman. Together with their father, Roy and his sister Burdoena, left South Tacoma on the fated car. The father is seriously injured but will likely recover. He is injured internally and his left eye is badly damaged.<br>
<br>
The young girl left the hospital late in the afternoon. The body of the dead boy together with that of the boy aged about fourteen who ws unknown at the hospital was removed at noon to Mellinger's undertaking rooms.<br>
<br>
At the Morgue<br>
<br>
The scene at the morgue was a pitiful one. Bodies were brought in bruised and managed almost beyond recognition. It seemed as though the doomed passengers had been hurled forward to fall with a terrible force on their heads. Skulls cracked like egg shells and the bruises and cuts about the faces and heads of the victims left little of the original likeness to many.<br>
<br>
Blood stained and crushed the faced presented a most ghastly sight. Clothing was reeking in blood and many of the victims had broken arms and legs in addition to other injuries. All, apparently, were injured internally as well, though as a rule death was undoubtedly caused by bruise on the head.<br>
<br>
One unknown man lies on a slab at Hoska's. His head is bruised and crushed beyond recognition. Half of the skull has been torn away by a fearful force and on the body especially the legs are bruises and cuts that show the victim must have been buried deep in the wreck and to have been struck by a force that crushed life out instantly.  He probably never knew what had occurred.<br>
<br>
May be an iron molder<br>
<br>
The man may be an iron molder. His hands indicate that he worked at some such trade. What is left of his clothing betokens the laboring man, though the clothes he wore are torn to shreds. Fife and York have been suggested as his name, but no one is positive he knows the man. Only a car ticket or two were found in his pockets and the attendants at the morgue were compelled to cover up the form and county him as the  "unknown dead."<br>
<br>
An arm, cut off almost as clean as though it had been done with a surgeon's knife, was picked up by one of the rescuers and placed with one of the bodies which were sent to Hoska's. It was evidently the arm of a young boy, but it belonged to none of the bodies at the undertaking parlors.<br>

A large amount of clothing found near the wrecked car was sent to the undertaking houses. Some of the clothing belonged to those who had been killed but a part was the property of injured persons sent to the hospital. This led to some confusion as friends and relatives called to inquire for loved ones and finding the clothing were led to believe the ones sought were dead.<br>
<br>
Waiting for tidings.<br>
<br>
Almost from the time reports began to come of the accident people gathered in front of the undertaking houses to await returns. The crowd in front of the coroner's office was densest. Men, women and children waited eagerly for the bodies to arrive. Many were drawn by curiosity,but there were scores who had friends on the car and who were anxious to know their fate.<br>
<br>
Even after the bodies had arrived it was some time before the doors could be thrown open and the crowd admitted. It was a sickening task to prepare the bodies of the dead for the inspection of friends and for their identification. Many had not even as much as a scrap of paper to show their name or residence and these had to be restored to their life-like condition and the bruises concealed as much as possible to enable identification.<br>
<br>
The crowd outside the doors waited persistently. Until nearly two o'clock scarcely one moved away and when the doors were opened to admit a few at a time the crowd pushed and jostled forward to enter.<br>
<br>
Those who were believed to be able to identify some of the dead were admitted first where ever possible and practically all the victims had been identified by 5:00 o'clock.<br>
<br>
Many women faint<br>
<br>
The strain was too much for many relatives, especially the women. Several women swooned and had to be attended by the morgue employees. Others wept almost hysterically before the rigid forms of friends and relatives while the men were affected just as deeply. Some of the women attempted to stop in front of the dead lying on the slabs and now and then an attempt was made to embrace the form of a loved one. The employees of the undertaking rooms interfered mercifully and assisted those so affected from the room.<br>
<br>
Curiosity drew many of the crowd. These gazed with interest on the forms of the dead and passed on hurriedly. Others did not wait to look at all the bodies but turned away when the horrible effects of the accident came home to them and hastened from the room.<br>

Was An Accident.<br>
<br>
Street railway officials claim the disaster was the result of an accident and one entirely unforeseen and impossible to have prevented. An officer of the road stated last night that the company recovered the register and this showed sixty-six fares<br>
The number of children on the car is not, of course, included and the commuters state their tickets are never rung on the register. Estimated on the basis of the dead and injured it is believed about one hundred passengers were on the car, and this is the number the street car officials estimate.<br>
<br>
The street railway company as soon as the disaster was known directed the hospitals to prepare to receive all the injured. Every physician the company could secure was sent to the scene and since then the hospitals and physicians have been directed to treat the injured at the expense of the company.<br>
<br>
General Superintendent F.L. Dame gave an explanation of the disaster yesterday. He said:<br>
<br>
"The car was in charge of Motorman Braehm and Conductor Calhoun. Mr. Braehm is an experienced man and was selected for the South Tacoma run on account of his experience. He was for nine years an employee of a Cincinnati electric line and thoroughly competent. Conductor Calhoun had been working for the company about two months.<br>
<br>
"I posted an order at the street car barn last night (Tuesday) instructing all street car employees not to attempt to keep on schedule time on the Fourth. They were told to pay the utmost attention to the safety of passengers and to be especially careful about teams and pedestrians who might be on the tracks. This applied to all lines as well as the South Tacoma system.<br>
<br>
Car in Good Order.<br>
<br>
"The car was in perfect condition. Braehm was at the car barn Tuesday night working on the car. He took out the old sand and put in new; tested his brakes and the current. The brakes did not fail, for an examination shows they were not broken. I understand the motorman tested his sand at the top of the hill.<br>
<br>
"Just how the car got beyond the motorman's control is not known. The rail was bad, and it may have started to slip. There was just enough mist and rain to make the rails slippery, and the sand may not have been sufficient to hold the car. It certainly got a start and the brakes would not hold it.<br>
<br>
"The current was reversed as a last resort. There was not much chance of its holding, as it is apt to burn out as soon as the first notch is reached. That is probably what it did, but the
only chance of stopping the car was to turn on a reversed current.<br>
<br>
Speed Was Terrific.<br>
<br>
"The car must have come down at a terrific rate of speed for it leaped the track clear over the guard rail. The curve is an unusually high one, and under ordinary circumstances, there would not have been any danger. The guard rail and timber did not stop the car; in fact a stone wall would have been of no use.<br>
<br>
"The brakes on the car were found half set. Little can be told from this, however, as the fall would have dislocated the brakes. It is probable they were set on as hard as possible. The trucks and motor were not destroyed but the rest of the car is ruined.<br>
<br>
"The accident is a most terrible and deplorable one, but it is one that could not have been foreseen and is purely the result of causes over which we had no control."<br>
<br>
There was a strong feeling against the railway company manifest on the streets and wherever men congregated last night. Threats against officers of the company were made in some quarters and the sheriff's office and police took immediate steps to quell the impending disturbance. Sheriff Mills last night issued the following warning:<br>
<br>
"The authorities are preparing to make a thorough investigation of the wreck at the C Street bridge and the causes that led up to it. In the meantime both Coroner Hoska and myself would advise the public to await the results of a fair investigation and not to attempt any inflammatory demonstration which would injure rather than aid the cause of justice.<br>
<br>
A.U. Mills,<br>
Sheriff of Pierce County."<br>
<br>
Accidents on the grade<br>
<br>
The Delin street grade has been fated for accidents. Twice during the days the old motor line ran to Oakes addition lives were lost by accidents on the street and since the electric line was built there has been one other accident beside that of yesterday.<br>
<br>
This was during the time the line was under the management of the Tacoma Traction Company. A car jumped the track at the C Street curve but did not gove over the bridge.<br>
<br>
It was on this grade that two motor cors collided with force about ten years ago and half a dozen men were maimed and at least one death occurred. It was on Sunday and both trains were heavily loaded with pleasure parties, either bound to or returning from Wapato Lake. The list of injured was confined to those on the
platforms.<br>
<br>
A steam motor leaped over the bank and into the gulch during the time the steam road was operated. A worman lost her life in this accident.<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
EIGHT MORE OF THE VICTIMS OF THE WRECK MAY DIE<br>
<br>
(Eight more of the victims of the wreck may die at the hospitals. No hope of their recovery is entertained by nurses and physicians," <B>Tacoma Daily Ledger.</B> July 6, 1900.).<br>
<br>
At a meeting of the City Council last night councilman Jones, of the Sixth Ward, introduced a resolution extending condolence to families bereaved by the plunging of the street car over the bridge and callling attention to the fact that the street railway company overloads its cars and runs them too fast.<br>
<br>
The resolution was adopoted unanimously, but not until nearly every member of the council had something to say on the subject. Some of the members condemned the company outright and made the charge that incompetent men were employed, while others counseled withholding blame until the corner's jury has investigated the facts and renders a verdict. The resolution as originally introduced reads as follows:<br>
<br>
"Whereas, a most horrible accident carrying death and disaster to many of our people occurred, on the morning of July 4 at the 26th Street bridge on the Edison line of the Tacoma Railway and Power Company, and<br>
<br>
"Whereas, said accident occurred when the car of said company was running beyond all reasonable speed; and<br>
<br>
"Whereas, said accident occurred when said Tacoma Railway and Power company was carrying passengers on a car loaded beyond all reasonable limit; and<br>
<br>
"Whereas, said Tacoma Railway and Power Company has persisted in running cars upon its lines in this city bgeyond all reasonable speed; and<br>
<br>
"Whereas, there is no state commission whose duty it is to supervice the competency of street car employes of our state; therefore be it<br>
<br>
"Resolved that the city council do hereby pass resolutions of sympathy and condolence to the bereaved families and the afflicted ones; and be it further<br>

"Resolved that the city council, with a vew toward the prevention of a recurrence of such a deploable accident, do hereby take such measures as we deem wise and fitting by instructin gthe city attorney to immediatley prepare an ordinance controlling and reglating the street car traffice in our city; that he be instructed to draft said ordinance so that the speed of cars be brought within the limit of safety; that the overloading of cars beyond the seating capacity of each car be forbidden and that the placing of incompetent and unskilled men in charge of the cars either as condutor or as motorman be condemned and forbidden as a menace to the safety of the public; and be it further<br>
<br>
"Resolved that we do hereby memorialize the legislature of the State of Washington  at its first session hereafter to pass a law ordering the forming of a commission to examine into the fitness and capabilities of street railway conductors and motormen, so that only competent and skilled men be permitted to have charge of street cars."<br>
<br>
Curve is always dangerous<br>
<br>
Hewitt said he hoped it would be possible to compel the company to change the right of way of the line at that point as with a heavy grade and a sharp curve  on the high bridge, it would always be dangerous no matter how competent the employes are. He made the statement that but one man has been discharged from the line in the past year and a half, and that the motorman on the wrecked car was a man of much experience in Cincinnati and other cities.<br>
<br>
"How many new men have there been on your line?" he asked Mr. Jones. Jones--The change them so often that I cannot keep track of them.<br>
<br>
Many incompetent men<br>
<br>
Boardman--Perhaps Mr. Jones is like I am. The incompetent men on the street car lines of the city are so many that it is impossible to keep track of them. Every day there are incompetent men on the Old Town line. Only the other day a passenger on one of the Old Town cars asked to be let off at Tacoma Avenue and the conductor asked the passenger to tell him when the car reached Tacoma Avenue as he did not  know the streets.<br>
<br>
Dueval called attention to the terrific rate of speed the Old Town and Sixth avenue cars attain running down C street, and said a dozen teams had been run into in the past year. It was useless, he said, to speak to Superintendent Dame about cars running fast, as the superintendent had an unpleasant habit of asking objectors what they know about speed.<br>
<br>
Roice also spoke of the number of new and incompetent men now employed by the street car company.<br>

President Smith though Hewitt's suggestion to change the line in order to do away with the curve was the only sensible solution of the problem, and that the ordinance now in force regulating the speed of street cars in enough; all that it needs is enforcement.<br>
<br>
Man at motor was new<br>
<br>
Jones--I have been told by employes of the company that the morotman on the wrecked car never came down that hiill in h is life before, and that he turned on the current right at the top of the hill.<br>
<br>
Roberts--On account of it being a holiday, Wednesday, the service on the Edison line ws doubled and men from other lines in the city were used on the line in order to handle the crowds.<br>
<br>
Boardman--The second clause of Mr. Jones' resolution states that the car was running beyond all reasonable speed and that is something none of us know anything about. So I offer the following as a substitute for that section:<br>
<br>
"Whereas, public opinion condemns the present location of the car line on the side hill  where the accident occurred yesterday; therefore be it<br>
<br>
"Resolved, That the city attorney be directed to examine the franchise of the company and also the laws of the state and see if there is any way that the present location can be condemned as dangerous to life, and said location of the line be ordered changed."<br>
<br>
Day counseled going slow in the matter, as the action of the council might prejudice the cornor's jury now investigating the case.<br>
<br>
Inquest on Monday.<br>
<br>
The inquest over the bodies of the victims of Wednesday's street car wreck will be held in Judge Kean's court room at l:00 o'clock Monday afternoon. About twenty-five witnesses will be called by the coroner and examined by the jurty.<br>
<br>
Everyone who saw the accident, several of those on the car and experts who have examined the track and position of the wreck since will testify. The sheriff and coroner are now summoning witnesses.<br>
<br>
The coroner's jury is: F.T. Olds, flour manufactuers; Peter Irving, capitalist; J.H. Babbitt, clerk; John R. Turner, manager for Fawcett Wagon Company; Charles H. Plass, grocer; Charles D. Atkins, South Tacoma. The jury was summoned to meet at 10 o'clock yesterday morning.<br>
<br>
There were thirty-seven bodies at the undertkaing rooms when the
jury was empaneled and these were viewed. As soon as the bodies had been viewed the coroner released them to their relatives or friends.<br>
<br>
Coroner holds the wreck<br>
<br>
The jury went from the morgue to the scene of the street car accident. An inspection was made of the bridge and then the six men dropped over the bluff and went down to the wrecked car as it lay near the bottom of the gluch. A careful inspection was made of both the ruined car and the broken bridge supports. The jury finally decided to order the wreck to remain as it was until after the inquest.<br>
<br>
The coroner is still in charge of both the bridge and wreck. Deputy sheriffs are on duty there and acting under his instructions will permit no one to go near the scene. It is intended the wreck shall not be disturbed until the jury has reached some conclusion in the matter.<br>
<br>
Blackman holds an inspection<br>
<br>
State Railiway, Mill and Factory Inspector William Blackman also made an inspection of the wreck and tracks yesterday. He went over the grade on Delin Street examining the track from the top of the hill, investigated the curve on the bridge and then looked over the wrecked street car. He paid particular attention to the condition of the rails and the wheels of the car. speaking last night of the result of his investigation, he severely condemned the roadbed at that point.<br>
<br>
"I do not think the curve is wide enough for such a grade," he said." The city council that granted a franchise to the street car company should never have permitted it to lay its tracks in such a manner. Of course the franchise was granted years ago and the present council has nothing to do with the matter, but the old body should have exercised more caution.<br>
<br>
"I found the inside of the outer rail was much worn. The wheelers of the car as the curve is passed do not roll around but rather bump over the curve and on such a rail the danger of their jumping the track is much greater. New rails should have been put in before the track became so worn.<br>
<br>
"An examination of the trucks shows that two new wheels had recently been put on the car. It cannot be told definitely from the position of the car, but I believe these were on the rear truck as the car was approaching the city.  The flanges on what wee probably the front truck wheels were badly worn. New wheels were needed.<br>
<br>
"The car must have been running at a very high rate of speed when it left the track. It is not clear from an examination of the
track just how the car when over the bridge. Tehre are not marks on the high guard rail to show it had struck there and there are few marks of the car on the bridge itself. It probably struck the rail at the curve and leaped over, turning completely over in the fall.<br>
<br>
"At such sharp curves as that at the end of the bridge railroad companies all over the country place an open switch leading to a sidetrack running up  a steep grade. In case of a runaway the open swith sends the train onto the sidetrack and it runs up the grade and its speed is exhausted. Accidents are few under such circumstances.<br>
<br>
""The street railroad company should have one of those witches at the bridge. The open swith would run on Delin street down the bicycle path and the car wold come to a stop either on the switch or runn off onto Pacific avenue. If there is a possibility of building a steep grade this would be better.   This would compel every car bound toward the city to stop at the curve and throw the switch and would result in reducing the danger to a minimum.<br>
<br>
"I do not know how an easier grade down the side of the gulch could be found, but I did not examine the street carefully."<br>
<br>
Sorrow at the homes.<br>
<br>
At South Tacoma, Lakeview, Parkland and Lake Park, where practically all the victims of the disaster lived, a feeling of desolation and an air of gret grief was apparent.  Lake Park suffered the heaviest for nearly all the residents of that suburb who were on the car were either instantly killed or died later of their injuries.<br>
<br>
The entire suburb was grief-stricken, and those w<br>
ho did not lose friends or relatives on the car spent the day consoling the griefg stricken friends and relatives of the victims. Some of the best known residents of Lake Park and Parkland were killed in the wreck, and it was an especially hard blow for those two suburbs to bear. Lakeview shared in the loss but not so heavily.<br>
<br>
South Tacoma appeared to be bewildered yesterday by the great shock, Eleven of those killed in the wreck had been employes of the car shops, while at the hospitals another man lay hovering between life and death, and thirteen  more were suffered from injuries. In other families children or wives had either been killed or had been severely injured.<br>
<br>
Mourning for the dead<br>
<br>
The suburb was in mourning for its dead. Flags hung at half mast and at the car shops employes were continually asking for information regarding the welfare of men they had worked with for years. Not many married men had been killed, but the death list
included some of the most popular railroad men in South Tacoma.<br>
<br>
The predominance of single men was marked. There were many married men from South Tacoma on the car, but they were fortunte enough to escape with lighter injuries. The single men, chidlren and girls seemed fated to lose their lives.<br>
<br>
The railroad men are caring for their dead and are offering every attention to the living who are lying at the hospitals. Master Mechanic H.H.Warner searched all over the city yesterday, among the hopsitals and at the undertaking parlors, to locte the men from the car shops and all railroad men who had been injured or killed.<br>
<br>
A careful list was prepared which showed the following railroad men had been killed:<br>
<br>
Car Shop's List.<br>
<br>
Robert Steele, rivet heater<br>
E.E. Bray, boiler maker<br>
G. McMillin, machine hand.<br>
C.W. Woodruff, bulldozer man.<br>
A.T. Silfberg, driller<br>
Gorton Newton, car repairer<br>
W.L. Williams, car repairer<br>
C.D. Davis, machinist's helper<br>
Roger Lingerman, employee of the depot agent.<br>
G. Vanderschelden, blacksmith<br>
G.H. Gaul, store helper.<br>
<br>
At the hospitals were these railroad men:<br>
J.B. Lingerman, foreman of the store laborers.<br>
J.J. Jaeger, blacksmith's helper<br>
F.T. Startzel, machinist.<br>
Frank O'Hara, machinist.<br>
Alfred Anderson, car builder<br>
Anton Hanson, blacksmith's helper<br>
Ole Friberg, carpenter.<br>
M.M.Hosking, fireman<br>
Samuel Mathews, car repairer's helper<br>
J.A. Lyberg, machiist.<br>
G.A. Swanson, car repairer<br>
Otto Johnson, machine hand.<br>
O.M. Parks, superintendent's clerk.<br>
H.L. Weir, night operator.<br>
<br>
The railroad men will care for these men. They are all entitled to the sick and death benefits which are provided by the men and unless objection is made by the relatives he dead men will be buried by their fellow employes.  Both Mr. Watner and General Foreman Gilman will watch the men at the hospital carefully to furnish them any needed assistants and the company surgeons have
been instructed to attend them.<br>
<br>
Two More Are Dead<br>
<br>
Bray, one of the dead railroad men, died about 2 o'clock yestereday afternoon at the Fanny Paddock Hospital. His death had been prematurely announced the day before.  The attending physicians had given up all hope of saving his life, but they continued the fight against big odds in the hope of saving him.<br>
<br>
Mrs.Emma Flemming also died at the Fannie Paddock hospital during the day. She had been one of the most seriously injured of the victims and her death had been expected momentarily ever since the accident. Her death swelled the total number of deat to thirty-nine.<br>
<br>
While their mother lay dying at the Fanny Paddock hospital two of the Flemming children were at the St. Joseph's Hospital under the care of the nurses there. Little Dot Flemming, whose left arm is broke, and whose head had been severely bruised, lay on her bed of pain without uttering a word of protest or complaining of her conditiion. Her brother lay in a ward below her. Both children were ignorant of their mother's death.<br>
<br>
Visitors are Kept Out<br>
<br>
Visitors are not permitted to see the victims of the wreck  at either of the hospitals. The conditionof many of them is so precarious that nay interference would seriously impair their chances of recovery. Several of them are believed to be beyond human aid, but the nurses and physicians are working hard to save life.<br>
<br>
Five were able to go home yesterday. One of these was fron the Fanny Paddock hospital and the other two from the St. Joseph's. Little Goldie and Bernice Hoffman were taken to the home of friends. Their father and mtoehr lie side by side at the St. Joseph's Hospital, the mother painfully bruised and suffering equally as much over the condition of her husband.<br>
<br>
The condition of Mr. Hoffman is serious, but he will recover. Neither father nor mother can be removed at prsent, but the faces of both sufferers lighted up with joy when they learned yesterday that their children were able to go to the home of friends. The two little girls bade a fond goodbye to their parents last night.<br>
<br>
Leave the Hospital<br>
<br>
Herman Moser and Oscar Brottem have not yet recovered, but both were able to leave the hospital and they were taken away. Young Moser has a broken leg and Brottem's sholder was dislocated. The injuries of both are expected to be healed within a short time.<br>
<br>
Russell Hays was discharged from the Fanny Paddock hospital. His
injuries were principally bruises, more painful than serious, and he was able to return to his home yesterday.<br>
<br>
H.L. Wier is at the Fanny Paddock hospital in precarious condition. A consultation of physicians was held on his case yesterday morning and Drs. Hamilton Allen, the Northern Pacific's local surgeon, and T.F. Smith, the street railway company's surgeon, operated on him. He was sent back to his ward after undegoing the operation and some hopes of his recovery are entertained.<br>
<br>
More will die.<br>
<br>
At the St. Joseph's hosptial several deaths are expected though the hospital has thus far been unusally successful in its cases. But few have died from their injuries and the most serious cases are doing well. A number of volunteer nurses including representatives from the Red Cross are assisting the sisters.<br>
<br>
An unknown man is still unconscious at the hospital. He is injured seriously about the head and his chances of recovery are slim. Earl Hoskins has not yet recovered consciousness. His injuries are to the head and his condition is alarming.<br>
<br>
Little or no hope is felt for five patients in the female wards. Their condition is so alarming that the nurses are compelled to be with them constantly, and it is regarded as only a question of a few hours before they will have succumbed to their injuries<br>
<br>
Three on one family killed<br>
<br>
Mrs. Louis Dinger may pull through. Several bones are broke, but the critical stage has passed ans she is gathering strength. By her side lies little Vida Dinger, scarcely injured, but her mother finds her presence a gret comfort and she is permitted to remain in the hospital. In another room lies the little 10 months<br>
babe the mother was calling for the day before. The babe is severely injured and for twenty-hours has been beyond the aid of medical skill. Severe bruises about the head made it certain that the little one will die, but the nurses have worked faithfully to restore life to the little frame.<br>
<br>
From Wednesday night to Thursday afternoon the babe was continually going into convulsions, but though it seemed it would die at any minute, it hung tenaciously to life. The mother was told of the baby's condition and has become reconciled.<br>
<br>
When the baby dies three out of a family of five will have been killed by the accident and a fourth member, the mother is severely injured. Only the daughter Vida escaped without serious injury. Dorothy and Louis Dinger are now at the morgue.<br>
<br>
                          She cannot recover
Sophie Storasli cannot recover. Her skull is crushed and her face is swollen to an unusual degree. A nurse is constantly at her side, but the girl has only recovered cinsciousness for a few moments since the accident. She has spoke a few words and then lapsed again into unconsciousness.<br>
<br>
Mrs. M. G. Swanson's skull is crushed and no hope of her recovery is entertained. She has been unconscious ever since the wreck and it is doubtful whether she will ever be able to speak.  Her death may occur at any time. A piece of bone was removed by the surgeons from her brain.<br>
<br>
Paulina Christenden has spoken a few words in her native tongue, and though they could not be understood, it is believed they were not connected and did not indicate that she has returned to consciousness. She is very restless and her condition is most serious. Her recovery is questionable and at first the physicians held out no hope.<br>
<br>
There is little hope of the recovery of Hilda Glano, a nine year old girl at St. Joseph's Hospital. Her right leg is broke, two serious cuts wee made on the left leg and her head is bruised and crushed and internal injuries are shown by the child's restless complaints of injuries about her body.<br>
<br>
It was learned yesterday that three sisters had been taken from the wreck direct to theirhome in South Tacoma. They are Veda, Mary and Gladys Waring. Miss Veda Waring is a fourteen year old girl. She was bruised severely about the face and has a cut on her leg.<br>
<br>
Twelve year old Mary Waring sprained her wrist severely and has severe face and head injuries. Gladys, a younger sister, is more seriously hurt. Her right arm is broken, the left shoulder severely sprained and she has many bruises. All three will recover.<br>
<br>
John and Walter Ristuet of Brookdale were slightly injured. They are brothers, 17 and 10 respecitvely and are now stopped with Mrs. Louis Anderson, 424 North Fifth Street.<br>
<br>
The othere patients at the Fannie Paddock and St. Joseph's Hospitals are all reported to be on the road to rapid recovery. It is now practically cdrtain the death list will reach forty-
five or more. Nine have already died since being taken to the hospitals. Two of these died yesterday and the others did ot live long after being taken from the wreck.<br>
<br>
Unknown Man Identified<br>
<br>
The body of the unknown man which has been lying at Hoska's awaiting identification for twenty-four hours was identified yesterday as that of G.H. Gaul, a Steilacoom boy, aged sixteen, who has been working at the car shops.
His aged mother came to the morgue yesterday morning asking for her son. None of the coroner's assistants knew whether the boy was there or not. He was certainly not among the identified. The mother was taken to the mangled fram lying in the rear and after the face had been bidden she ws permitted to look at the clothes. she recognized the form immediately and fell on her knees sobbing her grief.<br>
<br>
While the body of William Nelsen was lying at the morgue awaiting burial word came from Lake Park that a relaive of his had died there and the two will probably be buried at the same time.<br>
<br>
Scenes at the Morgue<br>
<br>
The same affecting scenes of Wednesday were reenacted at the morgue yesterday and the crowd of curious visitors increased. In order to allow his assistants to work and prepare the bodies for removal, Coroner Hoska was compelled to refuse admittance to a large number and is probably no  one will be permitted to see the bodies today. Coroner Hoska in person remonstrated yesterday with curiosity seekers and asked them not to insist on passing inside.<br>
<br>
He asked them to compare the feelings of breaved relatives with those they would entertain under similar circumstances, and not to visit the morgue. He was unable to turn the tide.<br>
<br>
Between today and Sunday the funerals of practically all the victims of the wreck will be held. The number of funerals to be held will make almost an unending procession from the city to the cemeteries. Some of the bodies are to be sent out of the city for interment, but most of them will be laid away in nearby cemeteries....<br>
<br>
Wanted to give something<br>
<br>
A little girl and her mother were passing a relief barrel in front of a downtown cigar store last night. In her left hadn the girl tighly grasped a ten cent piece and with the other she held to her mother's dress, not to lose her in the crowd. The barrel on the sidewalk attraced the girl's attention and she whispered.<br>
<br>
"Mamma, what is that barrel, for?"<br>
<br>
"Its for the little children who have lost their mammas," she answered softly.<br>
<br>
"The little girl hesitaged a moment and then released he rhold on her mother's dress. Confidently she stepped foreward and reaching the barrel's edge, pulled herself up on her tip toes and reached over the top. Her left hand opened and the dime, reserved for firecrackers, dropped into the pile of coin below. " I guess I'll give them my firecracker money," she said.<br>
<br>
There was a peculiar feeling among the bystandings and then,
moved by a common impulse, all stepped forward and dropped something into the barrel. The firecracker money had earned for the bereaved families greater interest than was ever paid before.<br>
<br>
All classes are contributing to the relief funds, and doing it gladly and willingly. Women and children are touched by the mute appealof the big barrels and the stores of hte lost ones who had families to support and are contributing their mites. Men pass the barrels quietly slip a coin into them and pass on without stopping.<br>
<br>
Now and then pennies are found which tell the story of someone who did not have anything more, but offered what he or she could.<br>
<br>
The game of baseball held yesterday for the relief of the sufferers only netted twenty five dollars. The attendance was surprisingly small and the Tacoma players immediately resolved to add something to it. Each man in the team volunteered to give one dollar and nine more dollars were added to the total. As a esult the relief fund was enriched a total of thirty five dollars from the game.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Two more victims are added<br>
<br>
(Two more victims are added, death record of the street car tragedy, seven of the injured are still unconscious at the hospitals and little hope of their recovery is entertained, more money needed," <B>Tacoma Daily Ledger,</B> July 7, 1900).<br>
<br>
The death list of the C Street car disaster has reached forty-
one. The six month old babe of Louis Dinger and wife died at the St. Joseph's Hospital at 4:45 o'clock yesterday afternoon and now lies at the morgue besides the bodies of its sister and father.<br>
<br>
Earl Hoskins died at 6:00 p.m.<br>
<br>
Five more victims are still lying unconscious at the St. Joseph's Hospital another is gradually returning to conscioiusness at the Fanny Paddock and still antoher has not regained his consciousness at the same hospital.  These constitute the list of those who may die at any time.<br>
<br>
Ever since the wreck the Dinger baby has been lying either unconscious or so badly dazed that it could give little sign of life. It could not be aroused at any time from a semi-comatose condition and the nurses and physicians had given up all hope of saving the infant. The vitality of the baby was wonderful.<br>
<br>
The blow on the head was one sufficient to have killed many adults and it seemed as though death wold have been almost instantaneous, but almost ot he last the child's pulse beats were
as strong as those of many of the nurses themselves.<br>
<br>
Mother is Reconciled.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Dinger lies in an adjoining room dangerously injured. She was told yesterday of the child's desperate condition and made several anxious inquiries regarding the possibility of its recovery. Then she sated quietly, "If the child's brain will be affected ifit should recover, I would rather see it die than live to become an imbecile. I think that would be better for the baby."<br>
<br>
Mrs. Dinger had become reconciled to the thought of her baby's death, but the nurses decided it would not be best to tell her of it last night.<br>
<br>
This makes the third member of the fmaily who has died as a result of the diaster, Louis and Dorothy Dinger, father and daughter, were killed almost instantly. Mrs.  Dinger was seriously injured, a number of bones being broken. A daughter is with her mother at the hospital slightly injured. The funerals of the three members of the family will be held Sunday and the bodies sent to Parkland for burial.<br>
<br>
Operating on the victims<br>
<br>
The unknown man at the St. Joseph's Hospital has been recognized as James Gemell, a Frenchman aged thirty, who lived at Steilacoom. He is still unconscious and little hope of his recovery is entertained. The hosptial corps of physicians will conduct an operation on him today and my be able to save his life.<br>
<br>
He is suffering from a concussion of the brain and his left side is gradually becoming paralyzed. The operation to be performed will be to open the skull over the motor centers on the right side and remove a clot of blood which has formed there. The operation will be a most delicate one. Gemell at present is very restless.<br>
<br>
An operation was performed yesterday by Dr. Libby, assisted by Drs. Case, Brown, and Keho, on Earl Hoskin who had lain at the St. Joseph Hospital in an unconscious condition ever since the diaster. His skul had been fractured and the bone was lifted where it had been pressed down. An incision was made into the exudative matter and the secretion let out. He ssmed tohave stood the operation well, but died before night.<br>
<br>
Condition of Lyberg<br>
<br>
J.A. Lyberg, is coming through the shock of his operation well but his condition is desperate. His injuries were internal and the opeation was natually a delicate one. He has a fracutre of one of his ribs and is in an emphysematus condition. Lyberg is
still unconscious. Dr. Case conducted the operation on Mr. Lyberg and he states that his recover is doubtful.<br>
<br>
Two of the women who are in a dangerous condition were trepanned y esterday by Drs. Brown and Case. They are Mrs. C.M. Swanson and Sophie Storaasli. Both are unconscious. Paulina Christenden in the same ward, is also unconscious and showing little sign of improvement. She has spoken a word or two in her native tongue, but no other sign of consciousness has been given. sophie Storaasli has spoken a few times but Mrs. Swanson has given no sign of life.<br>
<br>
Regains Consciousness<br>
<br>
Hilda Glasso who has been expected to die has regained consciousness for a few moments at a time and is apparently improved somewhat. At present she is unconscious and her condition is critical. A sister was discharged from the hospital yesterday. J. B. Lingerman, who lost a son in the wreck was also discharged  from St. Joseph's Hospital yesterday. Edith Swanson, whose mother is so dangerously injured was able yesterday to walk about some and may leave the hsopital in a few days. Her  brother, Swan Swanson, was discharged yesterday from the Fanny Paddock hospital. O.M. Parks left the same institution.<br>
<br>
Mrs.  Sulter who is at the St. Joseph's Hosptial suffering from brokenribs and ankle is improving rapidly.<br>
<br>
Otto Johnson, who had been at the Fanny Paddock hosptial unconscious since the wreck, is showing signs of returning consciousness. His injuries were all on the head. Robert Hannah, a boy who has a broken arm and leg is still delrious.His condition is serious. H.L. Wier is reported to be improving.<br>
<br>
Danger of Blood Poisoning<br>
<br>
There is danger of blood poisoning setting in with some of the patients. Lyman Lee is the only one who has shown any such symptoms as yet, but the hospital authorities say the time has not yet arrived for such symptoms to appear with most of the patients. Young Lee's face is badly swollen and serious complications may arise. This is being guarded against by the hosptial authorities.<br>
<br>
Other patients at the hosptial are reported to be improving rapidly. The less seriously injured at the Fanny Paddock, who are in the larger wards, were able yesterday to move about a little or to sit up and take nourishment. Several of them may be discharged within a few days. Some of the patients at the St. Joseph Hospital where most of the serious cases are located, were able yesterday to move about.<br>
<br>
Four More Funerals.<br>

Arrangements were made yesterday for four more funerals. The funeral service over the body of Mrs. Emma Flemming will be held at 9:30 o'clock Sunday morning at Hoska's. A.L. Healy's body will be taken to the school house at Lake View where his funeral will be held at l0:30 o'clock Sunday morning. The funeral of Richard Lee will be held at ll o'clock Sunday morning from the Methodist Church at South Tacoma, and at 4:30 o'cloc, p.m. on the same day the funeal of Lottie Suiter will be held from the Methodist Church at the same place.<br>
<br>
The funeral of J. D. Calhoun, the dead conductor on the ill fated car No. 116 was held from Roberts and Green's last night. The Masons had charge of the funeral and the rites according to their ritual were performed. Mrs. Calhoun started East last night with the body of her husband.<br>
<br>
Flowers for the Dead<br>
<br>
John Simon found yesterday that a large number of the dead had received no flowers andhe returned to his home immediately gathered a large number and took them to the morgue. Each casket was covered with beautiful roses and other flowers.<br>
<br>
A meeting was held in Mayor Campbell's office yesterday morning of the committee which he appointed to take charge of the fund raised for the relief of the street car disaster sufferers. May Cmapbell was immediately elected chairman of the relief committee with O.W. Barlow,of South Tacoma, secretary. Mr. Barlow is preparing a complete list of all those who are left helpless as a result of the disaster.<br>
<br>
The committee yesterday disbursed six hundred dollars. This money was shown to be needed immediately and it was ordered sent to the sufferers. As soon  as reports come to the committe of the need of the funds money will be forwarded. Meetings are to be held daily at the mayor's office to attend to relief measures.<br>
<br>
Funds are Needed.<br>
<br>
Mayor Campbell spoke yesterday in positive terms of the need of larger donations and prompt attention to the wants of the suffers. "The list of those who are left helpless as a result of the disaster is a long one," he said. "The people must respond to it at once and respond generously. We will need three times the amount we have secured at present and there shold be no hesitancy in subscribing.<br>
<br>
"Many of the victims of the disaster were the sole support of large families and now that they are gone there is no one left to provide for them. The committee has already disbursed six hundred dollars and will wnat more  money immediately for more cases. Those in the hosptials will not be able to return to th eir work for some time and in the meantime something must be done for the support of those who were dependent upon them."
Inquire for Relatives<br>
<br>
Anxious meassages of inquiry from other towns came in eysterday to the police and the newspapers. the list of the dead left many in doubt whether their own relatives wee in the wreck, and they telegraphed immediately for information. Similar initials were responsible for some of the inquiries, but in some cases it was a case of undue anxiety.<br>
<br>
Flags in the city yesterday hung at half mast and they will remain so until after the funerals of the victims have been held. The funerals which are to be held today are:<br>
<br>
A.T. Silfberg, 2 p.m. from 5411 Birmingham Avenue.<br>
<br>
Robert Steele and Joseph McCann, 8 a.m. from St. Leo's.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Campbell 10:00 a.m. from Roberts and Greens,the body to go to Parkland.<br>
<br>
The funerals of the Rev. Herbert Gregory and Miss Lois Drake held yesterday were both largely attended. There was a profusion of floral offerings and the bodies were followed to the cemetery by a large number of friends.<br>
<br>
Carpenters Express Regret.<br>
<br>
The carpenter's union yesterday passed the following resolution:<br>
<br>
Resolved that Carpenter's Union No. 470 of Tacoma hereby extends its heartfelt sympahty to those afflicted by the distressing accident  of July 4 and especially to our member and brother George Fleming for the loss of his wife and children.<br>
<br>
Resolved that in token of our sympahty our charter be draped for thirty days and that a coy of these resolutions be spread on the minutes of the union, a copy sent to Brother Fleming and one each to the daily papers for publication.<br>
<br>
Give a Benefit<br>
<br>
Plans are being made for a benefit theatrical performance, the proceeds to be given to the street car disaster sufferers. fred Williams and D.C. Arnold are planning to present" In the tolls of hte Spanish," written by J. C. Williamson,. They are now seduring a cast.<br>
<br>
Officers of the National Guard met yeterday and passed the following resolution:<br>
<br>
Resolved that we desire to express our prfound sympahty to the
families of those killed and injured in the terrible street car accient of July 4th.<br>
<br>
Theory of the Wreck<br>
<br>
A theory, new to the public, has been advanced by street car men and former employes to explain the disaster. It is a complicated theory, involving the study of physics, but one that street car men agree they have learned from practives,  and is absolutely correct. Yet it is one the general public or rather that portion which has heard it, has been skeptical over.<br>
<br>
It is stated by street car men that the brakes must be loosened when going around curves. If set tight the brakes hold the trucks rigid and there is not enough flexibility to permit the truck to turn and follow the curve. To go into a curve with the brakes set hard is to court disaster, motormen claim. The car is almost certain to jump the track.<br>
<br>
Brakes Set Hard<br>
<br>
In line with this theory it is argued that the motorman probably had his brakes set hard when he hit the curve. The car, as a result, went straight ahead, the wheels refusing to follow the curve. Either that result, they claim, or broken chains would certainly follow.<br>
<br>
If the brakes had been released just as the car was to hit the curve the old street car men claim it would have remained on the track or in all events might not go off the bridge. It is acknowledged, though, that this might have been done and in spite of the precaution the car went over.<br>
<br>
Another instance is cited in support of this theory. A car on the street railway jumped the track at a curve, and was smashed. It had been running at a high rate of speed but was not in danger. An old street car man was on the car and after the accident he accused the motorman of going into the curve with his brakes set hard.  He finally acknowledged he had done so.<br>
<br>
Whether the theory is good or no, stret car men believe in it and insit experiences has taught them that it will hold.<br>
<br>
J.A. Lyberg is coming through the shock of his operation well, but his condition is desperate. His injuries were internal and the operation was natually a delicate one. He has a fracture of one of his ribs and is in an emphysematus condition. Lyberg is still unconscious. Dr. Case conducted the operation and he states that his recovery is doubtful.<br>
<br>
Two of the women who are in dangerous condition were trepanned yesterday by Drs. Brown and Case. They are Mrs. G.M. Swanson and Sophie Storassli. Both are still unconscious. Paulina Christensen
in the same ward is also unconscious and showing little sign of improvement. She has spoken a word or two in her native tongue, but no other sign of consciousness has been given. Sophie Storassli has spoken a few times, but Mrs. Swanson has given no sign of life.<br>
<br>
Hilda Glasso, who has been expected to die, has regained consciousness for a few moments at a time and is apparently improved somewhat. At present she is unconscious and her condition is critical. A sister was discharged from the hospital yesterday.J.H. Lingerman, who lost a son in the wreck was also discharged from the St. Joseph's hospital yesterday.<br>
<br>
Edith Swanson, whose mother is so dangeroulsy injured was able yesterday to walk some and may lave the hospital in a few days. Her brother Swan Swanson was discharged yesterday from the Fanny Paddock hosptial. G.M. Parks also left he same institution.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Sutter, who is at the St. Joseph's Hosital suffered from broken ribs and ankle, is improving rapidly.<br>
<br>
Otto Johnson, who has been at the Fanny Paddock Hospital, unconscious since the wreck is showing signs of returning consciousness. His injuries were all on the head. Robert Hannah, a boy who has a broken arm and leg is still delirious. His condition is serious. H.L. Weir is reorted to be improving somewhat.<br>
<br>
There is danger of blood poisoning setting in with some of the patients. Lyman Lee is the only one who has shown any such symptoms as yet, but the hospital authorities say the time has not yet arrived for such symptoms to appear with most of the patients.<br>
<br>
Young Lee's face is badly swollen and serious complications may arise. This is being guarded against by hospital authorities.<br>
<br>
Other patients at the hospital are reported improving rapidly. The less seriously injured at the Fanny Paddock who are in the larger wards wee able yesterday to move about a little or to sit up and take nourishment. Several of them may be discharged within a few days. Some of the patients at the St. Joseph's hospital where most of the serious cases are located were able yesterday to move about.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------------------------------------------
---------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
"Witnesses tell of the wreck," <B>Tacoma Daily Ledger.</B> July 12, 1900.<br>
<br>
The car which brought sorrow and death to the people of this city on July 4 was running at the rate of twenty-five miles an hour
when it made the plunge over the bridge. The motorman testified to this yesterday as he lay on his bed of pain in the Fannie Paddock Hospital. Others said the car was going at a much higher rate of speed.<br>
<br>
There was some dispute as to whether the car capsized when it passed over the tracks and dropped off the bridge. Some of the witnesses said it turned over and others were of the opinion that it dropped down front platform foremost.<br>
<br>
There was one thing developed by the inquest and that is that the motorman, F.L. Boehm was a comparatively new man on the road. His testimony given yesterday was very important. He had made a few trips on the line and had been under the impression on the night before the accident that he would take out another car. He tinkered with the other car and when morning came was told to take out the coach which carried so many to death. It was the largest car he had ever handled, although he had several yars experience as a motorman in Cincinnati.<br>
<br>
Boehm answerd all the questions put to him by Deputy County Attorney McMurray and the members of the coroner's jury without hesitation. He grew faint before the inquiry ended, but he made a very good witness. The testimony of George C. Bott was also taken at the hospital. His story was very similar to the one told by hm to a reporter of <B>The Ledger</B> on the morning of the wreck.<br>
<br>
The Inquest Opens.<br>
<br>
The inquest was called for l:30 o'clock yesterday in Judge Kean's courtroom. There was a large number of spectators present when Coroner Hoska rapped for order. Witnesses pf tje accodmt were few. jwpever. amd at 3"00 o'clock it was necessary to adjourn to the hospital to take the testimony of the motorman and Mr. Bott.<br>
<br>
F.A. Olds, a member of the jury was unable to be preent on account of the death of his father, F.T.Olds. The insquest was carried on with the following five persons:<br>
<br>
Peter Irving, Charles Plass, Charles Adkins, J.H. Babbitt, and F. A Turner. All of these gentlemen are well known residents of the city.<br>
<br>
Deputy Prosecuting Attorney McMurray and Major Bates repreenting the people. B.S. Grosscup and Charles S. Fogg were preent, but did not take any part in the proceeding. Superintendent Dame of the  Railroad company was also present. William Blackman, state labor and factory inspector asked a number of questions and aided the attorneys of the people.<br>
<br>
Saw the Wreck<br>
<br>
Charles Hersay of 4576 South L Street was called to the stand after Coroner Hoska opened the inquest. He said he boarded an
outgoing car on the morning of the accident and was held at the switch at 26th Street to wait for the incoming car to pass. It was a little after 8:00 o'clock and he began to worry over the delay.He asked the motorman on his car if the other car was not a little late.<br>
<br>
The motorman said that it was, and shortly afterward the car came in sight.  It jumped the track after passing the water tank, ran along one side and then left the bridge. Witness rushed over to the side of the bridge, saw the dead and the maimed in the gulch and then hurried to the laundry at 26th Street and Pacific Avenue and endeavored to telephone the police.  He could not get the station and told Central what had happened.<br>
<br>
When he returned to the street the fire engines were racing to the scene. He saw Georg Bott lying on the edge of the gulch and saw a number of injured lying on the ground below.  Witness could not remember whether the bell of the wrecked car was ringing or not, but he thought the car was running at the rate of about forty miles an hour. He saw a number of boys jump off the platform of the car before it left the bridge. One of the boys told him afterward that his arm was borken and he remarked that he was lucky to be alive.<br>
<br>
Was Aboard the Car<br>
<br>
The next witness, Samuel G. Mathers, had escaped from the doomed car with his life, but he was badly bruised. His head was bandaged and there were bandages on his right hand and wrist. He boarded the wrecked car at South Tacoma. He was then employed in the Northern Pacific Shops. When he entered the cr there were between eighty and one hundred people on board. The aisles of the car were crowded.<br>
<br>
The wintess aid he lost consciousness almost as soon as it left the track. He did not remember anything afterward until he found his wounds bandaged.<br>
<br>
The next witness, John Wedemeyer, said he was on the front plantform and jumped just as the car started down the hill. He did not hear the motorman ask for help with the brakes.<br>
<br>
David Dowden was at Tacoma Avenue anxious to take the car, but it passed without stopping.It was crowded to the platforms and he remarked at the time, that it was going too fast. He saw it go over the bridge.<br>
<br>
Loren L. Thorpe, who was called to the stand said he was employed at the Northern Pacific Shops. He boarded the car at South Tacoma. It was well filled then and more people got on as it neared the city. He jumped when near the bridge. Just before this he saw Mr. Wedemeyer jump. There were about fifteen people on the frong platform at the time.<br>

Witness said that it had been raining, but the tracks were not wet. He thought of his wife just befor e he jumped for she had arranged to come to town on another car. He was only slightly injured.<br>
<br>
The next witness was J.W. Roberts, an undertaker. He testified to having cared for a number of bodies taken from the wreck. He told of the funerals and of the identification of the deceased.<br>
<br>
C.C. Mellinger, another undertaker, testified to burying a number of the dead from the wreck.He gave the names of the victims and said they had been identified by their friends.<br>
<br>
Deputy Coroner Coombs followed. He gave the names of the dead who had been taken to Hoska's undertaking rooms and told of their identification and burial.<br>
<br>
An adjournment was taken to the Fannie Paddock hospital for the purpose of taking testimony of Motorman F.L. Boehm and George C. Bott. The jurors were escorted to the hospital by Sheriff Mills and Coroner Hoska, and the attorneys followed.<br>
<br>
The testimony of Mr. Bott was taken first. He said he had been in the habit of walking to business in this city, but the doomed car had reached him at 52nd Street and he boarded it. All went well until 33rd Street as reached. There a stop was made for a boy. The car was so crowded at the time that the little fellow could not get on.  Mr. Bott advised him to get on the cow catcher and he did. After the accident Mr. Bott saw him. He had escaped with a broken arm.<br>
<br>
Men Begin to Jump<br>
<br>
Not long after leaving Tacoma Avenue the motorman lost control of the car. Men began to jump off the platforms and the witness jumped when close to the bridge. As he lay on the ground the car turned almost on its side and seemed to be running on its right wheels.  When Mr. Bott jumped he landed on his feet and turned two or three somersaults before he came to a stop.<br>
<br>
He was on the rear platform next to the conductor when the car began its terrible race down the hill. He heard the bell ringing but could not say who was pulling the rope. At that time there were as many people aboard the car as could possibly be carried. He and other passengers conversed about the motorman having lsot control of the car. Mr. McMurray asked the witness how fast the car was running then, and he answered, "About as fast as I ever traveled."<br>
<br>
Mr.  Bott had known the conductor a few weeks, but he had not seen the motorman at all. He was of the opinion that the latter had turned on the current at the top of the hill and then had turned it off and reversed it. He was sure that the motorman had
endeavored to stop the car.<br>
<br>
The Motorman's Story<br>
<br>
F.L. Boehm, the motorman whose cot is almost opposite the one occupied by Mr. Bott was visited. He is rapidly improving and is resting very comfortably, considering his injuries. He was subjected to a very severe examiniation.<br>
<br>
Mr. McMurray, Mr. Blackman, Mr. Grosscup and members of the jury took turns questioning him. He said that on the morning of July 4 he left South Tacoma ten minutes late. A large number of people got on the car at tht place and more had boarded it at Spanaway and the Puyallup junctions. At 34th Street the witness inspected the car brakes and found them to be in good working order.<br>
<br>
A slight mist began falling as the car started down the hill on the other side of the bridge. The car began to slide and Boehm put on the brakes, but the car continued to slide. He used the sand box and reversed the current but the car was beyond his control.<br>
<br>
Several passenge who stood on the platform with him started to jump  off, but he told them to remain in their palces, because he thought he could bring the car to a stop at Tacoma Avenue.However, it ran away from him and left the track just before the curve was reached. Then it capsized over the bridge. Before it made its mad race down the hill the fuse blew out.<br>
<br>
Witness has been in the employ of the Company since June 8. He cme to this city from Cincinnati. He was employed on electric motor cars in that city and since he cme here he has been over the company's South Tacoma line about thirty times. He thought there were about eighty people on the car the day of the wreck.<br>
<br>
Altogether he has had about three years' experience as a motorman. He was employed on the Westwood line in Cincinnati and he thought the grades were just as steep there as they ar h ere.He had never had an accident before, but he admitted that he had never taken out a car as heavy as the one that was wrecked. The brakes of the car were in good condition, but he had not examined the wheels.<br>
<br>
Sand Was Working<br>
<br>
Boehm insisted that he had plenty of sand; it worked well when he used it and seemed to check the speed of the car. It did not, however, prevent the wheels from sliding.<br>
<br>
"How much time did the company allow you to break in?" asked Mr. McMurray.<br>

"Just two days," the witness replied, but he added that he had been over the line nearly thirty times before he was given a run. Mr. Moon and Mr. Neff, experienced men took him over the road. "What did  you do on the day before the accident?" asked Mr. Hoska.<br>
<br>
"I worked in the car barn," the witness and answered.<br>
<br>
He continued that he worked on car 115, thinking that he would be given charge of it the next day. Another man was giventhis car and was ordered to take out No. 116.<br>
<br>
Warned to go slow<br>
<br>
In answer to a question by Mr. Blackman, witness said there were no stop or slow down signs on the track. He had been warned that the curve near the birdge was dangerous and to go around it slowly. He thought just before the wreck occurred the car was traveling at the rate of twenty-five miles per hour.<br>
<br>
Boehm said he thought he could have stopped the cr had it been empty. The rear brake was not set, but he lost the current after leaving Tacoma Avenue.<br>
<br>
This closed his examiniation and he sank back on his pllow exhausted. Several of the jurors shook hands with him and then an adjournment was taken until 10:00 o'clock this morning in Judge Kean's court. At least two score more of witnesses are to be examined and it is probable that the inquest will last several days.<br>
<br>
("Witnesses tell of the wreck," <B>Tacoma Daily Ledger.</B> July 12, 1900).<br>
<br>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
<br>
Herbert Hunt, "Street Cars," <B>History of Tacoma.</B> p.11-12<br>
<br>
April 23. 1889, the city council had adopted ordinance No. 237 giving to Henry Villard, Paul Schulze, J. H. Cummings and others a franchise for cable railways.  May 4 the council had vacated certain portions of Cliff Avenue at the foot of Thirteenth Street and donated it to Villard and his associates for power house pur-
poses.<br>
<br>
Later in the year the Tacoma Railway & Motor Company acquired the franchises and other properties of the Villard Company but the cable railways up the hill did not materialize.  Citizens, seeing the bill districts were being retarded in development, protested,
and W. H. Fife presented a petition asking that the cableline franchise be revoked.<br>
<br>
Fife and his fellow signatories said that while they did not desire to enter the railroad business, rather than see the development of the  hill district  farther retarded, they would bind themselves to build cable lines if the council would clear  the way and give them a franchise.  A few days later the council passed an ordinance in which the company was permitted to build either electric or cable lines to K Street, within six months.<br>
<br>
It was on April 22, 1890, that the first car was run on the Point Defiance line, completed shortly before that time by Allen C. Mason and associates.  Promptly at 2.30 P. <B>M., </B>Supt.  George Balch rang the bell on the new motor and Engineer Nelson Bedell turned on the steam.  At the foot of North First Street the motor encountered grease on the rails which caused some trouble.  At I Street a stop was made for a tank of water and about two miles further on wood for fuel was taken on board.<br>
<br>
The smelter was reached a few minutes before 4 o'clock.  The return trip was made in forty minutes and the next morning regular hourly service to Burlingame's Saw Mill near the smelter was established.<br>
<br>
By the middle of July, Superintendent Cummings, of the Tacoma Railway & Motor Company had completed plans for the cable road on Thirteenth Street and had let contracts.  The A. B. Todd Company, of Tacoma, was making the cast iron cable yokes.  The cars were to be equipped for operation on both cable and electric lines and would be switched to the latter at K Street from which point they would go to Nineteenth and out that street to a point to be decided upon later.<br>
<br>
New and larger engines and dynamos bad been ordered, and the company expected to put about three hundred and fifty thousand dollars in improvements.<br>
<br>
In August the company began building the Tacoma Avenue line.  Tacoma Avenue had great expectations.  It was the first street to undertake paving of a more substantial character than planking.  The Bituminous Rock Company had 100 men and thirty teams at work between Ninth and Fifteenth streets.  On a base of concrete the company was laying about two inches of bituminous rock.  The contract price was $52,000.<br>
<br>
Fifteen minutes before noon on June 29, Frank 0. Meeker drove the last spike in the narrow gauge Tacoma & Puyallup Railroad.  The exercises were held about three miles this side of Puyallup.<br>
<br>
Herbert Hunt, "Street Cars," <B>History of Tacoma.</B>
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++<br>
FOURTH OF JULY WRECK.<br>
<br>
Herbert Hunt, "Fourth of July Street Car Disaster," <B>History of Tacoma.</B> Chicago: S.J. Clarke Publishing Company, 1916, II, p. 209-211.<br>
<br>
One of the Northwest's most disastrous street car accidents occurred on the morning of July 4, 1900, at the south end of the bridge that at that time spanned the gulch at Twenty-sixth and South C streets.<br>
<br>
Car No. 116, heavily loaded with people bound for the celebration in Tacoma ran away down the DeLin Street hill, jumped the track at the curve and plunged over the bridge and was crushed upon the logs 100 feet below.  Forty-three persons were killed and many injured.<br>
<br>
The car, in charge of Motorman F. L. Bohem and Conductor J. D. Calhoun, left South Tacoma shortly after 8 o'clock.  Soon every inch of space was occupied and passengers were clinging to the outside railings.  Shortly after leaving the top of the hill the motorman realized that the car was beyond control.  Brakes were tightly set, sand was used and the current was reversed, but without decreasing the speed of the car.<br>
<br>
Passengers jumped to the ground and the track for 300 feet was bordered with the injured.  At the bridge the car cleared the twelve-inch guard rail and plunged into the gulch.  The crash was beard for blocks.  Dead, dying and injured men, women and children, splintered wood and twisted iron were piled together in the bottom of the gulch whose steep sides made the work of rescue very difficult.  Veterans of the Philippine war, then in Tacoma for their first reunion, rendered valuable assistance.<br>
<br>
Mayor Campbell re-fused to take part in the holiday exercises and turned his attention to relief measures.  Subscription lists were started and about three thousand dollars was given.  Sheriff Mills, under instructions from Coroner Hoska, took charge of the wreck and placed deputies on guard.<br>
<br>
For months citizens had protested against the dilapidated cars.  The council had passed an ordinance regulating the speed, but the ordinance had not been enforced.  After the accident the council met and heard resolutions condemning the company for discharging old employees <B>and </B>putting new men in their places; for overloading the cars and for exceeding the speed limit.<br>
<br>
Action on the resolution was deferred <B>pending </B>the findings of the coroner's jury a few days later.  The jury, composed of Peter Irving, Charles Plass, Charles Atkins, J. H. Babbitt and F. A. Turner, spent three days in investigating and brought in one of
the most severe arraignments of a street car company ever returned.<br>
<br>
Motorman Bohem, then recovering from his injuries, testified that he had had three years' experience in Cincinnati, but that he had never had charge of a car over the DeLin Street grade until the morning of the accident.  Among the many witnesses were street railway experts from other cities who examined the tracks, which they found to be badly worn, and the flanges of some of the car wheels were thin and weak.  The track had been in use for ten years and was in bad condition.<br>
<br>
The jury found the accident due to the carelessness of Motor<B>man </B>Bohem and asserted that the "Tacoma Railway & Power Company was grossly and criminally careless and negligent in permitting said Motorman F. L. Bohem to go out on said car <B>116</B> over said dangerous grade without any previous effort to ascertain his efficiency."<br>
<br>
The company was "grossly and criminally careless in maintaining said. dangerous grade without installing any safety appliances and was also careless and lax in the maintenance of its track and equipment."<br>
<br>
The thirty-seven killed outright were Lois Drake, Annie Glasso, Lottie Suitor, Dorothy <B>Dinger, </B>Louis Dinger, Charles Moser, Albert Moser, Richard Lee, Mrs. Grossman, G. Bertoli, Ole Larson, Ole Ranseen, James Benston, Charles Davis, William <B>J. </B>Williams, John Paulis, William Nieson, Robert Steele, G. H. Gaul, Rev.  Herbert Gregory, Griffith Vanderhelden, A. L. Healy, G. M'Mullin, Mr. and Mrs. John J. Shanger-who had they lived a few days longer would have celebrated their fiftieth wedding anniversary; they were buried in the same grave.<br>
<br>
W.      H. Davis, Joseph McCann, Leroy Lingerman, Gordon Newton, Richard Sonberg, G. H. Brown,,William Hastings, Mrs. George Elliot, Conductor J. D. Calhoun, Mrs. Campbell, C. W. Woodruff and A. T. Silberg.  Edward Bray, Mrs. Emma Flamming, Floyd M. Dinger, Earl Hoskins, J. Gimel and Hilda Glasso died after being removed from the wreckage.<br>
<br>
The DeLin Street grade and the dangerous curve had been the cause of other accidents.  The first of these occurred about ten years before when two motor cars loaded with men collided, killing one man and injuring a dozen others.  Two cars of green wood hauled by a dummy engine with Nelson Bedell in charge, ran away and went over the bridge.  Other accidents had resulted in the death of two women.<br>
<br>
Damage suits arising from the wreck cost the company more than one hundred thousand dollars.  The piled-up suits almost led to the appointment of a receiver for the company.  It finally set
aside a sum exceeding one hundred thousand dollars and informed the lawyers for the injured that they could take that sum and distribute it, and that a greater demand would bring about a receivership.  The lawyers accepted the offer.<br>
<br>
Herbert Hunt, "Fourth of July Street Car Disaster," <B>History of Tacoma.</B> Chicago: S.J. Clarke Publishing Company, 1916, II, p. 209-211.<br>
<br>
