<img src="../unset.gif" align=middle>Tacoma Public Library - NorthWest Reference Databases
 - <B>Unsettling Events</B><br>
<h1>UFOs--Orting</h1>
<p>Enter a new <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/unsetng.htm">Unsettling Events search</A>, Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us/nwr/nwhome.htm">NWR Home Page</A> or Return to the <A HREF="http://www.tpl.lib.wa.us">Tacoma Public Library Home Page</A>
<hr>
<br>
UNIDENTIFIED FLYING OBJECTS - UFO' s<br>
<br>
Alice  Rushton, "Orting and the UFOs," <B>The History of the Town of Orting. 1854-1981.</B> Orting, Washington: Heritage Quest, 1989,p. 186-87.<br>
<br>
Much controversy and secrecy abounds the mysteries of the UFO's making the subject, perhaps, one that does not belong in this history of Orting.  However, some citizens of the area have sighted these objects, and the probability of the mystery being solved, grows greater with each passing day.<br>
<br>
On a cold, clear night in 1965, Mrs. Ozzie (Shari) Williams and the familys' baby-sitter, Sharon McComas, left the Williams' residence intending to drive into town.  But in leaving the house they noticed a strange buzzing noise much like the "hum" of electricity passing through electric wires but, somehow, "different.  "<br>
<br>
Mrs. William's horse began bucking and galloping in fury around the pasture.  The Great Dane pet ran in circles, unable to define the disturbance.  The sound seemed all around them.  Not able to know where it was coming from, they could not tell where to even begin looking.<br>
<br>
Then, against the hill to the east over the Carbon River, they spotted a lighted object which was hovering, not moving.  It was shamed slightly like the cigar others have reported, yet it was outlined by a hazy fog, with a brighter light shining from within.<br>
<br>
Mrs. Williams dashed into the house to call her husband, telling Miss McComas to remain in the yard.  However, Miss McComas also returned to the house.  When they all went to look a moment later, all that could be seen was a portion of the.,object, as it had moved closer toward town and was partially hidden by the hillside.<br>
<br>
The Williams immediately reported the sighting to the Air Force Base at McChord, who were able to detect the object upon their radar, and to follow it's movements for several minutes.<br>

A captain from the Air Force contacted Mrs. Williams at her home the following day.  A week later she received a questionnaire from Washington D. C., asking her to outline her viewpoint and for a detailed description.  They intimated that nothing would be related to her of their findings; and to date, this has been the case.<br>
<br>
Alice  Rushton, "Orting and the UFOs," <B>The History of the Town of Orting. 1854-1981.</B> Orting, Washington: Heritage Quest, 1989,p. 186-87.<br>
<br>
