<HR>

<H2>Seeing the Pacific Northwest with Kids<BR>
A Bibliography of Library Resources</H2>
<HR>

<H4><A HREF="kids.htm">Return to the Just For Kids Home Page<BR></a>
Return to the Especially for Parents Home Page<BR>
<A HREF="../index.htm">Return to the Tacoma Public Library Home Page</H4></a>

<P>
(The &quot;call numbers&quot; after the author's name will help
you find it at Tacoma Public Library branches. If you are at a
different library, you will need to check your library for each
title.)<HR>

<P>
<B>Kidding Around Seattle : A Young Person's Guide to the City.</B>
<BR>
Rick Steves. 917.977 ST47K <BR>
<I>Sights to see and things to do, garnished with history, geography,
and interesting trivia.</I> 
<P>
<B>Washington : Off the Beaten Path.</B> <BR>
Todd Litman. 917.97 L714W <BR>
<I>This &quot;guide to unique places&quot; leads to little-known
treasures in each area of the state, from horse-drawn trolleys
and Stonehenge to petroglyphs and petrified forests.</I> 
<P>
<B>Places to Go with Children Around Puget Sound.</B> <BR>
Elton Welke. 917.97 W458PL3 <BR>
<I>Organized by type of activity, with prices and suggested ages
included, this covers a great variety of interests: whale watching,
old forts, glass blowing, clamdigging, etc.</I> 
<P>
<B>Unique Washington : A Guide to the State's Quirks, Charisma,
and Character.</B> <BR>
Tom Barr. 917.97 B27U <BR>
<I>From trolls under bridges to steam trains, local festivals
to famous people, there are super ideas on what to explore.</I>

<P>
<B>Umbrella Guide to the Inland Empire.</B> <BR>
Bill London. 917.97 L846U <BR>
<I>One of the few guides specific to Eastern Washington, with
gold mines, fossil digging, fruit picking, and a zillion mushrooms
at WSU.</I> 
<P>
<B>Discover Washington and Seattle with Kids.</B> <BR>
Rosanne Cohn. 917.97 C661D <BR>
<I>Regional delights are listed, complete with hours, addresses,
phone numbers, and prices. See Hoquiam's castle, bonsai, a kite
museum, sleigh and hay rides, planetariums, etc.</I> 
<P>
<B>Free Campgrounds of Washington and Oregon.</B> <BR>
KiKi Canniff. 917.97 C164FR3 <BR>
<I>Need to travel cheaply with the kids? This has sites, directions,
and facilities.</I> 
<P>
<B>Camper's Guide to Washington and Oregon : A Guide to the Region's
Improved Campgrounds.</B> <BR>
KiKi Canniff. 647.94 C164CA <BR>
<I>Unlike the free facilities, these have conveniences -- and
a price.</I> 
<P>
<B>Quick Escapes in the Pacific Northwest : 40 Weekend Trips from
Portland, Seattle, and Vancouver, B.C.<BR>
</B>Marilyn McFarlane. 917.97 M164Q2 <BR>
<I>Two to three days' worth of activities at a time, these fast
family outings have something everyone can enjoy.</I> 
<P>
<B>Insider's Guide to Tacoma and Surrounding Areas of Pierce County.</B>
<BR>
Carla Lee. 917.9778 L51I 1994 <BR>
<I>This covers children's interests, as well as general sightseeing
and activities.</I> 
<P>
<B>Pocket Guide to Seattle.</B> <BR>
Duse McLean. 917.977 M223P4 <BR>
<I>Good places to visit, with costs, hours, phone numbers, etc.
See totem poles, the underground, museums, festivals, ferries,
Monorail, etc.</I> 
<P>
<B>Taking the Kids to the Pacific Northwest : Everything That's
Fun to Do and See for Kids - and Parents Too!</B> <BR>
Eileen Ogintz. 917.95 OG4T <BR>
<I>Places, fun trivia, history, games, and handy tips liven up
a guide to the region.</I> 
<P>
<B>Washington State Parks : A Complete Recreation Guide.</B> 
<BR>
Marge Mueller. 917.97 M887W <BR>
<I>This has where to go and what to do, along with hours, prices,
facilities, maps, access, and activities.</I> 
<P>
<B>Unforgettable Pacific Northwest Camping Vacations.</B> <BR>
KiKi Canniff. 917.97 C164U <BR>
<I>Seven areas offer diverse wonders : mountain trekking, &quot;ice
age&quot; landscapes, sunken ships, magnificent forests, sea lions,
the view from a 900-ft. high rock, etc.</I> 
<P>
<B>Atomic Marbles and Branding Irons : A Guide to Museums, Collections,
and Roadside Curiosities in Washington and Oregon.</B> <BR>
Harriet Baskas. 917.97 B292A <BR>
<I>If you love the weird and wonderful, don't miss this book!
A miniature Dodge City, a radio museum, mastadon tusks, a bell
collection, and the New Museum of Hysteria and Indecision are
just a few of the places that have to be seen to be believed.</I>

<P>
<B>Wandering in Washington : 470 Sites to Discover and Explore.</B>
<BR>
Sally Windom. 917.97 W724W <BR>
<I>From Beacon Rock (the U.S.'s largest monolith) to a grist mill,
oyster hatchery, historic houses, a living ghost town, and wildlife
viewing, there is something for everyone here.</I> 
<P>
<B>Around Portland with Kids.</B> <BR>
Judi Siewert. 917.95 SI19AR <BR>
<I>The book is almost a decade old but still a great guide to
the Rose City's historical and fun sites, organized by type of
activity.</I> 
<P>
<B>Green Guide, Washington : A Travel Guide to Natural Wonders.</B>
<BR>
Archie Satterfield. 917.97 SA81G <BR>
<I>If you love to watch animals, waterfalls, volcanos, mountains,
forests, and nature in general, this tells you where to find it.</I>

<P>
<B>Washington in Your Pocket.</B> <BR>
KiKi Canniff. 917.977 C164W <BR>
<I>A wonderful guide to northwestern Washington's attractions,
even if it is 10 years old : 90% + of them should still be there.</I>

<P>
<B>Washington Wildlife Viewing Guide.</B> <BR>
Joe La Tourrette. 917.97 L351W <BR>
<I>For animal lovers, a guide to where, when, how, and what you
can see : birds, elk, mountain goats, bears, etc.</I> 
<P>
<B>Guide to Mountain Bike Riding in Washington.</B> <BR>
Carla Black. 917.97 B561G <BR>
<I>For the athletic (or terminally physically fit) , this guide
has maps, trail descriptions and difficulty ratings, water availability,
time, and distance covered.</I> 
<P>
<B>2 to 22 Days in the Pacific Northwest. <BR>
</B>Richard Harris. 917.95 H243TW 1992 <BR>
<I>In a 22 day itinerary you can explore from Seattle through
the Sound, eastern Washington, the national parks, the Columbia
Gorge, Crater Lake, the Oregon coasts, the rain forests, and back
to Seattle. You can also break the trip down and take a few days
at a time.</I> 
<P>
<B>Oregon Family Adventure Guide : Great Things to See and Do
for the Whole Family.</B> <BR>
Cheryl McLean. 917.95 M223F <BR>
<I>Stuff too good to miss, organized by area and indexed by type
of activity.</I> 
<P>
<B>Seattle Cheap Eats : 300 Terrific Bargain Eateries.</B> <BR>
Kathryn Robinson. 647.95 R563SE <BR>
<I>Want to take the kids someplace special to eat? Eat your way
through the best : this lists location, vital info, and specialties
to make your mouth water and your stomach growl.</I> 
<P>
<B>Going Places : Family Getaways in the Pacific Northwest.</B>
<BR>
John Bigelow. 647.94 B481G <BR>
<I>Guide to places to stay where kids are welcome : motels, cabins,
farms, resorts. Also tells what kids can see and do, prices, and
kids' own comments.</I> 
<P>
<B>Best Hikes with Children in Western Washington and the Cascades.</B>
<BR>
Joan Burton. 917.97 B955B <BR>
<I>Geographically organized guide to hikes kids can enjoy, including
information on length, difficulty, day or overnight, when to go,
and sights.</I> 
<P>
<B>Washington Free : A Guide to the Best of the State's Cost Free
Attractions.</B> <BR>
KiKi Canniff. 917.97 C164W <BR>
<I>How to have fun for free, from agate collecting to a french
fry factory.</I> 
<P>
<B>Oregon Free : A Guide to the Best of the State's Cost Free
Attractions.</B> <BR>
KiKi Canniff. 917.95 C164O3 <BR>
<I>How to have fun in Oregon without spending money.</I> 
<P>
<B>Best Choices in the Seattle-Tacoma Area.</B> <BR>
Myles Montgomery. 917.97 M767Y <BR>
<I>Though this is mostly aimed at adults, it also tells where
to find the best bookstores, toy stores, delis, cookie shops,
and other places dear to the hearts of children.</I> 
<P>
<B>Enjoying Seattle's Parks.</B> <BR>
Brandt Morgan. 917.997 M821E <BR>
<I>Each park is described, with size, activities, bus route, history,
size, and nearby attractions.</I> 
<P>
<B>South Sound Places : A Guide to Olympia, Lacey, Tumwater and
Thurston County.</B> <BR>
Nancy Patterson. 917.977 P277S <BR>
<I>Local events, bike routes, outdoor activities, nature areas,
historical sites, and tours are among the activities suggested.</I>

<P>
<B>Old Fashioned Festivals and Community Celebrations in Washington.</B>
<BR>
Gail Folgendalen. 394 F711O <BR>
<I>You will never be at a loss for a weekend celebration with
this - something is always going on somewhere!</I> 
<P>
<B>Best Free Historical Attractions in Oregon and Washington.</B>
<BR>
KiKi Canniff. 917.95 C164B <BR>
<I>You can learn a lot of history the fun way without spending
a dime. Cheap and interesting educational ideas. </I>
<P>
<I>This booklist was prepared by Laura Shomshak, Librarian, Tacoma
Public Library</I> 
