<TITLE>HTML></TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="David Domkoski">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<IMG SRC="kids6.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A NAME="topofpage"></A> 
<HR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>Imagine wandering around the world's largest library, art museum
(and history, science and performing arts centers), university,
shopping mall and roadside attraction. In a nutshell, that's the
World Wide Web. Information and resources about everything imaginable.
Terrific places for kids and families to visit. Where do you start?
Here are some of our favorite places for parents, plus a few resources
of our own.</I> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H4><A HREF="kids.htm">Return to Just for Kids Home Page</A><BR>
<A HREF="../index.htm">Return to Tacoma Public Library's Home Page</a></H4>
<HR>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="kidtrip.htm">Seeing the Northwest with Kids:</a> <I>a bibliography of library resources</I></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Want to get out of the house and away from it all but don't have a
clue where to go? Check out these guides to discovering the Evergreen State with
kids. Day trips to the city, camping information, outdoor activities, hints for
rainy day fun...lots of ideas of where to go and what to do when you get there!</BLOCKQUOTE><LI><A HREF="http://www.yahooligans.com">Yahooligans!</a><BR>
Takes you to sites from the environment to history to trivia.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.mckinley.com/mckinley-cgi/iopcode.pl">Magellan Kidzone</a><BR>
Kidzone has 556 sites, rated by stars, of educational and recreational
interest to kids.
<LI><A HREF="http://ipl.sils.umich.edu/youth/">Internet Public Library Youth Division</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ucalgary.ca/~dkbrown/index.html">Children's Literature Web Guide</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.parentsplace.com/readroom/childnew/index.html">Children's Literature Home Page</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://mgfx.com/Kidlit/">KidLit Children's Literature Home Page</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://plainfield.bypass.com/bypass/users/union/vcchildren.html">Writing for Children</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.hmco.com/hmco/school/rdg/index.html">Reading/Language Arts Center</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.users.interport.net/~hdu/">Books for Children and More: An Editor's Site</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://sln.fi.edu/tfi/hotlists/hotlists.html">Educational Hotlists</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.cochran.com/theosite/Ksites.html">Berit's Best Sites for Children</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.vividus.com/ucis.html">Ultimate Children's Internet Sites</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://i-site.on.ca/isite/education/bk_report/booknook/default.html">Book Nook</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.kidlink.org/">KIDLINK: Global Networking for Youth 10-15</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://plaza.interport.net/kids_space/">Kids' Space</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.pbs.org:80/readingrainbow/rr.html">Reading Rainbow Home Page</a><BR>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ucalgary.ca/%7Edkbrown/awards.html">Children's Literature Award Lists</a><BR>
Find the books that won awards chosen by other children as well
as awards from the US, Canada, and England, including recent Caldecott
and Newberry Medal winners plus international awards recipients.
Also, local kids may learn how to choose their own favorite book
to win the Pacific Northwest Library Association's Young Reader's
Choice Award.
</UL>

<P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://funnelweb.utcc.utk.edu/~epling/readaloud.html">Read Aloud! A Guide to Reading Children's Books</a><BR>
Wonderful lists of books to share, split up into age groups: babies
&amp; toddlers, ages 3-5, ages 5-7, ages 7-9, ages 9-11, and ages
11-13. Also has a great list of the benefits of reading aloud
if you need to nudge or coerce your parents.
</UL>

