<H2>The Director of the Tacoma Public Library</H2>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>The Tacoma Public Library is seeking qualified candidates for
the position of Library Director. The following is information
about the position, the Tacoma Public Library, the city of Tacoma
and the Pacific Northwest, and the application process.</I> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#Tacoma">About Tacoma</A> 
<LI><A HREF="#Library">About the Tacoma Public Library</A> 
<LI><A HREF="#director">The Director of the Tacoma Public Library</A>

<LI><A HREF="#application">Application Process</A> 
<LI><A HREF="#process">Recruitment Timeline</A> 
<LI><A HREF="#ADA">Americans With Disabilities Act</A> 
</UL>
<HR>

<H3>About Tacoma<A NAME="Tacoma"></A></H3>

<P>
Tacoma, an inland coastal town, is situated in the heart of what
one early northwest explorer called, &quot;the land of the sea
in the forest.&quot; First settled in 1862, the city is surrounded
by the beautiful waters of Puget Sound, the fertile farmlands
of the Puyallup River delta, snow-capped mountains and primeval
forests. Tacoma has the sixth busiest port in the U.S., the military
communities of Fort Lewis Army Post and McChord Air Force Base,
a center for high-technology industries and extensive trade relationships
with Pacific Rim countries.
<P>
A variety of recreation facilities are available in the Puget
Sound area. City park facilities include areas for bicycling,
jogging, tennis, soccer, basketball, baseball and boating. The
700 acre Point Defiance Park, one of the nation's largest urban
parks, features a variety of gardens and hiking trails and is
home to the city's zoo and aquarium. Within short driving distances
from Tacoma are excellent ski facilities, ocean beaches and lush
rain forests. Puget Sound waters offer sports fishing, sailing,
water skiing and swimming.
<P>
The community enjoys professional theater and dance companies,
classical and contemporary musical events including a resident
symphony orchestra, chamber orchestra and opera company, numerous
community theaters, art galleries, art and historical museums,
and an AAA baseball team. The city is served by excellent public
and private educational facilities, including two private universities,
the Tacoma campus of the University of Washington, three community
colleges, and numerous trade and business schools. Only 27 miles
from Seattle, Tacoma is close enough to enjoy all the advantages
of this major metropolitan area.
<P>
Given Tacoma's location and climate, housing and living costs
are below the national average. The city is comprised of unique
neighborhoods with turn of the century homes; suburbs with stunning
water and mountain views; waterfront residences, and secluded,
wooded rural communities within easy commuting distance to the
heart of the city. The region is consistently rated as one of
the best places in the United States in which to live and raise
a family.
<H4><A HREF="#topofpage">Return to top of page</A></H4>
<HR>

<H3>About the Tacoma Public Library<A NAME="Library"></A></H3>

<P>
As one of the most important community institutions in the city,
the Tacoma Public Library plays a significant role in the quality
of life in Tacoma, the state's third largest city.
<P>
The city's 90.000 square foot downtown Main Library, renovated
and enlarged in 1991, includes the first Carnegie Library built
in the state. The 1903 library is now home to the Library's Special
Collections, community meeting rooms and the Thomas Handforth
Art Gallery. Nine branch libraries - eight of which were renovated
and enlarged through a $15.8 million Library Construction Bond
passed in 1984 - are scattered throughout the city's thriving
neighborhoods and include two large regional branch libraries.
<P>
The Library has a collection of 1.14 million items (not including
government documents); and in 1995 had a circulation of 2.493
million items (approximately 14.8 circulations per capita - the
highest in the state). The Library is fully automated with OPAC,
Internet access and many networked databases. The Tacoma Public
Library has a record of exceptional fiscal support and customer
usage.
<P>
The Tacoma Public Library is governed by an appointed 5-member
Board of Trustees , and 95% of the organization's funding comes
from budget allocations made by the Tacoma City Council from the
City of Tacoma's General Fund. The current (1995-96) biennial
operating budget is $16,734,933. Employees, except for five administrative
positions, belong to one of three separate bargaining units: two
AFSCME (American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees)
units, and one Teamsters unit.
<P>
The Tacoma Public Library has long been recognized as a national
leader in the utilization of new technology in the delivery of
library services. The Library is currently working cooperatively
with Data Research Associates (DRA) in the co-development of a
new state-of-the-art computerized circulation control system.
<P>
A snapshot of the Tacoma Public Library in 1995 - 1996 would reveal:
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>Receipt of a $2.4 million bequest from a longtime community
resident. Funds from the bequest will be used primarily for the
renovation of a branch library and the improvement of the Library's
automated infrastructure.</I> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>Completion of both a Long-Range Capital Needs study and a Strategic
Plan that, together, create a blueprint for the Library's future
growth and development.</I> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>Public internet and WWW access at the Main Library and two
regional libraries. Additional libraries will be brought on-line
dependent upon financial resources. Already available is dial-in
access to the Library's catalog and selected databases, and extensive
resources on the WWW via the Library's Home Page.</I> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>A dynamic series of programs and booksignings featuring local,
regional and national authors of books for children and adults.</I>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>Active, growing programs for children and families including
reading clubs, outreach to new parents, homeschooling workshops
and successful collaborations with the local school district.</I>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
The Tacoma Public Library offers challenging opportunities for
personal and professional growth, creative excellence and innovative
library programming.
<H4><A HREF="#topofpage">Return to top of page</A></H4>
<HR>

<H3>The Director of the Tacoma Public Library<A NAME="director"></A>
</H3>
<P>
Due to the impending August retirement of Library Director Kevin
Hegarty (who has served in that position for 20 years), the Board
of Trustees is seeking an exceptional and proven library director
with a strong public service philosophy to direct the services
and staff of this progressive and dynamic library system. This
challenging position requires an individual with a high level
of energy, vision, sensitivity and humor to serve a culturally
diverse community, and to lead a dedicated and talented library
staff. Candidates must possess significant experience in public
library administration and financial management, motivation and
innovation in providing public service, and comprehensive knowledge
of advanced library technologies and information services.
<P>
The Board of Trustees requires an articulate advocate who shares
the Board's dedication to excellence in service, library collections,
information access, and intellectual freedom; and who is willing
to make a long-term career commitment to the Tacoma Public Library.
The Library Director serves as liaison to local schools and universities,
the Tacoma community, and professional library and community organizations.
Demonstrated ability to work effectively with community leaders
in a politically challenging environment is highly valued.
<P>
The position of Library Director requires a minimum of ten years
of progressively responsible experience, five of which will have
been at the Director or Assistant Director level in a large urban
library system serving a population of 100,000 or more. A Masters
Degree in Librarianship from an ALA -accredited library school
is required.
<H5>Candidates for the position of Library Director will be expected
to have:</H5>

<UL>
<LI>Significant experience in public library administration and
financial management.
<LI>Substantial experience and a commitment to innovation in providing
public service.
<LI>Comprehensive knowledge of advanced library technologies and
information services.
<LI>Excellent written and oral communication skills; ability to
effectively reach out to a diverse range of citizens, community
groups, and local and state governments.
<LI>Strong leadership and management skills; the skill and ability
to manage change.
<LI>Demonstrated ability to work effectively with a cross section
of political, business and community leaders.
<LI>Experience in fund-raising, including work with government
and community groups to obtain grants and develop public/private
partnerships.
<LI>Demonstrated dedication to continuous improvement of a library
system.
<LI>A willingness to make a long-term career commitment to the
Tacoma Public Library.
<LI>Demonstrated experience working cooperatively with unions.
<LI>An ability to think strategically.
<LI>Experience in the development of a Library Foundation will
be an important consideration for the Board.
</UL>

<P>
The Tacoma Public Library's compensation package includes a salary
of $87,500, plus an extensive benefit package which is part of
a negotiated contract with the Board of Trustees.

<H4><A HREF="#topofpage">Return to top of page</H4></a>
<HR>

