<HEAD>
<TITLE>Nominees /1996 Murray  Morgan Prize </TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2><A NAME="topofpage"></A>Nominees for the 1996 The Murray Morgan Prize</H2>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>The Murray Morgan Prize is awarded yearly by the Tacoma Public Library
to an outstanding Washington author in recognition of a work published during
the previous year which is of high literary quality and wide interest, and
embodies the principles of narrative excellence and high standards of research
as exemplified in the distinguished career of author Murray Morgan. This year's
prize will be awarded at a special reception and lecture scheduled in early
November.</I>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"><A HREF="nwhome.htm">Northwest Room Home Page</a> | <A HREF="mmprize.htm">Morgan Prize Home Page</a> | <A HREF="../index.htm">Tacoma
Public Library Home Page</a></P>
<HR>
<H4>Books nominated for the 1996 Murray Morgan Prize are:</H4>
<H6><I>Sherman Alexie</I>
<BR><B>Reservation Blues</B></H6>
<P><I>Alexie mixes biting black humor, a healthy dose of magic, and sparkling
lyricism in this novel about the American Dream and the price of success.</I> 
</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Robert Ficken</I><BR>
<B>Rufus Woods, the Columbia River, and the Building of Modern Washington</B></H6>
<P><I>Biography of the longtime editor and publisher of the<B> Wenatchee
World </B>and one of the region's most influential journalists.</I> 
</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Delphine Haley </I><BR>
<B>Dorothy Stimson Bullitt - An Uncommon Life</B></H6>
<P><I>A richly detailed biography of the woman who created one of the nation's
first privately-owned broadcast empires.</I> 
</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Kathy Hogan, edited by Klaney Clark de nevers &amp; Lucy Hart
</I><BR>
<B>Cohassett Beach Chronicles: World War II in the Pacific Northwest</B>
</H6>
<P><I>Hogan's weekly columns for the <B>Grays Harbor Post </B>provide a
window onto how one community responded to World War II, and offers a remarkable
social history of the war at home.</I> 
</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Thom Jones</I><BR>
<B>Cold Snap</B></H6>
<P><I>A potent collection of hard-edged short stories set in Africa.</I> 
</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Jacob Jordan</I><BR>
<B>Six Seasons: A history of the Tacoma Giants (1960 - 1965)</B>
</H6>
<P><I>The story of Tacoma's baseball team, its origins, players and games.</I>

</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Jon Krakauer</I><BR>
<B>Into the Wild</B></H6>
<P><I>Krakauer, a contributing editor to <B>Outside</B> magazine, tells the
tragic story of 24-year-old Chris McCandless who walked into the Alaskan
wilderness with 10 pounds of rice, a collection of paperback books, a .22
caliber rifle and a vision.</I> 
</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Lucile McDonald, with Robert McDonald</I><BR>
<B>A Foot in the Door: The Reminiscences of Lucile McDonald</B>
</H6>
<P><I>The biography of a pioneering Northwest journalist and historian.</I> 
</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Tina Nunnally</I><BR>
<B>Maija</B></H6>
<P><I>A moving account of the immigrant experience in the Pacific Northwest.</I>

</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Keith C. Petersen</I><BR>
<B>River of Life, Channel of Death: Fish and Dams on the Lower Snake</B></H6>
<P><I>A chronicle of the building of the lower Snake River dams and the
natural resource devastation they wrought. </I>
</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Jessica Amanda Salmonson</I><BR>
<B>Phantom Waters: Northwest Legends of Rivers, Lakes &amp; Shores</B>
</H6>
<P><I>Twenty-three tales drawn from native American myths and contemporary
folk legends take readers on a mythical journey among the spirits and creatures
that haunt Northwest waters.</I> 
</P>
<HR>
<H6><I>Frank Wetzel</I><BR>
<B>Victory Gardens &amp; Barrage Balloons</B></H6>
<P><I>Bremerton during World War II as seen through the eyes of the teenagers
who fought the war through rationing, working at Puget Sound Naval Shipyards,
buying savings bonds and stamps, fighting and dying in the war.</I> 
</P>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><I>If you would like more information about the Murray Morgan Prize, or to
receive an invitation to this year's awards presentation, telephone the Tacoma
Public Library at (206) 591-5666. </I>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H4><A HREF="#topofpage">Return to top of page</A></H4>
