<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Digital Kitchen</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<BR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Summer Vegetable Salad</H2>				

<BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE>



<P><FONT SIZE=4>H</FONT>ere's another French recipe modified for healthier eating. This one would be wonderful on a summer picnic or a family pitch-in.</P>








<P><B>1 cup of diced carrots</B></P>





<P><B>1 cup of diced celery</B></P>





<P><B>1 cup of shelled peas or lima beans</B></P>





<P><B>1 cup of green beans</B></P>





<P><B>1 cup of yellow pepper</B></P>





<P><B>4 or 5 tablespoons of red or white wine vinegar salad dressing (low-fat or fat-free is best)</B></P>





<P><B>1/2 cup of low-fat or fat-free mayonnaise (Miracle Whip works too)
salt and pepper, if desired</B></P>


<BR>
<BR>



<P><B>Directions:</B></P>





<P>1. Dice the carrots and celery into pieces the size of peas. Shell the peas and discard the shells--unless you want to nibble on them while you are preparing the salad.  Next, break off the head and tail of the beans and break each into 1/2-inch pieces. Peel the pepper, if desired, discard the seeds, and cut into pieces the size of peas.</P>





<P>2. Put the carrot and the celery in cold, salted (about 1/4 teaspoon) water and bring to a boil. Simmer for about 10 minutes or until tender when poked with a fork. Drain and set aside.</P>





<P>3. Boil the peas and green beans in salted (about 1/4 teaspoon) water for about 6 minutes or until they are just tender when poked with a fork. Drain and immediately put them into a tub of cold water (this stops the cooking).  Then drain and set aside.</P>





<P>4. Mix all the vegetables in one bowl with the salad dressing. Set aside to cool before adding the mayonnaise.</P>





<P>5. Stir in just enough of the mayonnaise to lightly bind the salad together.
Refrigerate. The flavor improves as the salad marinates, so make at least 6 hours in advance.</P>





<P>Any number of vegetables can be used according to your taste. Try some of these: beets, potatoes, leeks, turnips, pearl onions, red pepper, green pepper. The object is to keep the salad colorful.</P>

<P>Copyright 1996, Enter, Inc. http://www.entermag.com</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
