<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Load 'Em Up, Move 'Em Out</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#660044" VLINK="#000000"> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=209  SRC="LoadHead.gif"></P><BR>
<BR>


<P><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Jeff Morris</A></P>


<P><FONT SIZE=4>W</FONT>hat's more stressful than seeing all your worldly possessions jammed into cardboard boxes in preparation for a move? Waiting for the cable guy would rank up there, but certainly moving from one home to another has got to be near the top of the list.</P>





<P>This is the mobile generation. Our parents didn't move this often, of course, but they had jobs, not careers. As a result of our constant migrating, moving has become something of a science. </P>





<P>Whether your moving across town or across the planet, here are some stress-reducing tips to prepare you for moving: Sit in a dark corner, assume an upright fetal position, and rock gently while sobbing for your mama. Or you can choose something more practical: 1) Locate a cheap moving company, or 2) trick your friends again.</P>





<P>I went the friend route for my first seven moves. After all, 12 cases of beer, four or five pizzas and you're there, right? And you must never forget The Moving Code of Ethics: Once the party of the first part (you) has been assisted in one move, any and all of the parties of the second part (all your friends) may call upon you to be available for every weekend move over the next two years.</P>





<P>There are many reasonable in-town moving companies that will tote your stuff across town for around $200 or so. Almost as cheap as the buddy system. You pack, move the valuable and breakable stuff, and they do everything else. Just make sure the mover you choose is bonded and insured.</P>





<P>"Bonded and insured basically means we carry the credentials and insurance to cover everything from mysterious disappearances to damaged deliveries. When our people are on the premises, we are responsible for them (the premises)," says Sharon Sugrue, customer satisfaction deptartment, A-Mrazek/United Van Lines.</P>





<P>Also, make sure you go over exactly what you'll need moved with the moving company estimator. <IMG WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=179 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="Box1.gif">They may not be able to handle things like hazardous goods or animals.</P>





<P>"We once had a guy who didn't tell us he was moving his pet iguana inside his car, which was then loaded on the truck," says Sugrue. "Iguanas can't adjust to temperature extremes and actually blew up inside the car."
</P>




<P>Of course, nothing's as sweet as having your new employer pay your moving expenses. All you have to do is find a place to live. The movers go to your old place, pack everything, take furniture apart, load the truck, drive the many miles to your new place, unpack the truck, and set up all the furniture. Total cost: $0. Your new company may even pay travel expenses for a visit to find a place to live. Remember to ask for the company's relocation policy in writing.</P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR><TD></TD>
