<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Glue Factory</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  LINK="#660044" VLINK="#000000"> 
<BR>
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=306 HEIGHT=45  SRC="gluehead.gif"></P>
<BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Bill Thornbro</A>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4>I</FONT>f excessive friction can cause severe problems in the office, imagine what it can do to your car's engine parts. You can't change co-workers every 3,000 days, but you can extend the life of your car's engine by replacing the oil every 3,000 miles. Motor oil cleans, cools and lubricates the engine.</P>

<P>"Growing up, my dad always said to keep an eye on your brake fluid and always check your oil," says Cary Cochran, who followed dad's advice and now manages a Q Lube franchise. "You can learn a lot about a car by the condition of the engine, not the outside of the car."</P>

<P>Most manufacturers and mechanics recommend changing your oil every 3,000 miles. "Some owner's manuals say you can go 7,500 miles without an oil change, but that's under 'normal driving conditions' and there's no such thing," says Cochran. "I'd say more than 80 percent of the people who come in here are doing high rpm driving on the interstate in excess of 55 or 65 mph."</P>

<P>Besides its function as a lubricant, motor oil cleans your engine. "There's all kinds of metal shavings and highway grime that can score your piston walls and lower the compression and decrease the life of your engine," says Cochran.</P>

<P>There's almost no excuse not to change your oil. Companies specializing in speedy oil changes have popped up like mushrooms in recent years, and all of them charge roughly the same amount and can get you into a service bay, change your oil and have you back on the street in nothing flat. For around $26, Cochran's employees will:</P>

<UL>
<LI>Replace your old oil with about four and a half quarts of oil 
<LI>Change the oil filter Lube the chassis 
<LI>Check and fill all fluids except coolants 
<LI>Adjust tire pressure Check differential, if applicable 
<LI>Wash the windshield.
</UL>

<P>Cochran says there are important environmental reasons to have your oil changed by professionals. Q Lube and its many competitors recycle old motor oil and some shade- tree mechanics might not. "We dispose of it properly," says Cochran.</P>

<P>Cochran says synthetic oil is better environmentally and it's good for the engine because it doesn't lose its viscosity for a long period of time. However, synthetic oil gets every bit as dirty as conventional motor oil and still needs replacing on a regular basis.</P>

<P>Full-service oil and lube stations also will replace air filters, those plastic-and-paper parts that catch dirt and road dust from entering your engine. Also, attendants at these stations will check your PCV (positive crankcase ventilation) system for clogging.  The PCV valve controls pollution from your vehicle and a clogged valve can be responsible for everything from jerky hesitation to actual stalling. Cochran says his station checks the air filters and PCV systems, advises drivers of their conditions. If the driver wishes them replaced, Cochran will do that for an additional cost. </P>

</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR><TD></TD>
<TD><A HREF="http://www.entermag.com/oct/carsncash/cnctoc.html"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="http://www.entermag.com/oct/tocart/cnc3.gif" ALT="Cars & Cash"></A></TD>

<TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><a href="http://www.entermag.com"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="http://www.entermag.com/oct/tocart/logo2.gif" ALT="Enter Magazine"></A>
</TD><TD></TD></TR>

</TABLE></CENTER>






