<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--So You Wanna Be a ... Medium</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="BBBBFF"> 
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=120  SRC="SoYouHead.gif"></P>
<BR>




<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Bill Thornbro</A></P>

<P><FONT SIZE=4>M</FONT>arie's husband died of a sudden heart attack more than 20 years ago. Marie knew she'd never find another man like Stan so she never remarried. She worked hard to put two children through college and never remarried. Marie isn't alone, however; she keeps in touch with Stan's spirit through a medium.</P>





<P>"I thought I might sell the house and get something smaller after the kids moved out," says Marie. "He told me not to. There are so many memories in the house--little things we had--and, you know, I would have lost all that. Stan said hang on to it."</P>





<P>At its most basic level, spiritualism is the belief that the dearly departed exist as spirits. Psychic communication between the living and the spirits is done through mediums, people with clairvoyant abilities who act as local service providers to the nether world. Spiritualism is a religion, true believers insist, and not nearly as dark as some might think. They say just about anybody with an open mind can learn to speak with a spook, gab with a ghost or even pal around with a poltergeist.</P>





<P>"Everyone has a psychic side," says spiritualist Judith Davis. "You may not know it. It happens sometimes on a haphazard basis."</P>





<P>Spiritualism has a rich history.  It became very popular around the Civil War, and pioneers took it to the prairies. "It really caught on with that bunch," says Willis Ward, a clairvoyant and historian. Readings, rappings and seances became common in big cities and small towns throughout the country. Even the Lincolns had more than a passing fascination with communication with the dead. Camp Chesterfield, a community of 75 to 100 spiritualists near Anderson, Ind., is celebrating its 110th year.</P>





<P>With a cathedral, a chapel, two hotels and a bookstore, quaint Camp Chesterfield is internationally famous. "We have people who come from all over the world to attend camp in the summer," says Davis, secretary to the Indiana association of spiritualists.</P>





<P>Followers can attend a "seminary" at the camp. "First you become a medium missionary. Then you advance to associate minister and go on to ordination," says Davis. "Not everyone who attends is interested in certification. Many just want to be educated."</P>





<P>But even the best spiritualists suffer a cloudy crystal ball now and then.</P>





<P>Besides being a clairvoyant, Ward, 70, also is a yoga instructor. Interestingly enough, yoga, the mystic Hindu practice that seeks harmony of mind and body while connecting with the universe through intense meditation and physical postures, can sometimes cloud his clairvoyant abilities. When asked who would win the 1996 presidential race, Ward froze. "Yogis are apolitical," he noted.</P>

<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=161  SRC="Cemetary.gif"></P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>
<BR>

