<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Let's Get Postal</TITLE></HEAD>  
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#660044" VLINK="#000000"> 
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG  SRC="postalhead.jpeg"></P><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><B><FONT SIZE=4>H</FONT>ad an absolutely awful job experience you'd like to share? Is your boss so evil you watch  <I>America's Most Wanted</I>  expecting to see his profile? We'd like to hear from you. We're looking for the funny, the outrageous or the just plain ridiculous. Let off some steam and <A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">send your stories</A> to us today.</B></P>

<!--IMG  ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="http://www.entermag.com/oct/work/postal/postaltoon.gif">

<BR>

<P><FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>he worst job I ever had wasn't a real job, it was strictly volunteer. I didn't earn a cent. You could even say the position was dangerous to my health. Three or four times a week I volunteered my services--and my tongue--to the re-election efforts of my local congressman.
</P>

 <P>This was my senior year in college and I was a political science major and very into causes and stuff. Like a lot of volunteers, I truly believed this man had vision and ideas, and I believed our district was well-served with him in Washington. I still do. But there were people on his staff I could have done without. In fact, I wondered if some of them even shared my love for our democratic process. One staffer was an obnoxious know-it-all, a control freak who tried to impress people by shouting orders and running around like a madman. Basically, his only job was to see to it we had phone numbers to call or envelopes to stuff. I'll call him Squiggy.</P>

 <P>Squiggy wouldn't even give us water or sponges to close envelopes. Each flap had to be licked. I learned to keep a large fountain Mountain Dew by my side just to keep my mouth dry, but that only worked so long. After a couple of hours my tongue would feel thick and useless, and simple speech was difficult. Other staff experienced similar results and our conversations were often hilarious.</P>

 <P>"Wad ah ooo doid fo lunge? I cad go to McDoddold's an ged uh cheedbooga."</P>

 <P>"Dad uh good idea. I wand uh Quaduhhpowder."</P>

 <P>It was something like that. Not that old Squiggy would ever know what we sounded like. He never talked to us. He told us what he wanted and we were expected to deliver. In the two months I volunteered at headquarters, he never thanked us for our work or showed any appreciation for the time we put in.</P>

 <P>The congressman stopped by three times during the campaign. Squiggy and other important people managed to get him through the building without stopping by our desks and folding tables. Once, though, the congressman broke free and came over to introduce himself.</P>

 <P>The congressman shook one volunteer's hand and said, "Thanks for your help. We can't win this election without you." The girl's tongue was thick as a brick. She just smiled and nodded her head. "What's your name?" he asked. She stopped smiling, pointed to her face and shook her head. "That's awright, I understand," the congressman said understandingly, and he turned and looked at me. "Thanks for your help, son, "he said. "Keep up the good work." I shook his hand and said, "Thad you, thir. Good lud in Novebber." The congressman took a step back, smiled and left the building quickly.</P>

 <P>I thought Squiggy was going to have a heart attack. The congressman probably believes he lost the election because of the morons at campaign headquarters--and he might be right.</P>


<P><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com"><I>Mark W.</I></A></P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>
<BR>

