<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Rewind</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#660044" VLINK="#000000"> 
<BR>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG  SRC="rewindhead.jpeg"></P>

<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Jeff Morris</A>



<P><FONT SIZE=4>O</FONT>ctober. Pleasant, cool evenings. Stunning autumn colors. Splashing entrails accented delightfully with blood-curdling shrieks. By far my favorite month of the year, October means Halloween, which, in turn, means Hollywood will once again attempt to oog us out by using the same tired, recycled horrorlines. Let's face it, with few exceptions (like <I>Silence of the Lambs</I>) movies just fail to scare us anymore. Why have we all become so numb to movie frights? Has real life become far more frightening than movies? Or is it the that nothing can be as terrifying as the lack of decent candidates in the upcoming presidential election? Either way, it makes one hunger for the days when movies could make us jump out of our skins.</P>


<BR>



<P><B><FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>he Beginning</B></P>





<P>  HALLOWEEN (1978) Jamie Lee Curtis, Donald Pleasance 90 min. Color. In the beginning, there was John Carpenter's groundbreaking <I>Halloween</I>. I don't know about you, but I distinctly remember wetting myself when Michael Myers' white mask came at us from the hall closet. This masterpiece was the first and, by far, the best of the "splatter films" and it opened the floodgates for hundreds of inferior imitators. A nonstop ride of suspense and shocks, babysitter Jamie Lee Curtis is the next target of Myers, an escaped maniac, who is on a killing spree on Halloween night.</P>





<P>Also by Carpenter: The Fog, Starman, The Thing (1982), Escape From New York </P>


<BR>



<P><B><FONT SIZE=4>C</FONT>lassic Horror</B></P>

 



<P>PYSCHO (1960) Anthony Perkins, Janet Leigh 109 min. B&W. Before Michael Myers began dusting babysitters, there was Norman Bates. As the first horror film I ever saw, this Alfred Hitchcock shocker still keeps me away from motel showers. Janet Leigh is a woman on the run who befriends Mama's boy hotel clerk Bates, played by Perkins. What is Norman's sinister secret? Will Leigh's sister, played by Vera Miles, find her? And exactly where is Mrs. Bates? The shower scene is so powerful to this day, many swear they watched Leigh knifed multiple times when the blade never actually touched her skin.
</P>




<P>Also by Hitchcock: Rope, Strangers On A Train, Rear Window, Vertigo, North By Northwest, The Birds.</P>




<BR>



<P><B><FONT SIZE=4>W</FONT>hat In THE Hell?</B></P>





<P>HELLRAISER (1987) Andrew Robinson, Clare Higgins 94 min. Color. Where would horror films be without those famous effects? And none are so famous as the stylings of Pinhead and his following of freaks. Top British horror writer Clive Barker penned and directed this chilling tale of a man trapped between life and death, and how he intends to sacrifice his brother and sister-in-law in order to reclaim his physical body. Bizarre shocker with unforgettable special effects.</P>





<P>Also by Barker: Hellraiser II and Hellraiser III: Hell On Earth, Transmutations, Rawhead Rex, Nightbreed, Candyman.</P>



<BR>




<P><B><FONT SIZE=4>O</FONT>h, They Can Hear You Scream</B></P>





<P>ALIENS (1986) Sigourney Weaver, Paul Reiser 137 min. Color. I know it's sci-fi and not horror, but it stills ranks as one of the scariest movies of all time. One of the few movies where I had to have my fingernails surgically removed from the armrests. In James Cameron's heart-stopping sequel to <I>Alien</I>, Ripley (Weaver) find herself on the way back to the infected alien planet with a battalion of Marines to rescue the colonists that have settled there in the years that Ripley was in suspended animation. Thanks to Reiser, the slimiest of corporate spawn, the marines end up in a battle for their lives. Also stars Michael Biehn, Bill Paxton and Lance Henriksen.</P>





<P>Also by Cameron: Terminator, Terminator II, The Abyss </P></BLOCKQUOTE>


<BR>

