<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Load 'Em Up, Move 'Em Out</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#660044" VLINK="#000000">  
<BR>
<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><IMG WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=207 ALIGN=LEFT SRC="Box2.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
"If a company is big enough to hire people from out of state, they usually expect some kind of relocation expenses," says Steve Loher, human resources manager, The Glennon Company. "Even junior people should be offered a moving allowance to cover most expenses like truck rental. If a company doesn't offer a letter outlining the details of their offer and their relocation policy, I strongly encourage them (the candidate) to ask for it."</P>





<P>Many of the tips below apply more to people moving to a new city with a new job, but can be adapted for in-town moves as well. And while the following checklist doesn't provide for every horror of moving, it should at least give you the basis for making your next move as smooth as possible.</P>





<P><B>Countdown: 6-8 Weeks</B></P>





<P>Arrange for movers or rent a truck. Look for a new home or apartment (Take a tape measure to give you an idea of where your things will fit). Establish credit with your new bank. Set up your auto and renter's insurance. Collect any personal records you'll need for the next few weeks--medical and dental records, insurance, etc. Ask your current doctor, vet, dentist, etc., for references in new city. Transfer club memberships. And give your new address to new employer.</P>





<P>Start collecting boxes (Ask the manager at your local supermarket). Start packing one room per week.
</P>




<P><B>Countdown: 4-6 Weeks</B></P>





<P>Forward mail: You can pick up a card at your local post office. If you plan on staying with friends or family while looking for a new place, make sure you notify the post office of your temporary address or have them hold your mail. Remember, your first-class mail is only forwarded for one year.</P>





<P>Notify magazines. They like the advance notice because subscription are typically only forwarded for 60 days.</P>





<P>Take care of some of this stuff both in the city you're moving from and the city you're moving to. The more you can get done ahead of time, the less time you have to take off of new job. Whatever you do, don't forget utility shut-off dates at your old place and turn- on dates at the new place for electric, gas, water, trash/sewer (if necessary), telephone, and cable TV.</P>





<P>Notify your doctor, dentist, vet, and insurance company. Notify business accounts like the dry cleaner, department stores, banks, finance companies and credit cards. Stop by the public library (and register to vote while you're getting your new library card). Call city hall and ask about pet licenses. Many cities have restrictions on the number of pets you can have. And don't forget the bureau of motor vehicles.</P>





<P>Also notify Social Security, the city and state income tax bureaus and the Internal Revenue Service, the newspaper boy, and book or music clubs. Tell your landlord, parents and friends of the impending move. And now's a good time to start using up things in the refridgerator.</P>





<P>Kill two birds with one stone by having a garage sale. Not only will you get rid of some stuff you don't want to take to your new place, but the extra cash might just cover a good chunk of your moving expenses.</P>





<P><B>Countdown: 2-3 Weeks</B></P>





<P>Give your car a thorough inspection before you move. Change the oil if necessary. Have a party (Why not? It helps to relax you. Just keep it simple). Drain flammables for moving company. Give away your plants (They'll just die from the move). Collect merchandise stored at the dry cleaners or in layaway. Return library books.</P>





<P><B>Countdown: 2-3 Days</B></P>





<P>Pack stuff you'll need in the car. Move any breakables early. Pack clothes. Pack snacks in the car for trips. Pack this stuff for the new place: Cleaning supplies, paper plates/plastic utensils, cooking untensils, toiletries, a hammer, screwdriver, pliers, trash bags, and telephone.</P>





<P>Empty fridge so it can dry. Pack your phone book (It sounds silly, but you'd be surprised how often you'll need to contact a company or person in your old city).</P>





<P><B>Countdown: Day Before</B></P>





<P>Disassemble anything you can. Unplug TVs, VCRs, computers, etc. (Electronics that are still hot can sustain damage from a move). Empty waterbeds. Check every room again, look in closets, drawers, etc.</P>





<P><B>Moving Day</B></P>





<P>Check maps.  Leave phone numbers. Shut the water off. Shut the furnace and air conditioning off. Shut lights off. Lock windows and doors. Leave your old house keys and garage door openers. </P>

 </BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0>
