<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Digital Kitchen</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#660044" VLINK="#000000">
<BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>	
<B><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><P>Candlelight Dinner of Burgundy Beef Tips, <BR>
Honey Glazed Carrots, Seasoned Rice,
 and dessert  <I>(perhaps a <A HREF="des1.html">Baked Apple</A>)</I>
</P></H3></B>

<P>Have you ever wanted to be romantic on short notice, and all that's in the refrigerator is beer, salsa, and chicken salad?  It's difficult, when you live alone, to be frugal with your money, but at the same time be elegant.  I have devised a menu that provides romance with easy steps, a small amount of time, and little money.  Get ready for a menu that will enhance a romantic evening!</P>



<BR>







<B>

<P>8-10 oz. of beef sirloin tips (you will probably have to buy beef sirloin 	and have the butcher cut it into pieces for you)</P>




<P>Burgundy wine or other dry red wine</P>




<P>1 red pepper</P>




<P>1 green pepper</P>




<P>1 small onion (I suggest vidalia or a white onion)</P>




<P>1 tablespoon of butter</P>




<P>1 small package of baby carrots</P>




<P>1 tablespoon of honey
White rice (enough for two people)
1 beef boullion cube</P>



<BR>
<BR>



<P>Directions</P></B>




<P>1. Cut the peppers into thin strips and discard the seeds.  Then cut the onion into thin rings.  Place enough of each for two people into a skillet with the butter.  Saute' until the veggies are hot and partially cooked, but still a bit crisp (about five minutes).  Set aside.</P>




<P>2. Heat a skillet or wok on high heat and add the beef tips.  Cook briefly on all sides to brown (this seals in the juices).  Turn the heat to medium, then add 1/4 -1/2 cup of the burgundy wine and continue to cook until the beef is no longer pink in the center.</P>




<P>3. While the beef is cooking, follow the directions for the rice and get that started.  Add the boullion to the water according to the instructions.  This will flavor the rice quite nicely.  </P>






<P>4. Go back to the beef tips while the rice is doing its thing.  Add the sauteed veggies to the tips, season to taste with salt and pepper, and turn the heat to low.</P>





<P>5. Check the rice before you move to the carrots.</P>






<P>6. The fastest and easiest way to cook these carrots is going to be in the microwave.  Put the carrots, about a teaspoon of water, and a dash of salt into a microwave safe container.  Cover with plastic wrap, place in the microwave, and cook on high for about three minutes.  After this time, poke them with a fork to test them.  They are done whenever they are as tender as you like.  Drain off the water, and add the honey.  Place the plastic wrap back over the bowl and place back inside the microwave (do not turn it on...this just provides a place to keep the carrots warm).</P>




<P>7. Check the rice.  Check the beef tips.  If everything is hot and done, you are ready to plate it up and eat it.  **If the sauce with the beef tips seems too runny, take about 1/8 to 1/4 of a teaspoon of cornstarch, mix it with a bit of cold water (to form a paste), and stir it into the beef tip mix.  This will thicken the sauce.  Continue to cook just a few minutes longer, and then serve.</P>



<P>Bon Appetit!</P></B>
<P>Copyright 1996, Enter, Inc. http://www.entermag.com</P></BLOCKQUOTE>

