<BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Dessert Coffees</H2>
<BR><BR>





<P><FONT SIZE=4>-P</FONT>ut a quarter of a vanilla bean into the bottom of a ten-cup coffee pot
before the coffee is brewed. The bean will steep in the coffee and
take on a wonderful flavor. Try serving with whipped cream and vanilla
sugar.*</P>




<P>- Place a cinnamon stick in the bottom of a ten-cup coffee pot. Follow the
directions above.</P>




<P>- Fill a coffee mug half full with coffee and then add one tablespoon of
chocolate syrup. Top with whipped cream and a sprinkle of cocoa.</P>




<P>- Use vanilla sugar or honey to sweeten your coffee.</P>




<P>- Present your guests first with their own cups of coffee, and then place a
saucer of hard candies on the table that they can drop into their coffee to
sweeten and flavor it. Good flavors to try are butterscotch, cinnamon,
peppermint, caramel, anise, vanilla, amaretto (Brachs makes a line of
International Toffees that would be excellent for this purpose).</P>





<P>For those who don't like coffee, the same ideas can be applied to hot
chocolate. This idea goes over well with youngsters.</P>





<P>*Vanilla sugar is made by burying a piece of vanilla bean in a cup or two
of sugar.  Seal both in a jar and allow to sit for a few days. Shake every
now and then to disperse the flavor.  Taste it to determine the intensity
of the vanilla flavor and use as desired.</P>





<P>Copyright 1996, Enter Inc. http://www.entermag.com</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
