<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Digital Kitchen</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<BR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><B>Kitchen Basics</B></H2>
<BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>What do you eat on the go? Is it scary to think about? Most fast-food junkies should find their diets more frightening than dirty gym socks. When you're on the run, you have to get what you can when you can, right? Wrong. Many of you are back in school, dashing from one side of campus to the other, and now is the time to learn how to keep eating healthy when time is lacking.

Here are a few rules for when you're "on the run."



<P><B>Rule #1: Plan Ahead:</B> Make a list before heading to the store. Think about your needs "on the go" as well as those for dinner. What can you pop in your bag that is satisfying but quick and healthy? Try some of these:</P>



<UL>
<LI>Fresh fruit: apples, oranges, bananas
<LI>Cereal bars: lots of flavors
<LI>Granola bars: energy on the run
<LI>Cereal-throw some in a baggy and voila! A healthy snack
<LI>Dried fruit-apricots, raisins, cranberries, etc.
<LI>Baby carrots: quick, crunchy, and healthy
<LI>Jerky: turkey, beef, whatever
<LI>Vegetable juice in a can
</UL>





<P>Before you go to bed, put one or more of these items in your backpack or purse, so you'll be prepared in your rush the next morning.</P>



<B>

<P>Rule #2: Be Prepared:</B> Keep something extra with you or in your car for those times when you don't get a lunch break. Eat your stash instead of a vending-machine "sugar glob." Even if the snack will not hold you until dinner, it will hold you until nutrition can be found in something other than a chocolate bar and a cola.</P>



<B>

<P>Rule #3: Be Smart:</B> There are times when either our stores have been depleted or we were too sleepy the night before to remember our "instant energy." Sometimes it's impossible to do anything besides fast food. In this case, be sensible and feel better about your choice. A number of places now have salad bars, grilled or roasted items, and some even have "light" menus. Use common sense...unless you left that at home with the granola bar.</P>





<P>Being on the go is rough, but eating smart can be easy. Plan ahead, be prepared and be smart. It's a lot cheaper to buy a box of eight cereal bars at the grocery than to buy eight cereal bars from a vending machine. Spend that hard earned cash on something else... like running shoes for those mad dashes across campus.</P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
