<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Digital Kitchen</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 

<BR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Healthy Eating--French Style</H2>
<BR>
<BR>



<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><FONT SIZE=4>W</FONT>hether you are trying your hand at classical French fare or are simply trying to keep the hot side hot and the cold side cold, here are a few ways to lighten your food and get you on the road to healthier eating and a happier life.</P>





<P>1. Try using non-stick pans to reduce the amount of oil or fat needed to cook with.</P>





<P>2. Saut&eacute; vegetables in water or a spritz of cooking spray instead of oil or butter. Season with herbs and spices.</P>





<P>3. Use lower-fat or no-fat ingredients when possible.</P>





<P>4. Ste am your vegetables whenever possible--this not only keeps them crisper, but they retain a lot more nutrients this way.</P>





<P>5. One cup of beans adds flavor and fiber, not to mention protein, to soups, stews and salads.</P>





<P>6. When a recipe calls for salt, either reduce the amount by half, or omit it all together and season with herbs. This lowers sodium in the diet.</P>





<P>7. If a recipe calls for whole eggs, try replacing 2 egg whites for every 1 whole egg. This lowers fat in the recipe (1 yolk has about 4 grams of fat) and cholesterol. </P>





<P>8. After cooking ground beef, place it in a strainer and rinse it with hot water to remove excess fat and grease.</P>





<P>9. When a recipe calls for butter, reduce the amount by a third and see what the result. You may be surprised. (This does not always work in baked products)</P>





<P>10. Substitute lean ground turkey or chicken for regular ground beef when possible.</P>





<P>There are many other ways to make a healthier you, but this will hopefully head you in the right direction.  Good Luck.</P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
