<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Digital Kitchen</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 

<BR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Your First Kitchen</H2>
<BR>
<BR>



<BLOCKQUOTE><P>As graduation approaches, we are all faced with the big questions.  How do I survive on my own?  What do I do?  What do I need?  Do I have what it takes to keep my underwear from turning pink in the washer?   Despite how huge the real world seems, it is possible to pull it into perspective.  Assuming your mother has helped you along until now, here is just a little more motherly advice to get you going. </P>

 



<P>The new apartment tenant must have a few things to survive in the kitchen.  Some people need more than others, but even if all you do is eat hot dogs and frozen dinners, I think the following will still apply.</P>





<P>The Absolutely Must-Have Kitchen Stuff</P>





<UL>
<LI> A small microwave (great for those frozen dinners and leftovers)
<LI>A paring knife and a chef knife (see the article in the May issue of ENTER)
<LI>Simple dishes (plates and bowls are a must; saucers and gravy boats are not)
<LI>Silverware (go for about 4 sets of knife, fork, spoon if you live alone)
<LI>Glasses (pickle and jelly jars work well here)
<LI> Basic spices (salt, pepper, cinnamon, etc.)
<LI> A sponge and dish soap (Do NOT use regular dish soap in dishwasher.  Use dishwasher soap, otherwise, you will be cleaning up suds for a long time.)
<LI> Plastic storage containers for leftovers (try Cool Whip containers and butter tubs)
<LI>One skillet and one saucepan (try to get a non-stick skillet)
<LI> A small four cup coffeepot (these also can make tea)
<LI> Dish towels and pot holders
<LI> Spoons and spatulas
</UL>




<P>As you get into your kitchen, you will probably want more than just these items, but these are the essentials.  Just think: if cavemen survived with sticks and rocks, you can survive with these simple basics.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
