<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Renting vs. Buying</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="Rentback.gif" LINK="#FF5500"> 
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=83  SRC="Renthead.gif"></P><BR>

<BR>
<BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>


<P><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Trisha Turner</A></P>




<P><FONT SIZE=4>I</FONT>f you're trying to decide whether it's better to rent or buy a home, look no further. Here's the definitive answer: It depends.
</P>




<P>"There's no rule of thumb," says Kim Donahue, education coordinator with Consumer Credit Counseling Service of Indiana. "But there are several questions people should ask themselves when deciding whether to rent or buy.</P>





<P>"First, ask, 'What is my goal?' If you are extremely mobile, as many young people are, then you don't want the burden of selling a house if you have to make a move. Second, ask, 'What is my lifestyle?' Do you really want the responsibility of taking care of your own maintenance, or is it easier to call a landlord? Once you buy a house, you are your own landlord."</P>





<P>There's always the issue of money. Here again, lifestyle should play a role in the consideration, according to experts.</P>





<P>"Young people change jobs frequently," says John Benjamin, associate professor of finance at American University in Washington. "When you buy, there's a selling commission of about six percent that you will have to stay in a home between three and five years to recover. There are also the hidden costs of home ownership--things like getting rid of termites."</P>





<P>Indeed, although house payments may appear to be no more--or even less--than the rent you're paying for that tiny apartment now, Benjamin says, don't be fooled. "You have to maintain this thing if you buy it," he says, "and, unless you're in an upper income bracket, you're not likely to benefit from using mortgage interest as a tax write-off. My vote is against buying a home as a young adult."</P>





<P>But the other side of the story, says Milwaukee real estate buyer-broker Michael Holloway, is that theoretically, "people are better off buying as soon as they have enough money to buy."</P>





<P>A brochure from North Dakota State University's extension service, "To Buy or Rent? The Choice," outlines several rules for paying for housing. For example, no more than 25-30 percent of total net monthly income should be spent on total housing expenses-- including utilities, telephone and cable television--and first-time home buyers should spend no more that two and a half times their annual gross income on a house.</P>















</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>
<BR>

