<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Calling Dr. Love</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="back.gif" TEXT="#FFFF55" LINK="#FF5500">
<BR>
<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>







<P><IMG WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=219 ALIGN=LEFT SRC="LoveHead.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Andrew Vitale</A></P><FONT SIZE=4>I</FONT>t's getting late. You flip on the radio and hear: "My girlfriend likes to use my penis to slap against her face in sex. Is something wrong with her?" Sex is never boring with Dr. Judy Kuriansky, Chris Jagger, Fuzzball and the entire cast of the late-night radio talk show <I>Love Phones</I>. It's their raw, unfiltered approach that makes the sexual side of life extremely popular with millions of listeners nationwide each night.</P>





<P>The syndicated show is a unique mixture of entertainment and self-help. It's a place where even the most bizarre aspects of sex are discussed live with compassion, sound effects, smart-ass comments and celebrity guests (or "Honorary Love Doctors" as Kuriansky, a.k.a. Dr. Judy, calls them). You would expect someone with a Ph.D. in clinical psychology, 10 years of medical experience and 15 years in the media discussing sex to stand out in a crowd. And Dr. Judy doesn't disappoint.</P>





<P>But even though her fiery red hair, glittering gold sunglasses and exposed bra scream sex, Dr. Judy says her message is less about sex than it is about people caring about each other. And her calm and understanding voice lead you to believe she means it.</P>





<P>When we caught up with Dr. Judy she was explaining to an inquisitive women the definition of the "turtle" position. Our interview began with the hole at the end of a penis as part of her explanation. Never at a loss for words--or visual aids--Dr. Judy explained why sex, love and fear are all a part of <I>Love Phones</I>.</P>





<P><B>Enter:</B> What is <I>Love Phones</I> about?</P>





<P><B>Dr. Judy:</B> We're talking about sex because people have questions about it. I've been in this business for a really long time. I'm a psychologist, but I've been a TV reporter and a radio talk-show host for 15 years, and writing columns and books and speaking to colleges all over the country. Things have not changed that much in the years that I've been doing it. People still have the same questions. They have incredible myths that are really, really bizarre.</P>





<P>I'm very secure about what I know, and that, I think, is communicated to other people. I want everybody to feel secure and confident about who they are and what they feel in life, and how they are in relationships. And that's what I've reached in my life. I know what I'm talking about when I'm on <I>Love Phones</I> and I'm giving advice because I know the range of experiences and problems and I feel that I'm the best at what I do.</P>





<P> <B>Enter:</B> Is there a message that you try to get across with every show?</P>





<P><B>Dr. Judy:</B> We're trying to get across that people should really care about each other. The three R's, they're like what's <I>Generation Sex</I>. Respect for yourself and for the other person. Responsibility, being responsible in sex, and the right to say yes and no to anything, particularly in sex. So, that's kinda the big message. The four letter word that we really try to get across ends in K is really TALK.</P>





<P>Because when I'm talking about sex I'm not really talking about sex. I'm talking about feeling good about yourself, making smart decisions, and choosing the people who are gonna love you and care about you, and self esteem.</P>





<P><B>Enter:</B> There are a lot of shows that discuss sex today. What is it that your show hits on that others don't?</P>





<P><B>Dr. Judy:</B> There is becoming more and more conservatism in this country about sex, and its this conservatism that makes people feel more threatened, fearful, ashamed and guilty about their feelings. They need a place like <I>Love Phones</I> to feel accepted so they can appreciate themselves and respect themselves. The more there is oppression, the more there is a need for expression.</P>





<P>That's why <I>Love Phones</I> is becoming more and more popular. People of all ages--and especially young people--need to feel that they are okay and normal, and they have a place where somebody can really respect how they feel without judging them, and that's what we do on <I>Love Phones</I>.</P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<BR>

