<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Glue Factory</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF5500"> 
<BR>
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=306 HEIGHT=45  SRC="gluehead.gif"></P>
<BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Bill Thornbro</A>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4>I</FONT>f an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure, a few bucks spent on an annual tune-up for your car could save you several hundred dollars in repair bills. And think how warm and cozy you'll be as you drive by all those frozen cars stalled in parking lots and driveways this winter.</P>





<P>The tune-up is an end-of-summer ritual for many drivers, although it doesn't matter when it gets done. Some mechanics, manufacturers and car dealers suggest a tune-up every 12,000 miles, but still drivers cling to the autumn tradition. When leaves begin to fall, cash registers at garages begin to jingle. In fact, because fall is tune-up season and a tune-up can take anywhere from an hour and a half to three or four hours to complete, some garages suggest calling ahead.</P>





<P>"You want to make sure it runs in the winter, so a lot of people get it done in the fall," says Terry Decker, a service manager. "Some people get it done in the summer if they know they'll be doing a lot of summer driving. And some people don't want to do it at all, so they wait until it doesn't start and then they get it done."</P>





<P>Prices for a little preventative maintenance can run as low as $35 to $40 to as much as $55 or $60, depending on the area of the country, the type of car, the garage doing the service and the depth of tune-up involved.</P>





<P>"The tune-up today is a lot different than it was, let's say, 15 years ago," says service manager Mike Bering. "With fuel-injection systems and distributor-less ignition systems, most tune-ups are basically changing the spark plugs."</P>





<P>Some tune-ups also require computer diagnostic checks, Bering adds. The typical tune-up should include:</P>



<UL>
<LI>Replacing the spark plugs
<LI>Checking all belts and hoses to make sure they're not brittle or weather-cracked.
<LI>Checking fluids and filters, distributor cap and rotor, wires, vaccum lines, PCV valves, and timing
<LI>Cleaning and lubing the carburator on cars without fuel injection
</UL>



<P>Safety checks that aren't part of a typical tune-up but should be made regularly--some even monthly--include: inspecting all exterior lights, including headlight alignment; checking the muffler and exhaust pipes; checking tires for wear and loose lug nuts; checking brakes.</P>

</BLOCKQUOTE> 
<BR>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR><TD></TD>
<TD><A HREF="http://www.entermag.com/sept/carsncash/cnctoc.html"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="http://www.entermag.com/sept/tocart/cnc3.gif" ALT="Features"></A></TD>

<TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><a href="http://www.entermag.com"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="http://www.entermag.com/sept/tocart/logo3.gif" ALT="Enter Magazine"></A>
</TD><TD></TD></TR>

</TABLE></CENTER>






