<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--So You Wanna Be a...Web Reviewer</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF5500">
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=358 HEIGHT=90  SRC="webhead.gif">
</P><BR>
<BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE> 


<P><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Andrew Vitale</A></P>

<P><IMG SRC="m.gif" ALIGN=LEFT ALT="M"><BR><BR>illions of people scurry through the twisting passages of this online world every minute and someone has to do a little house cleaning now and then.</P>


<P>"We're the janitors of the Internet," says Lauren Gonzalez, assistant editor at <I>Internet Underground </I>magazine. "That's what we do for technology." </P>





<P>For 12 to 14 hours a day, Gonzalez trudges through Web page after Web page trying to make sense of the thousands of diverse sites. Because much of what being a web reviewer is about is putting things in their place, "you have to have a librarian's mind," says Gonzalez.</P>

 



<P>According to Patrick Joseph, reviews editor at <I>The Net</I> magazine, a typical day begins by going through your e-mail for about two hours. Then, sipping on a cup of coffee with URLs in hand, you're off to explore every nook and cranny of the Internet. "You never know what you're looking at so it takes some time," says Joseph. "Things that you never looked at before you are looking at now."</P>





<P>As you discover roughly 60 sites a day without fear of the boss rushing in to see what's on your screen, keep in mind that you're going to tell the world your impressions of sites like the Ultimate Manure Spreader page, a site its creator and visitors may take very seriously. "By it's nature the rules are a little slippery. You're reviewing a site whose content you're not familiar with," says Joseph.</P>





<P>But it may be a little thing about a site that you tended to overlook for months that becomes the major striking point in a review. "You need to have ideas that spark other ideas," says Gonzalez. While it may be easy to rant on about the cool new 'zine that you found, a limit of around 100 words per review requires that you pack a lot of punch into little space. Reviewers need to write distinctly, says Joseph, and be able to do it "with some voice."</P>

 



<P>As days become weeks, and sites blur together into a never ending string of what's new, hot or what's not, you develop a clear sense of what's worth your time. "The more you do this, the more you realize if you want to review a site right away," says Gonzalez. </P>





<P>The difficult thing about spending all your time cataloging the Web is that you see a lot of sites that suck, according to Gonzalez. "But that's also the fun. It's a Catch 22 because you may find something really interesting." And that's what the job--and the Web--are all about. </P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR><TD></TD>
<TD><A HREF="http://www.entermag.com/sept/work/worktoc.html"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="http://www.entermag.com/sept/tocart/work3.gif" ALT="Work"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><a href="http://www.entermag.com"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="http://www.entermag.com/sept/tocart/logo3.gif" ALT="Enter Magazine"></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>






