<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Rewind</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF5500"> 
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG  SRC="rewindhead.jpeg"></P><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Jeff Morris</A></P>
<P>It's that wretched time of year again. The blistering dog days of summer are winding down. The days are getting shorter. It can only mean one thing: Back to school. Time to trade your tan for the healthy glow of inebriation. Instead of kegs on the beach, it's kegs at the beach parties. Oh yeah, and a few of those class things cluttering up your party schedule. Of course, if you're already out of school, September means nothing to you. After all, you rarely see the sun anyway. You'll be spending the rest of your summers chained to a desk working a fluorescent light tan. But don't fret, at least the pay is miserable. And at least we've put together a great list of videos to cheer you up.</P>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4>P</FONT>opularity 101 </P>
<P><B>Heathers</B> 1989 Winona Ryder, Christian Slater, Shannon Doherty 102 min. Color. Didn't you hate that smug clique of so-called "popular" people from high school? Didn't you just want to kill them? Welcome to the outrageously dark comedy of <I>Heathers</I>. It's <I>Breakfast Club</I> meets <I>Blue Velvet</I> as Ryder, the reluctant member of a popular quartet of girls, and her new psychotic outsider boyfriend, Slater, accidentally kill the lead Heather, setting off a rash of suicides by status-conscious teens looking for posthumous popularity.</P>
<P>
Also with Ryder: <I>Mermaids, Edward Scissorhands, Dracula</I></P>
<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>M</FONT>ost likely to succeed<P> <B>Back To School</B> 1986 Rodney Dangerfield, Robert Downey Jr. 96 min. Color. Think about how cool school would have been if you were a millionaire? You could have actually spent your book money on books instead of 12-packs. Dangerfield knows how it works in this uproarious tale of a self-made millionaire who decides to better himself by entering college with his son. Also with Keith Gordon, Sally Kellerman.</P>
<P>Also with Dangerfield: <I>The Projectionist, Easy Money, Ladybugs</I></P>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4>E</FONT>xtracurricular Studies</P>
 <P><B>Ferris Bueller's Day Off</B> 1986 Matthew Broderick, Jeffrey Jones 103 min. Color. Broderick is Ferris, a Chicago high school student who definitely has his priorities straight: classes should never get in the way of having fun. With his best girl and best friend piled into a borrowed vintage roadster, Ferris stays just one jump ahead of his moronic high school principal who lives to send Ferris to summer school. Mia Sara and Jennifer Grey also star in this hilarious John Hughes classic.</P>
<P>
Also by Hughes: <I>Sixteen Candles, The Breakfast Club, Weird Science, Pretty In Pink.</I></P>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4>W</FONT>hew! It's so hot, I could kill someone</P>
<B>Dog Day Afternoon</B> 1975 Al Pacino, John Cazale 130 min. Color One last fling in the summer heat with one of the hottest Pacino films. Based on a true story, Pacino turns in a outstanding performance as a confused criminal who holds hostages in a bank in exchange for money to pay for his lover's sex-change operation. Of course, in the grandest tradition of our sick society, he becomes a media hero for his trouble. Cazale is celluloid perfection as Pacino's dimwitted partner. Supporting cast includes Charles Durning and Chris Sarandon.
</P>



<P>
Also with Pacino: The <I>Godfather</I> trilogy, <I>Serpico, ...And Justice For All, Scarface, Sea Of Love, Frankie & Johnny, Scent of a Woman</I></P>


</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

