<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Renting vs. Buying</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="Rentback.gif" LINK="#FF5500"> 
<BR>
<BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>


<P><!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=250 HEIGHT=217 ALIGN=LEFT SRC="Rent.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR><BR>
<BR>
Fullhart says a first-time homebuyer shouldn't bring anything "to the table except themselves." She talks of a short "sequence of things they should do." First, there must be a "willingness to take on responsibility." Secondly, a new homebuyer should go to a mortgage company, bank or other lender and get "prequalified to find out how much they can afford. Then they'll know if maybe they should wait longer, save up for a better downpayment."</P>

<P>You can think of the downpayment as the homeowner's version of the renter's damage deposit and one month's rent in advance. The difference, of course, is thousands of dollars versus a few hundred. That downpayment can range from three percent to 20 percent of the price, says Fullhart. "Sometimes you can do a quick qualification over the phone, but you have to be honest (when asked financial questions). Honesty is very important."</P>





<P>If you think you can afford to buy, Holloway encourages doing so. That does not mean, however, that you should look to buy that four-bedroom home with the huge yard like the one where you grew up.</P>





<P>"People forget it took mom and dad 30 years to afford the house they live in," he says. He suggests buying a duplex, a building with more than one housing unit, and renting one of the units out. He speaks from experience. The profit he has made off of the duplex he bought 16 years ago is now his down payment on a condominium in Vail, Colorado.</P>





<P>Are condominiums yet another alternative to renting? Absolutely, says Fullhart. "Remember, a condo is purchasing real estate. You do get a deed." Any advantage in condo living isn't necessarily measured in dollars and cents, she adds. "I won't say it's more expensive. It's just not any cheaper. The biggest advantage to condos, as I see it, is somebody is taking care of the external maintenance."</P>





<P><IMG WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=166 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="Sale.gif">Holloway also argues against the theory that home ownership will tie you down. "I might move away tomorrow. I might also get hit by a bus, right? I know people who've said they're going to move for 20 years. They haven't."</P>





<P>Still, Washington University's Benjamin suggests it's wiser to put money in other investments before the age of 30 when you consider what he calls "the hassle factor" of owning your own home.</P>





<P>But what's best for you? Consumer Credit Counseling Service's Donahue says only you know that answer. The bottom line is simple, she says.</P>





<P>"Make sure you do all the homework you can." </P>



</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>
<BR>

