<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Breathe Easy</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000"  LINK="#1EDC19"> 



<BR>
<BR>
<BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE>


<P></P>



<P><IMG WIDTH=272 HEIGHT=232  SRC="breathehead.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Don Orban</A><BR><BR>
<BR>


<IMG WIDTH=38 HEIGHT=46 ALT="L"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="ldrop.gif">ook at any magazine, or watch TV and you'll see that human beings, must be pretty foul creatures. It seems we emit smells that offend anyone in our immediate vicinity. For years, Madison Avenue targeted the self-consciousness of consumers by advertising the "latest" or "newest" cure for one of these problems, bad breath.</P>


	


<P>For years, the prescribed cure for bad breath was brushing and using mouthwash (you decide - "mediciney" or "minty"). Dr. Howard Smith's Fresh Breath and Dr. Harold Katz's California and New York Breath Centers have grabbed a lot of media attention in the less than three years that they have been in existence. According to Dr. Katz, "The demand for our services has stunned us. We have successfully treated over 3,000 people since we started. In 1995 alone, we received over 10,000 inquiries [and] the number grows exponentially daily."</P>


	


<P>Halitosis, as the condition is formally known as, afflicts a wide spectrum of people. Dr. Katz estimates about 20 percent of the general population has this condition, with most of his patients falling in the 25-75 year old range. "However, we have seen patients as young as six, and as old as 86. It is evenly distributed between the sexes." says Katz "As far as socio-economic or other determinants, we have attorneys, bank presidents, physicians, computer <IMG WIDTH=133 HEIGHT=289 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="breath3.gif"> executives, teachers, scientists, etc. as patients. We also have dentists who have come to us for this problem." This condition is truly an "equal opportunity problem" Katz says.</P>


	


<P>Dr. Smith agrees that the condition is not limited to any single social or biological constraint, but he has found that "it has been our experience that middle-aged females are most likely to seek treatment, perhaps more so because of the social ramifications of living with this condition." Both doctors report requests for help and information from around the world.</P>


	


<P>Opinions for treatment vary. The toothpaste and mouthwash manufacturers continue to push their products, but the latest research is showing that these products have limited effects, and in some cases may only exacerbate the problem. Mouthwashes that contain alcohol will cause the mouth to dry out, one of the causes of halitosis. Dr. Katz recommends sufferers of this condition avoid alcohol, "whether it says Budweiser or Listerine on the label."</P>


	


<P>According to Dr. Smith, "80 percent of bad breath originates from the mouth, and 80 percent of these cases originate from the back of the tongue." He attributes this to numerous causes, including "poor oral hygiene, a diet that includes spicy foods, or dishes with a lot of garlic, onions or different cultural spices; a poor diet [lacking] the proper foods from the suggested food groups; not enough liquid intake (i.e. water); medications that tend to cause a dry mouth; and lastly, different systemic conditions which may lead to bad breath, such as infections in the lungs, stomach ulcers, or upper airway infections."</P>


	


<P>The actual odor can be attributed to "anaerobic bacteria that are located on the back of the tongue, and in the throat," Katz says. He adds that these bacteria are not "infectious or bad bacteria," but actually have a function in the digestion of food particles, "particularly proteins, by breaking them down into smaller chemical units, so that the digestion process is assisted."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

