<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--A Debtor's Prison</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="prisonhead.jpeg">
</P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<P><IMG ALT="T"ALIGN=BASELINE SRC="t.jpeg">psychic on the other end of the phone had just shown remarkable insight into your existence.</P>





<P>"You're in debt way over your head."
</P>




<P>But how could they know? Could Dionne Warwick and her psychic friends hold some remarkable power? No.</P>





<P>"Sir, your VISA was just rejected. Do you have another credit card perhaps?" the psychic questioned. </P>





<P>Why yes, you do. Several in fact, but they all appear to be maxed out at the moment.</P>





<P>Could this be you? Grasping for any attempt to straighten out the mess of debt you created in college. For $5.95 a minute psychic hotlines are not your last bastion of hope. You can be your own savior, or at the very least find someone to help you out of the ever-growing hole of debt.</P>





<P><B>Yeah, whatever. What options do    <!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG ALIGN=BASELINE SRC="i.jpeg">have?</B></P>



<P>The first step to ending the debt nightmare is to contact your creditors directly and throw yourself onto their mercy, according to Stephen Rhode, president of
<A HREF="http://www.debt-experts.com/">Debt Counselors of America</A> (800-680-3328), a non-profit credit counseling agency.  </P>





<P>By contacting your creditors you can fend off any calls or stop the ones that may already be coming. Creditors don't enjoy trying to track down their delinquent accounts, and most are willing to work with you to establish a payment plan. But be ready to answer some tough questions about why you haven't been paying. </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>
