<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Just looking, thanks</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<!-- Graphic Tag -->
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG  SRC="lookhead2.jpeg"><P>








<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<IMG  SRC="lookpic1.jpeg" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<P>So you've found what may be your next car and it's used. Before you drive into the sunset with the wind blowing through your hair, you need to carefully examine the car first.</P>






<P>We spoke with LemonBusters of Texas and Lemon Aid of Pennsylvania, two professional used car inspection services, about how to inspect a used car for potential signs of wear, tear, and damage. </P>





<P>Before you begin any inspection, make sure that a "Buyer's Guide" is displayed on the car if it is at a dealer. Federal law requires dealers to display the "Buyer's Guide" sticker to give buyers the warranty information. Read it carefully, because in many states the words "as is" declares a denial of warranty coverage, according to Consumer Reports.</P>





<P>If the car is from a private seller, ask for the service records, repair bill, or warranty information. If they look perplexed or can't show any documentation you may want to begin looking elsewhere for a used car.</P>



<P>If you're satisfied with the information you have gotten so far, it's time to begin a thorough inspection of the vehicle.</P>





<B><P>Start the engine<BR></B>

Begin by starting the car and letting it run during the entire time you're checking things out.</P>





<P>"Sometimes people will try to mask engine problems by putting very heavy oil in the engine to quite it down," said Greg Geske of Lemon Aid. "You will be able to hear any problems by letting it run for a while."</P>





<P>Some sounds such as ticking may indicate stuck valves or lifters, and a knocking sound could be more severe.</P>





<B><P>Get inside<BR></B>

Go over every inch of the interior of the car. If there is a button or switch use it and check for and any signs of water stains or moisture. Explaining to a cop you bought this car and didn't know the brake lights were out may not get you out of a ticket.</P>




<B><P>Under the hood<BR></B>

Check all of the fluids and look for any leaks. This includes the oil, transmission, radiator (shut engine off for this and let it cool down), power steering, and brake fluids.</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>




<BR>
<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD></TD><TD><A HREF="/august/carsncash/cnctoc.html"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/storycnc.gif" ALT="Cars & Cash"></A></TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><a href="http://www.entermag.com"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/logo.gif" ALT="Enter Magazine's Survival Guide"></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><A HREF="looking2.html"><IMG WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=29  SRC="/august/tocart/ForwardMove.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="forward"></A></TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>




