<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Leasing: The Fine Print</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG  SRC="leasehead.jpeg"></P>

<BR>
<BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>here are people for whom leasing a new car might be an attractive option. But leasing isn't for the faint of heart. If you qualify, the process and terms of the deal can be complicated enough to drive the most experienced CPAs and tax attorneys bonkers, and the average consumers, if they're not careful, can find themselves driven straight to the cleaners.</P>





<P>To give you an example of what you're in for when leasing,  Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine quoted a general manager of a large import-make dealership: "Unfortunately, buyers are not really wise on leasing right now...If you are willing to pay $250 a month, I can make a lot of money on you. If you haven't compared me with other dealers on the details, I can probably really take advantage of you...if I were that kind of guy." </P>





<P>Leasing is all about the fine print so it's important to decide if this option is right for you. According to <I>Car Buyer's and Leaser's Negotiating Bible</I> by W. James Bragg (1996 Random House) there are advantages.</P>




<UL>
<LI>Monthly payments are lower.
<LI>You can drive a new car every two years.
<LI>You can drive cars you couldn't afford to buy.
<LI>Rarely a down payment.
</UL>



<P>Coming straight out of college, the lack of a down payment and low monthly payments are very attractive, but according to Bragg there are also disadvantages.</P>





<P>
<UL>
<LI>Leasing usually means keeping your miles under 15,000 a year.
<LI>You have zero equity in the car.
<LI>Leased cars aren't covered by "lemon laws."
<LI>End-of-lease charges can be killers.
</UL></P>





<P>Mileage can kill any initial cost advantage you may have if you drive a lot. Written into every lease is a cost-per-mile if you exceed the maximum allotment. The charge ranges from 10 to 15 cents a mile.
</P>




<P>If you're ready to look at leasing as an option, always remember to get the best price you can on the car first. Even if you know what payment your monthly budget allows, and you're set on leasing, you'll lose any negotiating advantage if you let the dealer know that payment up front. Make sure you're getting the car and options you want at what you believe is a good price. Consult new-car pricing guides such as Edmunds and Consumer Digest for option packages and retail prices. </P></BLOCKQUOTE>


<BR>
<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD></TD><TD><A HREF="/august/carsncash/cnctoc.html"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/storycnc.gif" ALT="Cars & Cash"></A></TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><a href="http://www.entermag.com"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/logo.gif" ALT="Enter Magazine's Survival Guide"></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><A HREF="lease2.html"><IMG WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=29  SRC="/august/tocart/ForwardMove.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="forward"></A></TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>


</BODY> 
