<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--Too Good To Be True?</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00EE66" TEXT="#000000">

<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=366 HEIGHT=151  SRC="toogoodhead.gif"></P><BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE><P><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Bill Thornbro</A></P>

<BR>


<P><IMG WIDTH=41 HEIGHT=60 ALT="T"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="tdrop.gif">he ads and infomercials promise easy money for little work and minimal investment. Some of them are legitimate business deals, some are outright ripoffs. Many straddle the ethical-legal line. Nearly all of them can leave an unsuspecting individual with third-degree burns.</P>





<P>You've seen the ads. Often tucked away in the employment section of newspaper classifieds or near the back of cheap supermarket tabloids, the ads suggest thousands--even millions--of dollars can be made working part time out of the home. "Learn the secrets that made me a millionaire!" is a common claim. You won't learn those secrets for free, of course. You have to buy the book, kit, audio or video tapes. They're not cheap.</P>





<P>Nobody knows exactly how many people fall prey to these job or investment scams every year. An investigator with a state attorney general's office said many people would rather forget the experience and right off their lost investment rather than admit they bought the exaggerated claims of a fly-by-night outfit. Who wants to admit they're a sucker?</P>





<P>Even victims who seek justice will have a difficult time. "The laws are there and they can be enforced," says law professor James P. Nehf., "but the first problem is finding the perpetrator." There are consumer protection laws in every state, but the con artists and grifters seldom have a permanent address; they often rely on mail drops and post office boxes, travel frequently and change company names when they fear the law approaching.</P>





<P>To make matters worse, "consumer fraud is never very high on a state legislator's agenda," says Nehf. "It's not a high enough priority to get legislation that's helpful." Victims are not "getting ripped off for thousands and thousands of dollars, they're getting ripped off for a few hundred dollars."</P>





<P>That can be very frustrating to a person who hoped an ad might pave the way to riches--or at least provide the lucrative second income needed to get out of debt. "It's as if there's nothing you can do. To have a legal remedy but not be practically able to pursue it, it's like there's no remedy at all," says Nehf.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD></TD><TD><A HREF="/august/carsncash/cnctoc.html"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/storycnc.gif" ALT="Cars & Cash"></A></TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><a href="http://www.entermag.com"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/logo.gif" ALT="Enter Magazine's Survival Guide"></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><A HREF="toogood2.html"><IMG WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=29  SRC="/august/tocart/ForwardMove.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="forward"></A></TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

