<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Glue Factory</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#FF5533"> 
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG  SRC="gluehead.jpeg"></P><BR>
<BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE=4>E</FONT>ach month The Glue Factory is devoted to covering topics that relate to keeping your car properly maintained and (nearly) hassle free. If you have questions about auto maintenance, send them to  <A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">us</A>.  </P>










<P><B>Question:</B> My tires are losing traction and are getting pretty bald, but I don't have $300 to $500 to put four new tires on my car. What can I do before I get a flat that leaves me stranded?</P>









<P><B>Answer:</B> New tire prices can be intimidating and cost nearly as much as a month's rent. If you are looking for a good set of tires that will get you by for a year or so, then look into used tires. At many junk yards, gas stations and some tire dealerships, you can find a lot of tires with 50-to-90 percent of the tread left on them. It is not uncommon to replace all four tires for less than $100.</P>





<P>Although used tires are a bargain, there are some things you need to do before buying.</P>





<P>1. Visually inspect the tires for bulges, patches or cracking. Then run your hand across the tire to feel for unevenness. 
</P>




<P>2. Look for uneven wear. The best way to check is to bring along a penny. Place the penny between the tread on one side of the tire and mark with your thumb how deep the penny is into the tread. Then do the same with the other side of the tire. Make sure there is not a lot of difference between the depth on each side. </P>





<P>3. Check the inside of the tire to see if there is ground-up rubber. Shavings inside a tire indicate it was driven when it was flat.</P>





<P>According to one mechanic: "I found a set of four used tires for my truck and have driven 35,000 miles on them. I only paid $40 for all four."</P>








<P><IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="gluepic1.jpeg"><BR>
<B>Quick Tip:</B> The string of numbers on the side of the tire refer to its size. For example, 205/55R15 S means: 205--the cross-secion width of the tire in millimeters, 55--the Aspect ratio of the height to width, and 15-- the diameter of the rim in inches. The letter crammed in between the numbers refers to Radial Construction. The letter at the end refers to the highest speed a tire is designed to go. The letter designation's top speed, in miles per hour (mph) is: S--112 mph, T--118 mph, U--124 mph, H--130 mph, V--149 mph, Z--over 149 mph.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>
<BR>


<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD></TD><TD><A HREF="/august/carsncash/cnctoc.html"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/storycnc.gif" ALT="Cars & Cash"></A></TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><a href="http://www.entermag.com"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/logo.gif" ALT="Enter Magazine's Survival Guide"></A>
</TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>



