<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Glue Factory</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#1EDC19"> 

<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=306 HEIGHT=45  SRC="gluehead.gif"></P>
<BR>



<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE=4>E</FONT>ach month The Glue Factory covers topics designed to help you keep your car properly maintained and (nearly) hassle free. If you have questions about auto maintenance, send them to <A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">Enter</A>.</P>


 
 

<P><B>Question:</B>  I'm driving a used car and have no idea when the air conditioning was last recharged. How much can I expect to pay?</P>


 
 

<P><B>Answer:</B>  As long as you think your AC adequately cools your car, leave it alone. Unless there's a leak or seepage, most cars can go years before the AC needs recharging.</P>


 
 

<P>"I know people with '87 and '88 cars and they've never touched it," says Mike Bunch, a service manager. "If it's cold every year, there's no point in checking it. It's one of those things that if it's not broke don't fix it."</P>


 
 

<P>Standard AC draws hot air from the outside and cools it with a chemical before releasing the chilled air in the car. Depending on the make and model, you should feel a temperature change in 15 to 30 seconds. Service technicians check the AC's cooling ability by inserting what looks like a meat thermometer in one of the centerally located vents for a minute or two. Bunch says the temp should run 42 to 48 degrees.</P>


 
 

<P>Costs will vary around the country, but Bunch says labor at his shop will be about $40. Typical jobs require between two and four pounds of chemical coolant. One chemical is R12, commonly called Freon. Freon is a mixture of fluorine, carbon and usually chlorine and has been determined to damage the Ozone layer. Its price has skyrocketed lately and now runs about $25.50 a pound. "Supply and demand is driving prices up," says Bunch.</P>


 
 
 

<P>Freon's chemical cousin, the more environmentally friendly R134A, costs less than $20 in some places. Bunch sells it for $18.75.</P>


 
 

<P>Eventually all cars will use R134A. Drivers won't be switching from one chemical to another, however. "It's not going to be as simple as that," warns Bunch. Some cars will require adjusting of some fittings before going to the new chemical; it'll cost about the same as a recharging. Others, though, will need parts of the system replaced, and that could be $300 to $400 or more.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>

<BR>
<BR>


<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD></TD><TD><A HREF="/august/carsncash/cnctoc.html"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/storycnc.gif" ALT="Cars & Cash"></A></TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><a href="http://www.entermag.com"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/logo.gif" ALT="Enter Magazine's Survival Guide"></A>
</TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>



</BODY> 
