<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Awful Office</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=260 HEIGHT=157  SRC="officehead.gif"></P><BR>



<BLOCKQUOTE><P><FONT SIZE=4>T</FONT>here is no hell quite like an office where everyone hates each other. No cheerful "good morning" by the communal Mr. Coffee. Whispering cliques abound. Bosses preach teamwork in quiet meetings but practice favoritism when it counts. Anger and resentment, the twin viruses that kill productivity, thrive under weak, disinterested or incompetent management.</P>





<P>Hank Miller has heard all the nightmarish stories. As a manager of staff training, Miller leads workshops for university employees on workplace violence. His three-hour sessions are designed to "sensitize supervisors to violence early warning signals," but his experience in human resources has taught him that things don't have to reach that extreme before an office suffers emotionally.</P>


<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="scream.jpeg">


<P>"We need to communicate," says Miller. "Teamwork is more important than ever and so is group interaction. It's more important that people communicate and be open with each other."</P>





<P>Miller says "supervisors can control situations before they get out of hand," but that's assuming the supervisors aren't the cause of the problem. "That can be a little more difficult," he adds. "There are people who are technically proficient but who haven't been adequately trained in interpersonal skills or dealing with subordinates."</P>





<P>Like most HR personnel, Miller prefers "more informal" ways of correcting problems or dealing with the inevitable clash of personalities. "You need open communication to clear the air," he says.</P>





<P>Any company that believes all its internal squabbles are self-correcting is asking for disintegrating employee morale. Imagine a carpeted gulag full of brooding young malcontents, bitter mid-level managers stuck in office purgatory, and abusive bosses who openly pit workers against each other in almost gladiatorial battle.</P>





<P>Smart companies have grievance processes in place where employees can "go through the channels all the way through to arbitration, if that's necessary," says Miller. If the problem is with the boss, though, employees need to think long and hard. "It's a natural inclination that people would be apprehensive about going to a supervisor with problems with that supervisor."</P></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>


<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD></TD><TD><A HREF="/august/work/worktoc.html"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/storywork.gif" ALT="Work"></A></TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><a href="http://www.entermag.com"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/logo.gif" ALT="Enter Magazine's Survival Guide"></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><A HREF="awful2.html"><IMG WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=29  SRC="/august/tocart/ForwardMove.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="forward"></A></TD></TR>
