<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--The Peace Corps Alternative</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="back.gif" TEXT="#FFC024" LINK="#00EE66"> 
<BR>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="peacehead.gif"></P><BR>
<BR>



<BLOCKQUOTE>



<P><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Heather Brophy</A></P>

<BR>


<P><IMG WIDTH=53 HEIGHT=50 ALT="W"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="wdrop.gif">ith 7,000 volunteers serving in 93 countries, a lot of people apparently love the "the toughest job you'll ever love," the Peace Corps, the number one employer of college graduates.</P>





<P>Many people envision a hut deep in a Third World forest when they think of the Peace Corps. But today a volunteer is just as likely to live in an apartment building and work in an office complete with phones and computers. For thirty-five years the United States has been sending volunteers to countries to help share technical knowledge as well as build understanding between countries. </P>

 



<P>While being a volunteer is not the most financially rewarding position--you will  earn mere peanuts--it does offer an opportunity to gain international experience, technical skills and, in most cases, a new language. Plus, you will have an advantage in getting federal government employment later. It even lets you put off the "real world" a little while longer. Experience of a lifetime--<IMG WIDTH=227 HEIGHT=219 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="peace1.gif">travel, adventure, helping others--what else could you want? But is it the career move to make? And how difficult is it to join?</P>





<P>Only four out of every 10 applicants are invited to serve. The first step to joining the Peace Corps is to get an application. Call or write the Peace Corps office, or visit their web page and ask for one to be sent to you. By the end of the summer you will even be able to download it from the web page. The application is long and Michael Wiedel, recruitment coordinator of the Chicago regional  office, suggests filling it out in detail and spending a lot of time on it.</P>





<P>"We're looking for interest and knowledge--through volunteering and education--that qualify (the applicant) for a position," says Wiedel.</P>





<P>Most volunteers work in four basic areas--agriculture, education, health or business. These and related degrees are helpful in obtaining a nomination.  There are also programs which do not require a specific degree but are based on work or volunteer experience. Teaching a vocational trade like carpentry is one example. Other experiences and certifications can also help so be sure to include CPR training and that vegetable garden you had last summer. Language skills are also a bonus, especially French and Spanish. While a college degree is not required, most volunteers are college graduates. And you must be at least 18 and a US citizen.</P>





<P>The next step is an interview, done either by phone or in person at a regional office or college campus. Two soon-to-be volunteers both felt face-to-face interviews were better.</P>





<P>Colleen Turner went to Chicago for her interview. She felt it gave her a chance to connect with her interviewer. She also felt she had more time with her interviewer compared to friends who interviewed on campus.</P>



<P>Throughout his application, Ahmad Ali never saw or spoke in person with anyone. Instead, he conducted his interview over the phone through the Dallas regional office while he lived in Santa Fe, New Mexico. While he was nominated, he felt a face-to-face interview would have given him a chance to really show his recruiter why he wanted to join the Corps.</P>





<P>Wiedel says recruiters are looking for someone committed and patient, with strong leadership skills as well as specific skills that qualify her or him for a  position.</P>





<P>Patricia Garamendi, associate director of recruitment, agrees the Peace Corps wants motivated, committed people with cross-cultural sensitivity because "all the skills in the world don't do any good without cross-cultural sensitivity." She says if you don't qualify for a position due to a lack of experience, you can work with the recruiter by doing some volunteer work--like six months of ESL (English as a Second Language) tutoring--to qualify for a position.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>


