<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--So you wanna be...a beer taster</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 


<TABLE>
<TR><TD></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP><IMG  SRC="mug3.jpeg"></TD><TD COLSPAN=10><!--this is space here--!></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP><P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=320 HEIGHT=34  SRC="so.gif">
<IMG WIDTH=196 HEIGHT=24  SRC="byline.gif"></P>

<BR>
<BR>



<P><FONT SIZE=4>S</FONT>ounds like the perfect job, huh? After all, what could be better training than four (five, six, seven) years of college? I know I spent several Saturday nights trying to match my blood alcohol level with my GPA. I put in countless hours sleeping in dumpsters clutching 40-ouncers in both hands. And I took advantage of every opportunity to turn my liver into something resembling a fossilized lima bean. But I was surprised to find out that becoming a beer taster is hard work. If you think your ability to bong several metric tons of Schlitz will land you a job like this, it's time to sober up.</P>





<P>According to Donald Kent, a salesman for a midwestern beer distributor, most professional beer tasters are authors. Professional beer tasters "usually work for publishing houses or publications. Basically, they're specialized food critics," Kent says. "They travel the world tasting beer and writing about it. So it's probably a good idea to have some kind of background in English or journalism. And on top of that, many have experience as a brewmaster's assistant." 	</P>





<P>Brewmaster's assistant? That didn't sound very arduous. I found out, however, that becoming a brewmaster's assistant involves two more years of studying in a brewing academy. I envisioned classes like Foam 101 and Belching: Beer Remembered. But the curriculum includes a steady schedule of chemistry, biology and other yeasty sciences. So you see, becoming one of these beer-tasting food critics is quite a commitment.</P>

 



<P>I wasn't born yesterday. I watch TV, and I happen to know that every brewery needs someone within the facility to taste their beer. This was my next line of inquiry. Unfortunately, the outcome was similar. "This type of tasting is usually done in the brewery by a quality control panel, consisting mostly of the brewmasters themselves," Kent says. "But occasionally they do use test markets." </P>





<P>Ah, a ray of hope. I jumped on that tidbit like drunken sailor on a beer nut. According to Kent, when breweries are testing out a new beer, they take their product to the people. If you're lucky enough to be part of the demographic they're targeting, you may just get a taste. This won't lead to a job, but it may lead to a new favorite beer. However, the breweries have to find you. Pull up a stool and grab a brew--you might be waiting a while.</P>





<P>Don't lose heart. There are other ways to embark on the long road to barley and hops enlightenment. "You can gain some relevant insight from brewing your own or working for a beer distributor," Kent says. "But the easiest thing you can do is to just start tasting all kinds of beer." Amen.</P></TD><TD><!--space--!></TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<BR>
<BR>


<CENTER><TABLE>
<TR><TD></TD><TD><A HREF="/august/work/worktoc.html"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/storywork.gif" ALT="Work"></A></TD><TD WIDTH=5></TD><TD><a href="http://www.entermag.com"><IMG BORDER=0  SRC="/august/tocart/logo.gif" ALT="Enter Magazine's Survival Guide"></A>
