<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Enter Magazine--So you wanna be..a Movie Extra</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#1EDC19">

<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG WIDTH=248 HEIGHT=146  SRC="sohead.gif"></P><BR>
<BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><A HREF="MAILTO:enter@entermag.com">By Jeff Morris</A></P>


<P><FONT SIZE=4>SCENE:</FONT> A balmy afternoon in New York City. Max (played by James Spader) 
has traveled several hundred miles from St. Louis and is about to enter 
the restaurant to reunite with his love, Nora (played by 
Susan Sarandon). He hesitates, then quickly ducks inside.</P>





<P>"Cut! You. Yes you, in the red shirt. Could you come out of the shop 
just a little sooner?"</P>





<P><IMG WIDTH=280 HEIGHT=238 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="crowd.gif">My big acting debut. For $25 a day, I had spent weeks just standing 
around drinking coffee, watching the action and waiting to be called. 
Only to be reduced to "you in the red shirt." But I couldn't be more 
thrilled. I was a movie extra in the feature film <I>White Palace</I>. Of 
course, when the movie hit the big screens, my celluloid debut (it was 
actually shot in the Central West End in St. Louis) didn't make it. Lost 
on the cutting room floor, as they say in the biz. I never even met any 
stars.</P>





<P>So how did I get there? A friend had heard about a cattle call audition 
on the evening news. We went, spent several hours in a cramped 
auditorium, filled out reams of paper, then went home to await our call 
to stardom.</P>





<P>According to Judy Welker, one of the midwest's premier casting 
directors, it sometimes happens that way. But only when vast numbers of 
people are needed. Like the cheering crowds in the movie <I>Hoosiers</I>. In 
New York or L.A. you can scour the ads in <I>Daily Variety</I> or the 
<I>Hollywood Reporter</I> for cattle calls, but most Hollywood casting 
directors won't even consider you unless you're with a Hollywood agent.</P>

 


<P>The midwest, however, is a different story. </P>





<P>"Many studios are now shooting in the midwest because [production] is 
cheaper, but also because the talent here are real people," says 
Welker, "so I don't necessarily look for people who are trained in 
acting because chances are that's not what the [studio] producer is 
looking for."</P>





<P>How do you become a movie extra? Try to arrange an appointment 
with a casting director like Welker, who operates Artistic Enterprises Midwest Casting. She keeps a database of 
profiles and photos that she calls upon when the Hollywood studios 
call upon her. Because of her busy schedule, it's tough to meet her and 
there's no guarantee you'll get any auditions. It all depends on her 
unique feel for the character and whether you fit that part. For 
example, the boy Welker cast in the part of a young Babe Ruth in 
<I>The Babe</I> had heard about the casting on the radio, visited the local 
library to research Ruth, then impressed Welker with his genuine 
personality. He ended up being the only child on the audition tape sent 
to Universal Studios.</P>





<P>According to Welker, these success stories sometimes feed local 
scams. "People hear these stories and think they can do it too. I always 
warn people to be very careful about answering newspaper ads. I rarely 
use advertising. I rely on my database. And I get paid by the studios, 
so I don't charge for auditions. There should never be a fee for 
auditions."</P>





<P>"Being an extra is a tough job for not much pay," says Welker. I 
couldn't agree more. "Excuse me, Mr. Coppola, what's my motivation for 
exiting this store?"</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<BR>


